    Writing activity 2.  Colons and semi-colons
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO  The effects of fascism have been studied extensively: many historians try to ignore associations between fascism and Christianity. 
    QUESTION 0 Is the colon in this sentence properly used?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  A colon should introduce a list, or expand on the information that precedes it.  If a colon is correctly used, you can usually swap it for the phrase 'that is to say'.  In this case, a new topic has been introduced.  Topic 1 is the effects of Fascism.  Topic 2 concerns historians.  I think these sentences would be better separated by a full stop.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  A colon should introduce a list, or expand on the information that precedes it.  If a colon is correctly used, you can usually swap it for the phrase 'that is to say'.  In this case, a new topic has been introduced.  Topic 1 is the effects of Fascism.  Topic 2 concerns historians.  I think these sentences would be better separated by a full stop.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">There were many questions to be answered concerning the transformation to democracy: what kind of democracy should be adopted? What kind of policies might work best? How was the transformation of the Hungarian system to be effected?</font> 
    QUESTION 0 Is the colon in this text properly used?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  Colons introduce lists - in this case a list of questions.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  I think the colon is properly used.  Colons introduce lists - and here we have a list of questions.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO  <font size="4">In addition, budgets were stretched; the sheer number of people reliant on the NHS pushed up spending beyond anything envisaged when it was first created.<br /><br />In addition, budgets were stretched in several ways: hospitals needed to find ?469 million to replace lifesaving equipment (Mirror 2011) and wages increased. <br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Is the semi-colon correctly used in sentence 1?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  In sentence 1 we have two sentences closely linked.  Each could stand alone, but a semi-colon helps the text to flow.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Here we have two sentences closely linked.  Each could stand alone, but a semi-colon helps the text to flow.  You wouldn't have to use a semi-colon here but its use is quite correct.
    QUESTION 1 Is the colon used properly in sentence 2?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  The second part of  sentence 2 gives specific illustrations of what has been asserted in the first part of the sentence.  In contrast, the second part of sentence 1 is closely linked to the first part, but makes a more general point.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  The second part of  sentence 2 gives specific illustrations of what has been asserted in the first part of the sentence.  In contrast, the second part of sentence 1 is closely linked to the first part, but makes a more general point.
        Task freetext difficulty 2
        Task freetext difficulty 1
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">1. This essay will examine theories about class put forward by: Durkheim, Marx and Weber.<br /> 2. This essay will examine the work of three class theorists: Durkheim, Marx and Weber.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 In which sentence is the colon used correctly?
        ANSWER: 1.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  The list of names here flows into the sentence.  A list is not flagged up by stating a number.  There's no need for any punctuation before 'Durkheim'.
        ANSWER: 2.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  In this sentence, a list is flagged up by stating a number - 'will examine three etc.  In sentence 1, where a number is not flagged up, the names flow into the sentence.
        ANSWER: Neither.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again!
        ANSWER: Both.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again!
