    Writing activity 02.  Colons and semi-colons
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">At higher levels, the ionic conductivity of the overall electrolyte is reduced, lower levels confer insufficient cubic stability.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 A semi-colon should replace one of the commas in this text.  Which comma?  The one after 'levels' or the one after 'reduced'?
        ANSWER: The comma after 'levels' should be a semi-colon.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  'At higher levels' is a sub-clause, i.e. it adds information to the main clause.  A comma is the best (and most proper) way to separate a sub-clause from a main clause.
        ANSWER: The comma after 'reduced' should be a semi-colon.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  This is a perfect place for a semi-colon.  Remember that a semi-colon is used to divide two complete sentences (i.e. sentences that could stand perfectly well on their own), when the sentences are closely related.  These two sentences, neatly juxtaposing 'higher levels' and 'lower levels', fit the bill exactly.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">This potential technology is seen as a solution to the world's energy problems but is predicated upon two conditions; that the sun continues to supply the earth with quantities of energy and that hydrogen can be produced from water at a sufficient rate. </font> 
    QUESTION 0 Is the semi-colon in this text properly used?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  A semi-colon divides two complete sentences that are closely related.  This is not the case here.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  A semi-colon divides two complete sentences that are closely related.  Here, the semi-colon is being used to introduce a list, which it is not designed to do. A colon is the correct way to introduce a list.
    QUESTION 1 Is there anywhere else in this text that a semi-colon might be useful?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  A semi-colon can also divide items in a list when the items are long.  In this text, it might be useful to put a semi-colon after the first item on the list, i.e. 'quantities of energy;  and that hydrogen etc.' This gives the reader time to take a breath.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  A semi-colon can also divide items in a list when the items are long.  In this text, it might be useful to put a semi-colon after the first item on the list, i.e. 'quantities of energy;  and that hydrogen etc.' This gives the reader time to take a breath.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO  <font size="4">But even with increased battery life, these products were not made commercially for several reasons - fuel cell electronic devices are just too expensive to compete with lithium ion batteries; and the methanol used to fuel them is toxic.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 The dash in this text should be replaced.  Which is the right replacement, a colon or a semi-colon?
        ANSWER: A colon.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  A colon should be used to introduce a list, and the phrase 'for several reasons' shows there is a list coming.  A semi-colon can separate items in a list, or separate two complete sentences that are closely connected.
        ANSWER: A semi-colon.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again!
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">There is no single answer to polymorphism each example requires a fresh approach.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 We need some punctuation in this sentence.  What do we need?
        ANSWER: A comma.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  We've two strong clauses so we need something stronger than a comma.  With a comma, the text reads like a 'run-on' sentence, i.e. two sentences that have not been divided properly.
        ANSWER: A semi-colon.
        FEEDBACK: You could put a semi-colon after 'polymorphism'.  You would then have two complete and related sentences with a pause between them.  That would work.  I don't, however, think that's the best punctuation here.
        ANSWER: A colon.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  I think we need a colon after 'polymorphism'.  A colon can stand for 'that is', which makes sense in this context, i.e. There is no one answer to polymorphism:  (that is) each example requires a fresh approach.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">In Altzheimer's patients, there is a shortage of acetylcholine, the acetylcholine esterase receptor breaks down even more acetylcholine which means the brain is not able to replenish the acetylcholine lost.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 Would the comma in this sentence best be left as it is, replaced by a semi-colon, or replaced by a colon?
        ANSWER: Left as it is.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  There needs to be a harder pause, as it were, between the two pieces of information offered.  They don't flow together naturally.
        ANSWER: Replaced by a semi-colon.
        FEEDBACK: This is an option, since we have two complete sentences closely related.  However, I don't think it's the best option.
        ANSWER: A colon.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  The second part of the sentence (beginning 'The acetylcholine esterase') expands on the first part, so a colon is the most appropriate form of punctuation here.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Tacrine has more serious side effect, a possible increase in alanine aminotransferase (ALT).</font> 
    QUESTION 0 What might best replace the comma in this text?
        ANSWER: Nothing:  the comma is fine.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again.
        ANSWER: A semi-colon.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again.
        ANSWER: A colon.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  When the second part of a sentence expands on the first, a colon is the most appropriate punctuation.  It is really standing in for 'that is to say' or introducing a particular example of a point made in the first part of the sentence.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">It is a proinflammatory cytokine; inducing inflammation.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 Is the semi-colon properly used here?
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  A semi-colon separates two complete sentences that are closely related.  'Inducing inflammation' is not a complete sentence because it has no driving verb, so a semi-colon is not appropriate here.
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  A semi-colon separates two complete sentences that are closely related.  'Inducing inflammation' is not a complete sentence because it has no driving verb, so a semi-colon is not appropriate here.
    QUESTION 1 If you feel the semi-colon is not properly used, what would you replace it with? 
        ANSWER: A colon.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  A colon introduces a list, or stands in for 'that is', i.e. an expansion on a point already made.  In the example text, 'inducing inflammation' is part of the initial point, not an expansion of the point.
        ANSWER: A full stop.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  'It is proinflammatory cytokine' is a complete sentence and could end with a full stop.  However, 'inducing inflammation' is a sentence fragment, i.e. it has no driving verb.  A full stop, therefore, would not help.
        ANSWER: A comma.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  A comma allows the reader to take a breath but the information flows together, which make much more sense.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO  <font size="4">Other treatments for the side effects include: anti-depressants, sedating anti-psychotic drugs and non-sedating anti-psychotic drugs.<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Is the colon correctly used in this text?
        ANSWER: Yes.  It introduces a list.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  There is a list in this text, but the list flows from the text, so the colon interrupts.  A colon only introduces a list that is flagged up as a list, e.g. There are three other treatments:  anti-depressants; sedating antipsychotic drugs; and non-sedating antipsychotic drugs.
        ANSWER: No.  The type of list in this text doesn't need to be introduced by a colon.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  A colon only introduces a list that is flagged up as a list, e.g. There are three other treatments:  anti-depressants; sedating antipsychotic drugs; and non-sedating antipsychotic drugs.
    Writing activity 03. Commas and run-on sentences
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">The basic principle of operation occurs by the ionisation of molecular oxygen to O<sup>2-</sup>ions at the cathode, the ionic potential is conducted through the solid state electrolyte, the </font><font size="4">O<sup>2-</sup> ions combine at the anode with H<sub>2</sub> and CO forming water and CO<sub>2</sub> and evolving 2e-, as the electrolyte is impermeable to electrons they can be induced to travel round a circuit and do useful work before ionising more oxygen. </font> 
    QUESTION 0 Why is this text in the 'commas and run-on' sentence category?
        ANSWER: It's too long.
        FEEDBACK: It is long, certainly, but that's not the main reason.
        ANSWER: The commas should be semi-colons.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not the reason.  Semi-colons would not be appropriate.
        ANSWER: The text contains too many pieces of information for one sentence.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  For clarity, information needs to be divided into sentences.  If you pile too much information into one sentence, the reader is inclined to lose track.  If a reader loses track, I'm afraid it's usually the writer's fault, not the reader's.
    QUESTION 1 How many pieces of information are in this text?
        ANSWER: 1.
        FEEDBACK: Really?  Read it again.
        ANSWER: 2.
        FEEDBACK: Not 2.  Try again.
        ANSWER: 3.
        FEEDBACK: Not 3.  Try again.
        ANSWER: 4.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  Read the text slowly.  There are four pieces of information.  In this particular text, it would be far better if each had its own sentence.  Sentence 1 "The basic principle ... cathode".  Sentence 2 "The ionic potential ... electrolyte."  Sentence 3  "The O2-ions ...2e-."  Sentence 4 "As the electrolyte ... more oxygen."
