    Writing activity 18. Checking your work for careless errors
        Task selectcat difficulty 2
        Task freetext difficulty 1
        Task selectcat difficulty 1
        Task selectcat difficulty 3
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">Reactive and endogenous describes the trigger of depression, reactive describe an environmentally stimulus such as bereavement, endogenous describe a trigger more seated in physiology.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 Are 'describes', 'describe' and 'describe' (see the text for context) all used properly in this sentence?  You can choose more than one option.
        ANSWER: Yes.  They're all grammatically correct.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.   Try again.
        ANSWER: The first two - 'describes' and 'describe' are the wrong way round.  We need 'describes' first, then 'describe'.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  Reactive and endogenous are two different things, so need the plural, i.e. 'reactive and endogenous describe'.  'Reactive' on its own is singular, so needs the singular 'reactive describes'.
        ANSWER: The final 'describe' is correct.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again.
        ANSWER: The final 'describe' is plural, when 'endogenous' is singular.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  The text should read 'endogenous describes ...'
    QUESTION 1 There are two commas in this text.  What might be good replacements?
        ANSWER: Nothing:  the commas are well used where they are.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  This sentence, with its commas, makes for a run-on sentence, i.e. one sentence that should be broken up.  Try again.
        ANSWER: We need two colons:  one after 'trigger of depression' and one after 'bereavement'.
        FEEDBACK: Half right.  I think a colon after 'trigger of depression' would be useful, but I think we need something stronger than a comma after 'bereavement'.
        ANSWER: We need a colon and a semi-colon.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  We need a colon after 'trigger of depression', since the information that follows expands on the first bit of the sentence.  A semi-colon would nicely divide the two topic items, 'reactive' and 'endogenous'.
        Task selectcat difficulty 3
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">To describe this affect I will use the well known equation relating the intensity of an electric fields with the polarization of the material P=@E equ where P is the polarization, E is the electric field intensity and @ is the polarizability. </font> 
    QUESTION 0 There is a word improperly used in this text.  Which is it?
        ANSWER: polarization
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  That seems correct here.
        ANSWER: affect
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  'Effect' is the correct noun here.  An effect is a result.
        ANSWER: polarizability
        FEEDBACK: This is quite a word, I agree, but though it's clumsy, it makes sense in this context.
    QUESTION 1 One character in the equation is wrongly formatted.  Which is it?
        ANSWER: P
        FEEDBACK: Not P.  Try again.
        ANSWER: =
        FEEDBACK: No, not =.  Try again.
        ANSWER: @
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  This should be an alpha, not an ampersand.
    QUESTION 2 Is this text written in active or passive mode?
        ANSWER: Active.
        FEEDBACK: It is.  'I will use' signifies the active mode.  However, academic texts should use the more impersonal passive mode.  Better to say 'the equation etc. was used'.
        ANSWER: Passive.
        FEEDBACK: It is actually written in the active mode - I will use -  though the more impersonal passive mode is correct in an academic essay.   Better to say 'the equation etc. was used'.
    QUESTION 3 Should well known be hyphenated?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  It is usually hyphenated as it has come to be almost one word.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Well-known is usually hyphenated since it has almost turned into one word.
        ANSWER: It doesn't matter.
        FEEDBACK: Most things matter!  Well-known should be hyphenated, as it has become almost one word.  It is muddling to read if it's not hyphenated.
    QUESTION 4 There's a singular/plural mismatch in this text.  Where is it?
        ANSWER: polarization of the material
        FEEDBACK: No.  Try again.
        ANSWER: an electric fields
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  Be careful!  Your reader doesn't know if this is simply a typo or a real grammatical error. Don't make them choose.
        ANSWER: the electric field intensity
        FEEDBACK: No, this is fine.  Try again.
