    Writing activity 08.  Avoiding colloquialisms
        Task wordclick difficulty 1
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task freetext difficulty 2
        Task freetext difficulty 2
        Task selectcat difficulty 3
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO The study and understanding of natural photosynthetic systems provides lots of information to help us get artificial systems up and running. 
    QUESTION 0 How many colloquialisms are contained in this sentence?
        ANSWER: 1.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.
        ANSWER: 2.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  I'd say 'lots of' and 'up and running' are too colloquial for an academic essay.  'Lots of' is also very vague, as is the case with many colloquialisms.  In an academic essay, you need to be as precise as possible.
        Task freetext difficulty 2
        Task multiplechoice difficulty None
INTRO <font size="4">Depression is a really awful affliction that affects men and women all over the world. It's a problem that dogs people in lots of different age-groups and the massive number of prescriptions issued by GPs over the years suggests that depression is looming ever larger on our horizons.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 How many colloquialisms can you spot in this text?
        ANSWER: 1.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again.
        ANSWER: 2.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again.
        ANSWER: 7.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  Go to the next question.
        ANSWER: 5.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again.
        ANSWER: 4.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again.
    QUESTION 1 Which of these are colloquialisms?
        ANSWER: really awful affliction
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  Better to say 'persistent neurological condition'.
        ANSWER: all over the world
        FEEDBACK: I wouldn't say this was a colloquialism, although 'worldwide' is snappier.
        ANSWER: It's
        FEEDBACK: Yes, quite right.  Don't contract in an academic essay.  Use 'it is'.
        ANSWER: a problem that dogs
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  I might say to you 'I'm dogged by depression', but in an essay it's better to use a more formal expression.  'a problem that affects' would be fine.
        ANSWER: lots of
        FEEDBACK: Yes.  This colloquialism crops up again and again in academic essays.  Apart from being too chatty, 'lots of' is extremely imprecise.  How many is 'lots of'?  You need a precise statistic, properly referenced.  'Lots of' smacks of slapdash research.
        ANSWER: different age-groups
        FEEDBACK: I'd say this was fine for an academic essay.
        ANSWER: massive number
        FEEDBACK: Yes, this is a colloquialism of the same sort at 'lots of'.  Apart from being too chatty, it's much too vague.  You need a statistic, properly referenced.
        ANSWER: GP
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  Your reader might not know what GP stands for.   Write out General Practitioner in full, with (GP) afterwards so that you can use the initials later in the essay.
        ANSWER: over the years
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  Again, as with so many colloquialisms, this is too general.  Use a statistic, properly referenced.
        ANSWER: looming ever larger
        FEEDBACK: Yes, this is another colloquialism.  'Increasing' would be quite enough in the example text, and would sound more professional.
    Writing activity 13. Introduction - strong v. weak
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title:</font><font size="4" style="font-weight: bold;"><br /><br />Altzheimer's Disease: Possible Causes and Synthesis of Treatments</font> 
    QUESTION 0 Which of the following opening lines would best fit this essay title?
        ANSWER: There are many neurodegenerative diseases in the present day.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  This opening line is too vague.  If possible, your essay should open with something punchy, not something bland.
        ANSWER: Altzheimer's disease affects one in every 14 people over the age of 65.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  This statistic is a good, attention-grabbing opening line.   It's the best on offer here. Don't forget that it needs a reference.
        ANSWER: Throughout the course of Altzheimer's disease, what are known as 'amyloid plaques' and 'neurofibrallary tangles' develop.
        FEEDBACK: This information should certainly appear in the essay, but is too detailed for an opening line.  An opening line needs to introduce the topic in an interesting, attention-grabbing way, opening the way to more detailed information.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO  <font size="4">Read the essay title, then choose the best opening line(s) for your introduction. All the options have explanations, so even if your first choice is also ours, it might be worth scanning through the rest and reading the comments. </font><br /><font size="4"><br /><span style="font-weight: bold;">Essay title:</span><br /><br />A History of Density Functional Theorem<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">Read the following essay title. Click on the best introductory paragraph. All the paragraphs have explanations, so it might be worth clicking on them all. </font> 
        ANSWER: With the advent of quantum mechanics in the early half of the 20th century, the question of how to describe systems with multiple electrons (the so-called 'many electron problem') was addressed with reasonable success by E. Fermi and L. Thomas with their subsequently named Thomas-Fermi theory (TFT).
        FEEDBACK: This opening line is informative, but has three faults: it's too long for an opening line;  it doesn't arrest the reader's attention; and it does not grasp the essay topic firmly.  It is leading up to the topic, but a strong opening line will actually address the topic.   Not the best option. 
        ANSWER: The history of density functional theorem (DFT) is still being made, yet since it is the way forward for quantum calculations, a review of its development reveals much about both its current status and future possibilties.
        FEEDBACK: I like this opening line.  It may be long, but it grasps the topic and tell us why the essay is going to be both interesting and informative.  This is the best choice on offer.
        ANSWER: Density functional theory (DFT) is 'a quantum mechanical modelling method used in physics and chemistry to investigate the electronic structure of many-body systems' (Wikipedia).
        FEEDBACK: Definitions are all very well but quoting from Wikipedia is not acceptable in an academic essay.  Wikipedia is not a reliable source. If you must start your essay with a definition rather than a thought, then find a reputable source from which to quote.   This is a very poor option.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title:<br /><br />Practical Syntheses of Efavirenz, Tenofovir and Emtricitabine: Novel Treatments in HIV</font>.<br /> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Read the essay title, then choose the best opening line(s) for your introduction. All the options have explanations, so even if your first choice is also ours, it might be worth scanning through the rest and reading the comments. </font>
        ANSWER: AIDS was first discovered in 1981 and was identified by showing effects on the immune system.  Symptoms included lung infections caused by Pneuymocystis Carinii.  
        FEEDBACK: Two assumptions are made here:  that the reader will know what HIV and AIDS stand for; and that they will associate AIDS with HIV.  Though you may think 'surely everybody knows these things', you cannot presume any such thing.  This is not a good option.
        ANSWER: Human immunodeficiency virus (HIV), the virus that causes acquired immune deficiency syndrome (AIDS), is treated mainly by drugs, and atripla, made up of compounds efavirenz, emtricitabine and tenofivir, is currently the most effective.  This essay will explore the practical synthesis for each of the three compounds, since economical and efficient synthetic processing will  enhance HIV treatment and save lives.
        FEEDBACK: These opening lines are direct, explanatory and inform the reader what the essay is about.  They inspire confidence.   I think they are the best on offer here.
        ANSWER: The HIV virus specifically targets cells of the immune system such as helper T cells, macrophages and dendritic cells, all of which have CD4 proteins on their surface.  By targeting these cells, the AIDS virus either kills the cells or disrupts their function.
        FEEDBACK: These lines might well appear in the body of the essay, but they are too detailed for opening lines.  They read like the middle of something, not the start.  They might well leave the reader slightly at sea and checking the essay title to see what the essay is actually about.  Not a good option.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title:<br /><br />The Asymmetric Epoxidation of Allylic Alcohols.<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">Read the essay title, then choose the best opening line(s) for your introduction. All the options have explanations, so even if your first choice is also ours, it might be worth scanning through the rest and reading the comments. </font> 
        ANSWER: Epoxidation is a vital transformation in organic synthesis.  The process produces important reactive species that find use as synthetic intermediates or, less often, as products in their own right, e.g. epichlorohydrin, a common compound found in epoxy resin.  Allylic describes an alcohol in which the hydroxyl group is bonded to an allylic carbon atom or a benzylic carbon atom.1
        FEEDBACK: These opening lines are clear, confident and informative.  They refer directly to the essay title and grasp the reader's attention by sounding authoritative.    These are strong opening lines, and the best on offer here.
        ANSWER: This essay is going to discuss the asymmetric epoxidation of allylic alcohols.  It will explore the history and uses of asymmetric epoxidation and examine what processes this involves.  This essay will also look at new research in this area.
        FEEDBACK: These opening lines are very weak.  It's certainly good to include terms from the essay title in opening lines, but you must add something to them, not just repeat them.  These lines are really just waffle disguised as an essay map.  An essay map needs more than vague indications of an essay's direction.  These lines could apply to almost any essay. They could also be left out without losing anything from the essay.  Not the best option here.
        ANSWER: Like many organic reactions, transition states play a crucial role in determining selectivity, be it regio- or stereoselectivity.  Epoxidations are no different:  their stereoselectivity is dependent on cyclic transition states.
        FEEDBACK: These lines might be a good start to a background section of an essay, but they don't work well at the start of your introduction.   An introduction needs to draw the reader in by explaining terms and providing an essay map.  These lines presume that we are already bedded into the essay.  Not the best option on offer for an introduction.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title:<br /><br />Antibiotics and the Development of New Compounds to Target Bacterial Resistance.<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">Read the essay title, then choose the best opening line(s) for your introduction. All the options have explanations, so even if your first choice is also ours, it might be worth scanning through the rest and reading the comments. </font> 
        ANSWER: The threat of bacterial infection is one that has been affecting humans since long before ideas of medicinal chemistry were in circulation.  Bacterial infections still cause many deaths each year;  for example C Diff was a factor in 597 deaths in Scotland in 2008 compared with 313 deaths in 2005.1 
        FEEDBACK: Though the first sentence in this introduction might do for a newspaper article, it is too general for an academic essay, particularly for an essay supposedly focused on bacterial resistance rather than bacterial infection.  In addition, the reference to C diff is not explained and the figure used is at least three years old.  This means that instead of enhancing the essay, the reference diminishes it.  These lines are not the best option on offer here.
        ANSWER: Perhaps the biggest development in antibiotics came in 1929 when Alexander Fleming noted that a penicillium mould contaminant could cause the lysis of colonies of staphylococci.   This led to the first successful chemotherapeutic agent produced by a microbe.
        FEEDBACK: If you start your essay with 'perhaps', you have already weakened it.  Always start with a confident statement.  The rest of these lines would be better in a 'background' section.  Your introduction needs to define your terms and also provide an essay map.  These lines do neither. 
        ANSWER: Bacterial resistance to antibiotics 
        FEEDBACK: These lines form a strong opening.  They tell us why the topic is important and outline the essay's specific focus.  If, after reading them, somebody asked the reader 'what's the essay about?', the reader would be able to answer without hesitation.  These are the best opening lines on offer here.
        ANSWER: threatens to undermine man's ability to tackle the infectious diseases it was hoped antibiotics might eradicate. New compounds to target bacterial resistance are being developed and this essay will focus on two specific classes of antibiotic:  beta-lactams and macrolides.
        FEEDBACK: 
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title:<br /><br />Polymorphism.<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Read the essay title, then choose the best opening line(s) for your introduction. All the options have explanations, so even if your first choice is also ours, it might be worth scanning through the rest and reading the comments. </font> 
        ANSWER: 'Every compound has different polymorphic forms and, in general, the number of forms known for a given compound is proportional to the time and money spent in research on that compound.'  Walter C. McCrone
        FEEDBACK: Starting an essay with a quotation is often an excellent way of grabbing the reader's attention.  It must, however, be a relevant quote.  I'd say this quote was entirely relevant, and so long as the writer went on to define polymorphism more specifically, and also to define the areas the essay was going to cover, I'd say this was a good opening to an introduction.  I still prefer one of the other options here, but I wouldn't write this one off.  N.B.  If you quote, remember to reference correctly.
        ANSWER: Polymorphism is a phenomenon with far-reaching implications in many fields of chemistry.  It is a vital consideration in drug discovery which is why it has been chosen as the subject for this essay.
        FEEDBACK: These lines are a little waffly.  A strong introduction needs more precision.  We need an example or two of the fields of chemistry, and one reason why polymorphism is a vital consideration in drug discovery.   There is a difference between too much detail in introductory sentences and too little.  This example offers too little.  Not a good option.
        ANSWER: Polymorphism is a phenomenon with far-reaching implications in many fields of chemistry, particularly crystallography and solid state chemistry.  It is also a vital consideration in drug discovery since different polymorphs can have different chemical and physical properties, often resulting in different effects on the user.
        FEEDBACK: These opening lines draw the reader in and, through offering examples, move the reader effortlessly from the general to the specific.  These are the best opening lines on offer in this exercise.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title:<br /><br />Fuel Cells: Current Technology and some Directions of Research.<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Read the essay title, then choose the best opening line(s) for your introduction. All the options have explanations, so even if your first choice is also ours, it might be worth scanning through the rest and reading the comments. </font> 
        ANSWER: With the end of oil being well in sight and popular, scientific and governmental awareness and opinion being largely united over climate change, energy security and sustainability, much effort is currently being spent on developing new and existing environmentally friendly or alternative energy technologies with ever greater degrees of efficiency and one such technology, which is the focus of a lot of research, is fuel cell technology.
        FEEDBACK: I feel quite breathless after reading this.  It contains good ideas but needs breaking up.  The tone is also too chatty - 'well in sight' and 'a lot of' are colloquialisms.  We also need references for all these assertions.   This is enthusiastic, but needs to be refined to score good marks in an academic essay.  Not the best option on offer here.
        ANSWER: The importance of developing fuel cell technology has increased in line with increasing global worries about climate change, energy security and environmental sustainability.1  This essay will look at current technologies, for example proton exchange membrane fuel cells (PEMFCs) and solid oxide fuel cells (SOFCs).  It will then examine how, with industry now interested in fuel cell research, the new technologies are being funded and whether the hopes pinned on them are likely to lead to a fundamental change in the way we produce and use energy.
        FEEDBACK: These opening lines provide a neat way into the essay.  They move from the general - current technologies - to the specific - the two examples.  This is very good practice.  These lines also provide a clear essay map.   They inspire confidence in the reader.  These are the best option on offer here. 
        ANSWER: The goal of meeting the energy needs of the planet with renewable ecologically sound technologies is mired in economic complications.  These provide obstacles to the more rapid advance of developing technologies, whose goal is to provide a fully environmentally friendly, sustainable hydrogen economy.  This essay will provide a history of the fuel cell to show how it came to develop and what it might, in the future, contribute to this goal.
        FEEDBACK: It's two sentences before we get to the fuel cell, and the title very clearly states 'current technology' not 'the history of'.  Be careful to look your title and not to wander off course right at the start.  Also, to strengthen the assertions made about economic complications and developing technologies, we need at least one example which will be developed further into the essay.  These lines are not the best option on offer.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title:<br /><br />Solid Phase Peptide Synthesis.<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">Read the essay title, then choose the best opening line(s) for your introduction. All the options have explanations, so even if your first choice is also ours, it might be worth scanning through the rest and reading the comments. </font> 
        ANSWER: Robert Bruce Merrifield, who died in 2006, was the inventor of solid phase peptide synthesis (SPPS).  Although his invention did not win him the Nobel Prize in Chemistry until 1984, he came up with the idea of SPPS in 1959.  SPPS was important because it was hoped that it might eliminate, or at least reduce, one of the biggest problems facing peptide synthesis to that date, namely the isolation and purification of the peptide from the liquid phase.
        FEEDBACK: The title of this essay gives no indication of its scope or point.  Take care with such titles, and with opening lines like these ones.  They read well but they don't actually lead anywhere.  By the end, the reader still has no idea of the point or scope of the essay.  If you choose an open title such as this one, your opening lines must convince the reader that the essay isn't just going to be a wander around solid phase peptide synthesis, but has something particular to discuss.  These lines are not the best option on offer.
        ANSWER: Solid phase peptide synthesis (SPPS) has produced peptides used to study the structure and activity of various biological molecules such as Bovine Pancreatic Robonuclease A7 and HIV-1 protease.1  From these, a number of peptide analogues, mainly small organic molecules to avoid the problem of low bio-availability, have been synthesised. 
        FEEDBACK: As opening lines, these lines don't work because they introduce, without definition or explanation, too many different terms.  Your introduction must do what the section title suggests, i.e. introduce.   These lines may belong in the essay, but they don't belong right at the start.
        ANSWER: Solid phase peptide synthesis (SPPS) creates peptides (short polymers of amino acids linked by peptide bonds) and proteins in a synthetic manner.1  This essay will chart a brief history of SPPS;  assess its advantages;  provide a detailed overview of chemical reactions SPPS produces; and finally, assess the likelihood of  biotechnology replacing the chemical synthesis of peptides some time in the future.
        FEEDBACK: These lines provide a definition of solid phase peptide synthesis and an essay plan.  The plan is crucial when you have such a general heading as this one.  The reader needs to feel confident that the writer isn't just going to ramble.  These lines are the best option of those on offer.
    Writing activity 14. Conclusion - strong v. weak
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO  <font size="4">Essay title:<br /><br />Using organometallics as an example, does conjugate addition deserve its status as one of the most important reactions in chemistry?<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Read the essay title, then choose the best concluding line(s). All the options have explanations, so even if your first choice is also ours, it might be worth scanning through the rest and reading the comments. </font> 
        ANSWER: In conclusion, conjugate addition of organometallics is a very effective way of forming new C-C bonds.  As this essay has shown, by altering the conditions of the reaction, using additives and employing chiral ligands, a high degree of regioselectivity and enantioselectivity can be achieved.  As has also been shown, recent research into reagents could provide useful new transformations.  Thus, using organometallic nucleophiles as an example, it is clear that conjugate addition deserves its status as one of the most important reactions in chemistry.  
        FEEDBACK: These concluding lines follow the essay through, and answer the question the essay writer set.  They are the best concluding lines on offer here.
        ANSWER: In conclusion, the first example of a conjugate addition was reported in 1883 by Komnenos.  However, in 2011, it still has a wide range of applications in synthetic organic chemistry.
        FEEDBACK: These concluding lines are very weak.  The essay title asks a question, which these lines do not answer.  Instead they seem to belong to a different essay.  If your title asks a question, use your conclusion to answer it boldly.  After all, you have your whole essay to back up your answer.  Giving a bold and clear answer is a very attractive and satisfying way of drawing a questioning essay to a close.  These lines are not the best option here.
        ANSWER: In conclusion, I think I have shown that by altering the conditions of the reaction, using additives and employing chiral ligands, a high degree of regioselectivity and enantioselectivity can be achieved.  As I've also shown, recent research into reagents could provide useful new transformations.  All of this means that, using organometallic nucleophiles as an example, I can state with some confidence that conjugate addition deserves its status as one of the most important reactions in chemistry.
        FEEDBACK: This conclusion contains the same information as choice 1, but its tone is too personal.  You must retain the academic tone right to the very last word.  These lines are not the best option on offer.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title:<br /><br />Materials for nonlinear optics.<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Read the essay title, then choose the best concluding line(s). All the options have explanations, so even if your first choice is also ours, it might be worth scanning through the rest and reading the comments. </font> 
        ANSWER: Thus, when talking about nonlinear optics, one must be very careful not to think of it being confined to physics for it has some very important chemical applications as well.
        FEEDBACK: With general titles such as this, it is even more important that the essay should stick to a clear path.  It would be hard, from this closing line, to know what the essay had been about, and for that reason I'd say it was a weak conclusion.  Not the best option on offer here.
        ANSWER: Thus it can be argued that organic crystals are the materials offering the best prospects for research into second phase harmonic generation, and the prospects are exciting.
        FEEDBACK: This concluding line clearly connects with the title of the essay, and offers a strong conclusion.  This is the best option on offer.
        ANSWER: It has only been within the past few decades that nonlinear optics has been studied properly, the key date being the invention of the commercial laser in 1961.  However, study has come a long way since then and promises to go further in the future.
        FEEDBACK: These lines are too general - as though the essay has run out of steam.  Make sure your concluding lines remain focused tightly on the subject of your essay.  Remember, last impressions really do count.  These lines are not the best option on offer here.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title:<br /><br />An Overview of Depression and Antidepressant Drugs.</font><br /> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Read the essay title, then choose the best concluding line(s). All the options have explanations, so even if your first choice is also ours, it might be worth scanning through the rest and reading the comments. </font> 
        ANSWER: As has been shown, depression is a term coined for a wide spectrum of illnesses, many of which require different treatments.  However, with the advances from MAOIs to tricyclic MARIs to atypical MARIs and the advent of more effective drugs with fewer side-effects, sufferers have a better chance now than ever before of some relief.
        FEEDBACK: The essay title was 'an overview' and these lines draw an 'overview' nicely to a close.  Examples remind the reader of what was in the body of the text and keep the conclusion from wandering.   These are the best lines on offer.
        ANSWER: Masses of money is spent researching depression and hopefully this means it won't stay a mystery much longer and that soon, better medication will help sufferers lead more normal lives with brighter futures.
        FEEDBACK: These lines read more like a magazine article than an academic essay.  Take care with the tone of your final lines.  It's easy to relax before you've quite got to the end!  The last lines must retain the academic tone and not drift off into banalities and generalities.  This option is not the best on offer.
        ANSWER: 
        FEEDBACK: This concluding line leave the reader turning the page, wondering if the conclusion has been deleted by mistake.  Your ending must obviously be an ending.  Don't leave the reader hanging in mid air.  This is not the best option on offer here.
