        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title:<br /><br />Fuel cells.<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Read the essay title, then choose the best concluding line(s). All the options have explanations, so even if your first choice is also ours, it might be worth scanning through the rest and reading the comments. </font> 
        ANSWER: Fuel cells are the future.
        FEEDBACK: Short, crisp sentences often make snappy final lines, and so long as the text has led up to a bold final statement, the line should be fine. Beware, however, of making your ending too abrupt - as though you had just run out of things to say.  In short, this line might be fine in its context but I hesitate to say it's the best option here. 
        ANSWER: As this essay has shown, fuel cells have attracted interest and investment because of their capacity to prolong battery life for days rather than hours.  In addition, the prospect of instant recharging overcomes what might have been a major difficulty.  
        FEEDBACK: These lines are fine in themselves but it's not clear that they are final lines.  Your reader needs to feel a sense of closure at the end, not be left hanging on, wondering if they've reached the end or not.   These lines have qualities but are not the best option on offer. 
        ANSWER: Despite the drawbacks discussed, this essay has shown that fuel cells have attracted interest and investment.  This is partly because of their capacity to prolong battery life for days rather than hours and partly because the prospect of instant recharging overcomes what might have been a major difficulty.  These two factors alone ensure that fuel cells have secured their place in all our energy debates and will play a big part in our future.
        FEEDBACK: These lines combine the information of option 2 above and the closure achieved by option 1.  This is the best option on offer.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title:<br /><br />Anti-malarial Drugs.<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">Read the essay title, then choose the best concluding line(s). All the options have explanations, so even if your first choice is also ours, it might be worth scanning through the rest and reading the comments. </font> 
        ANSWER: In this essay I have discussed various ways in which the malarial parasite is being targeted and new methods of treatment which will hopefully be successful in decreasing malaria transmission.
        FEEDBACK: These words don't really read like a conclusion:  they are too bland.  It's not enough to state 'I've done this or that'.  Apart from being too personal (try not to use 'I' in an academic essay), such a statement is a statement of the obvious.  You need to add something to your concluding lines so that the reader is left with something to remember.  This is not the best option offered here. 
        ANSWER: In recent years, it is reported that fake medicines have been sold in south-east Asia and Africa.  These can prove fatal and stopping this unacceptable practice is yet another priority for the World Health Organisation.  For the moment Artemisinin Combination Therapies described earlier seem the most promising way forward and production methods are continually being improved.
        FEEDBACK: This is an example of a thought being parachuted into a conclusion.  Fake medicines cannot simply be dropped in to the conclusion from nowhere.  The last line then reads as though it's been tagged on.  If you suddenly think of another topic, you must insert it into the body of your essay, and also mention it in your introduction.   The parachuted topic means that despite what might have been a good closing line, this option is not the best on offer here.
        ANSWER: Notwithstanding the research outlined in this essay, the fight against malaria is not yet won.  The difficulty in finding an effective anti-malaria compound and continued debate about the ideal target of a vaccine means that anti-malarial drugs are still a live and contentious issue.  For the moment, Artemisinin Combination Therapies are the most promising way forward, and with production methods continually improving, may offer the best hope for the future.
        FEEDBACK: These lines neatly wrap up the subject and provide a nice feeling of closure.  If a reader were to be asked 'what was the essay about', they would be able to answer without saying 'er, I'm not really sure'.  This is the best option on offer here.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title:<br /><br />Heroin: the chemistry of addiction.<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">Read the essay title, then choose the best concluding line(s). All the options have explanations, so even if your first choice is also ours, it might be worth scanning through the rest and reading the comments. </font> 
        ANSWER: Strychnine is a toxic alkaloid used as a pesticide.  It is added to heroin for the same reason as quinine, since strychnine is one of the bitterest substances known.  Strychnine poisoning causes massive convulsions and death by asphyxiation or exhaustion.
        FEEDBACK: This is a strange ending, and leaves the reader turning page wondering if the conclusion has been left out, or whether they've strayed into the appendices by mistake.   Not a good option.
        ANSWER: In conclusion, many of the opiates derived from poppy seeds have found medicinal applications, principally as pain killers.  However, heroin has proven to be so addictive that pharmacological applications have been ruled out.
        FEEDBACK: This is a dull ending.  Not only that, it doesn't refer to any themes that might have been in the essay.   Your ending needs to acknowledge themes in the essay and move to a conclusion that is both authoritative and satisfying.   You'll have done such a lot of work on your essay.  Don't let it end on a damp squib.
        ANSWER: In conclusion, the chemistry of heroin addiction means that all early hopes of pharmacological applications have now been ruled out.  As has been shown, the biological effects, the withdrawal difficulties and the dangers posed by adulterants all conspire to make heroin highly problematic.  Unfortunately, as has also been shown, chemical adulteration cannot solve the problem of heroin addiction, and other ways of dealing with this blight must be sought.
        FEEDBACK: This conclusion refers back to the essay themes and draws a genuine  conclusion.  That is a big plus point.  In addition, even if you only read this paragraph, you'd know what the essay had been about.  That's the mark of a good conclusion.  This is the best option of those on offer.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title:<br /><br />Parkinson's Disease: Potential Causes and Treatments.<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">Read the essay title, then choose the best concluding line(s). All the options have explanations, so even if your first choice is also ours, it might be worth scanning through the rest and reading the comments. </font> 
        ANSWER: Although, as has been shown, PD models have offered great insights into the potential causes of the disease, and have been a strong basis for drug development, research is still in the very early stages.  As has been shown, a variety of effective drugs have been established to relieve PD symptoms but they do not offer a cure.  The development of an orally active prodrug that can compete with L-DOPA without longterm complications is clearly significant, however it seems very clear that more emphasis on determining the root cause of PD is still the best hope of a real breakthrough.
        FEEDBACK: This option refers back to the body of the essay and then draws a conclusion.  This is a very good model, reminding the reader of the essay content, and bringing the whole thing to a satisfying and informative end.  This is the best option on offer here.
        ANSWER: Parkinson's comes second to Altzheimer's Disease as the UK's most common neurdegenerative condition. More needs to be known about the root cause.  This is where research should be concentrated.
        FEEDBACK: This option is a little abrupt and the information about where Parkinson's comes on the UK's neurdegenerative tables would be better placed in the introduction.  A good conclusion should refer back to the themes of the essay, which this does not do.  This is not the best option on offer. 
        ANSWER: The reason I chose Parkinson's Disease as my essay topic is that my grandfather suffers from it.  I have therefore seen at first hand its symptoms: speech problems; cognitive/mood disturbances; and autonomic disorders.  As this essay has shown, the need for more research into the root cause is more likely to lead to a cure than any drug.  It is root cause research that money should be invested.
        FEEDBACK: This conclusion is too personal.  As an academic, you must remain objective, so this is not the right forum to speak about a relation.  Save personal stuff for a fund-raising appeal or a piece of personal journalism.  This is not the best option on offer here.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title:<br /><br />Biomineralization: Calcium Carbonate and the Mollusc Shell.<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">Read the essay title, then choose the best concluding line(s). All the options have explanations, so even if your first choice is also ours, it might be worth scanning through the rest and reading the comments. </font> 
        ANSWER: Research into nacre recently has been extensive.  Scientists are even exploring the possibility of using nacre as armour because it is so resistant and light.  These simple sea shells contain interesting properties upon inspection!
        FEEDBACK: Never finish an academic essay with an exclamation mark. Indeed, never use an exclamation mark in an academic essay.  Though exclamation marks now litter people's writing, they do have a very particular use:  they should follow an exclamation like Stop! or Danger!  The exclamation mark alone means that this is not the best option on offer.
        ANSWER: As has been demonstrated, molluscs are able to biomineralize a tough exterior as a protection mechanism.  The shell consists of an outer prismatic calcite layer and an inner aragonitic nacreous layer.  Both layers are composed of CaCO3 but exist as polymorphs of each other.  The nacreous layer, being one of the hardest substances known, is associated with osteogenic studies and thus has major implications for medicine and even for the arms industry.  The sea shell may be a familiar sight but all its hidden complexities have not yet been fully explored.
        FEEDBACK: This conclusion refers back to the essay title, and neatly summarises what we should remember.  The ending is satisfactory and clear.  I think this is the best option on offer here.
        ANSWER: In conclusion, as Lowenstam and Weiner remind us, 'biomineralisation refers to the process by which organisms form minerals ... when organisms evolved the ability to form mineralised hard parts, they provided themselves with a major adaptional advantage.' 10
        FEEDBACK: Ending your essay with a quote is not wrong, but be careful.  This quotation would fit much better at the start of the essay.  A quote at the end of your essay needs to wrap up your conclusions, not give a definition of the title.  This is not the best option on offer here.
    Writing activity 12. Using chemistry words and terms correctly
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO  <font size="4">Can you pick out the correct everyday definition of this word and the correct chemistry definition of this word? More than one definition may be correct.<br /><br />The word is:<br /><br />solvent</font><br /> 
    QUESTION 0 First, which is the everyday definition?
        ANSWER: Having money.
        FEEDBACK: Yes.  That's one definition.  People say 'the firm is solvent' if the firm retains more money than it owes.
        ANSWER: A problem that can be solved.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not right.
        ANSWER: A container of glue.
        FEEDBACK: Yes.  We talk about 'solvent abuse' when people sniff glue.
        ANSWER: A trouble-shooter.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not right.
    QUESTION 1 Secondly, which is the correct chemical definition?
        ANSWER: Glue.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not right.
        ANSWER: A compound solution that dissolves away into nothing.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not right.
        ANSWER: The component of a solution that's present in the greatest amount.  The substance in which the solute is dissolved, e.g. the solvent for air is nitrogen.
        FEEDBACK: That's correct.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO  <font size="4">Can you pick out the correct everyday definition of 'spin', and the correct chemistry definition of 'spin'?</font><br /> 
    QUESTION 0 
        ANSWER: A type of washing machine.
        FEEDBACK: It's the cycle on a washing machine, but not a washing machine itself.
        ANSWER: To travel round and round very fast.
        FEEDBACK: Yes, that's one everyday meaning.
        ANSWER: The intrinsic property of a particle relating to its angular momentum.
        FEEDBACK: Well done.  That's the right chemical definition.
        ANSWER: When chemicals get mixed up together and produce a different chemical.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not right.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">Can you pick out the correct everyday definition of 'group' and the correct chemistry definition of 'group'?</font> 
    QUESTION 0 First, pick out the everyday definition.
        ANSWER: People who follow a particular band or celebrity.
        FEEDBACK: No, these are usually called 'groupies' in a slightly disparaging manner.
        ANSWER: A collection of people or things.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.
    QUESTION 1 Now pick out the correct chemistry definition.
        ANSWER: A collection of chemicals.
        FEEDBACK: That's not a precise enough definition.  Try again.
        ANSWER: A vertical column in the periodic table.
        FEEDBACK: Well done.  That's the precise meaning.
        ANSWER: Chemicals that have characteristics in common.
        FEEDBACK: This is not precise enough.  Try again.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">Can you pick out the correct everyday definition, then the correct chemistry definition, of the following word:<br /><br />conjugate<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 First, the everyday definition:
        ANSWER: To recite poetry.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not right.
        ANSWER: To recite a verb in all its forms and distinctions.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  Conjugating verbs used to be a popular school task.  I go, you go, she goes etc.
        ANSWER: To multiply.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  To conjugate is to join together but nobody is going to say 'go forth and conjugate' ...
    QUESTION 1 Now, the chemistry definition:
        ANSWER: Relating to an acid and a base that are related by the difference of a proton.
        FEEDBACK: Yes, but there's more ... 
        ANSWER: Relating to acids and bases.
        FEEDBACK: That's not precise enough.
        ANSWER: Relating to a compound formed by joining two or more chemical compounds, or an acid and a base that differ from each other by a proton.
        FEEDBACK: Well done.  That's precise and comprehensive.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO  <font size="4">Can you pick out the correct everyday definition of this word and the correct chemistry definition of this word? <br /><br />accuracy<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 First, the everyday definition:
        ANSWER: Something that's correct.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.
        ANSWER: Something that's repeated exactly.
        FEEDBACK: Not quite.  Try again.
        ANSWER: An exact copy.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not right.  Try again.
    QUESTION 1 Now see if you can pick out the correct chemistry definition.
        ANSWER: A precise measurement.
        FEEDBACK: That answer is not precise enough.  Try again.
        ANSWER: Something determined by comparing a measurement against the true or accepted value.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  That's the precise definition.
        ANSWER: The standard by which measurements are deemed correct.
        FEEDBACK: This doesn't really make sense.  How can accuracy be a standard, since it is a concept?  Try again.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
