        ANSWER: A small furry animal that throws up irritating hills in people's gardens.
        FEEDBACK: Well done.  That's correct.
        ANSWER: A patch of darkly pigmented skin, sometimes raised and sometimes dangerous.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  Can you spot the other meanings, too?
    QUESTION 1 Can you pick out the chemistry definition?
        ANSWER: A quick way of saying 'molecule'.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not right.
        ANSWER: A chemical mass unit, defined to be 6.022 x 1023 molecules, atoms or another unit.  
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  Chemical definitions are very precise.
        ANSWER: A chemical that has intruded into another chemical's composition.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not right.  Try again.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO  <font size="4">Can you pick out the correct everyday definition of this word and the correct chemistry definition of this word? <br /><br />potential<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 First, the everyday definition:
        ANSWER: Showing you are good at something.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not quite the meaning.  Try again.
        ANSWER: Showing that you were good at something.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not the meaning either.
        ANSWER: Showing that you possess the capacity to be good at something.
        FEEDBACK: Yes, that's the right definition.
    QUESTION 1 Which is the correct chemistry definition?
        ANSWER: Manifest energy.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not right.  Try again.
        ANSWER: Energy waiting to be released.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not precise enough.
        ANSWER: Energy which could be converted into other forms of energy.
        FEEDBACK: Yes, that's precise.  Potential energy is also the energy something has because of its position.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO  <font size="4">Can you pick out the correct everyday definition of this word and the correct chemistry definition of this word? More than one definition may be correct.<br /><br />strain<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 First, the everyday definition:
        ANSWER: Stretching a limb.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not correct.  There's a difference between a stretch and a strain.  A stretch is natural;  a strain is an injury.
        ANSWER: Shouting loudly.
        FEEDBACK: You might strain your voice if you shout loudly, but the act of shouting doesn't automatically involve straining.
        ANSWER: Forcing something, often a part of the body, beyond its natural boundary.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.
    QUESTION 1 Now pick out the chemistry definition:
        ANSWER: The chemical stress of a molecule.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  Some dictionaries add that 'the effects of a strain on a compound can be measured using dynamic mechanical analysis'.  This makes the definition precise and comprehensive.
        ANSWER: Refers to when an acid is forced to mix with an alkaline.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not correct.  Try again.
        ANSWER: Refers to when a compound is separated into its constituent parts.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not right.  Try again.
    Writing activity 16. Reliable and unreliable sources
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">Which of these sources is reliable?</font> 
    QUESTION 0 
        ANSWER: Dalton Transactions
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  This is a peer reviewed journal, available from the Royal Society of Chemistry (RSC) website.
        ANSWER: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biomineralization
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Wikipedia might be right, it might be wrong.  Nobody checks.   Don't use it.
        ANSWER: A. D. Mount, PhD Thesis, Imperial College London (UCL), 1977
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  A PhD thesis passed by UCL will have certainly been reviewed by experts.  
        ANSWER: A. R. Jones, Angew. Chem., submitted
        FEEDBACK: This source has obviously not yet been passed by reviewers.  You may be able to use it if you acknowledge the fact that it has not yet passed the reviewers.  This could happen if it is reporting on pioneering research, not yet in the public domain.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Which of these sources is unreliable?</font> 
    QUESTION 0 
        ANSWER: http://www.gla.ac.uk/news/headline_191289_en.html
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  This is a link to a press release, drawing attention to a study.  The study itself may well be reliable but a press release should never be taken as evidence for an academic essay, since press releases are usually partial and seldom written by experts in the field.
        ANSWER: Radioisotope Data, UKAEA Reseach Group Report
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  This report, published by the UK Atomic Energy Authority, will be reliable.  Make sure you reference it correctly.
        ANSWER: internationalchemistrysolutions@google.com
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  Who knows who's behind such a website?
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">Which of these sources is reliable?</font> 
    QUESTION 0 
        ANSWER: www.bbc.co.uk/news/
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  I don't think any news channel is reliable, particularly when it comes to science.  News is written by journalists, not academics.
        ANSWER: Catalyst Deactivation, edited by Delmon and Froment, published in 1987
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  This will be reliable, but you need to take care since some of the findings may be out of date.  If you're quoting historic data, though, this book will be reliable.
        ANSWER: A Child's Chemistry Encyclopaedia
        FEEDBACK: This is an interesting one.  It probably is reasonably reliable, but everything will be in very simple form.  In any event, it would not look good in a list of citations for an academic essay.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Which of these sources is unreliable?</font> 
    QUESTION 0 
        ANSWER: http://alzheimers.org.uk
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  It may seem strange, but in most respects, this source would not be reliable enough for an academic essay.  Some information may be usable, for example the number of people affected by the disease in the UK.  However, organisations are often lobbying for something, so their information is written to solicit a specific reaction - perhaps money.  Academics need objective sources.
        ANSWER: A. S. Reber, Dictionary of Psychology, second edition, 1995
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  A published dictionary will be reliable.  However, some of the information may be out of date.  
        ANSWER: E. Tobinick, TNF-alpha Modulation for Treatment of Alzheimer's disease: a 6-month pilot study, MedGenMed
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  This is a reliable source.  Just because a study is a pilot, it doesn't make the information unreliable.  If you look up MedGenMed, you'll see it's a peer reviewed journal.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Which of these sources is reliable?</font> 
    QUESTION 0 
        ANSWER: Journal of Catalysis
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  This is a specialist journal and is peer reviewed.
        ANSWER: D. L. Trimm, Control of Coking, in Chemical Engineering Process
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  This journal is peer reviewed.
        ANSWER: http://www.platinum.matthey.com/media-room/events/international-symposium-on-catalyst-deactivation-delft-the-netherlands/
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  This is a discussion forum and I'd be concerned that information might not be reliable enough for inclusion in an academic essay of the kind that you are writing.  If you're unsure about sources like this, ask your tutor.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
