    Writing activity 02. Punctuation - colons and semi-colons
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <ol> 
  <li><font size="4">The main characters, however; the ones that reflect on Aeneas's character are not numerous.</font></li> 
  <li><font size="4">The main characters, however, the ones that reflect on Aeneas's character; are not numerous.</font></li> 
  <li><font size="4">The main characters, however, the ones that reflect on Aeneas's character, are not numerous.</font></li> 
</ol> 
    QUESTION 0 Which sentence is correctly punctuated?
        ANSWER: Sentence 1.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again.
        ANSWER: Sentence 2.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again.
        ANSWER: Sentence 3.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  Semi-colons link two complete sentences.  In neither sentence 1 nor sentence 2 is this the case.  You cannot make two complete sentences out of this text. This should tell you that a semi-colon has no place in this sentence.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">Equally: Juno is a strong, commanding presence: she was considered the matron goddess of Rome.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 Which of the colons is out of place here?
        ANSWER: The first colon.
        FEEDBACK: I agree. These types of words (adverbs) - equally, however, moreover, nonetheless, etc. - do not need colons.  Colons make the pause much too pronounced.  A comma is correct.  'Equally, Juno ...'  The second colon is fine, since the information that follows it expands on what comes before,
        ANSWER: The second colon.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  The first colon is out of place.  These kinds of words (adverbs) - equally, however, moreover, nonetheless, etc. - do not need colons.  Colons make the pause much too pronounced.  A comma is correct.  'Equally, Juno ...'  The second colon is fine, since the information that follows it expands on what comes before,
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task freetext difficulty 2
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO  <font size="4">Another aspect of Aristotle's work was his handling of the concept of time - he did not see time as something separate and distinct from 'temporal events' (citation needed).<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 What could we put in place of the dash?
        ANSWER: A comma.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  A comma allows the sentence to run on even though there are two distinct thoughts.  
        ANSWER: A semi-colon.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  A semi-colon would separate these two closely connected sentences very nicely.
        ANSWER: A colon.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  Sometimes semi-colons and colons are just a matter of taste.  You could certainly argue that the second part of the sentence expands on the first, and therefore that a colon was best.
    QUESTION 1 Are dashes ever appropriate?
        ANSWER: Sometimes.
        FEEDBACK: Sometimes dashes are appropriate.  They indicate an aside, i.e. something important - perhaps a reminder - inserted into the text, just as you might insert something into the conversation.
        ANSWER: Never.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Dashes are sometimes useful.   They indicate an aside, i.e. something important - perhaps a reminder - inserted into the text, just as you might insert something into the conversation.
