    Writing activity 05. Italics
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">Written in the last ten years of his life, the <span style="font-style: italic;">Aeneid</span> tackles a variety of controversial themes, with Aeneas as the hero of the<span style="font-style: italic;"> epic</span>.<br /><br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Are italics correctly used in this text? 
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  'Aeneid' is correctly italicised, as it is the name of a book.  'Epic' should not be italicised as it is being used as a common noun.  
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK:  I agree. 'Aeneid' is correctly italicised, as it is the name of a book.  'Epic' should not be italicised as it is being used as a common noun.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">Sophocles's <span style="font-style: italic;">Antigone</span>, though the third of his three <span style="font-style: italic;">Theban </span>plays, was written first. <span style="font-style: italic;">Antigone's</span> death, and the deaths at their own hands of King Creon's son and wife, is a tale of wisdom through punishment.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 Is the italicisation of Antigone correct?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: You're half right.  The first 'Antigone' is correctly italicised, since this is the name of the play.  The second 'Antigone' should not be italicised as here it is the heroine's name, and names are not italicised.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: You're half right. The first 'Antigone' is correctly italicised, since this is the name of the play.  The second 'Antigone' should not be italicised as here it is the heroine's name, and names are not italicised.
        ANSWER: One is right and one is wrong.
        FEEDBACK: That's correct.  The first 'Antigone' is correctly italicised, since this is the name of the play.  The second 'Antigone' should not be italicised as here it is the heroine's name, and names are not italicised.
    QUESTION 1 Is 'Theban' correctly italicised?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  'Theban' is being used as an adjective.  It is not part of a play's name, so it does not need to be italicised.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: That's correct.    'Theban' is being used as an adjective.  It's not part of a play's name, so does not need to be italicised.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">In Book Six, Ovid points to the similarities between his Fasti and Hesiod's Works and Days. He also makes reference to Virgil's Aeneid but again stresses the differences.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 What should be italicised in these lines?
        ANSWER: Book Six
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  We don't italicise book numbers.
        ANSWER: Ovid, Hesiod and Virgil
        FEEDBACK: No, we don't italicise names.
        ANSWER: Fasti, Works and Days, Aeneid
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  The names of books are always italicised, whether in the text or in the bibliography.
        Task wordclick difficulty 1
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Cicero issued a senatus consultum ultimum, (<span style="font-style: italic;">final decree of the senate</span>), a decree passed in times of emergency. Some argued that the consultum could not override the basic laws of the Roman state, but that it gave consuls power to do their utmost <span style="font-style: italic;">within the framework of the Roman constitution</span> to resolve the situation. </font> 
    QUESTION 0 Should (final decree of the senate) be italicised?
        ANSWER: Yes.  A translation needs to be italicised.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  Translations don't need to be italicised.  
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  Translations shouldn't be italicised.
    QUESTION 1 Should senatus consultum ultimum be italicised?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  All words in languages other than English or Greek should be italicised unless they have passed into our language and are used familiarly, e.g. senate, senator, forum etc. (Senatus, in this example, is in Latin not English form).
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  All words in languages other than English or Greek should be italicised unless they have passed into our language and are used familiarly, e.g. senate, senator, forum etc.  (Senatus, in this example, is in Latin not English form).
    QUESTION 2 There's another word that should be italicised.  What is it?
        ANSWER: emergency.
        FEEDBACK: No - that's a perfectly ordinary English word.
        ANSWER: consuls
        FEEDBACK: No.  This word has passed into common usage, so, like senator, should not be italicised.
        ANSWER: consultum
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  This word is Latin, so should be italicised.
    QUESTION 3 Should 'within the framework' etc. be italicised?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  In some circumstances, for example if you had been writing of a constitutional debate, you might italicise 'within the framework' etc. for emphasis.  In this context, however, it should not be italicised.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: In some circumstances, for example if you had been writing of a constitutional debate, you might italicise 'within the framework' etc. for emphasis.  In this context, however, it should not be italicised.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
