        ANSWER: Dinner at Tremalchio's.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  The Fasti is the title of a book, and needs italicising.  'Dinner at Tremalchio's' is the title of a chapter in a book and should be placed in inverted commas.
    Writing activity 07. Opening lines
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title:<br /><br />How does either Ovid in the <span style="font-style: italic;">Fasti</span> or Petronius in 'Dinner at Tremalchio's' use different literary traditions to create a new kind of work relevant to contemporary Rome?<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Which are the best opening lines?
        ANSWER: Ovid's Fasti is a truly unique work of its time.  He uses different literary traditions to make the work relevant to the world in which it was written. 
        FEEDBACK: These lines tell us virtually nothing.  Best to start your essay with a bang rather than a whimper.
        ANSWER: Ovid was a Roman poet who wrote a number of works, the best known of which is his Metamorphoses.  Petronius was a Roman courtier, living at the time of the Emperor Nero.  
        FEEDBACK: These lines are informative, but rather simplistic.  An academic essay should not just list information, but should try and seize the question right from the first line.  The essay question should always be the direct focus of the text.
        ANSWER: Ovid's Fasti and Petronius's 'Dinner at Tremalchio's' were written for different reasons:  the Fasti to complain, and 'Dinner at Tremalchio's' to entertain.  Neither complaints nor entertainment were novel in themselves, but unexpected content and use of metre offered something new to contemporary Rome, and both writers will have been aware of the novelty.
        FEEDBACK: This is an interesting start, which shows that the writer is actively engaging with the question.  We learn facts, but the facts are embedded into the question, adding weight, not just words, to the essay.  This is the best option.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Essay question:<br /><br />Why did Virgil choose the Aeneas legend as the principle subject of his epic?<br /><br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Choose the best opening line(s) for this essay title.
        ANSWER: Publius Virgilius Maro was the son of a farmer and believed to have been educated at home, then in Cremona, Milan and Rome, where he studied rhetoric, medicine and astronomy.
        FEEDBACK: Biographical details might be included to underpin an argument, but to list them like this has no value in an essay.   Not a good choice.
        ANSWER: 'Divine Aeneas' (Aeneid, p.640) , the hero of the Aeneid legend, possessed all the qualities deemed heroic in a Roman citizen when Virgil, perhaps Rome's greatest poet, was writing.
        FEEDBACK: This is a very good start.  It gets to grip with the essay question at once, and in a sophisticated way.  Beginning with a short quotation (properly attributed) adds weight to an opening line.
        ANSWER: Virgil chose the Aeneid legend as the principle subject of his epic because the Aeneid legend incorporated many ideas and stories that would be very useful to make the points Virgil wanted to make.
        FEEDBACK: This opening line is very uninspiring.  Instead of telling the reader that there are ideas and stories, why not cut straight to the chase and open with one of these stories or ideas, then showing why this story or idea was important to Virgil?  Too many essays don't really get going until page 2.  An essay with this opening line might well turn into one of those.  Not the best option.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title:<br /><br />What were the causes of the Catilinarian conspiracy? How good are Cicero's Catilinarian speeches and Sallust's <span style="font-style: italic;">Catiline</span> as evidence for it?<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Read the essay title and the opening lines. Which opening line is the best option? All the choices have explanations, so even if your first choice agrees with ours, it's worth clicking on all the options.</font> 
        ANSWER: When talking about the time of the Catilinarian conspiracy, we are looking at an important part of the decline and fall of the Roman Republic.
        FEEDBACK: This opening line makes far too general a point, in far too wordy a manner.  Your opening line must grasp the essay topic, not tiptoe around it.  A strong opening line gives the reader confidence.  Take some trouble over it. 
        ANSWER: Though Cicero's speeches against Catiline contain some of his most famous utterances - O tempora!  O mores - and Sallust's account of what is known as the Catiline conspiracy is gripping and colourful, as hard evidence for the causes of the conspiracy both are highly questionable. 
        FEEDBACK: I like this option.  We get straight into the texts with a neat use of quotation and description, and the question is directly addressed.  I think this is the best option.
        ANSWER: The invasion of Italy had resulted in civil war and after Caesar defeated Pompey, he made himself dictator for life.  Cicero re-established the senate and Octavian (later Augustus) took control of the armies.
        FEEDBACK: This opening line falls into the 'I'm going to tell you all I know about ancient Rome' category.  You must grasp the essay question from the first line to the last.  This is a very poor option.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO Essay title:<br /><br />Was Greek tragedy leading or following political debate in Athens?<br /> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Read the essay title and the opening lines. Which opening lines are the best option? All the choices have explanations, so even if your first choice agrees with ours, it's worth clicking on all the options.</font> 
        ANSWER: Tragedy is a 'form of art based on human suffering' (Wikipedia, 2010).
        FEEDBACK: A quotation often adds weight and punch to an opening line, but a quotation from Wikipedia is too unreliable and idle to achieve either of these benefits.  Don't use Wikipedia in academic essays.  There are plenty of reliable books in the library.  Not a good option.
        ANSWER: In form, Greek tragedy arose from 'a choral song in honour of Dionysus'.  The content, however, was less concerned with honour than with recounting 'terrible things about great people' (Leech 1969: 13-14).  It is in judging how far these 'terrible things' had wider significance than the immediate story that the answer to the essay question can be found.
        FEEDBACK: This is a thoughtful and interesting with a good use of quotation.  The reader would have confidence in an opening like this because the writer seems to know where he/she is going.  I'd say this was the best option.
        ANSWER: In Book V of the Poetics, Aristotle tells us that 'tragedy endeavours to keep as far as possible within a single circuit of the sun, or something near that'.  When trying to discover whether Greek tragedy led or followed political debate in Athens, Aristotle cannot be ignored.
        FEEDBACK: This is an odd option, since the quotation appears to have nothing to do with the question.  If you use a quotation that doesn't immediately appear relevant, you must link it up with the essay question.  If you cannot, then you need to find a different quotation.  This is not a good option.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO Essay title:<br /><br />How successfully did the Athenian empire use public space in Athens to create and promote political identity?<br /> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Read the essay title and the opening lines. Which opening lines are the best option? All the choices have explanations, so even if your first choice agrees with ours, it's worth clicking on all the options.</font> 
        ANSWER: The Athenian empire was very effective in using public space in Athens to create and promote political identity.
        FEEDBACK: Just repeating the terms of the question without adding anything is a very dull and uninspiring start to an essay.  If you find yourself doing this, go back to the opening line when you've finished your essay and see if you can improve it.  This is not a good option.
        ANSWER: All the evidence from existing records, both written and built, shows that public space in Athens was considered an important tool in the political armoury.
        FEEDBACK: This is a strong opening statement, which bodes well for the rest of the essay.  This is the best option.
        ANSWER: The Athenian Agora was an important space in which people could openly converse and debate.
        FEEDBACK: Presented with this, a reader might turn the page back to see if he or she had missed something.  This line has a place in the essay, but not right at the start.  You need to set the scene, even if in one brief sentence.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">Were the Augustan poets politically motivated to support Augustus' leadership, and in what way does their work reflect their views of Augustus?</font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Read the essay title and the opening lines. Which opening lines are the best option? All the choices have explanations, so even if your first choice agrees with ours, it's worth clicking on all the options.</font> 
        ANSWER: To be a poet in the age of Augustus was to be a public figure, and in imperial Rome, public figures walked a political tightrope that could, according to the whim of the emperor, end in glory or ignominy.
        FEEDBACK: This first line provides an excellent opening: it sets the scene without wasting any words.  I think this is the best choice.
        ANSWER: Augustus gained supreme authority in Rome and control of what was to become the Roman Empire after defeating Marc Antony at Actium in 31BC.
        FEEDBACK: This is true, but you should use your first line to grasp the essay question, not just to recite a list of facts.  This is a dull option.
        ANSWER: Horace, Ovid and Virgil were all poets in the age of Augustus and this essay will use their lives and works to assess whether Augustan poets were politically motivated to support Augustus's leadership and whether their work reflects their views of Augustus.
        FEEDBACK: It's good to refer to the terms of the essay question, but it's much less good simply to repeat them.  This opening line gives an impression of slightly desperate padding out before we've even got going.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO  <font size="4">Essay question:<br /><br />Discuss the differing portrayals of masculinity and femininity in Virgil's <span style="font-style: italic;">Aeneid</span>.<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Read the essay title and the opening lines. Which opening lines are the best option? All the choices have explanations, so even if your first choice agrees with ours, it's worth clicking on all the options.</font> 
        ANSWER: The portrayal of masculinity and femininity in Virgil's Aeneid is a portrayal not of stereotypes but of power.   
        FEEDBACK: This opening line makes a bold statement.  The final part of the sentence opens up a discussion.  An excellent start to an essay. 
        ANSWER: In Virgil's Aeneid, masculinity and femininity are portrayed in different ways.
        FEEDBACK: This opening line is a statement of the obvious.  If you took it out of the essay, nothing would be lost.  It is not a good option.
        ANSWER: The Aeneid was written at a time when the roles of men and women are seen differently from the roles of men and women today.
        FEEDBACK: This opening line threatens to send the essay down the wrong path.  The essay question asks about the portrayal of masculinity and femininity, not the roles of men and women.  Be careful to stick to the question asked.  The rephrasing means that this option is not a good one.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Essay question:<br /><br />To what extent does Aeschylus's <span style="font-style: italic;">Oresteia</span> depict the Homeric image of revenge?<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Read the essay title and the opening lines. Which opening lines are the best option? All the choices have explanations, so even if your first choice agrees with ours, it's worth clicking on all the options.</font> 
        ANSWER: Revenge is a dish best served cold, so we are told, but the ancient Greeks served it hot, cold and every temperature in between.
        FEEDBACK: I can see what the writer is trying to do here: inject life into the essay.  But I'm not sure it quite works.  You can only really use this type of opening when you're established as an expert.  This opening is not wrong, but I'd say it sets a lighter tone than might be advisable.
        ANSWER: Homer probably lived in the eighth century BC.  He wrote both the Illiad and the Odyssey, which are thought to be the first epic poems.
        FEEDBACK: You need to grasp the question, rather than just present historical facts.  This is not a particularly good option.
        ANSWER: Beginning with Homer, revenge is a popular theme in much ancient Greek literature and in his Oresteia, Aeschylus, like many others, mines this rich seam.
        FEEDBACK: This opening line sets the scene succinctly.  I think this is the best option.
    Writing activity 09. Concluding lines
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title:<br /><br />What were the Spartan war aims in Asia Minor from 399 to 394 B.C. and how effectively were they achieved?<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Which is the best concluding line for this essay?
        ANSWER: How effective were the Spartans in achieving their war aims between 399 and 394 B.C.?  Not very because their efforts were doomed before they began, so in the end, Sparta did not effectively achieve her objectives.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  It is not good practice simply to repeat the essay question as a question.  You certainly need to refer to the terms of the question, but putting them into context, using themes from your essay.  Your reader needs to feel a sense of a question properly worked through and answered.  This example leaves the reader feeling flat. 
        ANSWER: In their aim to unit Greece under Spartan leadership, the Spartans were unsuccessful, and even the taking of the Asia Minor Greeks' cities from Persia was undermined by an inability to defeat the Persians in open battle.  Yet the Spartans were never defeated themselves, and at Sardis, though indirectly, they removed Tissaphernes,  On balance, however, the results are too far removed from the objectives to say that the Spartans were successful, and certainly this has been the judgment of history. 
        FEEDBACK: These concluding lines successfully refer to themes that will have been included in the essay, and leave the reader satisfied that the question has been examined and answered.  This is the best option.
        ANSWER: Though the Spartans had some successes, for example they removed Tissphernes and successfully garrisoned towns they took from the Persians, they also failed to deliver a knock-out blow to their enemies.  Yet since they did not wholly fail in their objectives, we cannot say they were not effective at all.
        FEEDBACK: These lines refer back to the essay title, and to some of the essay's themes.  However, they are too colloquial:  the term 'knock out blow' is too informal for an academic essay, and the subjective 'we' adds to the informal tone.  In addition, the writer gives a weak final answer to the question.  Be brave!
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title:<br /><br />What were the causes of the Catilinarian conspiracy? How good are Cicero's Catalinarian speeches and Sallust's <span style="font-style: italic;">Catiline</span> as evidence for it?<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">Read the essay title and the concluding lines. Which concluding lines are the best option? All the choices have explanations, so even if your first choice agrees with ours, it's worth clicking on all the options.</font> 
        ANSWER: Knowing this, it is still hard to know how good these two sources are for evidence of a conspiracy.  With the help of a third party source we could possibly see if the speculation was enough to go on with some real fact and actions or whether it was just suspicion at a time of distress in Rome.
        FEEDBACK: This is a poor option, not because the conclusion drawn is a bad one - it's not - but the phrasing is clumsy and trips the reader up.  Remember that how you write is as important as what you write.
        ANSWER: These sources certainly provide some evidence.  However, as this essay has shown, Cicero's speeches tell us more about Cicero than the conspiracy, and Sallust is constrained both by the shadow of his patron and his own moral outrage.  Yet neither work should be discounted in the search for evidence of the Catiline conspiracy; both works contain a great deal of information.  That information must simply be processed not as evidence, but as a partial part of the picture.
        FEEDBACK: I like this option.  It refers directly to the essay question and the texts under discussion, and finally draws a logical conclusion.  The best option of these three.
        ANSWER: The causes of the Catilinarian conspiracy are so bound up with personal grudge and egos that they are impossible to discern, so we have as little evidence for it now as they did at the time.
        FEEDBACK: This is a little abrupt and, though what the writer writes is true, the tone of these lines leave the reader feeling flat.  Try and finish your essay with a flourish.  Even a poor essay can often be redeemed, at least slightly, by a good last line.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title:<br /><br />Was Greek tragedy leading or following political debate in Athens?<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">Read the essay title and the concluding lines. Which concluding lines are the best option? All the choices have explanations, so even if your first choice agrees with ours, it's worth clicking on all the options.</font> 
        ANSWER: As this essay has shown, the essence of Greek tragedy is the conflict between political (and paternal) authority on the one hand, and personal obligation on the other.  In the plays cited here, these are too deeply intertwined to provide evidence as to whether Greek tragedy led or followed political debate in Athens.  That they both reflected and informed debate, however, is indisputable and, for modern readers, is part of their drama. 
        FEEDBACK: This option uses the terms of the question to draw the essay to an excellent close.  Of the options available, I think this is the best.
        ANSWER: Was Greek tragedy leading or following political debate in Athens?  The evidence seems to show that it neither led nor followed, but was just part of the debate. 
        FEEDBACK: Simply repeating the terms of the question can sometimes work, but often makes the end of an essay very flat.  You want to keep your reader's interest right to the end.  This ending is a bit of a damp squib.  Not the best option.
        ANSWER: Antigone's personal fate is a real expression of Creon's political theory and the play may well have provoked the Athenian citizenry to question what happens when the state meets the personal and neither will give way.
        FEEDBACK: There is nothing wrong with this sentence, except it doesn't feel like a concluding line. Concluding lines must draw together all the strands of your essay and not simply come to a halt.  This line feels very abrupt.  I don't think this is the best option.
