INTRO <font size="4">Essay title:<br /><br />To what extent does Aeschylus's <span style="font-style: italic;">Oresteia</span> depict the Homeric image of revenge?<br /><br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">Read the essay title and the concluding lines. Which concluding lines are the best option? All the choices have explanations, so even if your first choice agrees with ours, it's worth clicking on all the options.</font> 
        ANSWER: Thus it can be argued that If 'what is new and innovative must be built on the foundations of inherited tradition' (Euben, 1982: 27), then Aeschylus's Oresteia is not a depiction of the Homeric image of revenge, but a development from it.
        FEEDBACK: This is a clear answer to the question, with a very well chosen quote to give that final punch.  I think this is the best option.
        ANSWER: I have shown that Aeschylus's Oresteia depicts the Homeric image of revenge to a very great extent and even develops it.
        FEEDBACK: The sentiments expressed in this concluding line are the same as in the first option, but not nearly so well expressed.  You need to craft your concluding lines so that your reader feels a sense of closure and satisfaction.  This concluding line is very flat, so it's not the best option here.
        ANSWER: What is revenge, except, as they say, 'a dish best served cold'?  We all, not just Aeschylus, owe a huge debt to Homer, because without Homer we would never have had Shakespeare!
        FEEDBACK: This may be true, and it is always tempting to end an essay with a broad, rhetorical flourish.  But few of us are Homer, and broad, rhetorical flourishes, particularly those ending in an exclamation mark, often make the reader wince.  For this reason, I don't like this option.
