INTRO <font size="4">Essay title:<br /><br />How effectively did the Athenian empire use public space in Athens to create and promote political identity?<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">Read the essay title and the concluding lines. Which concluding lines are the best option? All the choices have explanations, so even if your first choice agrees with ours, it's worth clicking on all the options.</font> 
        ANSWER: The statues of Athena spread across the Acropolis only enhanced its political identity as well as paying tribute to the gods.  Furthermore, the Athenians used the Pynx Hill to promote their political ideology to the Athenian people.
        FEEDBACK: The ideas behind these concluding lines may be sound, but they fit into the argument of an essay, not the conclusion.  Be careful that a reader doesn't end up feeling that a page has been missed out at the end.  This is not a good option.
        ANSWER: As this essay has shown, in the ancient world, the public spaces in cities often played key roles in the promotion of political identity.  In this, Athens was no exception.  However, the real success of the Athenian empire's use of Athens' public spaces was in fostering loyalty to the city and the empire in the common man for it was on the attitude of common man that the fate of the empire ultimately depended. 
        FEEDBACK: These lines refer back to the essay question but add something more, bringing this essay to a definite and pleasing halt.  The best option, I think.
        ANSWER: Athens' political identity was effectively increased through its monumentality, as all the new buildings gave a wealthy and powerful perception.
