        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title:<br /><br />'Greek tragedy is the drama of speech, not action.' Do you agree?</font><br /> 
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">Read the essay title and the concluding lines. Which concluding lines are the best option? All the choices have explanations, so even if your first choice agrees with ours, it's worth clicking on all the options.</font> 
        ANSWER: Any discussion about the primacy of speech over action in Greek tragedy hinges on a definition of action.  In many cases - Oedipus and Ajax, for example - this essay has shown that speech and action are different articulations of the same emotion, and that one loses power without the other.  Nevertheless, it is the words that remain with us, and their power, without actor or stage, proves that though Greek tragedy is, at base, a drama of speech.   
        FEEDBACK: These concluding lines have a good ring to them and don't beat about the bush.  Topics from the essay are drawn in and we finish with a proper answer to the essay question.  The best option here.
        ANSWER: In conclusion, the fact that speech seems to vitally important in the decision-making of characters, and in the act of providing the tragic elements of the tragedies, it can be said that tragedy is the drama of speech not of action.  Action seems to be used as a final shock, as in the case of Oedipus or Agamemnon where Clytemnestra proudly displays the bodies of her husband and Cassandra, whilst it is words and speech that provide the real, thought-provoking drama.
        FEEDBACK: The thoughts in these concluding lines are fine, but the first sentence is hard to follow.  Clarity is vital all the way through an essay, but to leave a good impression, it's very important not to slip up at the last moment.  The way these concluding lines are written means they are not a good choice.
        ANSWER: Staging events in plays, for example the earthquake in The Bacchae, was difficult, so it is unsurprising that Greek tragedy was the drama of speech rather than action.
        FEEDBACK: This concluding line seems very trite: the essay question was clearly about more than staging events.  Not a good option.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title:<br /><br />Were the Augustan poets politically motivated to support Augustus's leadership? In what way does their work reflect their views of Augustus?<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">Read the essay title and the concluding lines. Which concluding lines are the best option? All the choices have explanations, so even if your first choice agrees with ours, it's worth clicking on all the options.</font> 
        ANSWER: Augustus died in on 19th August AD14 and was succeeded by his stepson, Tiberius, who had also been his son-in-law and his adopted son.
        FEEDBACK: This concluding line bears no relation to the essay question.  Not a good option.
        ANSWER: Whatever the motives of the poets who wrote for him and about him, Augustus seems to have appreciated much of the poetry for its own sake, and though some of the poets' views of their emperor were not always completely adulatory, the emperor seems usually to have appreciated their efforts.
        FEEDBACK: This option focuses on Augustus rather than the poets, and it's the poets who should be centre stage.  Not a bad option, but not the best of the choices on offer.
        ANSWER: In conclusion, whether Augustus was Tacitus's bully or Suetonius's kindlier figure, the Augustan poets, Ovid in particular, seemed to be driven more by the demands of their poetry than of their emperor.   None of the poets discussed in this essay are cyphers, yet all seem to have been aware, as Horace so memorably said, that 'he gains everyone's approval who mixes the pleasant with the useful' (QuotationsBook, website 1).
        FEEDBACK: This is light and breezy, but still draws the essay to a neat close.  Of the options here, I think this is the best.
