    Writing activity 16. Referencing within your text
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">The Agora changed dramatically during the 5th century. <br /><br /><span style="font-style: italic;">&quot;Generally more modest in their building materials, made of limestone and mud brick as opposed to marble, with simple floors of packed earth, these buildings nonetheless demonstrate the extent of Athenian resources and energy while engaged in a major war.&quot; <span style="text-decoration: underline;"><sup>1</sup></span></span><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><br /><br /></span></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Should this quotation be italicised?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  Quotations should never be italicised unless they are in italics in the original text, in which case you should indicate this by writing [sic] (Latin for 'thus').  This shows that you have presented the quote as written in the original.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: That's right. Quotations should never be italicised unless they are in italics in the original text, in which case you should indicate this by writing [sic] (Latin for 'thus').  This shows that you have presented the quote as written in the original.
        ANSWER: It doesn't matter.
        FEEDBACK: I'm afraid it does matter.  Learning to format references correctly is an important academic discipline.  After university, you'll be required to write things in prescribed formats, so it's as well to get into the habit now.
    QUESTION 1 Is this quotation suitable for a Classics essay?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Quotations from secondary sources are supposed to reinforce your argument, not make your argument for you.  They should be limited to a word or a phrase.  Quotations from primary sources, e.g. from Virgil, Homer or other classical authors, can be longer.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  Quotations from secondary sources are supposed to reinforce your argument, not make your argument for you.  They should be limited to a word or a phrase.   Quotations from primary sources, e.g. from Virgil, Homer or other classical authors, can be longer.
    QUESTION 2 Should the superscript 1, which indicates a footnote, correctly placed and formatted?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: It is correctly placed:  footnote numbers come after the final full stop of a sentence.  It is not correctly formatted:  it should not be underlined.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: It is correctly placed:  footnote numbers come after the final full stop of a sentence.  It is not correctly formatted:  it should not be underlined.
    QUESTION 3 What style of referencing does the Classics discipline prefer?
        ANSWER: No preference.
        FEEDBACK: Read your course handbook, or click on the blue question mark!
        ANSWER: The author/date system.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  This system is the easiest to use.
        ANSWER: The footnote system.
        FEEDBACK: You can use the footnote system, but that's not the preferred system in Classics.
