INTRO  <font size="4">Commissioned by Augustus, the <span style="font-style: italic;">Aeneid</span> receives praise such as: 'Virgil is a poet who has most power in the world ... He, more than any other poet, has been part of the intellectual life of Europe' (Haskell House, 1972, p.8).</font> 
    QUESTION 0 Is this a good use of quotation?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  The quotation itself is fine but it's not smoothly incorporated into the sentence.  The writer flags it up unnecessarily. 
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  Though the quotation itself is fine, it's not smoothly incorporated into the sentence.  The writer flags it up unnecessarily.
    QUESTION 1 Something in this quotation jars.  What is it?
        ANSWER: The ellipses (...) irritate. 
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Ellipses are the proper way to show that part of a quotation has been left out.
        ANSWER: The quote is too long.
        FEEDBACK: It is long, but that's not the real problem.
        ANSWER: There is a mismatch between the emperor and the quotation.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  It jars to mention the commissioner of the epic, Augustus, who died AD 14, and then, in the same breath and with no further comment, quote praise from 1972.
