<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><span><font size="4">It is an infringement of a persons right to privacy.</font><o:p></o:p></span></p> 
    QUESTION 0 'Persons' isn't quite the right word in this sentence. Which of the alternatives is correct?
        ANSWER: persons'
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  If we wanted to say that it was an infringement of the privacy of several people, we would use the possessive (and plural) people's, not persons'
        ANSWER: person's
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  As we're only talking about one person, we only need to talk about the privacy of that one person. Therefore, the apostrophe is inserted before the possessive 's'.
        ANSWER: people's
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  We're only talking about the privacy of a person here (only one person).
        ANSWER: peoples
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  We're only talking about the privacy of one person here, certainly not that of several 'peoples'. People is only made plural if several races or tribes are being discussed.
        Task wordclick difficulty 1
        Task wordclick difficulty 1
        Task wordclick difficulty 3
        Task wordclick difficulty 3
        Task wordclick difficulty 3
        Task wordclick difficulty 3
    Writing activity 04. Punctuation - colons
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task wordclick difficulty 2
        Task wordclick difficulty 1
        Task wordclick difficulty 2
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO Given that the popularity of email in 2002 was great that that of traditional mail, which incurs a charge: I intend to argue that if a fee were charged to send an email, fewer would be sent that when the service was free. 
    QUESTION 0 The writer has used a colon to break up this sentence. Which punctuation mark do you think would be better suited here?
        ANSWER: full stop
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect - a full stop would create two sentences, the first of which would be an incomplete sentence. 
        ANSWER: semi-colon
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect - a semi-colon is used to link two closely related sentences. Here, the first clause is not a sentence in its own right - it needs the text after the colon to make sense.
        ANSWER: comma
        FEEDBACK: Correct - the first clause provides the conditions for the second: it is a 'If X, then Y' type of construct, whereby the comma provides a flowing link between the two.
        ANSWER: no punctuation mark at all
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect - removing the colon and not replacing it with anything would make the sentence harder to read, and may distract the reader from the meaning.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <link rel="File-List" href="file:///C:%5CDOCUME%7E1%5CABI-PE%7E1%5CLOCALS%7E1%5CTemp%5Cmsohtmlclip1%5C01%5Cclip_filelist.xml" /><link rel="themeData" href="file:///C:%5CDOCUME%7E1%5CABI-PE%7E1%5CLOCALS%7E1%5CTemp%5Cmsohtmlclip1%5C01%5Cclip_themedata.thmx" /><link rel="colorSchemeMapping" href="file:///C:%5CDOCUME%7E1%5CABI-PE%7E1%5CLOCALS%7E1%5CTemp%5Cmsohtmlclip1%5C01%5Cclip_colorschememapping.xml" /><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> Normal 0 false false false EN-GB X-NONE X-NONE MicrosoftInternetExplorer4 </xml><![endif]--><!--[if gte mso 9]> <![endif]--><style> &lt;!-- /* Font Definitions */ @font-face {font-family:&quot;Cambria Math&quot;; panose-1:2 4 5 3 5 4 6 3 2 4; mso-font-charset:0; mso-generic-font-family:roman; mso-font-pitch:variable; mso-font-signature:-1610611985 1107304683 0 0 159 0;} @font-face {font-family:Calibri; panose-1:2 15 5 2 2 2 4 3 2 4; mso-font-charset:0; mso-generic-font-family:swiss; mso-font-pitch:variable; mso-font-signature:-1610611985 1073750139 0 0 159 0;} /* Style Definitions */ p.MsoNormal, li.MsoNormal, div.MsoNormal {mso-style-unhide:no; mso-style-qformat:yes; mso-style-parent:&quot;&quot;; margin-top:0cm; margin-right:0cm; margin-bottom:10.0pt; margin-left:0cm; line-height:115%; mso-pagination:widow-orphan; font-size:11.0pt; font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;; mso-fareast-font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; mso-bidi-font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; mso-ansi-language:EN-US; mso-fareast-language:EN-US; mso-bidi-language:EN-US;} .MsoChpDefault {mso-style-type:export-only; mso-default-props:yes; font-size:10.0pt; mso-ansi-font-size:10.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt; mso-ascii-font-family:Calibri; mso-hansi-font-family:Calibri;} @page Section1 {size:612.0pt 792.0pt; margin:72.0pt 72.0pt 72.0pt 72.0pt; mso-header-margin:36.0pt; mso-footer-margin:36.0pt; mso-paper-source:0;} div.Section1 {page:Section1;} --&gt; </style><!--[if gte mso 10]><style> /* Style Definitions */ table.MsoNormalTable	{mso-style-name:"Table Normal";	mso-tstyle-rowband-size:0;	mso-tstyle-colband-size:0;	mso-style-noshow:yes;	mso-style-priority:99;	mso-style-qformat:yes;	mso-style-parent:"";	mso-padding-alt:0cm 5.4pt 0cm 5.4pt;	mso-para-margin:0cm;	mso-para-margin-bottom:.0001pt;	mso-pagination:widow-orphan;	font-size:10.0pt;	font-family:"Calibri","sans-serif";}</style><![endif]-->
<p><font size="4"> This problem can be approached in three ways; first, the significance of wire-tapping in enhancing collective security; second, the implications of the misuse of technology on individual privacy; third, the practical reality of implementation. </font></p> 
    QUESTION 0 A colon is required in this sentence: where would you put it?
        ANSWER: after 'in three ways', replacing the semi-colon
        FEEDBACK: Correct. Colons can be used to introduce a list, which is exactly how one should be used here.
        ANSWER: after 'collective security', replacing the semi-colon
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect. This item is part of the list, so the semi-colon here is correct.
        ANSWER: at the end of the sentence
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect. Colons always introduce more information. Full stops are the only punctuation mark that can be used at the end of a sentence.
        ANSWER: after 'approached'
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect. Colons can be used to introduce a list but the list in this sentence doesn't start until 'first, ...'
        Task freetext difficulty 1
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task freetext difficulty 3
    Writing activity 06. Punctuation - commas
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO  Spammers send out millions of messages per day, the sheer volume of messages sent means that even a tiny percentage of responses can generate a lot of money for the sender.<br />
    QUESTION 0 Should the comma in this sentence be...?
        ANSWER: left where it is
        FEEDBACK: The sentence cannot be left as it is - a comma should never be used to link two whole sentences together.
        ANSWER: replaced with a full stop
        FEEDBACK: The sentence could be broken into two sentences at the point of the comma. Both sentences would then be correctly punctuated, but both would then be rather abrupt and the link between them would not flow naturally.
        ANSWER: replaced with a semi-colon
        FEEDBACK: The ideal solution here is to replace the comma with a semi-colon. This would make the sentence grammatically correct and maintain a clear close link between the two sentences.
        ANSWER: removed
        FEEDBACK: 
        Task freetext difficulty 1
        Task wordclick difficulty 1
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO  <font size="4">Prison sentences such as the 11 year incarceration handed out to one boss, have enabled the American government to deal a serious blow to organised crime. </font>
    QUESTION 0 Should there be a comma (or commas) in this sentence?
        ANSWER: Yes
        FEEDBACK: Correct - the comma should come after 'sentences', since this is the beginning of the sub-clause that ends with the comma after 'boss' 
        ANSWER: No
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect - there should be two commas, one placed where it is after 'boss' and the other after 'sentence' to mark the beginning of the sub-clause.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <meta content="text/html; charset=utf-8" http-equiv="Content-Type" /><meta content="Word.Document" name="ProgId" /><meta content="Microsoft Word 11" name="Generator" /><meta content="Microsoft Word 11" name="Originator" /><link href="file:///C:%5CDOCUME%7E1%5CABI-PE%7E1%5CLOCALS%7E1%5CTemp%5Cmsohtml1%5C02%5Cclip_filelist.xml" rel="File-List" /><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> Normal 0 false false false MicrosoftInternetExplorer4 </xml><![endif]--><!--[if gte mso 9]> <![endif]--><style>&lt;!-- /* Font Definitions */ @font-face {font-family:Calibri; panose-1:2 15 5 2 2 2 4 3 2 4; mso-font-charset:0; mso-generic-font-family:swiss; mso-font-pitch:variable; mso-font-signature:-1610611985 1073750139 0 0 159 0;} /* Style Definitions */ p.MsoNormal, li.MsoNormal, div.MsoNormal {mso-style-parent:&quot;&quot;; margin-top:0cm; margin-right:0cm; margin-bottom:10.0pt; margin-left:0cm; line-height:115%; mso-pagination:widow-orphan; font-size:11.0pt; font-family:Calibri; mso-fareast-font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; mso-bidi-font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; mso-ansi-language:EN-US; mso-fareast-language:EN-US; mso-bidi-language:EN-US;}@page Section1 {size:612.0pt 792.0pt; margin:72.0pt 90.0pt 72.0pt 90.0pt; mso-header-margin:36.0pt; mso-footer-margin:36.0pt; mso-paper-source:0;}div.Section1 {page:Section1;}--&gt;</style><!--[if gte mso 10]><style> /* Style Definitions */ table.MsoNormalTable	{mso-style-name:"Table Normal";	mso-tstyle-rowband-size:0;	mso-tstyle-colband-size:0;	mso-style-noshow:yes;	mso-style-parent:"";	mso-padding-alt:0cm 5.4pt 0cm 5.4pt;	mso-para-margin:0cm;	mso-para-margin-bottom:.0001pt;	mso-pagination:widow-orphan;	font-size:10.0pt;	font-family:"Times New Roman";	mso-ansi-language:#0400;	mso-fareast-language:#0400;	mso-bidi-language:#0400;}</style><![endif]-->
<p> My opinion is that those who are now addicted to the virtual world, would have been addicted to something else in the absence of the Internet. </p> 
    QUESTION 0 The sentence below has one comma. What would you do with it?
        ANSWER: keep it, and add another comma after 'those'
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect - in some situations, you might want to turn 'who are now addicted to the virtual world' into a sub-clause, but here the phrase plays a critical part in defining who 'those' are, so it shouldn't be enclosed within commas.
        ANSWER: keep it
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect - this comma separates the subject ('those...addicted to the virtual world') and the verb ('would have been...'), which commas should never do.
        ANSWER: remove it
        FEEDBACK: Correct - no comma is needed in this sentence. For more info about how commas are used, click on the blue question mark near the top of the page.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO  <link rel="File-List" href="file:///C:%5CDOCUME%7E1%5CABI-PE%7E1%5CLOCALS%7E1%5CTemp%5Cmsohtml1%5C08%5Cclip_filelist.xml" /><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> Normal 0 false false false MicrosoftInternetExplorer4 </xml><![endif]--><!--[if gte mso 9]> <![endif]--><style>&lt;!-- /* Font Definitions */ @font-face {font-family:Calibri; panose-1:2 15 5 2 2 2 4 3 2 4; mso-font-charset:0; mso-generic-font-family:swiss; mso-font-pitch:variable; mso-font-signature:-1610611985 1073750139 0 0 159 0;} /* Style Definitions */ p.MsoNormal, li.MsoNormal, div.MsoNormal {mso-style-parent:&quot;&quot;; margin-top:0cm; margin-right:0cm; margin-bottom:10.0pt; margin-left:0cm; line-height:115%; mso-pagination:widow-orphan; font-size:11.0pt; font-family:Calibri; mso-fareast-font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; mso-bidi-font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; mso-ansi-language:EN-US; mso-fareast-language:EN-US; mso-bidi-language:EN-US;}@page Section1 {size:612.0pt 792.0pt; margin:72.0pt 90.0pt 72.0pt 90.0pt; mso-header-margin:36.0pt; mso-footer-margin:36.0pt; mso-paper-source:0;}div.Section1 {page:Section1;}--&gt;</style><!--[if gte mso 10]><style> /* Style Definitions */ table.MsoNormalTable	{mso-style-name:"Table Normal";	mso-tstyle-rowband-size:0;	mso-tstyle-colband-size:0;	mso-style-noshow:yes;	mso-style-parent:"";	mso-padding-alt:0cm 5.4pt 0cm 5.4pt;	mso-para-margin:0cm;	mso-para-margin-bottom:.0001pt;	mso-pagination:widow-orphan;	font-size:10.0pt;	font-family:"Times New Roman";	mso-ansi-language:#0400;	mso-fareast-language:#0400;	mso-bidi-language:#0400;}</style><![endif]-->
<p> <font size="4">The consequences of which, were that Mr XX lost his job and had to sell the family home. </font></p> 
    QUESTION 0 This sentence has one comma in it - what would you do with that comma?
        ANSWER: remove it completely
        FEEDBACK: Correct - it's inserting an unnecessary break in the sentence.
        ANSWER: leave it where it is
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect - this comma serves no purpose here. It's put an unnecessary break between the subject ('the consequences of which') and the verb ('were').
        ANSWER: move it to after 'of'
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect - a comma after 'of' would insert the break in a different wrong place!
        ANSWER: move it to after 'job'
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect - a comma after 'job' isn't needed here as the list of thing that Mr XX did (losing his job and selling his home) is short, and does not need breaking up in any way.
        Task freetext difficulty 2
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
