<p class="MsoNormal"><font size="4" style="font-family: trebuchet ms,verdana,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;">Read the following essay title and then the concluding line(s) that are offered. Choose the concluding line(s) you think best. Each selection has an explanation, so even if your choice agrees with ours, it is worth browsing through them all.</font><o:p></o:p></p> <!--EndFragment--> 
        ANSWER: Right now, the lines between real and virtual societies are becoming blurred.  Both sides tend to blend into each other.  As people become more comfortable with the internet, a society which is a blend of the current virtual and traditional societies will emerge.
        FEEDBACK: These lines may refer to arguments put forward in the essay but they don't refer directly to the question.   Moreover, the inbuilt contradiction between government spying and individual confidentiality opens up the last sentence for debate, when a last sentence should close the essay down.  
        ANSWER: As this essay has shown, eavesdropping by individuals and eavesdropping by governments are not the same thing.  Individuals living in society have given up certain rights, and the right to absolute privacy is one of them.  Any government should be able to listen in on its citizens' telephone conversations.  That eavesdropping by government is often abused is no reason to prohibit it. 
        FEEDBACK: These lines refer directly to the terms of the question and neatly state the essay's main premises.  The last line follows on logically from the arguments.  The reader may disagree with the essay's conclusion, but there is no doubt as to what the conclusion is.  This is the best option.
        ANSWER: I think, really, that it's only those who are a threat to society who need monitoring.  All the rest of us should have our right to privacy respected rather than abused.  We should certainly stop our government listening into our conversations.
        FEEDBACK: These lines are clear, but too colloquial.   The phrase 'I think, really' has no place in an academic essay.  Written in slightly more formal style, this ending would be fine.  For example:  Monitoring should be restricted to those who threaten our society.  Other citizens should have their right to privacy respected ... 
        ANSWER: Very little in life is completely right or wrong.  Wiretapping has been used to eavesdrop on citizens' telephone conversations for at least a hundred years.  It would be impossible to stop it.
        FEEDBACK: These lines are true, but much too general.  From them, the reader could neither accurately identify the essay question nor discover the writer's response.   <br />
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <meta name="Title" /><meta name="Keywords" /><meta content="text/html; charset=utf-8" http-equiv="Content-Type" /><meta content="Word.Document" name="ProgId" /><meta content="Microsoft Word 11" name="Generator" /><meta content="Microsoft Word 11" name="Originator" /><link href="file://localhost/Users/katiegrant/Library/Caches/TemporaryItems/msoclip1/01/clip_filelist.xml" rel="File-List" /><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> Normal 0 0 1 37 212 1 1 260 11.1282 </xml><![endif]--><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> 0 0 0 </xml><![endif]--><style>&lt;!-- /* Font Definitions */@font-face {font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; panose-1:0 2 2 6 3 5 4 5 2 3; mso-font-charset:0; mso-generic-font-family:auto; mso-font-pitch:variable; mso-font-signature:50331648 0 0 0 1 0;} /* Style Definitions */p.MsoNormal, li.MsoNormal, div.MsoNormal {mso-style-parent:&quot;&quot;; margin:0cm; margin-bottom:.0001pt; mso-pagination:widow-orphan; font-size:12.0pt; font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; mso-ansi-language:EN-GB;}table.MsoNormalTable {mso-style-parent:&quot;&quot;; font-size:10.0pt; font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;}@page Section1 {size:612.0pt 792.0pt; margin:72.0pt 90.0pt 72.0pt 90.0pt; mso-header-margin:36.0pt; mso-footer-margin:36.0pt; mso-paper-source:0;}div.Section1 {page:Section1;}--&gt;</style><!--StartFragment-->
<p><strong>Essay title:</strong></p>
<p>Suppose a fee (an electronic version of a postage stamp) was required in order to send an email message. How would this change the behaviour of email users? Suppose the fee was one penny. Do you think this would solve the problem of spam?</p> <!--EndFragment--> 
    QUESTION 0  <link href="file://localhost/Users/katiegrant/Library/Caches/TemporaryItems/msoclip1/01/clip_filelist.xml" rel="File-List" /> <!--[if gte mso 9]><xml>
