        ANSWER: Now it is up to us to decide whether we are ready to microchip.  Are you?
        FEEDBACK: Concluding with a question is not a good option.  The essay title asks the writer to make an argument for or against microchipping children.  The concluding line needs to reinforce the writer's thesis, not leave the essay open-ended.
        ANSWER: Most importantly, this essay has shown that microchipping has serious privacy implications and for this reason above all others, implanting microchips is an option to be discarded.
        FEEDBACK: This line is clear, wraps up the argument neatly and leaves the reader in no doubt as to the conclusion.  This is the best.
        ANSWER: Really, in the long run, parents are the best people to judge what is best for their children.
        FEEDBACK: 'Really, in the long run' is too colloquial for an academic essay, and the writer shies away from the questions asked in the essay title.  This is not a good option.
        ANSWER: Law and order authorities should remain alert so that kidnappers are caught easily and quickly.
        FEEDBACK: This concluding line shows the writer has not read the question properly.  This essay should focus more on microchipping than different ways to combat kidnappers.  Combating kidnapping is a different essay entirely. <br />
