<p> <font size="4">The example shows the final line(s) of a paragraph. Read the line(s), and then, from the options offered, choose the one you think is the best link to the next paragraph. All the options have explanations, so even if you find our preferred option quickly, it's worth browsing through the others. </font></p><!--EndFragment--> 
        ANSWER: By this definition, the society of the internet must also be regarded as an open society.
        FEEDBACK: The phrases 'by this definition' (i.e. Karl Popper's definition) and 'open society' relate directly back to the final line of the previous paragraph whilst pushing the argument on.  The link is seamless.  This is the best option.
        ANSWER: Observation shows that totalitarian states impose heavy restrictions on internet use. 
        FEEDBACK: This is too abrupt.  Internet use is not the same as internet society, so the link jars.
        ANSWER: Trust can be misplaced by many individuals in on-line relationships.
        FEEDBACK: This uses the word 'individual' but in a completely different context.  The reader would be left puzzled and wondering if a few paragraphs had been missed out.
        ANSWER: Bart Goddy has defined the internet with seven keywords, namely:  open, abundant, interactive, user-controlled and infrastructure independent.
        FEEDBACK: This line, with Goddy's definitions echoing Popper's, might be fine if the next sentence explicitly links Goddy, Popper, 'an open society' and the internet all together and then opens up a new argument.  For example:  'Though couched in technological jargon, this definition of the internet may, at first glance, echo Popper's definition of an open society.  However, the echo is deceptive.'  If this explicit link is not made in sentence 2, then the paragraph transition will not be smooth.
