        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO  <link rel="File-List" href="file://localhost/Users/katiegrant/Library/Caches/TemporaryItems/msoclip1/01/clip_filelist.xml" /> <!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> Normal 0 0 1 71 407 3 1 499 11.1282 </xml><![endif]--><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> 0 0 0 </xml><![endif]--> <style> &lt;!-- /* Font Definitions */ @font-face {font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; panose-1:0 2 2 6 3 5 4 5 2 3; mso-font-charset:0; mso-generic-font-family:auto; mso-font-pitch:variable; mso-font-signature:50331648 0 0 0 1 0;} /* Style Definitions */ p.MsoNormal, li.MsoNormal, div.MsoNormal {mso-style-parent:&quot;&quot;; margin:0cm; margin-bottom:.0001pt; mso-pagination:widow-orphan; font-size:12.0pt; font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; mso-ansi-language:EN-GB;} table.MsoNormalTable {mso-style-parent:&quot;&quot;; font-size:10.0pt; font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;} @page Section1 {size:612.0pt 792.0pt; margin:72.0pt 90.0pt 72.0pt 90.0pt; mso-header-margin:36.0pt; mso-footer-margin:36.0pt; mso-paper-source:0;} div.Section1 {page:Section1;} --&gt; </style> <!--StartFragment-->
<p style="font-family: trebuchet ms,verdana,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;"><strong>Essay title:</strong> Police used to search manually through mugshots (photos of people who have been arrested) to find one that matched a witness's description of a person who committed a crime. Modern computer techniques allow police to search large databases of digitised photos. What are some of the benefits and some of the risks of expanding the search to include the DVLC drivers' licence photo database, or even sites like Flickr? What is your point of view on this potential development? </p> <!--EndFragment--> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: trebuchet ms,verdana,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;">Choose the opening line or lines most appropriate to the essay title set. Every choice has an explanation, so if you find our preferred option quickly, it is still worth browsing through them all. The same essay title may be used more than once.</span></font><!--EndFragment--> 
        ANSWER: Solving crimes is a primary, and time consuming, objective of the police and mugshots are one of the investigative tools available.
        FEEDBACK: This sentence is too general.  It does use one of the words in the essay title - mugshot - but it simply makes a statement of the obvious.  A marker would not be impressed and might deduct marks.  
        ANSWER: Crime is a growing problem in our society, where every day the situation appears to deteriorate and we are constantly bombarded by news stories of violent crime.
        FEEDBACK: This option has focused on crime, when crime is not the focus of the assignment.   It also makes general and unsubstantiated assertions.   A marker would not be impressed and might deduct marks.
        ANSWER: Expanding the use of facial recognition technology to include the DVLC photo data base and other digitised photo database, of which Flickr is a good example, will add to tensions already voiced over the mugshot databases by the police
        FEEDBACK: This option directly addresses the question set by the assignment.  Even better, through using words also found in the title, the writer has linked his response directly to it.   A marker would find this a highly encouraging start. 
        ANSWER: The government ID card scheme has come in for sustained criticism over the draconian nature of the enforcement required to make it viable.
        FEEDBACK: If the question set was 'Do the draconian measures required to enforce the government's ID card scheme render it unviable?', this option would be good.  But the question set is about the benefits and risks of allowing the police to search large databases of digitised photos, including DVLC and Flickr.   This opening line has nothing to do with that at all and would lose you marks.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO  <link rel="File-List" href="file://localhost/Users/katiegrant/Library/Caches/TemporaryItems/msoclip1/01/clip_filelist.xml" /> <!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> Normal 0 0 1 36 206 1 1 252 11.1282 </xml><![endif]--><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> 0 0 0 </xml><![endif]--> <style> &lt;!-- /* Font Definitions */ @font-face {font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; panose-1:0 2 2 6 3 5 4 5 2 3; mso-font-charset:0; mso-generic-font-family:auto; mso-font-pitch:variable; mso-font-signature:50331648 0 0 0 1 0;} /* Style Definitions */ p.MsoNormal, li.MsoNormal, div.MsoNormal {mso-style-parent:&quot;&quot;; margin:0cm; margin-bottom:.0001pt; mso-pagination:widow-orphan; font-size:12.0pt; font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; mso-ansi-language:EN-GB;} table.MsoNormalTable {mso-style-parent:&quot;&quot;; font-size:10.0pt; font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;} @page Section1 {size:612.0pt 792.0pt; margin:72.0pt 90.0pt 72.0pt 90.0pt; mso-header-margin:36.0pt; mso-footer-margin:36.0pt; mso-paper-source:0;} div.Section1 {page:Section1;} --&gt; </style> <!--StartFragment-->
<p><font size="4"><strong>Essay title:</strong> Suppose a society holds that it is wrong for one individual to eavesdrop on the telephone conversations of another citizen. Should that society also prohibit the government from listening in on its citizens' telephone conversations? </font></p> <!--EndFragment--> 
    QUESTION 0 


        ANSWER: No.  The fundamental purpose of government is to maintain public order and security.  In my opinion, the issue is really about trust.
        FEEDBACK: An arrestingly combative start, but, alas, though you might respond like this in conversation, it is not a good way to begin an academic essay.  You have certainly been invited by the question to express your view, so nobody is asking you to tone your view down.  However, from the first lines of your response a marker or even just a general reader must be able to tell what the terms of the question were.  This is not possible here.  Nor does the second sentence clarify matters as to the question set, nor the third.  This would not get good marks.
        ANSWER: The monitoring of citizens' telephone conversations by their governments has, throughout the western world, become a bone of contention between the crime prevention and detection lobby and the civil liberties lobby.
        FEEDBACK: This option brings in the terms of the question and succinctly sets out where the essay is going:  i.e. the debate between the crime prevention lobby and the civil liberties lobby.  It is a good, focused start.
        ANSWER: Currently, under UK law, individuals are not prohibited from recording their own communications, providing that the recording is for their own use.
        FEEDBACK: This line probably has a place in the assignment, but not at this point.  It reads rather weakly because, though it echoes the theme of the title, it echoes none of the title's actual terms.   A marker would find it unsatisfactory.<br />
        ANSWER: In the following essay I intend to:  challenge the essay question itself;  broaden the discussion beyond eavesdropping;  lay out the West's traditional position on this subject through Rousseau's 'Social Contract'; analyse whether increased surveillance necessarily leads to greater security;  examine ethical issues surrounding information gathering and finally conclude with my own position on the topic.
        FEEDBACK: <br />
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO  <link rel="File-List" href="file://localhost/Users/katiegrant/Library/Caches/TemporaryItems/msoclip1/01/clip_filelist.xml" /> <!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> Normal 0 0 1 10 57 1 1 70 11.1282 </xml><![endif]--><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> 0 0 0 </xml><![endif]--> <style> &lt;!-- /* Font Definitions */ @font-face {font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; panose-1:0 2 2 6 3 5 4 5 2 3; mso-font-charset:0; mso-generic-font-family:auto; mso-font-pitch:variable; mso-font-signature:50331648 0 0 0 1 0;} /* Style Definitions */ p.MsoNormal, li.MsoNormal, div.MsoNormal {mso-style-parent:&quot;&quot;; margin:0cm; margin-bottom:.0001pt; mso-pagination:widow-orphan; font-size:12.0pt; font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; mso-ansi-language:EN-GB;} table.MsoNormalTable {mso-style-parent:&quot;&quot;; font-size:10.0pt; font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;} @page Section1 {size:612.0pt 792.0pt; margin:72.0pt 90.0pt 72.0pt 90.0pt; mso-header-margin:36.0pt; mso-footer-margin:36.0pt; mso-paper-source:0;} div.Section1 {page:Section1;} --&gt; </style> <!--StartFragment-->
<p> <link rel="File-List" href="file://localhost/Users/katiegrant/Library/Caches/TemporaryItems/msoclip1/01/clip_filelist.xml" /> <!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> Normal 0 0 1 53 307 2 1 377 11.1282 </xml><![endif]--><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> 0 0 0 </xml><![endif]--> <style> &lt;!-- /* Font Definitions */ @font-face {font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; panose-1:0 2 2 6 3 5 4 5 2 3; mso-font-charset:0; mso-generic-font-family:auto; mso-font-pitch:variable; mso-font-signature:50331648 0 0 0 1 0;} /* Style Definitions */ p.MsoNormal, li.MsoNormal, div.MsoNormal {mso-style-parent:&quot;&quot;; margin:0cm; margin-bottom:.0001pt; mso-pagination:widow-orphan; font-size:12.0pt; font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; mso-ansi-language:EN-GB;} table.MsoNormalTable {mso-style-parent:&quot;&quot;; font-size:10.0pt; font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;} @page Section1 {size:612.0pt 792.0pt; margin:72.0pt 90.0pt 72.0pt 90.0pt; mso-header-margin:36.0pt; mso-footer-margin:36.0pt; mso-paper-source:0;} div.Section1 {page:Section1;} --&gt; </style> <!--StartFragment--> </p>
<p><font size="4">Human beings have lived in societies of various kinds throughout their existence. Identify key characteristics of traditional societies and then show how well or poorly these characteristics are emulated in the 'society' of the Internet. Do you think that we will become ever more dependent on our electronic society? In your view, how far can such a society be taken?</font></p> <!--EndFragment--> <!--EndFragment--> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: trebuchet ms,verdana,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;">Choose the opening line or lines most appropriate to the essay title set. Every choice has an explanation, so if you find our preferred option quickly, it is still worth browsing through them all. The same essay title may be used more than once.</span></font><!--EndFragment--> 
        ANSWER: The internet was the latest in a series of huge revolutions in interpersonal communication.  In a few years it became an important part of millions of people's lives.  It is amazing that you can somehow talk with somebody on the other side of the world at 3 a.m. just with a simple application on your laptop.
        FEEDBACK: This opening is too general and unfocused.  It does not remotely reflect the essay title's main theme of society.  It also makes the advent of the internet sound historical rather than something happening here and now.<br />
        ANSWER: Development of internet technology has brought changes in traditional societies and introduced a new kind of society which we often call electronic society.  To explore the way in which traditional societies are changed through the internet, important characteristics of traditional societies will be introduced.
        FEEDBACK: <br />
        ANSWER: The word 'tradition' means an inherited pattern of thought or an action, or a specific practice of long standing.  Therefore, the word 'traditional' is something consisting of or derived from the tradition.  Traditional society is a society which was established in the past and continued its evolution during the course of time.
        FEEDBACK: 
        ANSWER: Traditional societies, i.e. the groups into which people gather for mutual protection and self-interest, have two key characteristics:  a common respect for an agreed set of rules or laws and a code of behaviour to which, though diverse in its particulars, all members of the society can subscribe.   It could be argued that at least in respect of codes of behaviour, the society of the internet is no different.
        FEEDBACK: The first sentence nicely reflects the theme of society but only states the obvious.  The second sentence is superfluous, adding nothing.  If you removed it, it would not be missed.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO  <link rel="File-List" href="file://localhost/Users/katiegrant/Library/Caches/TemporaryItems/msoclip1/01/clip_filelist.xml" /> <!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> Normal 0 0 1 35 201 1 1 246 11.1282 </xml><![endif]--><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> 0 0 0 </xml><![endif]--> <style> &lt;!-- /* Font Definitions */ @font-face {font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; panose-1:0 2 2 6 3 5 4 5 2 3; mso-font-charset:0; mso-generic-font-family:auto; mso-font-pitch:variable; mso-font-signature:50331648 0 0 0 1 0;} /* Style Definitions */ p.MsoNormal, li.MsoNormal, div.MsoNormal {mso-style-parent:&quot;&quot;; margin:0cm; margin-bottom:.0001pt; mso-pagination:widow-orphan; font-size:12.0pt; font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; mso-ansi-language:EN-GB;} table.MsoNormalTable {mso-style-parent:&quot;&quot;; font-size:10.0pt; font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;} @page Section1 {size:612.0pt 792.0pt; margin:72.0pt 90.0pt 72.0pt 90.0pt; mso-header-margin:36.0pt; mso-footer-margin:36.0pt; mso-paper-source:0;} div.Section1 {page:Section1;} --&gt; </style> <!--StartFragment-->
<p><font size="4">Suppose a fee (an electronic version of a postage stamp) was required in order to send an email message. How would this change the behaviour of email users? Suppose the fee was one penny. Do you think this would solve the problem of spam?</font></p> <!--EndFragment--> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: trebuchet ms,verdana,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;">Choose the opening line or lines most appropriate to the essay title set. Every choice has an explanation, so if you find our preferred option quickly, it is still worth browsing through them all. The same essay title may be used more than once.</span></font><!--EndFragment--> 
        ANSWER: Spam is a big problem for email users and generally there have been three suggested solutions:  litigation, filtering and charging.  We will look at all three.
        FEEDBACK: This starts well, but goes slightly off focus.  The question refers directly to a fee changing the behaviour of email users and the possibility of solving the problem of spam through charging.   Litigation and filtering would both come into the section of the essay dealing with spam, but, when placed here, make it look as though the writer has read only one part of the question, and that part not very carefully.  The question is not:  'What would solve the problem of spam?'  The question is 'Do you think charging would solve the problem of spam?'   You must stick to the terms of the question.
        ANSWER: I am going to look at the arguments both for and against paying to send electronic mail over the internet.
        FEEDBACK: This sentence is entirely superfluous because it gets us no further into the question set.   It would not be missed if it were deleted so was a waste of time to write. 
        ANSWER: Email is one of the most revolutionary and popular internet services.  Even if it started as a medium of exchanging simple electronic textual messages between users of an MIT project in 1961, today it is probably the most commonly used internet service.
        FEEDBACK: These sentences leave markers clicking their tongues and muttering 'get to the point'.  Opening essays with general statements about how things are in the world denotes an unhelpful wandering around the question instead of getting to grips with it.   <br />
        ANSWER: Email has become the second largest forum for the flow of information in the world, sitting just behind the telephone as the most commonly used form of communication [International Data Corporation (IDC), 2003].  Since there is no cost involved in sending individual emails, the notion of charging is attractive to those looking both to change the behaviour of email users and to solve the problem of generically produced emails known as spam.
        FEEDBACK: <br />
        ANSWER: With email the second largest forum for the flow of information in the world, the idea of solving the related problems of overuse and abuse through charging a fee for what is currently free is certainly attractive.
        FEEDBACK: 
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO  <link rel="File-List" href="file://localhost/Users/katiegrant/Library/Caches/TemporaryItems/msoclip1/01/clip_filelist.xml" /> <!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> Normal 0 0 1 35 200 1 1 245 11.1282 </xml><![endif]--><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> 0 0 0 </xml><![endif]--> <style> &lt;!-- /* Font Definitions */ @font-face {font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; panose-1:0 2 2 6 3 5 4 5 2 3; mso-font-charset:0; mso-generic-font-family:auto; mso-font-pitch:variable; mso-font-signature:50331648 0 0 0 1 0;} /* Style Definitions */ p.MsoNormal, li.MsoNormal, div.MsoNormal {mso-style-parent:&quot;&quot;; margin:0cm; margin-bottom:.0001pt; mso-pagination:widow-orphan; font-size:12.0pt; font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; mso-ansi-language:EN-GB;} table.MsoNormalTable {mso-style-parent:&quot;&quot;; font-size:10.0pt; font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;} @page Section1 {size:612.0pt 792.0pt; margin:72.0pt 90.0pt 72.0pt 90.0pt; mso-header-margin:36.0pt; mso-footer-margin:36.0pt; mso-paper-source:0;} div.Section1 {page:Section1;} --&gt; </style> <!--StartFragment-->
<p><font size="4">Suppose a fee (an electronic version of a postage stamp) was required in order to send an email message. How would this change the behaviour of email users? Suppose the fee was one penny. Do you think this would solve the problem of spam?</font></p> <!--EndFragment--> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: trebuchet ms,verdana,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;">Choose the opening line or lines most appropriate to the essay title set. Every choice has an explanation, so if you find our preferred option quickly, it is still worth browsing through them all. The same essay title may be used more than once.</span></font><!--EndFragment--> 
        ANSWER: With such a vast subject area to discuss, I intend to limit the scope of my discussion to one particular type of email spam known as 'phishing'.
        FEEDBACK: I would say that this limits the discussion too much.  Phishing should be a topic, but not take up the whole debate.
        ANSWER: The idea of imposing a fee, the suggested electronic version of a postage stamp, in order to send email messages is not hypothetical.
        FEEDBACK: This directly echoes the words of the essay title, and makes an interesting claim.  This is the best.
        ANSWER: As part of globalisation, people have been forced to invent new ways to connect with each other.  The introduction of stagecoach routes in the Wild West, for example, has assisted this, as well as the construction of railways.
        FEEDBACK: This is very unfocused and bears no relation to the title of the essay.  It could be cut out without being missed, which is not the hallmark of a good opening line.
        ANSWER: For many years, the traditional way of social interaction between people was face to face.  In the last century it changed and people began to use landlines.
        FEEDBACK: This is padding.  We need to get to the meat of the question in the first line, not wander through history, tempting as a wander is.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO  <link rel="File-List" href="file://localhost/Users/katiegrant/Library/Caches/TemporaryItems/msoclip1/01/clip_filelist.xml" /> <!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> Normal 0 0 1 20 116 1 1 142 11.1282 </xml><![endif]--><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> 0 0 0 </xml><![endif]--> <style> &lt;!-- /* Font Definitions */ @font-face {font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; panose-1:0 2 2 6 3 5 4 5 2 3; mso-font-charset:0; mso-generic-font-family:auto; mso-font-pitch:variable; mso-font-signature:50331648 0 0 0 1 0;} /* Style Definitions */ p.MsoNormal, li.MsoNormal, div.MsoNormal {mso-style-parent:&quot;&quot;; margin:0cm; margin-bottom:.0001pt; mso-pagination:widow-orphan; font-size:12.0pt; font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; mso-ansi-language:EN-GB;} table.MsoNormalTable {mso-style-parent:&quot;&quot;; font-size:10.0pt; font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;} @page Section1 {size:612.0pt 792.0pt; margin:72.0pt 90.0pt 72.0pt 90.0pt; mso-header-margin:36.0pt; mso-footer-margin:36.0pt; mso-paper-source:0;} div.Section1 {page:Section1;} --&gt; </style> <!--StartFragment-->
<p> <font size="4">Essay title: Should parents implant microchips into their children to make them easier to identify in case they are lost or kidnapped? Why, or why not?</font><br /></p> <!--EndFragment--> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: trebuchet ms,verdana,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;">Choose the opening line or lines most appropriate to the essay title set. Every choice has an explanation, so if you find our preferred option quickly, it is still worth browsing through them all. The same essay title may be used more than once.</span></font><!--EndFragment--> 
        ANSWER: In 2002, two 10 year old girls, Holly Wells and Jessica Chapman, were murdered by a horrible criminal.
        FEEDBACK: This would be a possible opening line for a newspaper article designed to shock, but not an academic essay.  It may be arresting, but the phrase 'horrible criminal' is to colloquial.  This opening line would not create a good impression.
        ANSWER: Digital microchips are already implanted into dogs and cats and have been quite useful when pets go astray in the park, are stolen from cars, or to make sure the right dog is in the right class at a pet show.
        FEEDBACK: Had this sentence moved straight to children after 'dogs and cats', it might have worked.  As it is, it is too long and mostly irrelevant. 
        ANSWER: Basically, there are two types of microchip, active and passive.
        FEEDBACK: This opening is too abrupt and the opening 'basically' too colloquial, i.e. a word you might use in conversation, but is not appropriate in an academic essay.
        ANSWER: Before we decide to do something new, we have to ask this question:  'do we have to do this?'
        FEEDBACK: This opening is rather pointless.  The essay title makes clear the questions that need to be answered.  Answering a question with another question adds nothing to the argument.   
        ANSWER: The implantation of Radio Frequency Identity (RFID) tags, or microchips, into children raises issues both ethical and practical.
        FEEDBACK: This opening line goes straight to the point, defining microchips and opening up two areas of debate.  This is the best.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO  <link rel="File-List" href="file://localhost/Users/katiegrant/Library/Caches/TemporaryItems/msoclip1/01/clip_filelist.xml" /> <!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> Normal 0 0 1 41 235 1 1 288 11.1282 </xml><![endif]--><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> 0 0 0 </xml><![endif]--> <style> &lt;!-- /* Font Definitions */ @font-face {font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; panose-1:0 2 2 6 3 5 4 5 2 3; mso-font-charset:0; mso-generic-font-family:auto; mso-font-pitch:variable; mso-font-signature:50331648 0 0 0 1 0;} /* Style Definitions */ p.MsoNormal, li.MsoNormal, div.MsoNormal {mso-style-parent:&quot;&quot;; margin:0cm; margin-bottom:.0001pt; mso-pagination:widow-orphan; font-size:12.0pt; font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; mso-ansi-language:EN-GB;} table.MsoNormalTable {mso-style-parent:&quot;&quot;; font-size:10.0pt; font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;} @page Section1 {size:612.0pt 792.0pt; margin:72.0pt 90.0pt 72.0pt 90.0pt; mso-header-margin:36.0pt; mso-footer-margin:36.0pt; mso-paper-source:0;} div.Section1 {page:Section1;} --&gt; </style> <!--StartFragment-->
<p><font size="4">Which is more likely to be effective in protecting intellectual property in digital media such as CDs and DVDs: tougher copyright laws or new technologies incorporating more sophisticated anti-copying measures? If you can argue that a third mechanism will be more effective, do so.</font></p> <!--EndFragment--> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: trebuchet ms,verdana,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;">Choose the opening line or lines most appropriate to the essay title set. Every choice has an explanation, so if you find our preferred option quickly, it is still worth browsing through them all. The same essay title may be used more than once.</span></font><!--EndFragment--> 
        ANSWER: This essay investigates which is more effective in protecting intellectual property rights in digital media, enforcing copyright law, new technologies or a third mechanism. 
        FEEDBACK: This opening line simply restates the essay question, adding nothing.  It is a waste of 24 words!
        ANSWER: Considering this issue, I personally feel that the only way to ensure protection of intellectual property when distributing media on digital mediums such as CD and DVD is to toughen up copyright laws.  
        FEEDBACK: Academic essays should not be personalised with 'I personally feel'.  It is much more professional to say 'this essay will argue'.  However, there is certainly a clear statement made here.  Not the best opening line, but not the worst either. 
        ANSWER: The evolution of digital technology and the internet has opened the way for new uses of digital content and enhanced users' digital entertainment experience.
        FEEDBACK: This sentence reads well but actually, just states the obvious.  As an opening line it performs no useful function.  If it were deleted, it would not be missed.
        ANSWER: A recent, peer-reviewed report (Grant 2009) makes it clear that neither tougher copyright laws nor anti-copying measures, however sophisticated, are ever likely to afford adequate protection for intellectual property rights.
        FEEDBACK: This starts with a confidence-giving citation (the full reference will be in the bibliography).  It echoes the words of the essay title but instead of just repeating them, it uses them to state the writer's thesis.  This is the best option.<br />
