    Writing activity 24. Evidence - footnotes, endnotes, embedded references and bibliographies
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO  <font size="4">Blundell, J. R., <span style="font-style: italic;">Security and Safety</span>, New York: Anyname Press, 2004<br />Smith, Gary, T<span style="font-style: italic;">he Role of the Computer Scientist in 20th Century Britain</span>, Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1984<br />Wallingford, Brian, <span style="font-style: italic;">Code Safety</span>, Cambridge, 2008<br /><br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Is this an endnote list or a bibliography?
        ANSWER: A endnote list.
        FEEDBACK: No, it's not an endnote list.  Endnotes are always numbered.
        ANSWER: This list is a bibliography.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  A bibliography is listed on its own, separate page, and the works listed are not numbered.
    QUESTION 1 In a bibliography, in what order should the referenced works be listed?
        ANSWER: In the order they were read by the writer.
        FEEDBACK: No.  This isn't correct.
        ANSWER: In alphabetical order, using the authors' initials or first names.
        FEEDBACK: No, this isn't correct.
        ANSWER: In alphabetical order, using the authors' surnames.
        FEEDBACK: This is correct.  A bibliography is always listed alphabetically, in order of surname.
        ANSWER: It doesn't matter, provided all the references are listed.
        FEEDBACK: It does matter, because the point of a bibliography is that it should be easy for a reader to find their way around.
    QUESTION 2 Are these references correctly styled?
        ANSWER: Yes.  
        FEEDBACK: No, they are not correctly styled.  The date of publication should come after the author's name, and the last reference is missing the name of the city of publication, and the name of the publisher.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  They are not correctly styled.  The date of publication should come in brackets after the author's name, and the last reference is missing the name of the publisher.
        ANSWER: It doesn't matter how they are styled.
        FEEDBACK: I'm afraid it does matter.  Referencing style has evolved to make it easier for readers to check references out. In this example, the date of publication should come after the author's name, and the last reference is missing the name of the publisher.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO  <font size="4">Parents could then contact the police, who can activate the code transmitted by the network.(1) A signal is then sent by the mobile phone which will pinpoint the child's location. According to the BBC Online Magazine, 'in the past five years, dozens of murderers have been convicted, partly as a result of evidence from mobile phones'.(2)<br /><br />(Appearing on a separate page at the end of the essay)<br /><br />(1) Parents look to microchip children, CNN, 2002, http://archives.cnn.com/2002/WORLD/europe/0903/index<br /> [accessed 14.12.2006]<br /><br />(2) Michael Lane, Would a microchip keep your child safe? BBC News Online Magazine<br /> http://news.bbc.co.uk./1/hi/magazine/s677890/2090/stm [accessed 23.12.2006]<br /><br /><br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 What are these references called?
        ANSWER: Bibliography.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not right.  A bibliography is a list of all works consulted (books, journals, websites). A bibliography appears on a separate page and the works not numbered, but listed alphabetically, by author surname. 
        ANSWER: Footnotes.
        FEEDBACK: No, although they are numbered, these are not footnotes.  Footnotes are indicated with superscript numbers in the text.  These bracketed numbers refer to endnotes, and the numbers correspond to references set out at the end of the essay.
        ANSWER: Endnotes.
        FEEDBACK: Quite right.  This writer has chosen to place reference numbers in the text, and then, at the end of the essay, to list the references corresponding to each number.
    QUESTION 1 Are these web references correctly styled.
        ANSWER: No.  There is no need to put in the entire url or the date accessed.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  It is necessary to put in the entire url, and the date accessed.
        ANSWER: Yes.  The writer has put in the whole url and the date accessed, both of which are needed.
        FEEDBACK: Quite right.  It is necessary to put in the entire url, and the date accessed.
        ANSWER: Doesn't matter how you style web references.
        FEEDBACK: I'm afraid it does.  The point of the reference is to make it possible for the reader to check your source.  To check web sources, it's necessary to have the whole url and the date accessed.
