    Writing activity 22.  paragraphs
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO  <font size="4">The first area of research was into the Doppler effect. In 1842, Christian Andreas Doppler first asked what happens when the source of a wave and its observer move relative to each other. Originally the 'Doppler effect', as it became known, was used to explain the apparent change in frequency of light being emitted from stars. The cause of this turned out to be the stars' orbit throwing them towards and away from us. This caused the shift. However, the term the 'Doppler effect' is more commonly used when referring to sound waves being emitted by a passing emergency service vehicle. After researching the Doppler effect, it became clear that this effect does not apply to this project. Since both the source (transmitter) and observer (receiver) do not move relative to each other, there is no Doppler shift between them. There are two Doppler shifts relative to the wind: one at the transmitter; the other at the receiver. Thus, the changes in frequency cancel each other out and overall, due to wind speed, there is no change to the frequency of the received signal. </font> 
    QUESTION 0 How many paragraph should this piece of text be divided into?
        ANSWER: It's fine as one.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again!
        ANSWER: Two.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree!  Try again.
        ANSWER: Three.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  The first paragraph will be the first sentence - ending in 'effect'.  This tiny sentence/paragraph sets the scene.  The second paragraph, beginning 'In 1842' tell us the history of the Doppler effect, and ends with 'emergency service vehicle'.  The third paragraph, beginning 'After researching the Doppler effect' tells of the relevance (or not) of the Doppler effect to the writer's project.   These three paragraphs have three distinct points to make.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">This project required a capacitive sensor system able to be integrated with an abacus. The reasoning behind this was that an electronic abacus would help teach visually impaired people simple arithmetic. The use of capacitive sensors is now widespread </font><font size="4">in every day household goods</font><font size="4">, with phones, for example, fully operated through screens. In most cases, capacitive sensing offers a better product finish; mp3 players are a good example. There are also distinct engineering advantages in capacitive sensing: fewer mechanical parts; and perhaps most usefully, capacitive sensing makes products less susceptible to liquid. </font> 
