        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">2.1.2. PLD<br /><br />The design of the system meant that the team had to choose a PLD which would be able to drive all of the VSYNC and HSYNC values to the display, as well as to manage the transactions to and from the RAM modules. Given the number of lines to manage these two operations alone, the PLD also required a number of communication lines allowing the microcontroller to control accesses to RAM, as well as to initialise the PLD. After much discussion, the team decided that the PLD would need around 106 pins in order to communicate with each of the sub=systems within the product. As well as this, the team would also require a PLD that had a high number of macrocells in order to handle the counts for addressing all of the locations within RAM, for when the display is consuming data. After conducting research into a range of PLDs, the team finally decided to use the EP11270T144C5N from Altera, which is part of the MAX 2 family. This decision was based around the fact that this PLD boasted a high enough pin count for the team's requirements, s well as allowing the team to have a number of spare pins should the system have to be redisigned at any point. As well as this, the PLD boasted 980 macrocells, which was more than enough to count through all the locations within the RAM modules. Another reason the team used this PLD was the presence of demo boards of other PLDs within Altera's MAX 2 range within the department. This allowed the team to familiarise themselves with the Quartus development environment and to generate the VHDL code required for the PLD, as well as perform pin assignment for the design of the PLD.<br /></font> 
