INTRO <font size="4"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Introduction</span><br /><br />Conventional fuels are becoming more expensive as they become scarcer, and burning them causes greenhouse gases which, in turn, leads to global warming. If, in the future, we power our vehicles with electricity, rather than with fuel from the tank, will it be better or worse for the environment? This article considers two issues related to providing an answer: the first is the type of electric vehicles adopted; the second is the source of energy the vehicle uses. Currently, the choice for vehicles is a fairly clear one: conventional, gasoline powered cars; and hybrids which combine orthodox engines with batteries that charge during driving and braking. The Toyota Prius is the first mass-produced example in the latter category. It is able to use fuel more efficiently but is only capable of limited range on electric power alone (1-2 km). It cannot be recharged from the grid. In November 2009, China released the world's first ever mass-produced plug-in hybrid. This is drawing on China's strength as a battery producing nation and the desire to use vehicle manufacture as a level for industrialisation. The Chinese hybrid is not available outside China.<br /><br /><font size="1">adapted from Daborn, ECS3, exam preparation 2010; original text Voelker, <span style="font-style: italic;">IEEE Spectrum</span>, March 2009, pp.42-45, 50-53</font><br /></font> 
