        Task freetext difficulty 2
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO 1. We made another hole in the mobile part, mostly to decrease the rigidity.<br /><br />2. As you can see from the isometric views of the final concept, it was not very thick. <br /> <br /> 
    QUESTION 0 What word makes sentence 1 rather vague?
        ANSWER: 'another'
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  It would be better to say 'a second' or 'a third' or whatever the appropriate number.  But there's another word too.
        ANSWER: 'mostly'
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  'Mostly' implies there was another reason.  It would be important to give the other reason.  If there is no other reason, leave out 'mostly'.  This is not the only word that's vague in this sentence.  
        ANSWER: 'mobile'
        FEEDBACK: No, 'mobile' is fine.  It defines the part.
    QUESTION 1 Does sentence 2 need more written detail if it has a picture?
        ANSWER: Yes.  It needs specific measurements.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  But the measurements might be attached to the picture, in which case that would be enough.  There's no need to repeat information.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: That would depend.  If the measurements were part of the picture, then no more written information would be needed.  Information needs to be given only once.  If there were no measurements on the picture, we would need more information in the text.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">1. In helicopter manufacture, there are strict regulations.<br /><br />2. A number of simulations were carried out.</font><br /> 
    QUESTION 0 What should come after 'strict regulations'?
        ANSWER: One example of a regulation. 
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  I think we need a citation, i.e. a numbered, or author/date reference.  This would match a full reference in the reference section of this report.  The reference would show us where to find a full list of regulations. 
        ANSWER: A reference.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  I think we need a citation, i.e. a numbered, or author/date reference.  This would match a full reference in the reference section of this report.  The reference would show us where to find a full list of regulations.
    QUESTION 1 For sentence 2, do we need to know how many simulations?
        ANSWER: No - it's enough to say 'a number'.  A project team may have forgotten to count them exactly in the lab. 
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  It's part of your work to make sure you note down everything you do.  A quick look through your lab report should tell you exactly how many simulations were carried out.
        ANSWER: Yes.  We should have counted.
        FEEDBACK: I agree. It's part of your work to make sure you note down everything you do.  A quick look through your lab report should tell you exactly how many simulations were carried out.
