<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size: 7.5pt;">Acknowledgment: these examples and styles are taken or adapted for teaching purposes from Weissberg and Buker (1990) <i>Writing up Results</i></span></p> <!--EndFragment--> 
    QUESTION 0 Do either of these statements indicate certainty?
        ANSWER: Neither show certainty.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  Try again.
        ANSWER: 1. shows certainty.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  There are two clues:  the word 'suggested' indicates a tentative finding; and the conditional verb 'may be' shows the author in tentative mode.
        ANSWER: 2. shows certainty.
        FEEDBACK: Well done.  Yes.  The use of the present tense in the findings - oats PRODUCE - indicates certainty.
    Writing activity 01. front page
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <div style="text-align: center;"><font size="4">Team Project 4<br /><br /><font size="5">Bridge Elevation Design</font><br /><br />Othmar Ammann, Thomas Brassey, Isambard Kingdom Brunel, Allston Dana <br /><br />July 2010<br /><br /><br /></font></div> 
    QUESTION 0 What's missing from this front page?
        ANSWER: The university's name.
        FEEDBACK: That is missing, but that's not vital.
        ANSWER: The supervisor's name.
        FEEDBACK: Yes, that would be necessary if this was a supervised report in 4th year or 5th year.  There's something else, too.
        ANSWER: Matriculation numbers.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  We need names and matriculation numbers - and something else too.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <span style="font-family: impact;"><span style="font-family: wingdings;"><span style="font-family: impact;"><font size="2">ANDREW ROANLEY<br />0898765</font><br /><br />Aqua Ski System Reliability<br /><br />July 2010<br /></span></span></span> 
    QUESTION 0 Is this a good front page?
        ANSWER: Yes, it contains all the information required.
        FEEDBACK: It does contain all the information, but it's hard to read.  Use a clear typeface such as 12 point Times Roman.  Fancy typefaces are often difficult to read.
        ANSWER: No, it's not good.
        FEEDBACK: I agree. This front page does contain all the information required, but it's hard to read.  Use a clear typeface such as 12 point Times Roman.  Fancy typefaces are often difficult to read.
    Writing activity 02. abstract
        Task selectcat difficulty 2
        Task selectcat difficulty 2
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Abstract</span><br /><br />We live in a diminishing world, and we need to find sustainable fuels if the planet is to survive. But sometimes we muddle up the terms 'sustainable', 'green' and 'organic'. People feel that 'organic' must be good, and that organic fuels can help relieve energy shortages and climate change. This is questionable. Corn ethanol was heavily subsidised in the US, whilst in Germany rapeseed has been popular, in India jatropha and in Brazil, sugarcane ethanol. All these crops use up land and water - both scarce resources. What can be done? We aimed to find out. <br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">Read the text, then answer the question(s).</font> 
        ANSWER: Yes.  It tells us the subject of the report. 
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  A report is a very specific piece of text.  This abstract is far too general.  It gives a reader no clue as to what's actually inside the report.
        ANSWER: No, it's too vague.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  We have no idea, from this abstract, what the specific goal of the experiment or research was, its methodology or its conclusions. An abstract has a very specific purpose, and this abstract does not fulfil it.
    QUESTION 1 Is the writing style of this abstract appropriate?
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  It's too chatty.  It's best to avoid the personal 'I' or 'we'.  It's also best to avoid rhetorical questions, e.g. 'what can be done?'  The style here is what we might term 'journalese' in that it would be appropriate for a popular newspaper.
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  I think the style is too chatty.  It's best to avoid the personal 'I' or 'we'.  It's also best to avoid rhetorical questions, e.g. 'what can be done?'  The style here is what we might term 'journalese' in that it would be appropriate for a popular newspaper.
    QUESTION 2 Abstracts are concise overviews of a project report.  Click on the blue question mark above the exercises for the themes that most abstracts include.   Does this abstract do its job?
        ANSWER: Yes, it tells us what the report is about.
        FEEDBACK: Does it?  I don't think so. Despite mentioning crops by name, it's very vague and general.  Would you know, from this abstract, exactly what to find inside?  If you were a student looking for information, could you tell whether this report would be any use?  Abstracts need to be more specific than this.
        ANSWER: No, it's too vague.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  Despite mentioning crops by name, it's very vague and general.  You couldn't know, from this abstract, exactly what you might find inside this report.   If you were a student looking for information, this abstract might irritate.   Abstracts need to be more specific than this one.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO This paper presents a model for assessing these costs and considers the case for photovalvic electricity to meet the world's energy needs.<br />The results show that bio-fuels will be unable to sustain the growing world economy whereas, at least in principle, inorganic fuels could.<br />Bio-fuels provide around 6.5 megawatt hours per day per square kilometre.<br /><br /> 
    QUESTION 0 Is sentence 1 the final sentence of the abstract, the introduction or a paragraph in the body of the report?
        ANSWER: It's the final sentence of the abstract.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again.
        ANSWER: It's the final sentence of the introduction.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  It tells us what the paper is presenting.  An abstract would give an overview of the entire paper, including method and most important conclusions.
        ANSWER: It's the final sentence of a paragraph in the body of the report.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  It's the final sentence of the introduction as it tells us what the whole paper (not just the next section) is presenting.
    QUESTION 1 Is Is sentence 2 the final sentence of the abstract, the introduction or a paragraph in the body of the report?
        ANSWER: Sentence 2 is the final sentence of the abstract.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  It gives a very concise summary of the most important result, and offers a pointer to the future. 
        ANSWER: Sentence 2 is the final sentence of the introduction.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  The introduction should present what's coming in the report, but not the conclusions.  Try again.
        ANSWER: Sentence 2 is the final sentence of a paragraph in the body of the report.
        FEEDBACK: It's possible, but being very concise, it's more likely to fit somewhere else.  Perhaps try again?
    QUESTION 2 Is sentence 3, the final sentence of the abstract, the introduction or a paragraph in the body of the report?
        ANSWER: Sentence 3 is the final sentence of the abstract.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  An abstract would be unlikely to end with a statement of fact like this.  An abstract should end with a very concise summary of the most important result(s) of a project, and a very concise recommendation for the future.
        ANSWER: Sentence 3 is the final sentence of the introduction.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  An introduction presents what's to come in a report and would be unlikely to end with a statement of fact like this.  Perhaps try again? 
        ANSWER: Sentence 3 is the final sentence of a paragraph in the body of the report.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  This is a detail that you'd expect to find in the body of the report.
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task freetext difficulty 3
