        Task freetext difficulty 3
    Writing activity 03. table of contents
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO  <font size="4"><font size="5">Contents</font><br /><br />Confidentiality Note<br />Acknowledgments<br />Abbreviations<br /><br /><span style="font-weight: bold;">Abstract<br /><br />1. Introduction ..................................... 8<br /><br />2. ERTF Process Overview ....................... 10<br /> </span>2.1 ERTF Process Chemicals ....................... 10<br /> 2.2 ERTF process description ...................... 10<br /><br /><span style="font-weight: bold;">3. Instrumentation</span> ................................. 14<br /> 3.1 Selected Instruments ........................... 15<br /> 3.1.1. temperature Measurements ................ 16<br /><span style="font-weight: bold;"><br /><br /></span> <br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 There are two things wrong with this table of contents.  What are they?
        ANSWER: The confidentiality note, acknowledgments, abbreviations and abstract should have page numbers.
        FEEDBACK: Not necessarily.  If you need a confidentiality note, acknowledgments and a page for abbreviations (you might want a separate page for abbreviations and acronyms if they play a big part in your report), it's not absolutely necessary to give them page numbers so long as they come before the actual start of your report.  You can include the page number of the abstract in your table of contents, but as the abstract is inserted before the table of contents, it's not wrong not to give the abstract page number in the table.  Everything that comes AFTER the abstract, however, must be listed, with the appropriate page number.
        ANSWER: Too much indentation of section numbers.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  I think it's fine to indent the section numbers, then indent again for sections within sections.  You're right to think about this, though.  If you've got sections within sections within sections, indentation might become a problem.
        ANSWER: Capitalisation is not consistent.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  A professionally laid out table of contents like this is spoiled by inconsistency in capitalisation.  Decide what you're going to put in capitals and stick to it.  When you proof read, check your use of capital letters very particularly as they often creep in, or are left out, inadvertently.  Watchword:  CONSISTENCY
        ANSWER: The page numbers should be in a line.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  Make sure your page numbers are properly aligned.  When you read a table of contents, isn't that what you prefer to see?  Somehow, properly aligned page numbers inspire confidence!
        Task freetext difficulty 1
    Writing activity 04. introduction
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO  <font size="4"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Introduction</span><br /><br />George Westinghouse patented his first invention, a railroad brake, in 1869. Since that time, despite its drawbacks, this system has been used to control freight trains, even as they have become longer and heavier. This report looks at how the airbrake works, the limitations of its operating process and what Electronically Controlled Pneumatic (ECP) braking offers. It considers the disadvantages and advantages of the new system and the likelihood that ECP will be implemented.<br /><br /><font size="1">adapted for teaching purposes from Mandelbaum, IEEE Spectrum, 2009, pp.46-49</font><br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Would you consider this a good introduction?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  Though very concise, it gives enough background to set the scene and lays out very clearly what is contained in the report.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Though very concise, this introduction gives enough background to set the scene and lays out very clearly what is contained in the report.  I think it is a good introduction.
    QUESTION 1 What makes this an introduction rather than an abstract?
        ANSWER: There's no difference.
        FEEDBACK: That's incorrect.  An abstract gives a complete overview of a report, i.e. also states (very concisely) the main findings, conclusions and recommendations for further work.  An introduction simply introduces the report.
        ANSWER: An abstract would be shorter.
        FEEDBACK: Not necessarily.  Remember that an abstract gives a complete overview of a report, i.e. also states (very concisely) the main findings, conclusions and recommendations for further work.  An introduction simply introduces the report.  An introduction will often be longer than an abstract but this need not necessarily be the case.  Don't feel you must put unnecessary information into an introduction just to pad it out.
        ANSWER: An abstract does a different job.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  An abstract gives a complete overview of a report, i.e. also states (very concisely) the main findings, conclusions and recommendations for further work.  An introduction simply introduces the report.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Introduction</span><br /><br />Conventional fuels are becoming more expensive as they become scarcer, and burning them causes greenhouse gases which lead to global warming. If, in the future, we power our vehicles with electricity rather than with fuel from the tank, will it be better or worse for the environment? This article considers two issues related to finding an answer to this question: first, the type of electric vehicles which are adopted; and second, the source of the energy the vehicle uses.<br /><br />The energy market is hard to predict, and the attraction of plug-in vehicles looks as though it will increase. This is related to lower carbon emissions, smog reduction and security for oil importing nations as the oil price rises and the cost of batteries falls. However, cost and carbon emission from the hybrid plug-in are not the only considerations. The evidence given in this report on secondary emissions might make the purchaser think twice. There are further problems to solve.<br /><br /><br /><br /><font size="1">adapted for teaching purposes from John Voelker, IEEE Spectrum, March 2009, pp. 42-45, 50-53</font><br /><br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Does this introduction fulfill a reader's expectations in terms of tone and content?
        ANSWER: Yes.  It reads clearly.
        FEEDBACK: It does read clearly, but there's still a problem.  Try again.
        ANSWER: It reads clearly but there's a mismatch between the paragraphs.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  The second paragraph comes from the conclusion section and has no place in the introduction.  When you write, make sure you think about the section you're writing and make sure the information you're conveying fits properly into that section.
        ANSWER: This reads more like an abstract.
        FEEDBACK: I know what you mean, in that the second paragraph states the conclusions and a nod to future work.  However, an abstract would be crisper, with methodology and less generalised conclusions.  The second paragraph actually comes from the conclusions section of this report, where it sits nicely.
    QUESTION 1 Is the rhetorical question in paragraph 1 suitable for a report?
        ANSWER: Yes, it draws the reader in.
        FEEDBACK: I agree, though be careful.  If you're not confident about your writing, it's best to leave rhetorical questions out.  This report was written by an experienced writer for a journal.  You are writing for an academic audience.  Always remember your reader. 
        ANSWER: No, rhetorical questions should be avoided.
        FEEDBACK: I agree that in an academic environment, it's best to leave rhetorical questions out.  This report, however, was written by an experienced writer for a journal, so is perfectly acceptable.  The key is always to remember what audience you are writing for.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO  <font size="4"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Introduction</span><br /><br />Dashboards, a key feature in racing cars, are under constant review for weight, reliability, ease of use and increased safety. <br />Team A was contracted to build a dashboard display using an OLED screen, and specific functions were specified. The screen was required to display rpm as a green-red bar across the top; a scale of </font><font size="4">O% to 100% on </font><font size="4">the fuel level bar; speed in mph; and gear position. Warning lights were also required to indicate the temperature of the engine and the coolant, low fuel levels and gear change rpm. Additional buttons should facilitate gear changing and allow the user to navigate through the menu system. Lastly, but very importantly, a phone-style cord had to be used to connect to the dashboard to allow easy disconnection of the steering wheel. <br /><br />The success of the project depended on meeting all these criteria. <br /><font size="1"><br /></font> </font> 
    QUESTION 0 Does this introduction fulfill all your expectations as a reader coming new to this report?
        ANSWER: Yes.  It's clearly written and sets out the aims of the project.
        FEEDBACK: It does, but I found it a little thin.  As a non-specialist (which many readers will be) I wanted a bit more background about racing car dashboards.  I wondered, for instance, if OLED screens were already in use, and this project was to enhance that use, or whether this was groundbreaking stuff.   I would also have liked more detail on method and perhaps some indication of how the report was divided up.
        ANSWER: No, it had some gaps.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.   As a non-specialist (which many readers will be) I wanted a bit more background about racing car dashboards.  I wondered, for instance, if OLED screens were already in use, and this project was to enhance that use, or whether this was groundbreaking stuff.   I would also have liked more detail on method and perhaps some indication of how the report was divided up.
    QUESTION 1 There is a style flaw in this text.  What is it?
        ANSWER: Colons and semi-colons are wrongly used.
        FEEDBACK: No, they're correctly used here.  See the section on colons and semi-colons on this website.
        ANSWER: The tenses are muddled:  'ARE under constant review'; 'WAS required'
        FEEDBACK: No.  The tenses are correctly used here.  We use the present tense for ongoing things, and reviewing dashboards is ongoing.  We use the past tense for orders which have been issued, so 'WAS' is acceptable here.  The report is telling you what Team A has done, rather than what they are doing now.
        ANSWER: The shortforms, or acronyms (e.g. OLED, rpm) should be written out in full when first used.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  Never presume that your reader will understand the shortform or acronym.  A first reference should be written '... using an organic light emitting diode (OLED)' or 'revs per minute (rpm)'.  After this first mention, you can use the acronym alone.
        Task selectcat difficulty 3
        Task selectcat difficulty 3
        Task selectcat difficulty 3
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Introduction</span><br /><br />I first saw a waterborne monoski on holiday, and used one for recreational purposes. It broke down a lot, which was both annoying and dangerous, and I wondered what tests there could be for monoskis with a view to improving reliability. These tests could be done from databases from manufacturers although a downside was that databases were often quite out of date and had tested monoskis made of old materials. Although many other pieces of recreational equipment are similar to the monoski, I concentrated only on reliability testing for monoskis. In this short report, I define reliability and offer some ideas, both theoretical and practical, about reliability testing for monoskis.<br /><br /><br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Is the tone of this introduction what a reader would expect from an engineering report?
        ANSWER: Yes - it may be chatty, but it's quite clear.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  The 'chattiness' makes the report vague.  What is meant by 'a lot' or 'quite out of date'?  An engineering report is useless if it's not specific.
        ANSWER: No.  It is too informal.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  The 'chattiness' makes the report vague.  What is meant by 'a lot' or 'quite out of date'?  An engineering report is useless if it's not specific.
    QUESTION 1 Is it acceptable to use the first person in an introduction like this, since the project was generated by a personal experience?
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  In an engineering report, it's best to use the impersonal form, i.e. Waterborn monoskis are used for recreational purposes.  The personal 'I' is not entirely wrong, but it sets an informal tone which is often not helpful to either writer or reader.
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.   In an engineering report, it's best to use the impersonal form, i.e. Waterborn monoskis are used for recreational purposes.  The personal 'I' is not entirely wrong, but it sets an informal tone which is often not helpful to either writer or reader.
    QUESTION 2 If you had to mark this introduction out of 3, with 3 being the best mark, how much would you give it?
        ANSWER: 1.
        FEEDBACK: Yes, I would too.  The use of 'quite out of date', 'a lot' and other colloquialisms, together with the use of the first person, seriously undermines this introduction.
        ANSWER: 2. 
        FEEDBACK: I'd say that was generous.  There is information in this introduction, but it's undermined by the vague colloquialisms, e.g. 'quite out of date', and the use of the first person.
        ANSWER: 3.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree entirely!  There is information here, but the vague nature of some of the statements - what does 'quite out of date' really mean? - undermines the whole introduction.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4" style="font-weight: bold;">Introduction<br /><br /></font><font size="4">'The motorcycle is the area that has changed the most in the last 100 years', according to NSW Inc. Looking further into this task, I found that motorbikes have become a lot safer from tyres and brakes to suspension, especially in the last 20 years. Many people say that motorbikes are dangerous but it's not necessarily the motorbike itself that's dangerous. The environment and the person driving could be the danger factor. 'Vehicle failure accounted for less than 3% of motorcycle accidents' according to the University of Southern California Traffic Safety Centre. So the reliability of motorbikes is good but not great. So looking into what I think are the main factors in unreliability, I think these are the main factors that cause a motorbike to fail: the engine, the brakes and the suspension.</font><br /> 
    QUESTION 0 Is the tone of this introduction what you might expect from an engineering report?
        ANSWER: Yes.  Though it may be a bit chatty, it's clear what the writer is writing about.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  I think the use of the personal 'I' has set the report off on too informal a route.  By the end of this paragraph, though we know the writer's opinion, we still don't know what the project aims are. 
        ANSWER: No.  It seems to wander.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  At the end of this paragraph, we still don't know the project's aims.  In a short report, this would be a waste of words.
    QUESTION 1 There is something wrong with the quotation that begins this introduction.  What is it?
        ANSWER: The writer should use double quotation marks.
        FEEDBACK: No.  Single quotation marks are correct for a direct quotation.  Double quotation marks are reserved for a quote within a quote.
        ANSWER: The figure 100 should be written in text, i.e. as 'one hundred'.  
        FEEDBACK: No.  If it was figures in the quotation, it needs to be figures here.
        ANSWER: The writer should have written out NSW in full as the reader may well not know what it stands for.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  If you have a shortform or acronym, you need to write it out in full the first time it is used.  After the first time, it can be used alone.  You may know, but I do not, what NSW Inc. stands for.  The web has countless NSWs.
    QUESTION 2 Is it acceptable to use phrases like 'a lot safer' in any part of an engineering report?
        ANSWER: Yes, it's fine to use generalities in an introduction because you'll move to specifics in the body of the report.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not right.  You must be specific right from the start.
        ANSWER: No, it's never fine to use generalities.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  You need to be specific from the beginning of the report right to the end.
