INTRO  <font size="4"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Conclusions (also sometimes called Discussion)</span><br /><br /><span style="font-weight: bold;">1.</span> The two projects outlined in this report threw up a variety of challenges and new technologies. <span style="font-weight: bold;">2.</span> Many new techniques were learned. <span style="font-weight: bold;">3.</span> The projects both ended up with most of the features listed in the aims and objectives. <span style="font-weight: bold;">4.</span> However, there were a few unresolved issues.<br /><br /><span style="font-weight: bold;">5. </span>For a start, had more time been available, a better circuit interface could have been developed for both the locker discs and the parking discs, with more robust features and a more user-friendly layout. <span style="font-weight: bold;">6.</span> We also just had a single demonstration, which did not provide adequate testing.<br /><br /><span style="font-weight: bold;">7.</span> This was a major lesson: thorough testing and debugging is vital. <br /><br /><span style="font-weight: bold;">8.</span> In the end, though, all the specifications and requirements were met and the project seemed a success.<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Is sentence 1 a good way to begin a conclusions (discussion) section?
        ANSWER: Yes.  It leads the reader in.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  The reader has already got to the end of the report.  The conclusions/discussion section needs to be snappy and factual.  If challenges and new technologies are mentioned, there must be examples, not just vague references.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  The reader has already got to the end of the report.  The conclusions/discussion section needs to be snappy and factual.  If challenges and new technologies are mentioned, there must be examples, not just vague references.
    QUESTION 1 What does sentence 2 lack?
        ANSWER: Nothing.  It's fine as it is.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  We need examples.  Bland statements are just padding.
        ANSWER: We need examples, although the whole concept of personal goals might be challenged as suitable for inclusion in a project conclusions/discussion section.
        FEEDBACK: I agree. The conclusions or discussion section should really concentrate on the results of the project rather than personal goals.
    QUESTION 2 What is wrong with sentence 3?
        ANSWER: Nothing.  It refers back to the aims and objectives, which are all relevant to the conclusion(s).
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  It is good to refer back to the aims and objectives, but this sentence is undermined by the use of 'most of'.  We need to know WHICH aims and objectives were fulfilled. 
        ANSWER: It's too general.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.   It is good to refer back to the aims and objectives, but this sentence is undermined by the use of 'most of'.  We need to know WHICH aims and objectives were fulfilled.
    QUESTION 3 Is the tone in sentences 4, 5 and 6 appropriate for a formal report?
        ANSWER: No. It's too chatty.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  The phrases 'a few unresolved issues'; 'for a start'; and 'a better circuit' are too vague for a report.  Always include examples. 
        ANSWER: It is a little chatty, but fine for the conclusions or discussion section.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Chattiness is never good in a report.  Also, the phrases 'a few unresolved issues'; 'for a start'; and 'a better circuit' are too vague.  It will nearly always be better to include an example, however brief.
