<p> The design delivered most points of the PDS: </p>
<ul>
  <li> Unisex usability with appropriate dimensions of handle size and reach to trigger </li>
  <li> 1 litre capacity </li>
  <li> Good chemical resistance </li>
  <li> Good UV resistance </li>
  <li> Exposed temperature range -5C to 35C </li>
  <li> Centre of mass of filled bottle at handle region </li>
  <li> Non drip </li>
  <li> Stable when placed on flat surface </li>
  <li> Large filler opening </li>
  <li> Environmentally friendly </li>
  <li> Maximum sales price of ?5 </li>
  <li> Visually different to other trigger spray bottles </li>
  <li> Manufactured through plastic injection molding </li>
</ul><br />Lessons learned:<br />
<p> If more time had been spent familiarizing the designer with Plastics Advisor 8 and the mold design tools in Solid Works, the final stages of the design process would have been smoother. The undercut that caused problems was very obvious and should have been noticed earlier, either from the prototype or just in the CADdesign. That could have been picked up when the first rough designs were produced rather than waiting until detailed design work had been completed. It would also have been useful to step back from the process and conduct an overview rather than concentrating on each separate part of the process. </p> <!--EndFragment--> 
    QUESTION 0 Here is the conclusion section of a report, and the recommendations.  Is the tone of these recommendations suitable for a Design Report?  
        ANSWER: No.  It should be more about the product, less about what went wrong.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  This is a design report and the writer has successfully combined the personal lessons learned with the design itself.   The solid text 'recommendations' paragraph is also a nice contrast with the conclusion's bullet points.  A reader would appreciate this change in style.
        ANSWER: Yes, it reads well.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  This is a design report and the writer has successfully combined the personal lessons learned with the design itself.   The solid text 'recommendations' paragraph is also a nice contrast with the conclusion's bullet points.  A reader would appreciate this change in style.
    QUESTION 1 If there was one criticism, what would it be?
        ANSWER: It's too long.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  It's as long as it needs to be.  There's nothing superfluous here.  
        ANSWER: It's too short.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  It's a good length, saying exactly what it needs to say.
        ANSWER: The 'most' in the first line, as in 'most points' should be more specific.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  To perfect this, 'most' would be changed to a specific figure, e.g. 13 out of 15, or 95%, or whatever was appropriate.
