    Writing activity 08. references - when required, how to format
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4"><span style="font-weight: bold;">References</span><br /><br />Kuwana, Y. &amp; Shimoyama, I., 1998, 'A pheromone-guided mobile robot that behaves like a silkworm moth with living antennae as pheromone sensors', <span style="font-style: italic;">International Journal of Robotics Research</span>, 17 (9): 924-933, 930<br /><br />TC Limited, 'Guide to Thermocouple and Resistance Thermometry', Product Information Guide, Issue 6.1, 2009<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Here are two references from the same reference section.  There is one error.  Can you spot it?
        ANSWER: There should be no italics.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not right.  Book titles and journal titles are italicised.
        ANSWER: The Product Information Guide should be listed ahead of the journal.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not it.  References should be listed in alphabetical order by author surname (the first author in multi-author works).  Works without a specified author should be slotted in alphabetically by title.
        ANSWER: There is an inconsistency in the order.
        FEEDBACK: Quite right.  The publication date in the first reference comes after the authors and in the second reference comes at the end.  Either is correct, but BE CONSISTENT.
    QUESTION 1 What are all the figures at the end of the first reference?
        ANSWER: 924-933 are the span of the article.  930 is the specific page from which the quotation is taken.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  The listing of a specific page as well as the article span means that there will be a direct quotation from that page, enclosed within quotation marks, in the text. 
        ANSWER: They show the ISBN number of the journal or book.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  9924-933 is the full span of the article.  930 is a specific page.  The listing of a specific page means that there will be a direct quotation, enclosed within quotation marks, in the text.
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO  <font size="4">One application of AI is where robot control algorithms have been developed to locate the centre of a chemical plume by following the plume upwind (1).<br /><br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Does this text need a reference?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  The phrase 'robot control algorithms have been developed' is a clear reference to a project that has already been done.  You must cite a reference for this statement.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  The phrase 'robot control algorithms have been developed' is a clear reference to a project that has already been done.  You must cite a reference for this statement.
    QUESTION 1 What does the (1) stand for?
        ANSWER: It shows that only one project has been carried out.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not right.  The (1) refers to an entry in the references section of the report, where the reader can find all the details of the project referred to in the text. 
        ANSWER: It refers to a corresponding number in the references section of this report.
        FEEDBACK: Quite right.  The (1) refers to an entry in the references section, where the reader can find all the details of the project referred to in the text.
    QUESTION 2 Are there other ways of referencing, apart from by number?
        ANSWER: No.  Numbering is the usual way.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  The 'author/date' or Harvard system is another popular way.  Instead of a figure, this gives, in brackets, the author name and the date of the cited publication, e.g. (Kuwana and Shimoyama, 1998).  The full details of this publication would be found in the reference section.
        ANSWER: Yes.  You can use the author/date system.
        FEEDBACK: Quite right.  The 'author/date' or Harvard system is another popular way.  Instead of a figure, this gives, in brackets, the author name and the date of the cited publication, e.g. (Kuwana and Shimoyama, 1998).  The full details of this publication would be found in the reference section.
