<p><font size="4">Whoever has Daisy, has the upperhand.</font></p> 
    QUESTION 0 This sentence contains a comma, but the comma hasn't been used correctly. Which of the following alternatives should the writer have used instead?
        ANSWER: Whoever has, Daisy, has the upperhand.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect - Daisy is a key element of this sentence and shouldn't be bracketed using commas.
        ANSWER: Whoever has Daisy has the upperhand.
        FEEDBACK: Correct. 'Whoever has Daisy' is the subject of the verb 'has', while 'the upperhand' is the object. No comma is needed in the sentence - it works best without.
        ANSWER: Whoever, has Daisy has the upperhand.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect - it's critical that 'Whoever has Daisy' isn't separated by a comma - the phrase forms the subject of the verb.
