    Writing activity 05. Punctuation - quotation marks
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">'Orlando', by Virginia Woolf, is a novel that creates an idea of selfhood that is not gender specific. This is evident in the very first line of the novel, &quot;He - for there could be no doubt of his sex, though the fashion of the time did something to disguise it.&quot; Clothes are used to similar effect in Shakespeare's &quot;Hamlet&quot;. For example, when his mother accosts him about his seeming over-reaction to the loss of his father and her own marriage to his uncle, Hamlet answers: &quot;Seems, madam? Nay, it is. I know not 'seems'./Tis not alone my inky cloak, good mother,/Nor customary suits of solemn black/<sup>2</sup> .&quot; Here, clothing is illustrative of the 'turmoil' within Hamlet's soul.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 Are the quotation marks in this passage all properly used?
        ANSWER: Yes
        FEEDBACK: No, none of them are.  The names of the works, Orlando and Hamlet, being the names of plays, should be in italics with no quotation marks. The quotation from Orlando should be enclosed in single quotation marks.  The full stop at the end should come after the closing quotation mark because this quotation is enclosed within a sentence. The quotation from Hamlet, being longer than two lines, should be set apart from the main text and indented (but not centred) and, when layed out in that way, requires no quotation marks. 'Turmoil' requires no quotation marks unless you are using it as a direct textual quotation, in which it requires a reference to make this clear. 
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  The names of the works, Orlando and Hamlet, being the names of plays, should be in italics with no quotation marks. The quotation from Orlando should be enclosed in single quotation marks.  The full stop at the end should come after the closing quotation mark because this quotation is enclosed within a sentence. The quotation from Hamlet, being longer than two lines, should be set apart from the main text and indented (but not centred) and, when layed out in that way, requires no quotation marks. 'Turmoil' requires no quotation marks unless you are using it as a direct textual quotation, in which it requires a reference to make this clear.
        ANSWER: Some are and some are not.
        FEEDBACK: No, none of them are.  The names of the works, Orlando and Hamlet, being the names of plays, should be in italics with no quotation marks. The quotation from Orlando should be enclosed in single quotation marks.  The full stop at the end should come after the closing quotation mark because this quotation is enclosed within a sentence. The quotation from Hamlet, being longer than two lines, should be set apart from the main text and indented (but not centred) and, when layed out in that way, requires no quotation marks. 'Turmoil' requires no quotation marks unless you are using it as a direct textual quotation, in which it requires a reference to make this clear.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO  <link rel="File-List" href="file:///C:%5CDOCUME%7E1%5CABI-PE%7E1%5CLOCALS%7E1%5CTemp%5Cmsohtml1%5C04%5Cclip_filelist.xml" /><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> Normal 0 false false false MicrosoftInternetExplorer4 </xml><![endif]--><!--[if gte mso 9]> <![endif]--><style>&lt;!-- /* Style Definitions */ p.MsoNormal, li.MsoNormal, div.MsoNormal {mso-style-parent:&quot;&quot;; margin:0cm; margin-bottom:.0001pt; mso-pagination:widow-orphan; font-size:12.0pt; font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; mso-fareast-font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;}@page Section1 {size:612.0pt 792.0pt; margin:72.0pt 90.0pt 72.0pt 90.0pt; mso-header-margin:36.0pt; mso-footer-margin:36.0pt; mso-paper-source:0;}div.Section1 {page:Section1;}--&gt;</style><!--[if gte mso 10]><style> /* Style Definitions */ table.MsoNormalTable	{mso-style-name:"Table Normal";	mso-tstyle-rowband-size:0;	mso-tstyle-colband-size:0;	mso-style-noshow:yes;	mso-style-parent:"";	mso-padding-alt:0cm 5.4pt 0cm 5.4pt;	mso-para-margin:0cm;	mso-para-margin-bottom:.0001pt;	mso-pagination:widow-orphan;	font-size:10.0pt;	font-family:"Times New Roman";	mso-ansi-language:#0400;	mso-fareast-language:#0400;	mso-bidi-language:#0400;}</style><![endif]-->
<p><font size="4">I shall look at Herbert's poem <i>The Collar</i> and two of Donne's poems: <i>A hymn to God the father</i> and <i>Sonnet No. Fourteen</i>.</font></p> 
    QUESTION 0 Should the poems' titles be italicised?
        ANSWER: Yes
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  Italics are used for individually published works: for example, books, plays, journals and longer poems, but not for the titles of individual, shorter poems.
        ANSWER: No
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  Italics are used for book titles, but not for poem titles.
        ANSWER: It's a matter of personal choice.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  There are rules about the use of italics. Italics are used for individually published works: for example, books, plays, journals and longer poems, but not for the titles of individual, shorter poems.  It is important to stick to these rules.
    QUESTION 1 Should the poems' titles be enclosed in quotation marks?
        ANSWER: Yes
        FEEDBACK: Correct - to clearly indicate to the reader that these are specific poems, quotation marks should be used.
        ANSWER: No
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect - the poem titles need to be clearly indicated as such to the reader.
        ANSWER: It's a matter of personal choice.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect - there are rules about the use of quotation marks. Click on the blue question mark near the top of this page to find out more.
    QUESTION 2 Are the words in the poems' titles correctly capitalised?
        ANSWER: Yes
        FEEDBACK: No. The Collar and Sonnet No. Fourteen are correctly capitalised, but A Hymn to God the Father should be capitalised in this way, not as in the example.
        ANSWER: No
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  The Collar and Sonnet No. Fourteen are correctly capitalised, but A Hymn to God the Father should be capitalised in this way, not as in the example.
        ANSWER: It's a matter of personal choice.
        FEEDBACK: No, it's not a matter of choice.  There are rules, which are not there to annoy, but to provide consistency and clarity.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
