<p>The truth was that Jay Gatsby of West Egg, Long Island, sprang from his Platonic conception of himself' (Fitzgerald 105).</p> 
    QUESTION 0 There's something wrong with the punctuation in this sentence - what is it?
        ANSWER: There are too many commas.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  The commas in this sentence are all needed.
        ANSWER: There shouldn't be brackets around the reference details.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  The reference details are critical.  Brackets single them out but don't interrupt the main flow of the sentence.
        ANSWER: There's an opening quotation mark missing - it isn't clear where the quotation begins.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  Where does the quotation start? The reader doesn't want to have to look up the page in the book to find the quote, so it's crucial that the quote is correctly defined by quotation marks.
