<p><font size="4">George Herbert asserts that he is not concerned when death will strike; as long as his life is one that could be considered 'good' in the eyes of God.</font></p> 
    QUESTION 0 The writer has used a semi-colon in this sentence, but hasn't used it correctly. Which punctuation mark should replace it?
        ANSWER: colon
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect - this sentence needs to flow more naturally than a colon would allow it to. 
        ANSWER: full stop
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect - inserting a full stop would mean that the newly created second sentence would have to be rewritten as it isn't currently a complete sentence. However, the content of this second phrase is critical to the meaning of this sentence, so another punctuation mark would be better suited to this situation.
        ANSWER: comma
        FEEDBACK: Correct - a comma would work best here. As the two phrases are both critical to the meaning of the sentence, they shouldn't be separated but subtley linked. For more information on using commas, click on the blue question mark near the top of the page.
