INTRO <font size="4">The <span style="font-style: italic;">chansons de geste</span>, written in western Europe, take for their subject matter the development of the <span style="font-style: italic;">chivalric ethos</span>. This <span style="font-style: italic;">ethos</span> includes many virtues, all important to knights' perceptions of their role in society. We see this in the <span style="font-style: italic;">Arthurian </span>stories. But it's not only Arthur's knights who are remembered through the <span style="font-style: italic;">chansons</span>. Who could forget Roland's dying vision, not of his love, <span style="font-style: italic;">La Belle Aude</span>, but of Charlemagne, his king and lord.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 What should be italicised in this piece of text?
        ANSWER: Everything that is italicised at the moment.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.
        ANSWER: 'Chansons de geste' and 'chansons' because they are foreign words.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  These terms are now too familiar to italicise.  Click on the blue question mark above the tasks for more information.
        ANSWER: La Belle Aude because it's a foreign name.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  We don't italicise foreign names.  Click on the blue question mark above the tasks for more information.
    QUESTION 1 Should 'chivalric ethos' be italicised?
        ANSWER: Yes.  It is a peculiar term, so needs italicising.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  This term is not unfamiliar;  nor does it need special emphasis.  No italics either for 'ethos' on its own.
        ANSWER: No.  It doesn't need italicising.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  This term is not unfamiliar;  nor does it need special emphasis.  No italics either for 'ethos' on its own.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">In both Samuel Becket's Krapp's Last Tape and Virginia Woolf's Orlando, the idea of self is explored through the use of clothing. We meet Krapp reminiscing about his past self. <span style="font-style: italic;">Orlando</span>, too, is defined by what he wears. Before examining the effects of the characters' wardrobe, it is important to define the idea of <span style="font-style: italic;">self</span>. The dictionary states that the self can be &quot;The union of elements that constitute the individual identity of a person&quot;. This self can change, and we can see how the self changes in both &quot;Krapp&quot; and &quot;Orlando&quot; through clothes. As Woolf says: <span style="font-style: italic;"> He - for there could be no doubt of his sex, though the fashion of the time did something to disguise it - was in the act of slicing at the head of a Moor which swung from the rafters.</span><sup>2</sup><br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 In the first sentence, are there any italics missing?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  The titles of both books should be in italics.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  The titles of both works, being individually published, should be in italics.
        ANSWER: It's a matter of personal choice.
        FEEDBACK: No.  The departmental guidelines on italics, as on many other questions of style, are there to help with clarity and consistency.  In academic essays, both are vital.  Personal choice is not an option.
    QUESTION 1 Should the second mention of Orlando, at the beginning of sentence three, be italicised?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  As the title of an individually published work, it should be in italics.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  As the title of an individually published work, it should be in italics.
        ANSWER: It doesn't matter whether it's italicised or not.
        FEEDBACK: No.  The departmental guidelines on italics, as on many other questions of style,  are there to help with clarity and consistency.  In academic essays, both are vital.  Personal choice is not an option.Incorrect.  Here, the writer is using Orlando as the name of the main character, rather than the name of the book.
    QUESTION 2 Should the two quotes, the first from the dictionary and the second from Woolf, be italicised?
        ANSWER: It doesn't matter if they are italicised or not.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  It does matter.  Quotes like this should never be italicised, but should appear within single quotation marks.
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  Quotes like this should never be italicised, but should appear within single quotation marks.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: Correct. Quotes like this should never be italicised, but should appear within single quotation marks.
    QUESTION 3 In the penultimate sentence, are Krapp and Orlando correctly styled?
        ANSWER: Krapp is but Orlando isn't.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  Krapp is being referred to as a character, so his name should in in ordinary font.  Orlando is being used as the name of the book, so should be in italics.
        ANSWER: Krapp isn't but Orlando is.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect. Krapp is being referred to as a character, so his name should in in ordinary font.  Orlando is being used as the name of the book, so should be in italics.
        ANSWER: Neither are styled correctly.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  Krapp is being referred to as a character, so his name should in in ordinary font.  Orlando is being used as the name of the book, so should be in italics.
