    Writing activity 20. Argument and evidence - how to assess the structure of your work
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Rochester does not ascribe any value to social class, wealth or propriety, and does not let his higher status affect the way he speaks to Jane. He appears to value more an intellect that matches and complements his own. What Jane sees in Rochester is something a little different. She feels sexual love, but also the thrill of empowerment and liberation. The language both characters use reflects this, and since Jane is the narrator, we are drawn to Rochester with her, willing her on.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 What was the title of the essay from which this paragraph was drawn?
        ANSWER: Discuss the relationship between self and religion with reference to two texts from the course.
        FEEDBACK: No, it wasn't this.
        ANSWER: Discuss the relationship between the self and sexual love.
        FEEDBACK: Yes, this is the title, although you wouldn't be absolutely sure, since in this paragraph no explicit link is made by the writer.
        ANSWER: Explore notions of social clas with reference to two texts you have studied. 
        FEEDBACK: No, this wasn't actually the title, although it certainly fits.
        ANSWER: Is Jane Eyre a study in Victorian sexual repression?
        FEEDBACK: No, this isn't the title, although from the paragraph, you might be forgiven for thinking it was.
    QUESTION 1 Is there anything lacking from this paragraph?
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I think there is.  If you're going to make assertions such as are made about both Jane and Rochester in the example, they must be backed up by quotations, properly styled and referenced.  Without textual evidence, an essay is fatally weakened.
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  If you're going to make assertions such as are made about both Jane and Rochester in the example, they must be backed up by quotations, properly styled and referenced.  Without textual evidence, an essay is fatally weakened.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">However, where Gatsby's illusion is crushed by reality, Jane Eyre paradoxically flourishes by virtue of Bronte's fairytale structure. Her persona acts as a mask that protects her against the obstacles of sexual and social oppression. By constructing her sense of self around her own morality and refusing to compromise, she realises her potential.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 What was the title of the essay from which this paragraph is drawn?
        ANSWER: Discuss the relationship between self and social class with reference to two texts you have studied.
        FEEDBACK: No.  The paragraph mentions 'social oppression' but that's not its main thrust.
        ANSWER: Jane Eyre and Jay Gatsby have a great deal in common: discuss.
        FEEDBACK: No.  This doesn't fit.
        ANSWER: Discuss role playing in two novels you have read on this course.
        FEEDBACK: This is correct, and if you read the passage carefully, you'll see that the writer has not forgotten the essay title.
    QUESTION 1 Is there anything lacking in this paragraph?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  If you are going to mention something like Bronte's fairytale structure, you must back this up with evidence.  Quote from the text (properly styled and footnoted or embedded in your essay), and go to the library to find secondary evidence relating to fairytales.  You cannot make assertions from thin air.  Evidence is vital, or a good point is lost.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  If you are going to mention something like Bronte's fairytale structure, you must back this up with evidence.  Quote from the text (properly styled and footnoted or embedded in your essay), and go to the library to find secondary evidence relating to fairytales.  You cannot make assertions from thin air.  Evidence is vital, or a good point is lost.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">As Gatsby envisages Daisy as his America, Nicole represents America in Fitzgerald's <span style="font-style: italic;">Tender is the Night</span>. Dick Diver, as Nicole's doctor, begins to see in her a woman he could look after and love. Their marriage disintegrates because she cannot live up to the ideal Diver has created in his mind. Again, as in <span style="font-style: italic;">Gatsby</span>, the female is as perishable as anyone else. Diver wants to fulfil his ambition and become a highly respected doctor of psychiatry. However, having to look after Nicole deprives him of this dream. As Nicole and Dick grow together, they grow to become almost one. Unfortunately, their relationship does not fill the gaps in Dick needs to fill in his life, and Nicole merely reinforces that which is already present in his personality. The idea of the fragmentary human being is strengthened by the chronology of the narrative.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 What is the essay title from which this paragraph is drawn?
        ANSWER: 'Fitzgerald's Nicole Diver embodies an America of dreams'.  How true is this?
        FEEDBACK: No, this wasn't the title.  Ask yourself why you thought this might be the title.  Has the writer not linked the paragraph and the title clearly enough together?
        ANSWER: Discuss the nature of women in two novels on this course.
        FEEDBACK: No, this isn't the title.  Ask yourself why you thought it might be.  Has the writer not made the point of the paragraph sufficiently clear?
        ANSWER: Discuss the concept of the American Dream in 20th century American literature.
        FEEDBACK: Yes, this is the title, and I think the writer has tried to make the link clear in the first line, but tails away into narrative.
    QUESTION 1 Is there anything missing from this paragraph?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I think so too.  If you are going to make assertions, such as that Nicole doesn't fill the gaps in Diver's life, then you need textual references (either properly footnoted or embedded in the text).  Without references, the whole paragraph is fatally weakened.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I think there is. If you are going to make assertions, such as that Nicole doesn't fill the gaps in Diver's life, then you need textual references (either properly footnoted or embedded in the text).  Without references, the whole paragraph is fatally weakened.
    QUESTION 2 Is the last line of the paragraph a good last line?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I don't think so. The last line of a paragraph should either lead directly to a new paragraph on the same topic, or link very clearly back to the title. 
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  The last line of a paragraph should either lead directly to a new paragraph on the same topic, or link very clearly back to the title.  For more information, see the section of this site devoted to concluding lines, or look at the whole essay example.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Essay title:</span> 'If an artist's work is strikingly different from that of his predecessors or contemporaries, one may well look for the source of his originality to those of his interests which fall outside the proper sphere of his own medium.' To what extent is it possible for visual art to influence literature?<br /><br />Gertrude Stein's Three Lives and the poetry of William Carlos Williams are both very different from the work produced by their contemporaries. They are striking for many reasons, most notably for their originality. In their work, these two writers found new forms of prose and poetry. This essay will look at the sources of their inspiration - the visual arts - and the influence that art had on their work.<br /><br /><br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Is this first paragraph relevant to the essay title?
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  It seems highly relevant.  I think if you didn't know the essay title, it would be possible to guess what it was from this paragraph. 
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  If you couldn't see the essay title, it would be possible to guess it.  The writer speaks of different sources of inspiration for writers and how this contributed to their originality.
    QUESTION 1 Is there anything missing from this paragraph?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  We need a concrete reference to the time these writers were writing.  Were they contemporaries?  What century are we in?  Don't assume your reader will fill in these kinds of gaps.  References add weight to an essay and inspire confidence.  You can never have too many.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  We need some concrete reference to the time Gertrude Stein and William Carlos Williams are writing.  Were they contemporaries?  It's not clear from this paragraph. Don't assume your reader will fill in these kinds of gaps.  References add weight to an essay and inspire confidence.  You can never have too many.
        Task freetext difficulty 1
        Task freetext difficulty 2
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title: Write on one of the following: paratext; parody; pastiche; revision; screen adaptation; source; the book; with reference to two works you have studied on this course.<br /><br />As mentioned previously, the adapting of written works for film and television has been around for many years. For as long as there have been people writing scripts there has been some form of adaptation for the big or small screen. There are many different types of adaptation, including comic-book adaptations, video-game adaptations, television adaptations and film adaptations. Usually, these adaptations are made for a target audience. The film version of <span style="font-style: italic;">Wuthering Heights</span> was fairly popular, as was the film version of <span style="font-style: italic;">The Importance of Being Earnest</span>, which also won a couple of minor awards. Screen adaptations are very interesting because they also take liberties with the text.<br /></font><br /><br /> 
    QUESTION 0 Is this a good example of an evidence based argument?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: A marker certainly wouldn't agree.  This paragraph states the obvious and does not present an argument.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I quite agree.  There is no argument presented here, and the terms 'fairly popular' and 'a couple of minor awards' do not constitute evidence.
    QUESTION 1 What should come next?
        ANSWER: A new topic.
        FEEDBACK: No.  This topic has not been dealt with properly yet. 
        ANSWER: Examples.
        FEEDBACK: Yes.  An assertion has been made - that screen adaptations are interesting because they take liberties with the text.  Now we need concrete, referenced examples.
    QUESTION 2 Would a tutor mark this paragraph with a tick, a cross or nothing at all?
        ANSWER: Tick.
        FEEDBACK: There is nothing to tick.  This paragraph states the obvious and does not present an argument.
        ANSWER: Cross.
        FEEDBACK: I shouldn't think a marker would bother.  With no argument presented, the paragraph isn't really worth marking. 
        ANSWER: Nothing at all.
        FEEDBACK: Correct. A marker would leave such a paragraph unmarked because the vague generalisations and lack of examples mean that it's just padding.
