    Writing activity 21. Argument and evidence - relevance of content to question
        Task wordclick difficulty 2
        Task wordclick difficulty 2
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO  <font size="4">Essay title: Intertextuality and Influence: assess Roland Barthe's view that texts 'blend and clash' with reference to two works you have studied.<br /><br />Texts chosen: <span style="font-style: italic;">The Waste Land</span>, by T. S. Eliot and <span style="font-style: italic;">Wuthering Heights</span> by Emily Bronte.<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Read the essay title and then the following short paragraphs. In your view, are the paragraphs relevant or irrelevant? When you've decided, click on the text and see if your opinion agrees with ours. Each paragraph comes with an explanation, so it's worth browsing through them all.</font>
        ANSWER: Wuthering Heights is the only novel that Emily Bronte published.  She was one of the three famous Bronte sisters, the others being Charlotte and Anne.  To avoid the stigma attached to female writers, Emily published under the pseudonym Ellis Bell.
        FEEDBACK: None of this is relevant to the essay title.  The biographical details of authors are seldom relevant in themselves.  If a writer uses such details, he or she has to make them relevant by relating them directly to the essay title.
        ANSWER: The posthumous second edition of Wuthering Heights was revised by Charlotte, so although the book was written by Emily alone, the version we read is not solely Emily's work.  Charlotte could not be described as a co-author, but her influence, though hidden to the general reader, is evident throughout.
        FEEDBACK: This is relevant.  The writer is showing how, even in a work we associate entirely with one author, another author's influence is present.  The use of the word 'influence' links it directly to the essay title.
        ANSWER: Although James Joyce is not referenced by Eliot, his writing style, particularly in Ulysses, is echoed in The Waste Land.  James Joyce published Ulysses in 1922.  The book was divided into eighteen chapters or episodes, and the text attracted controversy right from the start.  There is no unified manuscript of Ulysses, with the result that the text, written in chaotic style, is also editorially chaotic.
        FEEDBACK: The reference to Ulysses is good, but the writer does not keep the reference focused, instead going off on a Joycean tangent.  None of the details about Ulysses are related back to the essay title, leaving the reader puzzled as to their relevance.  Always ask yourself:  what point am I trying to make?  Then make sure you you have actually made the point explicitly.  Your essay marker is not a mind-reader. 
        ANSWER: Even the title of The Waste Land is not original, but alludes to the old Arthurian legend, The Fisher King.  The king has, for whatever reason, become infertile and as a result, his kingdom is as infertile as he is.  To restore the kingdom's fertility, the king must wait for someone to come along and ask the right questions.  For Eliot, the world was similarly sterile.  Many fertile young men had been killed in the First World War, 150,000 on the Somme alone.  England seemed like a 'waste land'.
        FEEDBACK: The allusion to The Fisher King is good, but though the following sentences are not completely irrelevant, they drift.  The sentence 'For Eliot, the world was similarly sterile' starts to link back to the essay title, but then veers away.  The Somme statistic is unnecessary:  this is an essay about intertextuality.  Take care not to let your references control you rather than you controlling them.
    Writing activity 25. Structure - concluding lines
