<p class="MsoNormal"><font size="4" style="font-family: trebuchet ms,verdana,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;">Read the following essay title and then the concluding line(s) that are offered. Choose the concluding line(s) you think best. Each selection has an explanation, so even if your choice agrees with ours, it is worth browsing through them all.</font><o:p></o:p></p> <!--EndFragment--> 
        ANSWER: So, the American dream continues to haunt Americans. 'Bring me your huddled masses' is just as potent now as it ever was.  
        FEEDBACK: These lines are too general.  They give no clue as to what the essay was specifically about.
        ANSWER: The American story 'is the history of all aspiration - not just the American dream, but the human dream'.  Human beings are not perfect and every dream is corrupt.  That is what 20th century American literature teaches us.
        FEEDBACK: This quote should be attributed.  The rest of the ending isn't connected quite firmly enough to the essay title. 
        ANSWER: Thus we can see that 20th century American literature explores both the idea of unattainable perfection and the corrupt idea of the American Dream through total immersion.  Contemporary authors could not remain detached.  Of these authors, F. Scott Fitzgerald may be the most famous but, as this essay has shown, he was by no means alone.
        FEEDBACK: This is the best option.  It clinches the essay, referring directly to the title and to the material in the essay.  It finishes everything off neatly.
        ANSWER: 20th century American literature cannot help exploring the idea of an unattainable perfection and the corrupt idea of the American Dream.  I think it makes 20th century American literature interesting and readers can learn a lot from it.
        FEEDBACK: This option starts well but drifts off into the personal 'I think' and the colloquial 'can learn a lot from it'.  An academic essay should finish in an academic way.
