<p class="MsoNormal"><font size="4" style="font-family: trebuchet ms,verdana,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;">Read the following essay title and then the concluding line(s) that are offered. Choose the concluding line(s) you think best. Each selection has an explanation, so even if your choice agrees with ours, it is worth browsing through them all.</font><o:p></o:p></p> <!--EndFragment--> 
        ANSWER: As this essay has shown, Fitzgerald seems more concerned with manipulating the text to stand for ideas and opinions whilst Browning moulds characters and tells their story.  That two authors can use one literary medium to two such different effects very clearly demonstrates the power of an English language novel.
        FEEDBACK: Just reading these lines, you might think the essay question was on the power of the English novel rather than the relationship between the writers' opinions and their work.  A neat finish, but of the wrong essay?
        ANSWER: As this essay has shown, Fitzgerald's opinions, at least on the subject of money, are clearly related to his work, whereas the relationship between Browning's opinions and his work is rather more opaque.  As this essay has also shown, this is partly the difference between a novelist and a poet.  However, It is also clear that understanding this relationship is crucial to a full understanding of a text, which is why the study of a writer's life is so satisfying and productive. 
        FEEDBACK: These lines draw in the two chosen writers, contrasting them and then finishing with a closing statement that brings them together.  This is the best option.
        ANSWER: There is always something interesting about authors' opinions.  We all like to share what we think.  These days those of us who do not write books or poetry as Fitzgerald and Browning did, have access to Facebook and other social networking sites.  That way, we all know exactly where we stand.
        FEEDBACK: The first line here is fine but the writer has then wandered off.  Mentioning the two poets is good, but should be in the context of the content of the essay, not bringing in something new.  The last sentence has a sense of finality but is the wrong sentence for this essay.<br />
