<p class="MsoNormal"><font size="4" style="font-family: trebuchet ms,verdana,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;">Read the following essay title and then the concluding line(s) that are offered. Choose the concluding line(s) you think best. Each selection has an explanation, so even if your choice agrees with ours, it is worth browsing through them all.</font><o:p></o:p></p> <!--EndFragment--> 
        ANSWER: In the works of both Shakespeare and F. Scott Fitzgerald, we find role-playing and performance in all their many guises.  As this essay has shown, these devices are not just significant.  For plot and character development in both play and novel, performance and role-playing are vital. 
        FEEDBACK: This is the best option.  These lines refer directly to the essay question and to the two chosen authors. The last line makes a bold closing statement.
        ANSWER: Performance and role-playing in these two texts create more realistically complex and hard-to-decipher personalities.  Identity is irrevocably affected by the behaviour cause by the role-playing and the direct or indirect consequences which that behaviour had on the self.  In the end it is left up to the readers to speculate and use their own judgement to form their impression of each character's true self.
        FEEDBACK: These lines refer to words in the essay title but we then bump into the colloquialism of 'hard-to-decipher'.   The themes of the essay, for example, identity, may well be reprised, but not in the terms of the essay title.  The concluding line drifts off the point. 
        ANSWER: All life is a performance and it is no different in the works of Shakespeare and Fitzgerald.  Playing roles is what people do to get through life.  The characters Hamlet and Gatsby are made human by this.  It is why we are interested in them.
        FEEDBACK: These lines are more pub philosopher than academic essay writer.  It's so tempting to end an essay with a conceptual flourish.  Resist it.  It never works, not even when linked to two literary characters.
    Writing activity 24. Structure - linking lines
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <span style="font-family: trebuchet ms,verdana,arial,helvetica,sans-serif; font-weight: bold;">Final line:</span><br style="font-family: trebuchet ms,verdana,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;" /><br style="font-family: trebuchet ms,verdana,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;" /><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: trebuchet ms,verdana,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;">To develop these ideas further, I shall take Herbert%u2019s poem %u2018The Collar%u2019 and two of Donne%u2019s poems: %u2018A Hymn to God the Father%u2019 and %u2018Sonnet XIV%u2019.</span><!--EndFragment--> 
    QUESTION 0  <link rel="File-List" href="file://localhost/Users/katiegrant/Library/Caches/TemporaryItems/msoclip1/01/clip_filelist.xml" /><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> Normal 0 0 1 23 132 1 1 162 11.1282 </xml><![endif]--><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> 0 0 0 </xml><![endif]--><style>&lt;!-- /* Font Definitions */@font-face {font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; panose-1:0 2 2 6 3 5 4 5 2 3; mso-font-charset:0; mso-generic-font-family:auto; mso-font-pitch:variable; mso-font-signature:50331648 0 0 0 1 0;} /* Style Definitions */p.MsoNormal, li.MsoNormal, div.MsoNormal {mso-style-parent:&quot;&quot;; margin:0cm; margin-bottom:.0001pt; mso-pagination:widow-orphan; font-size:12.0pt; font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; mso-ansi-language:EN-GB;}table.MsoNormalTable {mso-style-parent:&quot;&quot;; font-size:10.0pt; font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;}@page Section1 {size:612.0pt 792.0pt; margin:72.0pt 90.0pt 72.0pt 90.0pt; mso-header-margin:36.0pt; mso-footer-margin:36.0pt; mso-paper-source:0;}div.Section1 {page:Section1;}--&gt;</style><!--StartFragment-->
<p> <font size="4">The example shows the final line(s) of a paragraph. Read the line(s), and then, from the options offered, choose the one you think is the best link to the next paragraph. All the options have explanations, so even if you find our preferred option quickly, it's worth browsing through the others. </font></p><!--EndFragment--> 
        ANSWER: Herbert purposefully names his poem 'The Collar' to provoke notions of repression and restraint.
        FEEDBACK: This is the best option.  The last line of the previous paragraph leads the reader to expect to read next about 'The Collar'.  The writer fulfils that expectation without any messing about.
        ANSWER: In the seventeenth century, poets often used religious imagery in their poems.
        FEEDBACK: This sentence may bear some relation to the essay, but it comes from nowhere.  It does not belong here.
        ANSWER: George Herbert was a poet who went to Trinity College, Cambridge.
        FEEDBACK: This is an entirely narrative line.  It does not further any idea.   The reader already knows that Herbert is a poet.  It jars.
        ANSWER: The opening line 'Batter my heart, three-person'd God' turns Donne's Sonnet XIV into a declaration of war.
        FEEDBACK: Had the final line listed Donne's Sonnet XIV first, i.e. before 'The Collar' and 'A Hymn to God the Father', this would have been a good link line.  As it is, it feels out of sequence.  If you make a list in your final line, unless you have very good reason not to, stick to the order.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: trebuchet ms,verdana,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;"><b>Final line: <br /><br /></b>Pip%u2019s childhood experiences have certainly helped to shape his adult self, but London is sure to shape him further.<span>&nbsp;</span></span><!--EndFragment--> 
    QUESTION 0  <link rel="File-List" href="file://localhost/Users/katiegrant/Library/Caches/TemporaryItems/msoclip1/01/clip_filelist.xml" /><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> Normal 0 0 1 23 132 1 1 162 11.1282 </xml><![endif]--><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> 0 0 0 </xml><![endif]--><style>&lt;!-- /* Font Definitions */@font-face {font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; panose-1:0 2 2 6 3 5 4 5 2 3; mso-font-charset:0; mso-generic-font-family:auto; mso-font-pitch:variable; mso-font-signature:50331648 0 0 0 1 0;} /* Style Definitions */p.MsoNormal, li.MsoNormal, div.MsoNormal {mso-style-parent:&quot;&quot;; margin:0cm; margin-bottom:.0001pt; mso-pagination:widow-orphan; font-size:12.0pt; font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; mso-ansi-language:EN-GB;}table.MsoNormalTable {mso-style-parent:&quot;&quot;; font-size:10.0pt; font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;}@page Section1 {size:612.0pt 792.0pt; margin:72.0pt 90.0pt 72.0pt 90.0pt; mso-header-margin:36.0pt; mso-footer-margin:36.0pt; mso-paper-source:0;}div.Section1 {page:Section1;}--&gt;</style><!--StartFragment-->
<p> <font size="4">The example shows the final line(s) of a paragraph. Read the line(s), and then, from the options offered, choose the one you think is the best link to the next paragraph. All the options have explanations, so even if you find our preferred option quickly, it's worth browsing through the others. </font></p><!--EndFragment--> 
        ANSWER: London features largely in Dickens' works because he both loved it and loathed it.
        FEEDBACK: This is not completely wrong, but reads a bit like padding.  You would need to demonstrate very quickly why you felt this information was relevant to your thesis.
        ANSWER: Pip is an orphan, who has seen his sister act with violence towards her gentle husband.
        FEEDBACK: This jolts.  It seems to bear no relation to what the reader has been led to expect.
        ANSWER: In London we see the first stirrings of an unbecoming snobbery in Pip.
        FEEDBACK: This relates directly to the final line. We see a repetition of 'London' in the context of Pip being 'shaped'.  It moves the essay on very smoothly.
        ANSWER: Great Expectations is set both in the country and the town.
        FEEDBACK: This is padding, and, not being what the reader expects, brings the essay to a halt rather than moving it on.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO  <span style="font-weight: bold;">Final line: </span><br /><br /><meta name="Title" /><meta name="Keywords" /><meta content="text/html; charset=utf-8" http-equiv="Content-Type" /><meta content="Word.Document" name="ProgId" /><meta content="Microsoft Word 11" name="Generator" /><meta content="Microsoft Word 11" name="Originator" /><link /><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> Normal 0 0 1 9 52 1 1 63 11.1282 </xml><![endif]--><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> 0 0 0 </xml><![endif]--><style>&lt;!-- /* Font Definitions */@font-face {font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; panose-1:0 2 2 6 3 5 4 5 2 3; mso-font-charset:0; mso-generic-font-family:auto; mso-font-pitch:variable; mso-font-signature:50331648 0 0 0 1 0;} /* Style Definitions */p.MsoNormal, li.MsoNormal, div.MsoNormal {mso-style-parent:&quot;&quot;; margin:0cm; margin-bottom:.0001pt; mso-pagination:widow-orphan; font-size:12.0pt; font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; mso-ansi-language:EN-GB;}table.MsoNormalTable {mso-style-parent:&quot;&quot;; font-size:10.0pt; font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;}@page Section1 {size:612.0pt 792.0pt; margin:72.0pt 90.0pt 72.0pt 90.0pt; mso-header-margin:36.0pt; mso-footer-margin:36.0pt; mso-paper-source:0;}div.Section1 {page:Section1;}--&gt;</style><!--StartFragment--> On both sides there is a clear attachment to personal wealth. <!--EndFragment--> 
