<p> <font size="4">The example shows the final line(s) of a paragraph. Read the line(s), and then, from the options offered, choose the one you think is the best link to the next paragraph. All the options have explanations, so even if you find our preferred option quickly, it's worth browsing through the others. </font></p><!--EndFragment--> 
        ANSWER: The Great Gatsby is narrated by Nick Carraway.
        FEEDBACK: This sentence may have a place in the essay, but not here.  It bears no relation to the final line of the previous paragraph.
        ANSWER: Fitzgerald, whose wealthy lifestyle bore little relation to his actual bank balance, tells Gatsby's story on many different levels.
        FEEDBACK: This sentence echoes the idea of wealth, but in a different context.  It leaves the reader floundering.
        ANSWER: Part of the American Dream is to acquire massive wealth and then retire.
        FEEDBACK: This sentence echoes 'wealth' but in an unrelated context.  The reader is brought up short instead of eased along.
        ANSWER: Wealth plays a central role in this novel.
        FEEDBACK: This is the best option because this sentence echoes the final line and states something useful.  To be fully effective, the next sentence must provide clear evidence.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <meta name="Title" /><meta name="Keywords" /><meta content="text/html; charset=utf-8" http-equiv="Content-Type" /><meta content="Word.Document" name="ProgId" /><meta content="Microsoft Word 11" name="Generator" /><meta content="Microsoft Word 11" name="Originator" /><link href="file://localhost/Users/katiegrant/Library/Caches/TemporaryItems/msoclip1/01/clip_filelist.xml" rel="File-List" /><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> Normal 0 0 1 19 110 1 1 135 11.1282 </xml><![endif]--><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> 0 0 0 </xml><![endif]--><style>&lt;!-- /* Font Definitions */@font-face {font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; panose-1:0 2 2 6 3 5 4 5 2 3; mso-font-charset:0; mso-generic-font-family:auto; mso-font-pitch:variable; mso-font-signature:50331648 0 0 0 1 0;} /* Style Definitions */p.MsoNormal, li.MsoNormal, div.MsoNormal {mso-style-parent:&quot;&quot;; margin:0cm; margin-bottom:.0001pt; mso-pagination:widow-orphan; font-size:12.0pt; font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; mso-ansi-language:EN-GB;}table.MsoNormalTable {mso-style-parent:&quot;&quot;; font-size:10.0pt; font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;}@page Section1 {size:612.0pt 792.0pt; margin:72.0pt 90.0pt 72.0pt 90.0pt; mso-header-margin:36.0pt; mso-footer-margin:36.0pt; mso-paper-source:0;}div.Section1 {page:Section1;}--&gt;</style><!--StartFragment-->
<p><strong>Final line:</strong> <br /> </p>
<p> The concept of possession is so important in <i>The Great Gatsby</i> that whoever %u2018has%u2019 Daisy is deemed to have the upper hand.</p><!--EndFragment--> 
    QUESTION 0  <link rel="File-List" href="file://localhost/Users/katiegrant/Library/Caches/TemporaryItems/msoclip1/01/clip_filelist.xml" /><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> Normal 0 0 1 23 132 1 1 162 11.1282 </xml><![endif]--><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> 0 0 0 </xml><![endif]--><style>&lt;!-- /* Font Definitions */@font-face {font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; panose-1:0 2 2 6 3 5 4 5 2 3; mso-font-charset:0; mso-generic-font-family:auto; mso-font-pitch:variable; mso-font-signature:50331648 0 0 0 1 0;} /* Style Definitions */p.MsoNormal, li.MsoNormal, div.MsoNormal {mso-style-parent:&quot;&quot;; margin:0cm; margin-bottom:.0001pt; mso-pagination:widow-orphan; font-size:12.0pt; font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; mso-ansi-language:EN-GB;}table.MsoNormalTable {mso-style-parent:&quot;&quot;; font-size:10.0pt; font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;}@page Section1 {size:612.0pt 792.0pt; margin:72.0pt 90.0pt 72.0pt 90.0pt; mso-header-margin:36.0pt; mso-footer-margin:36.0pt; mso-paper-source:0;}div.Section1 {page:Section1;}--&gt;</style><!--StartFragment-->
<p> <font size="4">The example shows the final line(s) of a paragraph. Read the line(s), and then, from the options offered, choose the one you think is the best link to the next paragraph. All the options have explanations, so even if you find our preferred option quickly, it's worth browsing through the others. </font></p><!--EndFragment--> 
        ANSWER: Possession, not just in its ordinary sense but also in the sense of people possessing each other, fascinated Fitzgerald.
        FEEDBACK: This is the best option.  It echoes both the words and the theme of the final line of the previous paragraph and broadens the topic out.  
        ANSWER: Nicole represents America in Fitzgerald's Tender is the Night.
        FEEDBACK: This jolts, since it bears no relation to the final line.  A new topic is fine, but must be linked to the previous topic.
        ANSWER: The Great Gatsby was the third of Fitzgerald's novels to be published.
        FEEDBACK: This is in danger of being irrelevant.  However, if this is the first time The Great Gatsby is mentioned by name, and the writer goes on to explain the reference to Daisy and possession, then the link would be made.
        ANSWER: The American Dream is challenged in The Great Gatsby.
        FEEDBACK: Unless the American Dream has been mentioned specifically in the previous paragraph, and in the context of possession, this is in danger of jolting the reader.
    Writing activity 23. Structure - opening lines
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO Essay title:<br /><br />In what way does 20th century American literature explore the idea of an unattainable perfection and the corrupt idea of the American Dream?<br /> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: trebuchet ms,verdana,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;">Choose the opening line or lines most appropriate to the essay title set. Every choice has an explanation, so if you find our preferred option quickly, it is still worth browsing through them all. The same essay title may be used more than once.</span></font><!--EndFragment--> 
        ANSWER: The American Dream has been the inspiration for many writers drawn to the United States to live and work.
        FEEDBACK: This option is too general.  If were deleted, it would not be missed.
        ANSWER: There has never been such a thing as the American Dream.  It is a construct dreamed up by newspapers.
        FEEDBACK: This option does not relate to the question.
        ANSWER: In his essay 'The Evolving American Dream:  The Pursuit of Happiness' in 'Gatsby, Tender is the Night and the Last Tycoon', John F. Callahan states that the author F. Scott Fitzgerald 'embodied in his tissues and nervous system the fluid polarities of the American experience:  success and failure, illusion and disillusion;  dream and nightmare'.
        FEEDBACK: This is the best option.  It is directly relevant to the essay title, addressing both sides of the question:  20th century American literature and the American Dream.
        ANSWER: According to Wikipedia, the American Dream is a 'national ethos of the United States of America in which democratic ideals are perceived as a promise of prosperity for its people. In the American Dream, first expressed by James Truslow Adams in 1931, citizens of every rank feel that they can achieve a "better, richer, and happier life'.
        FEEDBACK: Wikipedia is never a good place to start.  What's more, if you are going to define the American Dream, it's important to define it in relation to the essay question and not just give a blank definition.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO 'My future husband was becoming to me my whole world; and more than the world, almost my hope of heaven. He stood between me and every thought of religion, as an eclipse intervenes between man and the broad sun. I could not, in those days, see God for his creature, of whom I had made an idol.' (Charlotte Bronte, from <span style="font-style: italic;">Jane Eyre</span>). Discuss the relationship between the self and religion. 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: trebuchet ms,verdana,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;">Choose the opening line or lines most appropriate to the essay title set. Every choice has an explanation, so if you find our preferred option quickly, it is still worth browsing through them all. The same essay title may be used more than once.</span></font><!--EndFragment--> 
        ANSWER: The relationship between the self and religion is one of reliance and balance.  A religious experience could alter the self, while the self could alter perceptions of religion.
        FEEDBACK: These lines are the best option.  They get straight to the point.  It is clear what the essay title is and that the writer has thought about a snappy and arresting opening.
        ANSWER: A relationship between the self and religion has existed since the introduction of Christianity.   In Britain 72% of the population is Christian but only 10% attend church.
        FEEDBACK: These lines echo the words of the title, but go off at a tangent.  These statistics are entirely irrelevant.
        ANSWER: 'Religion is the opiate of the people,' said Karl Marx, which, for some, also defines the relationship between religion and self.
        FEEDBACK: This line echoes the language of the title but uses an irrelevant quotation.
        ANSWER: I am no longer religious because, like Jane Eyre, I found the relationship between religion and self confusing.
        FEEDBACK: The use of 'I' is frowned on in an academic essay, and personal reminiscences are inappropriate in an academic essay.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <span style="font-weight: bold;">Essay title:</span> 'Ours was the marsh country, down by the river, within, as the river wound, twenty miles of the sea. My first most vivid and broad impression of the identity of things, seems to me to have been gained on a memorable raw afternoon towards evening.' (Charles Dickens, from <span style="font-style: italic;">Great Expectations</span>). Discuss the ways in which two authors on this course depict the relationship between the external environment and the self. 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: trebuchet ms,verdana,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;">Choose the opening line or lines most appropriate to the essay title set. Every choice has an explanation, so if you find our preferred option quickly, it is still worth browsing through them all. The same essay title may be used more than once.</span></font><!--EndFragment--> 
        ANSWER: The relationship between our internal self and external environment can take on various forms, effects and purposes.
        FEEDBACK: This isn't bad, although some marker might think it just states the obvious.
        ANSWER: We are all born somewhere, and where that somewhere is clearly affects the person we turn out to be.
        FEEDBACK: This is a broad and highly questionable generalisation.  My husband was born in Kuala Lumpur, which bears no relation to the person he is now.  In any case, such a generalisation has no place in an academic essay.
        ANSWER: In both Charlotte Bronte's Jane Eyre and Charles Dickens' Great Expectations, the relationship between the external environment an the self is a crucial authorial device. 
        FEEDBACK: This sentence both names the chosen authors and opens up a discussion.  This is the best option.
        ANSWER: I think that the environment into which authors pitch their characters is one of the things a reader notices first.
        FEEDBACK: This assertion is questionable, and the 'I think' makes this opening far too conversational.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <meta name="Title" /><meta name="Keywords" /><meta content="text/html; charset=utf-8" http-equiv="Content-Type" /><meta content="Word.Document" name="ProgId" /><meta content="Microsoft Word 11" name="Generator" /><meta content="Microsoft Word 11" name="Originator" /><link href="file://localhost/Users/katiegrant/Library/Caches/TemporaryItems/msoclip1/01/clip_filelist.xml" rel="File-List" /><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> Normal 0 0 1 19 109 1 1 133 11.1282 </xml><![endif]--><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> 0 0 0 </xml><![endif]--><style>&lt;!-- /* Font Definitions */@font-face {font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; panose-1:0 2 2 6 3 5 4 5 2 3; mso-font-charset:0; mso-generic-font-family:auto; mso-font-pitch:variable; mso-font-signature:50331648 0 0 0 1 0;} /* Style Definitions */p.MsoNormal, li.MsoNormal, div.MsoNormal {mso-style-parent:&quot;&quot;; margin:0cm; margin-bottom:.0001pt; mso-pagination:widow-orphan; font-size:12.0pt; font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; mso-ansi-language:EN-GB;}table.MsoNormalTable {mso-style-parent:&quot;&quot;; font-size:10.0pt; font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;}@page Section1 {size:612.0pt 792.0pt; margin:72.0pt 90.0pt 72.0pt 90.0pt; mso-header-margin:36.0pt; mso-footer-margin:36.0pt; mso-paper-source:0;}div.Section1 {page:Section1;}--&gt;</style><!--StartFragment-->
<p><strong>Essay title:</strong></p> With reference to any two authors on this course, discuss the importance of family in defining or shaping the self. <!--EndFragment--> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: trebuchet ms,verdana,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;">Choose the opening line or lines most appropriate to the essay title set. Every choice has an explanation, so if you find our preferred option quickly, it is still worth browsing through them all. The same essay title may be used more than once.</span></font><!--EndFragment--> 
        ANSWER: Family life has always been important to authors.  It is where many get their inspiration from. 
        FEEDBACK: two mass generalisations, with no supporting evidence and only the vaguest connection to the question.  It is clumsy to finish a sentence with the preposition 'from' (see danglers elsewhere on this site).  
        ANSWER: There are few authors for whom the importance of family is more crucial in the defining or shaping of the self than Charles Dickens and Seamus Heaney.
        FEEDBACK: This is the best option. It starts with a confident bang.  The writer gets straight into the question.  
        ANSWER: When authors talk about defining or shaping the self, they often draw on their own upbringing.  
        FEEDBACK: This sentence is far too general.  If it were removed, would it be missed?  Not really.
        ANSWER: To answer this question, I'm going to use F. Scott Fitzgerald and Charlotte Bronte.
        FEEDBACK: This is both too abrupt and too colloquial.  It does present information, but the style is aggressive, not academic.  In addition, the personal 'I' is best avoided in academic essays.  Markers are looking for objectivity.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <p><strong>Essay title:</strong></p>
<p>%u2018My future husband was becoming to me my whole world; and more than the world: almost my hope of heaven. He stood between me and every thought of religion, as an eclipse intervenes between man and the broad sun. I could not, in those days, see God for his creature: of whom I had made an idol.%u2019 </p> Discuss the relationship between the self and religion in two texts you have chosen. <!--EndFragment--> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: trebuchet ms,verdana,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;">Choose the opening line or lines most appropriate to the essay title set. Every choice has an explanation, so if you find our preferred option quickly, it is still worth browsing through them all. The same essay title may be used more than once.</span></font><!--EndFragment--> 
        ANSWER: In discussing the relationship between the self and religion, I shall use Charlotte Bronte's Jane Eyre and Shakespeare's Hamlet, within these two texts I shall evaluate the impact of religion on the self, and the development of the self that occurs through a relationship with religion.
        FEEDBACK: Apart from identifying the texts, this over-long sentence adds little to the opening of this essay.  It simply restates the question in different ways.
        ANSWER: There can be no doubt that in Charlotte Bronte's Jane Eyre and in Shakespeare's Hamlet, the relationship between the self and religion plays a prominent role.   Bronte suggests that Mr. Rochester is becoming, or becomes, almost holy.  She questions God indirectly and more directly throughout the novel.  Jane is surrounded by individuals of different beliefs.
        FEEDBACK: This starts well.  The first sentence is bold and arresting. It then wanders off into Jane Eyre, making no distinction between real author and fictional heroine, leaving the reader puzzled. 
        ANSWER: The relationship between self and religion is fundamental to two classic but very different texts, Charlotte Bronte's nineteenth century novel, Jane Eyre, and Shakespeare's sixteenth century play, Hamlet.  This essay will use both texts to demonstrate how religion, and crucially, its loss, alters the sense these very different characters have of themselves, thus linking Jane and Hamlet in unexpected ways.  The case must not be overstated.  However, this essay ... 
        FEEDBACK: This is the best option.  The opening sentence is short but full of information, and is followed by an exposition of the essay's thesis.  In an interesting twist, the author demonstrates an awareness that her thesis may be overblown, but also a confidence that she can carry the reader along.   Awareness and confidence are attractive in opening lines. 
        ANSWER: A relationship between the self and religion has existed for as long as historical record has been able to evidence it.  Over the centuries, since the introduction of Christianity, its role within countries, communities and the lives of individuals has been constantly changing.  In 2008, 33% of the world claimed to be Christian.
        FEEDBACK: This might be a decent essay opening, but not for this essay.  Every single piece of information is irrelevant.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: trebuchet ms,verdana,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;"><b>Essay title:<span>&nbsp;</span></b><br /><br />How does anticipation of death shape the self in the works of two writers you are studying.<span>&nbsp;</span></span><!--EndFragment--> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: trebuchet ms,verdana,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;">Choose the opening line or lines most appropriate to the essay title set. Every choice has an explanation, so if you find our preferred option quickly, it is still worth browsing through them all. The same essay title may be used more than once.</span></font><!--EndFragment--> 
        ANSWER: Death comes to us all.  That is a fact of life.  Every day we live is a day nearer to death.   Anticipation of death is, as far as we know, restricted to mankind, which is perhaps why we draw, paint, write or make music.
        FEEDBACK: Too much flannel here.  Ask yourself, with reference to the essay title, 'if these sentences were deleted, would they be missed?'  The answer is no.  General, all-embracing and clichd comments have no place in an academic essay.
        ANSWER: Hamlet by William Shakespeare and assorted poems by the poet Robert Browning deal very closely with the idea of the anticipation of death.
        FEEDBACK: This gets halfway to the point but 'assorted poems' is incorrect in this context.  You need to offer named examples.  There is no mention of 'self'.
        ANSWER: Anticipation of death is central to the definition of the self in the poems of both George Herbert and John Donne.
        FEEDBACK: This is the best option.  It gets directly to the heart of the question and introduces the chosen authors neatly.
        ANSWER: In the poem 'Life', George Herbert asserts that he is not concerned when death will strike as long as his life is considered 'good' in the eyes of God.
        FEEDBACK: This sentence might be appropriate further into the essay.  The opening sentence needs to introduce the two writers you have chosen and link them directly to the essay question.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <span style="font-weight: bold;">Essay title:</span><br /><br />HAMLET: He that plays the King shall be welcome [...] (William Shakespeare, Hamlet, Act 2, scene 2). Discuss the significance of role-playing or performance in the work of two of the authors you have studied on the course.<br /> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: trebuchet ms,verdana,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;">Choose the opening line or lines most appropriate to the essay title set. Every choice has an explanation, so if you find our preferred option quickly, it is still worth browsing through them all. The same essay title may be used more than once.</span></font><!--EndFragment--> 
        ANSWER: Performance, or role-playing, is a prolific function in both the drama of Hamlet and the poetry of John Donne.
        FEEDBACK: This opening line, though it does mention the two texts chosen, doesn't make much sense.  Prolific function?  Make sure your opening line is clear and unambiguous.
        ANSWER: The function of role-playing is of vital significance in literature.  
        FEEDBACK: This may be true, but should perhaps be shown through the essay and used in the conclusion rather than just stated at the outset.
        ANSWER: The Oxford English Dictionary defines role-playing as "the changing of one's behaviour to fulfil a social role".  In literature, though, I think it's often the rejection of a role that makes us warm to the characters.
        FEEDBACK: Try not to start with a dictionary definition.  'I think it's' is too colloquial.  A general mention of 'literature' is often a waste.  Better to reveal the texts you are going to use.  
        ANSWER: Role playing and performance are not quite the same thing.  Tough both are of central significance in the two texts chosen for this essay, Shakespeare's Hamlet and Charlotte Bronte's Jane Eyre, the differences soon become apparent.
        FEEDBACK: This is the best option. The opening sentence is short, bold and addresses the essay title directly.  The writer offers a potentially interesting thesis.  The chosen texts are quickly identified and the lines carry a forward momentum.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title:<br /><br />Discuss how anticipation of death defines or shapes the self.</font><br /> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: trebuchet ms,verdana,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;">Choose the opening line or lines most appropriate to the essay title set. Every choice has an explanation, so if you find our preferred option quickly, it is still worth browsing through them all. The same essay title may be used more than once.</span></font><!--EndFragment--> 
        ANSWER: George Herbert and John Donne are two poets most commonly associated with the metaphysical style of poetry.
        FEEDBACK: This opening line is clear and crisp but bears no relation to the essay title.  It's very important that your essay relates to the title right from the start.
        ANSWER: William Shakespeare's Hamlet and assorted poems by Robert Browning deal closely with the idea of the anticipation of death.
        FEEDBACK: This opening is weakened by the phrase 'assorted poems', which has no place in an academic essay.  Name the poems.
        ANSWER: Anticipation of death is the driving force behind both Shakespeare's Hamlet and Robert Browning's 'The Bishop Orders his Tomb at St. Praxted's Church'.
        FEEDBACK: This is the best option. Clear, with the beginnings of an argument - the writer will have to prove this assertion - this line launches us neatly into the essay.
        ANSWER: 'To die, to sleep' says Hamlet.  I think this shows an anticipation of death, which shaped Hamlet's self.
        FEEDBACK: Fine to use a quotation (make sure it is properly referenced in a footnote), but the rather simplistic use made of the quotation here, plus the use of the personal 'I' makes this an unconvincing start.
    Writing activity 22. Argument and evidence - insertion of quotations and referencing style
        Task freetext difficulty 1
        Task freetext difficulty 2
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
