<p class="MsoNormal"><font size="4"><span lang="EN-US">As we are reminded in Graves and Hodge's <u>The Reader Over Your Shoulder</u>, <o:p></o:p></span></font></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-left: 36pt;"><font size="4"><i><span lang="EN-US">&quot;the word 'vocabulary', where it does not mean 'the range of language' means 'the sum of words in a language'.<sup>2</sup><span> </span>Thus, 'it (the language) ever expands.</span></i><sup><span lang="EN-US">3</span></sup></font><span lang="EN-US"><font size="4">'</font><o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><b><span lang="EN-US"><o:p> </o:p></span></b></p> <!--EndFragment--> 
    QUESTION 0 In the book title The Reader Over Your Shoulder, are the capital letters correct?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: No, they're not:  'over' and 'your' should not be capitalised.  Go to the 'formatting - capitals' section of this site for more information.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: That's correct:  'over' and 'your' should not be capitalised.  Go to the 'formatting - capitals' section of this site for more information.
    QUESTION 1 Should the book title The Reader over your Shoulder be underlined?  If not, how should it be formatted?
        ANSWER: No, it should not be underlined.  The title should be italicised.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  Book titles, journal titles, long poem titles and the titles of individually published works should be italicised.
        ANSWER: Yes, underlining is fine.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  Book titles, journal titles, long poem titles and the titles of individually published works should be italicised.
    QUESTION 2 Should this quotation be italicised, enclosed within quotation marks and indented?
        ANSWER: It should be in plain font but indented and within quotation marks.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  Long quotations are indented (though an indented quotation needs to be over 3 lines long).  Indented quotations ARE NOT also enclosed in quotation marks.
        ANSWER: It should be italicised and indented, but does not need quotation marks.
        FEEDBACK: It's true that long quotations are indented (though an indented quotation needs to be over 3 lines long).  However, indented quotations ARE NOT italicised or enclosed in quotation marks.
        ANSWER: This quotation should not be indented or italicised, but should be part of the text and enclosed in quotation marks.
        FEEDBACK: Correct. It's true that long quotations are indented, but an indented quotation needs to be over 3 lines long and this one is not, so should be run into the text and enclosed in quotation marks.  Indented quotations ARE NOT enclosed in quotation marks.
    QUESTION 3 Are the quotation marks correctly used here?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  They are the wrong way round.  Single quotation marks are used for quotations, and double used for quotations within quotations.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  They are the wrong way round.  Single quotation marks are used for quotations, and double used for quotations within quotations.
    QUESTION 4 Should the brackets round (language) be round, as here, or square?
        ANSWER: Round.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  If you insert something into a quotation, you use square brackets.  Square brackets show that it's your insertion, and not part of the quotation.
        ANSWER: Square.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  If you insert something into a quotation, you use square brackets.  Square brackets show that it's your insertion, and not part of the quotation.
    QUESTION 5 Which footnote number, 2 or 3, is correctly placed?
        ANSWER: 2
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  The footnote number comes after the final punctuation, in this case the full stop.
        ANSWER: 3
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  The footnote number is placed after the final punctuation;  in this case a full stop.
    QUESTION 6 Should closing quotation marks before footnote 2 come before or after the final full stop?
        ANSWER: Before.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.   If the quotation is part of a bigger sentence, the closing quotation mark comes before the full stop, as the quotation is part of the sentence.  The closing quotation mark comes after the full stop if the quotation is a whole sentence in itself. 
        ANSWER: After.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  If the quotation is part of a bigger sentence, the closing quotation mark comes before the full stop, as the quotation is part of the sentence.  The closing quotation mark comes after the full stop if the quotation is a whole sentence in itself.
