    Writing activity 19. Hello and goodbye - how to start and finish letters
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">Can you match these salutations with the appropriate sign off?</font> 
    QUESTION 0 Dear Mrs. Grant,
        ANSWER: Yours faithfully,
        FEEDBACK: No - Yours faithfully is only used when the salutation is Dear Sir or Dear Madam (i.e. not named).
        ANSWER: Yours ever,
        FEEDBACK: This is a first letter, so this is too informal.
        ANSWER: Very best,
        FEEDBACK: This is more appropriate for an email.
        ANSWER: Yours sincerely,
        FEEDBACK: Yes. This is the most appropriate for a letter beginning 'Dear Mrs. Grant,'.
    QUESTION 1 Dear Sir,
        ANSWER: Yours faithfully,
        FEEDBACK: That's correct.  We use 'Yours faithfully' with 'Dear Sir' or 'Dear Madam' (i.e. to an unnamed correspondent).
        ANSWER: Yours sincerely,
        FEEDBACK: No - we use 'Yours sincerely,' with a named person, e.g. 'Dear Mr. Carnforth,'.  Try again.
        ANSWER: With best regards,
        FEEDBACK: No - 'With best regards' is too informal to write when the correspondent is not even named.  Try again.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Can you choose the right salutation for the following sign off phrases?</font>
    QUESTION 0 Yours sincerely,
        ANSWER: Dear Anne Jones,
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  We use 'Yours sincerely' to a formally named person.
        ANSWER: Dear Madam,
        FEEDBACK: No - we use 'Yours faithfully,' if the correspondent is not named.
        ANSWER: Dear John,
        FEEDBACK: You might use 'Yours sincerely' if you didn't know him very well.  But if you are on first name terms, have had a protracted exchange of letters, and particularly if you've met, then you might move to 'Yours ever,'.  This would be very rare with a potential employer.
    QUESTION 1 Yours faithfully,
        ANSWER: Dear Sir,
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  We use 'Yours faithfully,' when the correspondent is not named.
        ANSWER: Dear Lord Sugar,
        FEEDBACK: No - we only use 'Yours faithfully,' when the correspondent is not named.  Try again.
        ANSWER: Dear Prime Minister,
        FEEDBACK: No - we only use 'Yours faithfully,' when the correspondent is not named.  Try again.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Which of the examples is the best start to a covering letter?</font>
    QUESTION 0 Dear Mrs. McGrath,
        ANSWER: Hello.  I'm really interested in your company and especially the job advert posted on the university website.  
        FEEDBACK: Not a good choice!  There could hardly be a more unprofessional beginning to a letter.  'Hello' is too chatty.  The letter has a gushing start.  If you're replying to a job advertisment (always spell out advertisement in full) then say so at once.
        ANSWER: I would like to apply for the job advertised on the university website.
        FEEDBACK: This is calm, quiet and clear.  The best choice on offer here.
        ANSWER: I think I'm highly qualified  and suitable for the job advertised on the university website.
        FEEDBACK: This sounds arrogant and unprofessional.  Your CV will show your qualifications and the employer will judge your suitability.  Not a good choice.
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Which of these covering letter opening sentences is likely to be most attractive to an employer?</font>
    QUESTION 0 
        ANSWER: I am writing about the fantastic job opportunity advertised in the Times.  It has been my life's ambition to work in your company.  If you employ me, you will not regret it.
        FEEDBACK: This is a very overblown response, even if the opportunity really was marvellous.  A potential employer might think you were being ironic.  You need to temper your enthusiasm with professionalism.  Not the best choice here.
        ANSWER: I am writing to apply for the post of junior marketing manager, as advertised in the Times.  I fully appreciate that opportunities to work in companies of such standing do not arise often, and hope that you will find my attached CV of interest. 
        FEEDBACK: This response is keen, but also polite.  I think an employer would appreciate the determined but respectful tone.
        ANSWER: Attaching my CV in response to your advert in the Times.  Hope to hear from you soon.
        FEEDBACK: This is very peremptory and careless.  It would probably hit the bin without the CV being read at all.
