        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">Which of the following salutations and sign offs are correctly paired?</font>
    QUESTION 0 
        ANSWER: Dear Karen,  Yours sincerely,
        FEEDBACK: Correct.
        ANSWER: Dear Lady Bain, Yours faithfully,
        FEEDBACK: Incorrectly.  We only use 'Yours faithfully' to an unnamed correspondent (usually after Dear Sir or Dear Madam).
        ANSWER: Dear Mr. McNeil, With best regards,
        FEEDBACK: In the context of a job application, this would be incorrect.  Use the formal 'Yours sincerely,'.
        ANSWER: Dear Kirsty Hamilton, Yours faithfully,
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  We only use 'Yours faithfully,' when the correspondent is unnamed.  We need 'Yours sincerely,' here.
    Writing activity 17b. Articulating your skills: competency statements
        Task freetext difficulty 2
        Task freetext difficulty 2
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO Employers often ask 'what is your greatest weakness and can you demonstrate how you overcome it'. What would be a good opening sentence for your answer? 
    QUESTION 0 
        ANSWER: I don't have any weaknesses.
        FEEDBACK: Not even tempting!
        ANSWER: I have many weaknesses but work hard at them all.
        FEEDBACK: Aaah!  No!
        ANSWER: I recognise that I'm very bad at time-keeping.
        FEEDBACK: I wouldn't go for this one.  To many employers, time-keeping is key.  Make sure it's not a weakness.
        ANSWER: I used to find asking for clarification if I didn't understand an instruction first time intimidating, but I've developed a phrase to use to get me over that hump.
        FEEDBACK: This option is the best on offer here, and not a bad one either.  It shows that once you've recognised a weakness, you set about adopting a strategy to overcome it.  The weakness itself is well chosen.  Many employers will have experienced it themselves.  A shared weakness is often a bond, not a barrier.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO  <font size="4">From the options given, choose the best answer to the competency-based question 'Can you demonstrate how you cope with major change?'. </font> 
    QUESTION 0 
        ANSWER: Change is always a challenge.  A major change for me was moving to university far from my home town.  I joined clubs (swimming, debating, history), volunteered and sat in the common room rather than my bedroom.  I learned that getting over the challenges of change are as much down to your own efforts as the efforts of other people.
        FEEDBACK: This is a good reply.  It describes a real situation and what was learned from it.
    QUESTION 1 
        ANSWER: I've experienced a lot of change.  We've moved house many times because of my dad's work.  I've been to five different schools, but my results never suffered.
        FEEDBACK: This is a poor option.  A situation is described, but not the kind of learning process an employer wants to see.
    QUESTION 2 
        ANSWER: Change is a challenge.  I understand that you need to be very open to it and decide to embrace it in order to be successful in today's world.
        FEEDBACK: This is a bland statement of the obvious.  It would not impress an employer.  Not a good option.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">From the options offered, which is the best response to the question 'What value does your university degree bring to an employer?' <br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 
        ANSWER: University is where you discover yourself and learn to stand on your own two feet.
        FEEDBACK: Not an attractive option for an employer.  You don't need to go to university to achieve either of these cliched attributes.
        ANSWER: My university degree was in history, and over my four years I learned to think clearly, communicate effectively and to understand the value of feedback and reflection.  In first year, I also did a course in astronomy so learned to adapt to different academic requirements.  University also taught me how to set and achieve high goals. 
        FEEDBACK: This answer rings at least six key bells for employers.  This is the best option here.
        ANSWER: During my time at university I studied physics and was also was a member of the rugby club and debated for the university.  I also volunteered in the student counselling service and learned to drive the university mini-bus.
        FEEDBACK: Just listing what you did is pointless if you don't also point out the value.  Studying physics at university makes you meticulous, inquiring, investigative.  Rbgy involves team-building.  Counselling develops listening skills.  Driving the university mini-bus is evidence of responsibility and trustworthiness.  An employer won't work these things out for him/herself.  It's up to you to articulate the skills you've learned and the value of those skills.
