        FEEDBACK: It wouldn't be wrong to put 'the' in front of both those nouns, but it's not strictly necessary.  We can use 'invitations' and 'drink' as a concept or something specific in this instance.  There are two other words which definitely need 'the'.
        ANSWER: In front of 'Sixth Year' and 'license'.
        FEEDBACK: Yes, that's right.  We need 'the' because these are two very specific things: the Sixth Year Year book; and the license for this particular event.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <p><font size="4">Extract from a personal statement:</font></p>
<p><font size="4">I am an experienced administrator, having had the summer work in office ofSchool of Psychology at University of Glasgow. I also organised Study Day event, linkingup for project withthe students at Strathclyde University.</font></p>
    QUESTION 0 Is 'the' properly used for the names of the universities, i.e. 'at University of Glasgow'; and 'at the Strathclyde University'?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  We need 'at the University of Glasgow', since this phrase describes a particular university.  Q - the university of where? A - the University of Glasgow.  We do not need 'the' in front of Strathclyde University, as this is a plain name, like Jane Smith or Yan Hui.
        ANSWER: It doesn't matter.
        FEEDBACK: It always matters.  Try again.
    QUESTION 1 Is it right, in this context, to use 'the' in front of 'summer work' and in front of 'students'?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again.<br />
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  'Summer work' is actually a concept, rather than a specific.  A specific reference would be 'the summer clearout' or 'the summer recruitment drive'.  We don't need 'the' in front of 'students' because you're not referring to all the students at Strathclyde University: you're referring to some of the students, so it's more accurate just to say 'students'.  <br />
        ANSWER: It doesn't matter.
        FEEDBACK: It always matters.  Try again.
    QUESTION 2 Apart from the 'the' in front of 'University of Glasgow' there are three other missing instances of 'the'.  Where should they go?
        ANSWER: In front of 'office; in front of 'School of Psychology'; and in front of 'project'.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  These are all specific references.  Q:  which office?  A: the office of the School of PsychologyQ: which school? A:  the School of Psychology.  We need 'the' in front of project because it is a particular project, i.e. a Study Day event.
    QUESTION 3 Should there be an article in front of 'Study Day event', and if so, what should it be?
        ANSWER: No article needed.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again.<br />
        ANSWER: We need 'the'.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  We do need an article, but not 'the'.  We'd need 'the' if the Study Day event was given a specific time and day, i.e. 'the Study Day event on 14th December'. <br />
        ANSWER: We need 'a'.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  We are referring in general terms to a Study Day event, of which the particulars are not yet known. <br />
