INTRO <p><font size="4">From a CV:</font></p>
<p><font size="4">2009 - 2010 MSc Electronics Design, the University of Glasgow</font></p>
<p><font size="4">2005 - 2009 B.E. Electronics and Communications, Vivera Technological University, Singapore</font></p>
<p><font size="4">Dissertation:</font></p>
<p><font size="4">The design of a stockcontrol system for a publishing warehouse.</font></p>
    QUESTION 0 Do you need to say 'the University of Glasgow' in a CV?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  In a CV, we pare down to the basics, almost to note form, so we leave out articles.  In a letter, where complete sentences are required, we would use 'the University of Glasgow'.
        ANSWER: It doesn't matter.
        FEEDBACK: It always matters. Try again.
    QUESTION 1 In a CV, do we need articles in the dissertation description?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again.<br />
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  In a CV, we pare down, and leave out the articles.  This gives a CV a different tone from a covering letter or personal statement, where whole sentences are used.  Whole sentences need appropriately used articles.  For a CV, the text should read:  Design of stock control system for publishing warehouse.<br />
        ANSWER: You can choose.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  For a maximum impact CV you need to get the tone right.  Try again.
