    Writing activity 03. Capitals
        Task freetext difficulty 1
        Task wordclick difficulty 2
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">My interest is in Psychological theories, in particular theories about Alzheimer's disease and the differences between this Vascular Dementia.</font>
    QUESTION 0 Should 'Psychological' be capitalised?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  In this context, 'psychological' is an adjective.  Q: what kind of theories?  A: psychological.  Adjectives don't need capitals unless in titles, e.g. A. Curran's book, Psychological Insights.
        ANSWER: It doesn't matter.
        FEEDBACK: There are some instances where you can choose whether to capitalise or not, but this isn't one of them.  Try again.
    QUESTION 1 Should 'disease' be capitalised?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  'Alzheimer' should be capitalised as it's a proper name, but disease is a common noun and doesn't need capitalising.
        ANSWER: I can choose.
        FEEDBACK: I wouldn't say so.  The disease is called 'Alzheimer's', so the word 'disease' is a common noun and common nouns are not capitalised.
    QUESTION 2 Is it right to capitalise vascular dementia.
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  Vascular dementia is a condition like cough, appendicitis or osteoperosis.  We only capitalise if diseases or conditions are called after people, e.g. Alzheimer's disease; Crohn's disease; Down's syndrome.
        Task wordclick difficulty 3
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task wordclick difficulty 2
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <p><font size="4">Referees:</font></p>
<p><font size="4">Mr. J. M. Mccromarty, </font><font size="4">Senior lecturer, </font><font size="4">Computing science, 12 University avenue, University of Glasgow</font></p>
<p><font size="4">Mrs. Sarah d'albi, reader, Computing Science,12 University Avenue, university of Glasgow</font></p>
<p><font size="4"></font></p>
    QUESTION 0 Is Mccromarty correctly capitalised?
        ANSWER: Yes. 
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  Scottish names beginning Mc nearly always need a capital after the suffix:  McCromarty
    QUESTION 1 Should both words in the 'senior lecturer' be capitalised, or neither?
        ANSWER: Both.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  In a list of referees, you are giving titles, so capitals are appropriate.
        ANSWER: Neither.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.   In a list of referees, you are giving titles, so capitals are appropriate:  Senior Lecturer
    QUESTION 2 Should 'avenue' be capitalised?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  In an address, all parts are capitalised: University Gardens, University Avenue, Great Western Road etc.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.   In an address, all parts are capitalised: University Gardens, University Avenue, Great Western Road etc.
    QUESTION 3 How should Sarah's surname be capitalised?
        ANSWER: D'Albi
        FEEDBACK: Unl;ess she expressly wants d'Albi, I'd say this was correct.
        ANSWER: d'Albi
        FEEDBACK: Possibly, but this may not be right and another spelling is more likely.  Try again.  (If this was a real person, you'd look up her name to make sure you capitalised it correctly.)
        ANSWER: D'albi
        FEEDBACK: This is almost certainly wrong.  Try again.
    QUESTION 4 Should 'reader' be capitalised?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  'Reader' is a title, like 'Professor' and when being used as a title should be capitalised.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again.
    QUESTION 5 Should 'university' be capitalised?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: Quite right.  When 'university' is part of a title - the University of Glasgow - it should be capitalised.
