    Writing activity 04. Colons and semi-colons
        Task freetext difficulty 1
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <p><font size="4">My skills proved valuable during my internship, they secured business for the firm, and boosted the half-yearly profits.</font></p>
    QUESTION 0 Which of the commas should be changed to a colon or a semi-colon?
        ANSWER: The first comma.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  The first comma doesn't provide the right kind of pause.  For maximum impact, we need a colon or a semi-colon so that the second part of the sentence stands out.
        ANSWER: The second comma.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree. This part of the sentence should flow, so the comma should be removed, not replaced.
    QUESTION 1 Once you've decided which comma needs to be changed, should it be changed to a colon or a semi-colon?
        ANSWER: A colon.
        FEEDBACK: Actually, either would do.  A colon signals an explanation or examples to come; a semi-colon links two complete sentences that are closely related.  Both these conditions apply here, so you can take your pick.
        ANSWER: A semi-colon.
        FEEDBACK: Actually, either would do.  A colon signals an explanation or examples to come; a semi-colon links two complete sentences that are closely related.  Both these conditions apply here, so you can take your pick.
