INTRO <p><font size="4"><strong>Profile</strong></font></p>
<p><font size="4">Graduated from University of Glasgow with First Class Honoursin Engineering with Music. </font></p>
<p><font size="4">Since graduation, I have worked in three recording studios in Glasgow and am currently developing electronic software app, for people who want to compose on the move. </font></p>
<p><font size="4">Keen member of the university music club, I was in charge of publicity, thus developing skills in MS Word, Adobe Photoshop, Macromedia Dreamweaver, Garageband.</font></p>
<p><font size="4">I wasalso was in charge of complying with regulations when we organised gigs. </font></p>
<p><font size="4">When I graduated, my organisational skills and team leading talents were recognised by my peers, who presented me with a ticket to Snow Patrol.</font></p>
    QUESTION 0 This is a profile appearing at the top of a CV.  Should a profile be one paragraph, or can it be divided as it is here?
        ANSWER: A profile needs to be one paragraph.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  A profile should be one paragraph, since it sits at the top of a CV and its function is to contrast with the very clipped information that will appear in the rest of the CV.  It therefore needs to be carefully constructed so that information isn't lost.  Here, I think the list of skills should be elsewhere.  The profile could then include additional relevant information.
        ANSWER: A profile can be many paragraphs.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree. A profile should be one paragraph, since it sits at the top of a CV and its function is to contrast with the very clipped information that will appear in the rest of the CV.  It therefore needs to be carefully constructed so that information isn't lost.  Here, I think the list of skills should be elsewhere.  The profile could then include additional relevant information.
