    Writing activity 06.  Singular/plural common errors
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Duties were to designpublicity material, tickets, emails and website; and training a student to use the software. This was unsupervised. </font>
    QUESTION 0 All the duties undertaken by this applicant were unsupervised.  Is this clear from this text?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  On the one hand we have 'duties' (plural), and on the other hand we have 'this' (singular).  The singular 'This' leads the reader to understand that only the student training was unsupervised.  I'm not sure, though, that this is what the writer actually means.<br />
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  On the one hand we have 'duties' (plural), and on the other hand we have 'this' (singular).  The singular 'This' leads the reader to understand that only the student training was unsupervised.  I'm not sure, though, that this is what the writer actually means.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <p><font size="4"><strong>Experience</strong></font></p>
<p><font size="4">Assistant to a freelance webdesigner. They asked me to return after a successful placement in summer 2010.</font></p>
    QUESTION 0 Where is the singular/plural mismatch here?
        ANSWER: 'a successful placement'
        FEEDBACK: No - there was only one placement, so the 'a' is correct.
        ANSWER: Webdesigner should be plural - webdesigners.
        FEEDBACK: No - a webdesigner is one person.
        ANSWER: 'They'
        FEEDBACK: I agree. The term 'a freelance webdesigner' implies a one person business, so it must be 'he' or 'she' who asked the writer to return.
        Task freetext difficulty 1
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <p><font size="4">Dear Mr. Campbell,</font></p>
<p><font size="4">I am afraid that neither my current boss, Professor Salter, nor my previous boss, Dr. Argold, are free to take a call on Tuesday at 10 a.m. regarding my references. However, your alternative times of either 2 p.m. or 4 p.m. suits them both.</font></p>
<p><font size="4">Yours sincerely,</font></p>
<p><font size="4">Alison King</font></p>
    QUESTION 0 In the first sentence, is 'are' the correct verb?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  When we have two singular nouns listed as 'neither' 'nor' the verb is singular.  This is because the verb applies to each noun separately:  My current boss, Professor Salter, is not free.  My previous boss, Dr. Argold, is not free.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  When we have two singular nouns listed as 'neither' 'nor' the verb is singular.  This is because the verb applies to each noun separately:  My current boss, Professor Salter, is not free.  My previous boss, Dr. Argold, is not free.
    QUESTION 1 In sentence 2, is the verb 'suit' correct?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  The subject here is 'alternatives' which is plural, so we need a plural verb:  Your alternatives (of either 2 p.m. or 4 p.m.) suit them both.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Themes in my dissertation on the underlying causes of the 100 Years War attracted interest from academics in related war studies' researches and it formed the basis of further research for my Masters degree.</font>
    QUESTION 0 What is the subject of this sentence?
        ANSWER: Themes
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  And 'Themes' is plural.
        ANSWER: Dissertation.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  The noun 'Themes' is the subject.  
        ANSWER: The causes of the 100 Years War.
        FEEDBACK: No - that's not right. The word 'Themes' is the subject of this sentence.
    QUESTION 1 Should we choose 'it' or 'they'?
        ANSWER: it
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  'Themes' (the subject) is plural, so we need a plural pronoun (a pronoun is a word standing in for the noun).  In this case, we need 'they' (i.e. the themes).<br />
        ANSWER: they
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  'Themes' (the subject) is plural, so we need a plural pronoun (a pronoun is a word standing in for the noun).  In this case, we need 'they' (i.e. the themes).
