    Writing activity 11. Getting the tone right: CVs, covering letters, other communications
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">Can you answer these questions?</font> 
    QUESTION 0 In a CV, should you use the personal pronoun 'I'?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  A CV should use a clipped, informative tone, and leave out personal pronouns (see information behind blue question mark for examples).
        ANSWER: It's your CV so you can choose.
        FEEDBACK: It is your CV, but there's little point in writing one in a style employers dislike.  A CV should use a clipped, informative tone, and leave out personal pronouns (see information behind blue question mark for examples).
    QUESTION 1 Should you use complete sentences in a CV?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  In a CV, the tone is clipped and informative.  In a covering letter or personal statement, however, you should use complete sentences. 
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  In a CV, the tone is clipped and informative.  In a covering letter or personal statement, however, you should use complete sentences. 
        ANSWER: It doesn't matter.
        FEEDBACK: Yes, it matters because you want to look professional.  In a CV, the tone is clipped and informative.  In a covering letter or personal statement, however, you should use complete sentences.
    QUESTION 2 Which of the following two sentences fits best into a personal statement?

        ANSWER: Really enjoyed my time teaching in Malawi.  Great opportunity to meet some great kids.  Stayed on longer as couldn't tear myself away!
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  The tone here is lively, and would be fine in a personal letter.  It's too colloquial, though, for a personal statement to be read by a potential employer.
        ANSWER: I loved teaching children in Malawi literacy skills during my gap year, developing a strong sense of purpose and commitment.  I worked an extra six months unpaid and am still in regular contact with the class.
        FEEDBACK: The tone here is good:  enthusiastic but not gushing.  The care taken in crafting this will not go unnoticed by an employer.
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">From the start of a personal statement:<br /><br />I really want to do something important with my life, which is why I've decided to apply to the University of Glasgow to do a PhD on the changing nature of Coleridge's religious beliefs. I think, in our modern times, Coleridge speaks to us today and has a lot to tell us about ourselves, the universe and God. I've read everything there is to read on Coleridge, and have followed his tracks through the Quantocks and the Lake District, and even through the Hartz mountains in Germany.<br /><br />You may wonder why a PhD on Coleridge's religious beliefs is important. There are two reasons: first, I don't think anybody has examined this aspect of Coleridge's life in the kind of attention to detail I intend to bring; and secondly, not being a native English speaker, I notice things in his writings that native English speakers may not necessarily see. <br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Is the tone of this personal statement likely to be attractive to a potential PhD supervisor?
        ANSWER: Yes.  It's enthusiastic and clear.
        FEEDBACK: It is certainly enthusiastic and clear, but the tone is childish.  It is childish, for example, to write 'I really want to do something important with my life'.  That is taken as read with a PhD application.  
        ANSWER: No.  It's enthusiastic, but there's something not quite right about it.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  It is certainly enthusiastic and clear, but the tone is childish.  It is childish, for example, to write 'I really want to do something important with my life'.  That is taken as read with a PhD application.
    QUESTION 1 Are the reasons for wanting to do a PhD on Coleridge's changing religious beliefs set out persuasively?
        ANSWER: Yes.  The reasons are good, and set out clearly.
        FEEDBACK: The reasons may be good but they are not set out well.  If you're applying to do a PhD, you need to know whether your potential ground has been covered before.  In other words, writing 'I think' immediately injects an element of doubt.  A personal statement should 'know', not 'think'.  I also find the tone of the second reason - that native English speakers may miss things - a little patronising.  All in all, the tone of this personal statement is likely to irritate rather than engage a potential supervisor.
        ANSWER: No.  The reasons are neither good nor persuasive.
        FEEDBACK: I agree in part.  It's arguable as to whether the reasons are good, but in any event, they are not set out well.  If you're applying to do a PhD, you need to know whether your potential ground has been covered before.  In other words, writing 'I think' immediately injects an element of doubt.  A personal statement should 'know', not 'think'.  I also find the tone of the second reason - that native English speakers may miss things - a little patronising.  All in all, the tone of this personal statement is likely to irritate rather than engage a potential supervisor.
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">From a CV:<br /><br />Experience<br /><br />May 2009 - June 2011 (Saturdays)<br />Retail assistant, Boots the Chemist: manager of Saturday staff. Kept staff in line and made sure all health and safety measures adhered to. Checked staff for shoplifting at end of day. <br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Do you like the person in this CV?
        ANSWER: Yes.  The person sounds organised.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Organised, yes, but bossy too.   There would be more attractive ways of outlining these duties.
        ANSWER: No.  The person sounds a pain.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  The person sounds organised, but bossy.   There would be more attractive ways of outlining these duties.
    QUESTION 1 Do the duties need glossing over?
        ANSWER: Yes.  Better not to mention unappealing duties.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  You should list your duties, but you could adopt a different tone.  For example, 'line-managed staff; responsible for safety and security'.
        ANSWER: No.  You need to mention your duties, however unappealing they might be.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  You should list your duties, but you could adopt a different tone.  For example, 'line-managed staff; responsible for safety and security'.
