        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <p><font size="4">From a personal statement:</font></p>
<p><font size="4">All of my job have dealt with public, so I have confidence in my ability to interact with customer.My experiences as a doctors' receptionist gives me an insight into working under pressure, whilstmy complete of the Mark Scott Leadership for life award gave me valuable lesson in how to fundraise.</font></p>
    QUESTION 0 How many errors should a good proofreader have noticed in this text?
        ANSWER: 2
        FEEDBACK: Try again.<br />
        ANSWER: 5
        FEEDBACK: Try again.<br />
        ANSWER: 8
        FEEDBACK: Well done.<br />
        ANSWER: 6
        FEEDBACK: Try again.<br />
        ANSWER: 7
        FEEDBACK: Try again.
    QUESTION 1 There are two singular nouns that should be plural.  Can you find them?
        ANSWER: ability, insight
        FEEDBACK: No - try again.<br />
        ANSWER: job, receptionist
        FEEDBACK: Try again.<br />
        ANSWER: job, customer
        FEEDBACK: Well done. <br />
        ANSWER: customer, pressure
        FEEDBACK: Try again.
    QUESTION 2 There's a subject/verb mismatch.  Which one is it?
        ANSWER: experiences/gives
        FEEDBACK: Well done.<br />
        ANSWER: award/gave
        FEEDBACK: No - this is fine.  Try again.
    QUESTION 3 What's needs correcting in the Mark Scott Leadership for life award?
        ANSWER: It should be followed by an acronym, i.e. MSLFLA.
        FEEDBACK: No - this would only apply if you were writing a report which mentioned this award many times and you wanted to shorten the title for ease of reading.
        ANSWER: The 'L' of 'leadership' should be in lower case.
        FEEDBACK: No - try again.
        ANSWER: 'Life' and 'Award' should be capitalised.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  All the major words of the award should be capitalised:  the Mark Scott Leadership for Life Award.
    QUESTION 4 We're missing two articles (a, an, the).  Where should they go?  You'll need to choose more than one option, since there are two missing articles.
        ANSWER: We need 'the' in front of 'customer'.
        FEEDBACK: If the reference was to one customer only, then 'the customer' would be correct.  But the text is refering to customers in general, so should be plural, and because it is a general reference, no article is needed.<br />
        ANSWER: We need 'a' in front of 'valuable'.
        FEEDBACK: That's right, if you're using 'valuable lesson' in the singular.  Then we'd need 'a valuable lesson'.  If using the plural, i.e. 'valuable lessons', then no article is required because this is a general expression.<br />
        ANSWER: We need 'the' in front of 'pressure'.
        FEEDBACK: No - no article required in front of 'pressure', since pressure is a concept and concepts seldom need articles.<br />
        ANSWER: We need 'the' in front of 'public'.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  'The public' is a particular, identifiable entity, so needs an article.<br />
    QUESTION 5 There's a word wrongly used in this text.  What is it?
        ANSWER: 'interact'
        FEEDBACK: No - nothing wrong with 'interact'.<br />
        ANSWER: 'dealt with'
        FEEDBACK: No - that phrase is correct.<br />
        ANSWER: 'complete'
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  'Complete' is an adjective, e.g. 'the complete course'.  Here, we need a noun - completion - so the text should read:   '... whilst my completion of the Mark Scott etc.'
    Writing activity 15. CVs - what type is required?
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <p>As Parliamentary and Policy Officer you will be responsible for further developing the profile and influence of the YMCA within Government and Parliament and to reinforce the position of the YMCA as one of the main leaders in the voluntary sector. The role of Parliamentary and Policy Officer is an important role in achieving this aim, requiring an individual with sound Parliamentary/public affairs experience and some knowledge of the voluntary sector. </p>
<p>You will: </p>
<ul> 
  <li>Ensure that the YMCA has a strong public policy presence in England with key decision makers and organisations. </li> 
  <li>Co-ordinate the policy and public affairs activities of the YMCA  ensuring that Government, Parliament, other tiers of government and relevant organisations know about the work of the YMCA, what it stands for and what it is seeking to achieve. </li> 
  <li>Provide a full range of policy advice and support to the YMCA Movement. </li> 
  <li>Facilitate in the development of internal YMCA policy as directed by the YMCA Movement. </li> 
  <li>Line manage a Policy Intern. </li> 
</ul>
<p>We are looking for a professional with: </p>
<ul> 
  <li>Knowledge of Government and the Parliamentary process </li> 
  <li>Understanding of key government policies and how it impacts upon the work of the YMCA </li> 
  <li>Experience working in a Parliamentary public affairs or policy area </li> 
  <li>Producing and presenting policy reports and briefings </li> 
  <li>Excellent interpersonal skills with the ability and confidence to develop and maintain relationships </li> 
  <li>Able to work as part of a small team and flexible to accommodate the occasional travelling and out of hours working associated with the role </li> 
</ul>
    QUESTION 0 What type of a CV would be best to offer for this job?
        ANSWER: A chronological CV.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Read the advertisement carefully.  This employer is looking for quite specific experience and skills.
        ANSWER: A skills-based CV.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  A CV from which the relevant skills shine out will be well received here.
    QUESTION 1 Should you include, within the text of your CV, a sample of your policy report writing or briefing skills?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  You could attach a sample as an appendix and note that you have done so in your covering letter.  Never, unless specifically told to do so (which would be very unusual) include a sample of your work within the text of your CV itself.<br />
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: That's right. You could attach a sample as an appendix and note that you have done so in your covering letter.  Never, unless specifically told to do so (which would be very unusual) include a sample of your work within the text of your CV itself.<br />
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
