INTRO <font size="4">
<h1 id="jobTitle">No Experience, No Problem - CUSTOMER SERVICE OPENINGS </h1>
<div id="jobDescription">
  <p>CUSTOMER SERVICE/ CLIENT REPRESENTATIVE EXPERIENCE WELCOME AT MARKETING FIRM! <br /><br />We work with one of the UK's leading telecommunications providers and are looking to expand our portfolio by the end of the year. Since our client just launched a new media campaign, they want us to provide more face to face representation and branch out into new markets. <br /><br />We're looking for people with experience dealing with customers on a regular basis (ie: customer service call centres, retail sales, restaurant and bar staff, etc) who are looking for a new rewarding challenge. People with limited experience are welcome to apply because full product knowledge is available along with on-site demonstrations and coaching. In addition to customer service, we will provide you with guidance on basic marketing and sales techniques, client relations and develop your leadership abilities. You will be working independently and as part of a team and need to be at least 18 years of age in order to represent our clients to the public. <br /><br />Our client representation techniques involve both business to consumer and business to business campaigns, so you will be expected to have strong communication skills and be willing to expand comfort zones. We target potential customers where they work, live and shop in an effort to saturate our client's target market and help increase their market share. Earnings are accumulated on a daily basis, and rewarded only on completed sales.</p></div></font>
    QUESTION 0 What type of CV would be appropriate here?
        ANSWER: Chronological.
        FEEDBACK: Yes, I agree.  A chronological CV would highlight your experience and skills right up to the minute.
        ANSWER: Skills-based.
        FEEDBACK: It's true that 'strong communication skills' are a requirement, but I'd say that it would be best to demonstrate these through an up-to-date list of your jobs and experience.
    QUESTION 1 When you cut out the fancy language, what kind of a job is this?
        ANSWER: Writing sales material.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not right.
        ANSWER: Tele-sales.
        FEEDBACK: Yes.  It's a telesales job.
        ANSWER: Providing support for a sales team.
        FEEDBACK: No - the job is to be part of the sales team, i.e. to sell, and sell hard.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <p><font size="4">Imaginative, hard-working, self-motived?</font></p>
<p><font size="4">We're a smallindependent bookshop in the centre of Stirling, and we're opening another shop in Glasgow. We're looking for a graduate with a keen interest in modern fiction(not just British) tobe part of a two-person team. Your duties will be many and various, from making tea, dealing with customers,dreaming uppromotions and organising and running author events. The hours will be long and the pay pretty poor, but for the right person,this job offers a real opportunity to be part of a success story. Please start your one-page CV with a short, personal paragraph (no more than 50 words).</font></p>
    QUESTION 0 Which of these starts to the short paragraph would be likely to make the best impression?
        ANSWER: I am passionate about books.  Since graduating in 2007, I've been writing one of my own. 
        FEEDBACK: At the risk of rejecting the next J. K. Rowling, I wouldn't be impressed by this.<br />
        ANSWER: I've just graduated with a First Class degree in English Literature and have spent the past three Christmas vacations working in Waterstone's.
        FEEDBACK: This information would be in the body of your CV.  The 50 word paragraph is an opportunity for you to showcase your character.<br />
        ANSWER: I read your advertisement twice before I believed it was true.  This chance to be part of the fightback of the independent bookshop is a chance in a million.
        FEEDBACK: I like this one. It shows some originality and well-directed enthusiasm.  The applicant doesn't just rely on the hackneyed  'I love books':  there's an understanding of the difficulties faced by the potential employer.  Understanding is always attractive.  I'd go for this one.
    QUESTION 1 Do you need an English Literature degree for this job?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  A 'keen interest in modern fiction' is not limited to Eng Lit graduates.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  A 'keen interest in modern fiction' is not limited to Eng Lit graduates.
    QUESTION 2 After the 50 word paragraph, should this CV be arranged chronologically?
        ANSWER: Yes. You need some formality.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  The 50 word paragraph allows your personality to shine through.  After that, you need to show serious professionalism.<br />
        ANSWER: No. That would be too formal.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.    The 50 word paragraph allows your personality to shine through.  After that, you need to show serious professionalism.
    Writing activity 17a. Articulating your skills
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <p><font size="4">ImagTech: We're looking for a graduate trainee to join our team of Research and Development engineers. You must show sophisticated coding aptitude, plus an interest in graphics,video and embedded software.</font></p>
<p><font size="4">Our R and D team arecurrently top of the charity fundraisers at ImagTech.</font></p>
    QUESTION 0 Is this the perfect job for somebody who has no other interests apart from IT?
        ANSWER: Yes.  A CV for this job needs to show only hard IT skills.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Hard IT skills are crucial, but read the whole advertisement.  Successful charity fundraisers need more than brilliant IT skills.  The reason for inserting the last sentence is to see if the applicant picks up on this and provides evidence of excellent interpersonal skills as well.
        ANSWER: No.  More skills are needed
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  Hard IT skills are crucial, but read the whole advertisement.  Successful charity fundraisers need more than brilliant IT skills.  The reason for inserting the last sentence is to see if the applicant picks up on this and provides evidence of excellent interpersonal skills as well.
    QUESTION 1 Should computing science graduates always show evidence of soft skills (e.g. teamworking, interpersonal skills) as well as coding skills?
        ANSWER: No.  If the job specifies only IT skills, it's not necessary to provide evidence of other skills.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Almost nobody works entirely alone, so evidence of 'soft skills' is vital, even for computing scientists.
        ANSWER: Yes.  You should provide evidence of other skills.
        FEEDBACK: I agree. Almost nobody works entirely alone, so evidence of 'soft skills' is vital, even for computing scientists.
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task freetext difficulty 2
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">You contribute to, and occasionally single-handedly produce, the student newspaper. Which of these skills will you acquire? You can pick more than one.</font>
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">Read the text and answer the question(s).</font> 
        ANSWER: Analysing data
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  You'll analyse data on the number of hits, comments etc.
        ANSWER: Judging boundaries.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  If you occasionally run the newspaper single-handedly, you'll sometimes be in the editor's chair.  Editors make the final decision on content.
        ANSWER: Keeping accounts.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  You need a basic knowledge of accounting (money in, money out) to run a newspaper.
        ANSWER: Self-motivation.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  Nobody makes the student newspaper appear.  You get no marks for it.  But if you can keep it going through thick and thin, it's a great thing to put on your CV.
        ANSWER: Recognising skill shortages.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  You'll not be able to do all the jobs yourself. 
        ANSWER: Delegating.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  Delegating is an under-rated art.  Showing you have experience of delegating might be extremely helpful to an employer.
        ANSWER: Teamworking.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  Newspapers are run by teams of people.  A proven ability to run an effective team is hugely valuable to an employer.
        Task freetext difficulty 2
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">You have a first class degree in computing science. What other skills do you need to secure a job?</font>
    QUESTION 0 You have a first class degree in computing science.  What other skills do you need to secure a job?
        ANSWER: No other skills:  good coding skills are enough.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Millions of computing science students have good coding skills.  You must show you have other skills as well.
        ANSWER: You need good interpersonal skills.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  No matter how brilliant you are, employers need to feel you'll fit in.  Interpersonal skills, i.e. showing you can get on with other people, are vital. 
        ANSWER: You need detailed knowledge of every type of programming.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Employers don't expect you to know everything.  They do, however, expect you to have learned how to learn quickly and effectively.
        ANSWER: You need to be able to smile.
        FEEDBACK: Yes! You need to show that you want the job and are going to add to the general office cheeriness, not detract from it.
    QUESTION 1 Employability is all about your degree grade.
        ANSWER: True.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Your degree grade is important, but it's equally important to show evidence of other skills, including life skills, for example being self-motivated, being able to finish difficult tasks you've set for yourself (sport, music, art, volunteering, extra learning), and getting on with other people.
        ANSWER: False.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  Your degree grade is important, but it's equally important to show evidence of other skills, including life skills, for example being self-motivated, being able to finish difficult tasks you've set for yourself (sport, music, art, volunteering, extra learning), and getting on with other people.
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task freetext difficulty 3
    Writing activity 18. Power and action words/phrases
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <p>Can you answer the following question?</p>
    QUESTION 0 Which of the following beginnings of statements from a CV are what we call power words/phrases?
        ANSWER: It was my job to organise ...
        FEEDBACK: No, not this one.  Start with the verb.  'Organised ...'
        ANSWER: Delivered a powerpoint presentation to 500 people.
        FEEDBACK: Yes - that's clear and vigourous. 
        ANSWER: I offered to come in each Saturday.
        FEEDBACK: This sounds tentative rather than powerful.  Better to say:<br />
        Task freetext difficulty 2
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <p><font size="4">Which of these examples, taken from a covering letter, is the most likely to appeal to an employer?</font></p>
    QUESTION 0 
        ANSWER: When I was active in the SRC, I tried hard to facilitate agreement at the meetings where disagreements emerged.  I felt I was valued for my efforts, and in the end, we sorted out our differences.  I think this is a good example of leadership and working within a team.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  These sentences sound tentative, as if the writer isn't quite sure of him/herself.  The weak phrases are:  tried hard; felt I was; I think.<br />
        ANSWER: An active member of the SRC, it was always me who sorted things out at difficult meetings.  I am a proven leader and a highly valued member of any team.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  This is arrogant, as it doesn't just state what the writer did, it makes value judgements, for example: 'it was always me' (i.e. the others were useless); I am a proven leader; I am a highly valued member of any team.  This kind of language alienates a potential employer, who has to judge whether or not you will fit in with the current workforce.  Arrogance is never popular.<br />
        ANSWER: I facilitated agreements at difficult meetings of the SRC.  This skill was valued by the team and, over my four years on the committee, I learned many lessons about human relations.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  This extract is thoughtful.  It doesn't underplay the writer's skills, yet at the same time it displays some humility, for example 'I learned many lessons ...'  This is the option most likely to attract a potential employer.
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Which of the following examples, taken from a CV, packs the most punch?</font>
    QUESTION 0 
        ANSWER: Was asked to participate in the GU AmDram play.  Auditioned for, and was chosen for, the main role.  Play won Creative Scotland award.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  The information is fine, but the style is too wordy. A potential employer needs facts, not the story.
        ANSWER: Played main role in award winning GU AmDram production of King Lear.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  This states the facts clearly and professionally.
        ANSWER: GU AmDram King Lear won Creative Scotland award.  I played main role.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Your role should come first, since the CV is about you.  Putting the play first makes the statement about the play.
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Which of the following will be most attractive to employers?</font> 
    QUESTION 0 These examples are from a covering letter asking for an illustration of your teamworking skills.
        ANSWER: Took over chess club.  Organised timetable and players.  Organised competitions, including transport.
        FEEDBACK: This text is far too clipped for a covering letter asking for an illustration of teamworking skills.  There are no teamworking skills demonstrated here.  Organising people is not the same as working in a team.
        ANSWER: Three of us determined to re-invigorate the University of Glasgow chess club.  We identified our individual strengths and played to them. My task was to attract more members.  Between us, we attracted and retained 25 members, organised every aspect of competitions (transport, chess boards, clocks, score cards) and, this year, won the Scottish Universities' annual chess tournament. 
        FEEDBACK: This is an attractive way to set out a considerable achievement.  The teamwork shines through, and the end result is very impressive.
        ANSWER: When I arrived at the university, the chess club was moribund, so three friends and I decided to reinvigorate it.  We attracted many more members, and organised competitions.  This year we won the Scottish Universities' annual chess tournament.
        FEEDBACK: This text says nearly the same as the text above, but the style is conversational rather than professional.  No real detail about teamwork is given, for example, what the writer contributed.  Everything is a little vague.  Remember that an employer is looking for how you write as well as what you write.  Vague writing does not impress.
    Writing activity 16.  CV structure and format
        Task freetext difficulty 1
        Task freetext difficulty 2
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task freetext difficulty 1
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <p><font size="4">Dear Mr. Green, Thank you for your invitation to come for interview next week, the time suits me very well, I'll see you next week,</font></p>
<p><font size="4">yours sincerely,</font></p>
<p><font size="4">Mr. John Brady</font></p>
    QUESTION 0 What is the matter with this formatting?  You can choose more than one option.
        ANSWER: The 't' in thank you should not be capitalised.
        FEEDBACK: That's not correct.  The 't' in 'thank you' is the start of the letter, so should be capitalised.
        ANSWER: The letter is all one sentence.
        FEEDBACK: That's right, it is, and it should not be.  This text should be three sentences:  Thank you ... next week.  The time ... very well.  I will see you next week.
        ANSWER: The line spacing is incorrect.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  There should be a line space between Dear Mr. Green, and 'Thank you'. 
        ANSWER: The 'y' in 'Yours sincerely' should be capitalised.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  The signing off 'Yours sincerely' is deemed to be a new sentence.
        ANSWER: No room is left for the signature.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  You need a personal signature as well as a typed name.
        ANSWER: The contraction 'I'll' should be 'I will'.
        FEEDBACK: That's correct.  In a formal letter, don't use contractions.
        Task freetext difficulty 2
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <p><font size="4">From a CV:</font></p>
<p><font size="4"><strong>Education: </strong></font></p>
<p><font size="4">2010 to date: University of Glasgow, BSc in Psychological Studies:</font></p>
<p><font size="4">2005-2010: University of Central Wisconsin, MA in Psychology, with courses in:imaging techniques, experimental design, statistics, brain development, perception and visual cognition, physiology, therapeutic interventions and forensics.</font></p>
<p><font size="4"></font></p>
    QUESTION 0 Should the courses taken at the University of Central Wisconsin be listed?
        ANSWER: Yes.  It's important to set out the whole breadth of your academic learning.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Stating your degree subject is enough in a CV. <br />
        ANSWER: Yes, but not here.  These courses should be in a 'skills' part of your CV.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Stating your degree subject is enough in a CV.  The skills section lists what skills you acquired.  These skills will spin off from, but not necessarily be the same as, the courses taken.<br />
        ANSWER: No - setting out courses, unless specifically asked to do so, is unnecessary in a CV.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  A CV is an outline of your achievements, experience and skills.  It is not the place for course details.
    Writing activity 21.  Following up if no response
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">Which of the following phrases are appropriate 'follow up' phrases?</font>
    QUESTION 0 
        ANSWER: Call me!
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  You might text this to a friend, but such an order would not endear you to a potential employer.
        ANSWER: Please could you call me next week, to confirm you have my letter?
        FEEDBACK: This is not appropriate.  If you want confirmation, it's up to you to get it.  Asking a potential employer to do something for you will often send your letter and CV into the trash.  
        ANSWER: I will telephone next week to confirm that my application was received.
        FEEDBACK: This is much more like it, and certainly the only possibility on offer.
        Task freetext difficulty 2
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO  <font size="4">I answered your advertisement over three weeks ago now and have not heard anything. I really need to know if I am going to get an interview so wonder if you could call me? I'm on 07900 898 933.<br /><br />Thanks.<br /><br />John McBride<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 The language used in this text is grammatically correct and the message is clear.  But is it suitable to send to a potential employer?
        ANSWER: Yes.  It's good to present yourself as efficient and businesslike.
        FEEDBACK: It is certainly good to present yourself as efficient and businesslike, but this text sounds exasperated and cross.  You may well need to know if you're going to get an interview, but hectoring the potential employer is unlikely to trigger anything but a negative response.
        ANSWER: No, it's not suitable.
        FEEDBACK: Quite right.  It is certainly good to present yourself as efficient and businesslike, but this text sounds exasperated and cross.  You may well need to know if you're going to get an interview, but hectoring the potential employer is unlikely to trigger anything but a negative response.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">Dear Mr. Haldron,<br /><br />I am really sorry to bother you, but at the suggestion of Mrs. McNulty, I sent you my CV on 23rd January, and although you must be incredibly busy, I was wondering if it might be possible to arrange a time when I might come in and see you? It is a real imposition, I know, particularly when you are not actually advertising any jobs, but I would be so grateful for the opportunity. Thank you in advance.<br /><br />Yours hopefully,<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Would this text be likely to appeal to a potential employer?
        ANSWER: No.  
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  It's annoyingly apologetic and pleading.  It would not encourage a potential employer to pick up the telephone. Even when chasing someone up, remember that you're showcasing your skills.  Keep your language polite, clear but also dignified.
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  I think this text is apologetic and pleading, and would not encourage a potential employer to pick up the telephon.  Even when chasing someone up, remember that you're showcasing your skills.  Keep your language polite, clear but also dignified.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">You are following up, with a telephone call, a letter to which you've had no response. Which of the following openings would be likely to elicit the best response?</font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4"><br /></font> 
        ANSWER: Hi, Devinda Singh here.  Just following up my letter of last week.  Can you tell me if I'm likely to get an interview or not?
        FEEDBACK: This would not be a good opening gambit.  You give your name, but the person at the other end of the phone is unlikely to be the person to whom you wrote, and even if it was, many letters will have arrived since yours.  Nor do you specify the job for which you've applied.  If you make a call, write down in advance what you're going to say, making sure you include all relevant details.  You've just got the one chance, so make it work.
        ANSWER: Hello, I wonder whether I could speak to Ann Absworth in Human Resources, please.  My name is Devinda Singh.  I wrote to her on 12th January, and said that I would call.
        FEEDBACK: This is a good choice, and has a good a chance as any of working.  If, after such a polite and open approach, you don't get through, you are in a strong position to try again.  If it doesn't work at all, you know you have done your best and that your approach has been professional and dignified.  That's no mean feat in itself.
        ANSWER: Hello.  Ann Absworth, please.
        FEEDBACK: This gets marks for chutzpah, but might backfire as it sounds a little peremptory.  Not a bad choice, but I don't think it's the best choice here.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">You've sent your CV and covering letter by email, as requested, but, after two weeks, you've have had no response. If you choose to telephone, which of the following is likely to make the most positive impression?</font> 
    QUESTION 0 
        ANSWER: Hello, I'm ringing about the job advertised on 4th January.  Can I speak to Mrs. Jones in the HR department, please.
        FEEDBACK: This sounds like a first approach, which yours is not.  Also, put yourself in the shoes of the person at the other end of the phone. Being brisk is fine, but I think this is a little too brisk for a job applicant.  
        ANSWER: Hi, Mrs. Jones, please.
        FEEDBACK: This tone is more suited to a senior, longstanding member of staff.  A potential new recruit needs to adopt a less brisk approach. 
        ANSWER: Hello.  I wonder if I could speak to Mrs. Jones in HR?  I've applied to be a junior trainee, and her letter indicated that we were meant to hear back within a fortnight.   I've heard nothing and thought I'd better ring to make sure I haven't missed something.
        FEEDBACK: I think this is the best option here.  It's polite, whilst making your concern clear. Through the suggestion that you may have 'missed something', you are neatly not blaming Mrs. Jones.  She may, however, feel slightly guilty at not keeping her word.
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task freetext difficulty 3
    Writing activity 22.  Envelopes and postage
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO Can you answer these questions? 
    QUESTION 0 Do all sizes of envelopes require the same postage?
        ANSWER: Yes.  Postage is postage.
        FEEDBACK: I wish that were true, but it's not.  A4 sized envelopes always need a different stamp to smaller envelopes, even the A4 sized envelope contains only one piece of paper.
        ANSWER: No.  They require different stamps.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  A4 sized envelopes always need a different stamp to smaller envelopes, even the A4 sized envelope contains only one piece of paper.
    QUESTION 1 Is it ok to guess the weight of the envelope and stick on as many stamps as you feel certain will cover the cost?
        ANSWER: Yes. 
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Even if you over-estimate and pay more than required, your envelope will look very unprofessional.  Why risk it?  It's worth taking the time to go to the post office.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  Even if you over-estimate and pay more than required, your envelope will look very unprofessional.  Why risk it?  It's worth taking the time to go to the post office.
