INTRO <font size="4">Can you answer the following questions?</font> 
    QUESTION 0 When sending a CV in the post, is it ok to fold it in half to get it into a smaller envelope?
        ANSWER: Yes: so long as it's only folded once.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Whilst it's certainly not wrong to fold your CV, it looks much better if it's flat and unfolded.  I'd use a bigger envelope.
        ANSWER: No:  it's wrong to fold a CV.
        FEEDBACK: It's not wrong to fold a CV, but a CV certainly looks much better if it's flat and unfolded.  I'd use a bigger envelope.
    QUESTION 1 Does it matter whether the envelope containing your CV and covering letter  is white or brown?
        ANSWER: Yes.  It must be white.
        FEEDBACK: It certainly doesn't have to be white, but a white envelope often looks smarter.
        ANSWER: No.  It doesn't have to be white.
        FEEDBACK: I agree, it doesn't, but a white envelope often looks smarter.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">Can you answer the following question(s)?</font> 
    QUESTION 0 Where on an envelope should a stamp be placed?
        ANSWER: In the left hand corner.
        FEEDBACK: No - try again.
        ANSWER: In the right hand corner.
        FEEDBACK: Yes, that's right.  In the right hand corner, and make sure it's the right way up.
        ANSWER: It doesn't matter.
        FEEDBACK: If you want to impress, it does matter.  Try again.
    QUESTION 1 If you have to put multiple stamps on an envelope, where should they go?
        ANSWER: All the way across the top of the envelope.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not right.
        ANSWER: One should go in the top right hand corner and the rest anywhere they can fit.
        FEEDBACK: You might end up with a dreadful mess if you did this.  Try again.
        ANSWER: In a block in the top right hand corner.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  If possible, keep your stamps in a neat block in the top right hand corner.
        Task freetext difficulty 2
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">Can you answer the following question(s)?</font> 
    QUESTION 0 If you want to write to a company but don't know the name of the person you want to address, should you:
        ANSWER: Write 'To Whom it May Concern'?
        FEEDBACK: This is not a good idea.  Finding the correct name and title usually involves one telephone call.  Make that call.
        ANSWER: Just send it to the company: the person who opens the mail will give it to the appropriate person.
        FEEDBACK: This is not a good choice.  Letters addressed only to the company may well go straight in the bin.  Do a little research and find the name of an appropriate addressee.
        ANSWER: Find out the name of the person who seems most appropriate and address your letter and envelope to them.
        FEEDBACK: That's the right course of action.  The more personal you make your approach, the more likely you are to get a response.  In this respect, the envelope is just as important as your letter.
    QUESTION 1 Should you put your own name and address on the envelope?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: This is often a good idea.  The convention is for the sender to put their name either on the back of the envelope or in very small writing in the top left hand corner, marked 'From:'.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: This is often a good idea.  The convention is for the sender to put their name either on the back of the envelope or in very small writing in the top left hand corner, marked 'From:'
        ANSWER: It doesn't matter.
        FEEDBACK: You're right.  It's not necessary, but it does no harm.  The convention is for the sender to put their name either on the back of the envelope or in very small writing in the top left hand corner, marked 'From:'
    Writing activity 23. Email tone
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <p><font size="4">You're responding to an advertisement for an internship with an IT firm. They've asked you to attach your CV. Which of the following emails would be most likely to persuade them to ask you in for an interview?</font> </p>
<p><font size="4">Some browsers may delete all the paragraphing in these examples. If you are sending an email, remember to paragraph just as you would a letter. </font></p>
    QUESTION 0 
        ANSWER: Subject:  internship    Dear Mr. Higgs,  I would like to be considered for the internship in your firm, advertised online through my university website.  I have some experience designing, building, installing and testing software and hardware, having worked for AmbroIT over the summer.  An internship with your firm offers a chance to broaden my experience and skills in my chosen area of work.  I understand that the internship is unpaid, but the chance to work in a firm such as yours would be invaluable.  As requested, I attach my CV.   with best wishes,  Katrina Kallanova  07899 478 393
        FEEDBACK: This is a professional and workmanlike approach.  There's a tiny bit of personal information about previous experience.  Without flagging up the lack of pay unduly, the writer lets the reader know she has fully understood that the internship does not come with a salary.   She has provided a mobile number.  This is the best of the options here.<br /><br />
        ANSWER: Subject: advertisement for internship in the Guardian   Hi Mr. Higgs, saw your advert on my uni website and I'm really interested in an internship in your firm.  I've some experience in IT, having worked in AmbioIT over the summer.  Nevertheless, I'd really like an internship with you.  Hope to hear from you soon, Jim
        FEEDBACK: This email looks careless.  The subject is too long - 'internship' will do.  The tone implies a slightly cocky, breezy confidence, almost as if the writer was doing the potential employer a favour.  Don't shorten 'university' to 'uni'.  The word 'nevertheless' implies the sub-text 'I'm a bit grand for an internship'.  The signing off 'I hope to hear from you soon' irritates some employers, as it is a metaphorical poke in the ribs before the potential employer has had a chance to draw breath.  Also, no mention of a CV.  If you've attached yours as requested, say so, if only because it will remind you to do it.  The worst option here.<br /><br />
        ANSWER: Subject: internship  Dear Sir or Madam,  I saw your advertisement for an internship and would like to apply.  I attach my CV.  Yours sincerely, Adele McManus
        FEEDBACK: This is a perfectly serviceable response but may appear a little idle to an employer.  From the word go, you must try to catch the employer's attention.  This email certainly doesn't.  Not the best option here.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <p><font size="4">You've got through to the second round of interviews withtwo PR and marketing firms. They've both asked you to come in for a second interview on the same date and at the same time. You are anxious to go to both interviews if possible. Which of the following emails is likely to achieve that result?</font> </p>
<p><font size="4">Some browsers may delete all the paragraphing in these examples. If you are sending an email, remember to paragraph just as you would a letter. </font></p>
    QUESTION 0 
        ANSWER: Subject: sod's law  Dear Mr. Grant, I'm really sorry, but I've now got two second interviews on the same day at the same time.  I'm really hoping that you might be able to change?  Just let me know what other time might suit you and I'll try my best to be there.  Sorry!  Yours sincerely, Adam Gerrity
        FEEDBACK: The email doesn't start well.  The subject, 'sod's law'  may be apt but it could seem trite or rude.  In the text, anything that begins 'I'm really sorry' has the reader's heart sinking.  After that, the tone is irritatingly ingratiating:  'I'm really hoping' instead of simply 'I'm hoping'.  If the employer gives you another time-slot, you won't TRY to be there:  you'll be there.  Not a good option.<br />
        ANSWER: Subject: second interview 20th February  Dear Mr. Grant,  I am very pleased to be offered a second interview with Grant & Co. and am very keen indeed to return.  As you may imagine, with so much competition for every job, I have not limited my applications to one, and the time offered for the second interview coincides with another.  I do not, however, want to lose the opportunity of meeting you again.  Would it be possible to come in at 4 p.m. instead of 2 p.m. or at any time on Thursday 21st February?  Yours sincerely, James Jones
        FEEDBACK: This email is very positive in tone.  It doesn't skirt around the awkwardness of the situation but leaves the employer feeling that you've dealt with it as best you can.  You've offered other times, which is the professional thing to do.  If you lose the chance of the interview, you'll know that it was just one of those things, and not because you didn't try your best.  This is the best option here.<br />
        ANSWER: Subject: interview clash  Dear Mr. Grant,  Annoyingly, the time you've suggested for my second interview coincides with my second interview elsewhere.  Obviously, I don't want to blow my chances with you!  Could we rearrange?  Yours sincerely,  Brian Goldman
        FEEDBACK: The subject of this email is true, but not well-chosen.  A potential employer needs to feel that it's their job you want.  Make the subject neutral.  The first sentence could be read as you being annoyed with Mr. Grant, and should be rephrased.  The rest of the email is too colloquial - 'blow my chances'.  The question 'can we rearrange' is used more often between friends or existing colleagues.  You need to work a bit harder to remedy the situation.  Suggesting another time/day would help.  After all, you don't want the same situation to arise again.  Not the best option here.
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">Which of the following emails hits the right tone?</font> 
    QUESTION 0 
        ANSWER: Dear Mr. Rusbridge,  Writing about the job as junior planning officer and attach my CV as requested.  Really hope I get an interview.  Best, Andy Anderson
        FEEDBACK: Writing incomplete sentences, e.g. 'writing about the job' instead of 'I am writing about the job' looks sloppy.  'Really hope I get an interview' doesn't sound keen, which is the writer's hope.  Rather, it sounds a bit desperate.  Use your whole name (Andrew), not its diminutive (Andy).
        ANSWER: Hi Mr. Rubsbridge, I'm writing about the job as junior planning officer.  As requested, my CV's attached.  Thanking you in advance for your time.    Very best, Andy Anderson
        FEEDBACK: 'Hi' is too informal, as are the contractions 'I'm' and 'CV's'.  These should be 'I am' and 'CV is'.  Thanking people in advance is irritatingly meaningless and would have some employers grinding their teeth. 'Very best' could be used once you've secured the job.  Otherwise, stick to 'Yours sincerely'.  Use your whole name (Andrew), not its diminutive (Andy).
        ANSWER: Dear Mr. Rusbridge,  Job 411/23  I am writing to apply for the job of junior planning officer, and attach my CV as requested.  I note the timetable of two weeks for a response.  Yours sincerely,  Andrew Anscombe
        FEEDBACK: This is formal but not pompous.  It is also properly referenced and the writer has used his full name.  This is the best option here.
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">You're running late for an interview with Mr. Hardcastle of IT Consulting because your bus has broken down. What would be the best email/text to explain your predicament.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 
        ANSWER: Dear Mr. Hardcastle, I'm so sorry but my bus has broken down so though I left plenty of time, I'm now running late.  I should be with you in around half an hour.  I realise that this will be very inconvenient for you, and can only apologise again.  Yours sincerley, Adele Hooper
        FEEDBACK: This is a good option.  The text retains a sense of formality and displays good manners.  When things go wrong, the tone in which you inform a potential employer is very important.  This tone is fine.  This is the best option here.
        ANSWER: Running late - apologies - with you soon I hope Adele
        FEEDBACK: This is polite, but the tone is more suitable for keeping a friend waiting for coffee.  It would elicit a grunt of annoyance from an employer rather than an 'oh dear, the poor girl must be frantic', which is the response you want.  
        ANSWER: Really sorry!!! Bus broken down!!! With you soon! Adele
        FEEDBACK: Exclamation marks are never good, and never good in multiples.  Not the best option here.
