    Writing activity 24. Email salutations and signing off phrases
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <p><font size="4">Hi Malcolm,</font></p>
<p><font size="4">Thanks for your email. I'm really pleased that you've chosen me to interview.</font></p>
<p><font size="4">See you on 12th!</font></p>
<p><font size="4">Thanks a lot!</font></p>
<p><font size="4">Kirsty</font></p>
    QUESTION 0 From what you can gather from the content of this response, is the tone of this email appropriate.
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  This is clearly a response to an invitation to come for an interview.  An interview is a formal event, so however thrilled you are to get an interview, keep your response formal.  It is fine to call your correspondent 'Malcolm', if that's how he's signed his email to you, but 'Hi' is much too familiar.  Even if Malcolm himself wrote 'Hi', at this stage you should use 'Dear'.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I agree. This is clearly a response to an invitation to come for an interview.  An interview is a formal event, so however thrilled you are to get an interview, keep your response formal.  It is fine to call your correspondent 'Malcolm', if that's how he's signed his email to you, but 'Hi' is much too familiar.  Even if Malcolm himself wrote 'Hi', at this stage you should use 'Dear'.
    QUESTION 1 Is it acceptable to use contractions (thanks, I'm, you've) in an emailed response to a call for interview?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  At this stage, you need to be formal.  It's fine to express enthusiasm, but do so formally, e.g. Thank you; I am really pleased; you have chosen me.  
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  At this stage, you need to be formal.  It's fine to express enthusiasm, but do so formally, e.g. Thank you; I am really pleased; you have chosen me.
    QUESTION 2 There's another error in this email.  What is it?
        ANSWER: Kirsty hasn't written 'Yours sincerely'.
        FEEDBACK: You're right.  She hasn't.  I think she should have done, but that's not the error that's most concerning.
        ANSWER: Exclamation marks.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  Exclamation marks are never a good idea in a formal response. Exclamation marks are far too ubiquitous in all email correspondence.  Scattering them like confetti makes you look ditsy - not a good look for a potential employee.    
        ANSWER: The email is too short.
        FEEDBACK: No.  Short is excellent so long as the email says all it needs to say.  No employer wants to waste time on padding.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO  <font size="4">Which of the following are the best pairs of salutations and sign-offs for your response to this email:<br /><br />Hi Mary, <br /><br /></font><font size="4">It was good to meet you. </font><font size="4">With regret, we're not offering you the post of deputy manager in The Drinking Place at this time, but, if it's ok with you, would like to keep your CV on file so that if another post comes up we can contact you again.<br /><br />best,<br />Jazz <br /><br />Jazz Broadbent, Manager<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 
        ANSWER: Dear Mr. Broadbent, ...Yours sincerely
        FEEDBACK: The salutation seems a little formal, since the sender doesn't use his last name, and the position is clearly in a bar.  Not the best option.
        ANSWER: Dear Jazz,  ... Yours sincerely,
        FEEDBACK: This reflects the tone used in the email.  I'd say it was the best option.
        ANSWER: Jazz, ... Mary
        FEEDBACK: This looks peevish.  You need to be magnanimous in rejection, particularly as he's asked to keep your details on file.  Not the best option.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">Read the following email, then choose the best salutation and sign-off for the reply.<br /><br />Subject: Assistant Finance Manager<br /><br />Dear Noam Angelou,<br /><br />Agnew Finance are very pleased to offer you the job of Assistant Finance Manager, in line with the terms of the advertisement. Please do not reply to this email. Instead, contact Mrs. Janice Forman, who is copied into this email, to discuss starting dates and all other relevant details.<br /><br />Congratulations! We look forward to you joining our team.<br /><br />With best wishes,<br /><br />Andrew Aristeed<br />Senior Executive<br />Human Resources<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 
        ANSWER: Dear Andrew Aristeed, ... Yours sincerely, Noam Angelou 
        FEEDBACK: The email specifically says not to contact Mr. Aristeed.  Not the best option.
        ANSWER: Dear Janice, ... Yours ever, Noam (Noam Angelou)
        FEEDBACK: This would be much too familiar.  The email indicates that you've never met Mrs. Forman, so you need make a formal approach.   Not the best option here.
        ANSWER: Dear Mrs. Forman, ... Yours sincerely, Noam Angelou
        FEEDBACK: This is polite, and much the best option here.
