    QUESTION 0 
        ANSWER: Dear Sir Charles, ... Yours faithfully,
        FEEDBACK: This isn't correct.  Try again.
        ANSWER: Dear Sir Charles, ... Yours sincerely,
        FEEDBACK: This is correct.
        ANSWER: Dear Sir Goodwin, ... Yours sincerely,
        FEEDBACK: This isn't correct.  With 'Sir' you use the first name.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">You're emailing Professor Sir John Humbolt. Choose the correct salutation and sign-off.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 
        ANSWER: Dear Professor Sir John Humbolt, ... Yours faithfully,
        FEEDBACK: No, this isn't correct.  It's long, and muddles the two forms (Dear Sir, Yours faithfully, and Dear Professor Humbolt, Yours sincerely).
        ANSWER: Dear Professor Humbolt, ... Yours sincerely,
        FEEDBACK: This is correct.  If someone is a professor and a 'sir', and you're addressing them in a professional capacity, use the professorial title.
        ANSWER: Dear Sir John Humbolt, ... Yours sincerely,
        FEEDBACK: This isn't correct. Unless you're addressing the person in a social capacity, use the professorial title.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">Read this email, then choose the best pair of salutations and sign-offs for your reply.<br /><br />Subject: Trainee Buyer: FashionHouse<br /><br />Hi Maggie,<br /><br />Congratulations! We'd like to offer you the coveted job of trainee buyer for FashionHouse! Can you confirm asap whether you want to accept our offer or not. The start date is 3rd February. <br /><br />Looking forward to hearing from you!<br /><br />Chloe Bartle</font><br /> 
    QUESTION 0 
        ANSWER: Dear Chloe, ... with best wishes, Maggie  (Maggie Tulliver)
        FEEDBACK: Chloe's email is very informal, and this salutation and sign-off reflects that, whilst keeping some sense of formality.  This is the best option here.
        ANSWER: Dear Ms. Bartle, ... Yours sincerely, Maggie Tulliver
        FEEDBACK: This would be a very stiff response to a very informal email.  Try again.
        ANSWER: Hi Chloe, ... Until 3rd Feb!  Maggie
        FEEDBACK: This is too informal.  Remember that however friendly people are at interview, they still wanted to be treated with respect.  Not the best option here.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO Read this email, then choose the best pair of salutations and sign-off phrases for your response.<br /><br />Subject: online application<br /><br />Dear Miriam Golantes,<br /><br />Thank you for your application. It is now in the queue for processing and responses will be sent out in two weeks time. Please reply to this email. This will ensure that we have the correct email address on our system.<br /><br />TeamUK<br /> 
    QUESTION 0 
        ANSWER: Dear Team UK, ... Yours faithfully, Miriam Golantes
        FEEDBACK: We only use 'Yours faithfully' if the salutation is Dear Sir or Dear Madam.  Try again.
        ANSWER: Dear TeamUK, ... Yours sincerely, Miriam Golantes
        FEEDBACK: This is the correct style.  If you use a name in the salutation, you should use 'Yours sincerely' (or similar) in the sign-off.  
        ANSWER: Hi Team UK, ... Best, Miriam
        FEEDBACK: The response to the example email may be simply for confirmation purposes, but  you should still be polite.  You never know - it might be a test. This is not the best option.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Read this email, then choose the best salutation and sign-off for your response.<br /><br />Subject: change of interview date<br /><br />Dear Mr. Grant,<br /><br />A new business development means that Mrs. Alison Pryce, who was due to interview you on Friday for the post of deputy sales manager, is now unable to be here on Friday 21st January. We'd like to change the date of your interview to Monday 24th January, keeping it at the same time, i.e. 11 a.m. Is this possible? We apologise for the inconvenience this may cause.<br /><br />Yours sincerely,<br />Marjorie Somerston<br />P.A. to Managing Director</font><br /> 
    QUESTION 0 
        ANSWER: Dear Ms. Somerston, ... Yours sincerely,
        FEEDBACK: This is the correct option: the whole tone of the email indicates that you need to reply formally and politely. 
        ANSWER: Hi Ms. Somerston, ... See you on Monday!  Andy Grant
        FEEDBACK: This is too familiar.  Given that, from the tone of the email, it's clear that you don't know  Ms. Somerston, such familiarity is not warranted.  Try again.
        ANSWER: Dear Marjorie, ... with best wishes, Andy (Andy Grant)
        FEEDBACK: This is too informal.  The email suggests that you've never met Marjorie Somerston so you need a little more formality than this.
    Writing activity 20.  How to get a response
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">Which of the following phrases will make the best impression?</font> 
    QUESTION 0 
        ANSWER: Hi!  Saw your advert on a jobs website and thought I'd get in touch.
        FEEDBACK: This casual approach would probably go straight into the trash.
        ANSWER: I am very interested in the job advertised on your website.  As requested, I am making contact by email.  My CV is ready to send.  Would this be the right email address to use?
        FEEDBACK: The tone is professional and the question direct and easy for the employer to answer.  This would be a good choice.
        ANSWER: Dear Sir or Madam, I am answering the advertisement advertised on your website and am answering by email as requested.  My CV is ready to send.  Thank you.
        FEEDBACK: This is clumsily written and there's no question at the end.  Not the best choice.
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Which of the following is most likely to elicit a positive response? </font>
    QUESTION 0 
        ANSWER: Dear Sir or Madam,  I have read your advertisement with great interest and would like to apply for the job described in the advertisement I found on the internet today which seems to require just the skills I have acquired and now feel ready to use, so I attach my CV as requested and wait to hear from you.  Yours sincerely, Angela
        FEEDBACK: The tone of this email is fine, but the sentence is much too long and, by stating that the writer will wait to hear, leaves the ball in the recipient's court.  Better to keep the ball in your own court if possible.
        ANSWER: I'd like to apply for this job and attach my CV.  best,  Kate Risborough
        FEEDBACK: The brevity of this email may appeal to a potential employer, particularly if the response to the advertisement is overwhelming.  Nevertheless, it does not invite a conversation.  I'd beware of making an email too clipped.
        ANSWER: I read the job advertisement on your website today with great interest, and attach my CV as requested.  I wonder if you could let me know what the likely timescale for interviews might be?  I look forward to hearing from you.  Yours sincerely,  James McArthur
        FEEDBACK: This response is professional but friendly, and invites a response.  It is the best option here.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO  <font size="4">Herend Accounting: We are looking for a graduate trainee to join our busy commercial department, and we would like to hear from you. No attachments, please.<br /><br />Which of the following responses to this advertisement would make the best impression?</font> 
    QUESTION 0 
        ANSWER: Job reference: 93/903  I have read this advertisement with great interest and would like to apply for the graduate traineeship.  I wonder if you could let me know to whom I should send my CV?  Thank you.  Yours sincerely, Jane Wilkes
        FEEDBACK: This opens the way for Jane to get in contact again if she hears nothing.  It is also wise to ask for a named person to receive your CV.  This is the best option here.
        ANSWER: I've seen this advertisement, and would like to apply.  Here's my CV.  Yours, Alan McMann
        FEEDBACK: Some potential employers might find this abrupt to the point of rudeness, particularly the 'Here's my CV' when the advertisement clearly states not to send an attachment.  A poor option.
        ANSWER: To Whom it May Concern:  I would like to apply for Job 93//903.  Thank you.  Kirsty Kale
        FEEDBACK: To Whom it May Concern is never a good way to begin an email.  Make an enquiry and find a name, or start with the job reference.  Not the best option here.
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">You've sent an on-line application form, but a fortnight has passed and the only response you've had is an automated acknowledgement. What should you do next?</font> 
    QUESTION 0 
        ANSWER: Nothing:  a fortnight's not long enough for a follow-up.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  A fortnight is long enough, unless there's a specific timetable outlined in the application.  Don't give up just because you hear nothing.  The ball is in your court.  Time to give it a push.
        ANSWER: Re-send the application.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  This will generate another automated response.  It will also muddle your first application. 
        ANSWER: Go onto the organisation's website and find a real person to email.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  Showing initiative usually pays dividends.  An employer isn't going to be put off by a polite enquiry - rather the opposite.  Too many people give up because they hear nothing.  Don't give up without making another attempt.
        ANSWER: Write a letter expressing your dissatisfaction.
        FEEDBACK: Not a good option!  Try again.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO If applying for a traineeship with a firm of solicitors, which of the following would be likely to elicit the most positive response? 
    QUESTION 0 
        ANSWER: Hi, Here is my application for a traineeship with your firm.  Could you let me know as soon as possible if I'm likely to be called for interview?  Thank you for your time.  Very best, Andrew Pearce
        FEEDBACK: This is so clearly a generic email that's going to be sent on the rounds that even if a firm had been thinking of offering you an interview, they might now think again.  A poor option.
        ANSWER: Dear Mr. Dundonald, Attached, as requested, is my CV and covering letter.  A traineeship with your firm would be amazing, and I would not let you down.  I cannot see a timetable for applicants.  Am I likely to hear soon?  Thank you in anticipation.  Yours sincerely, Andrew
        FEEDBACK: This email starts well, but then dissolves.  Don't try to flatter the email's recipient meaningless phrases and promises you've no idea if you could keep.  Also, don't thank in anticipation.  This really annoys employers as it's a very crude form of attempted manipulation.  Finally, make sure you put your last name in the body of the email.  Many Andrews may have applied.
        ANSWER: Dear Mr. Dundonald,  As requested in your email, I attach my CV and covering letter as part of my application for a traineeship with Dundonald and Roberts.  I note that there is no timetable given for application processing, and wonder if it might be possible to let me know approximately when I might hear whether I have got through to the interview stage?  Yours sincerely, Andrew Pearce
        FEEDBACK: This option shows some thought.  The firm's name is mentioned, so this is clearly not a generic email.  The language used is professional, and the question is asked politely.  The tone of this email makes it likely that Mr. Dundonald would feel it polite to reply.
