    Writing activity 09. Formatting - italics
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO  <font size="4">Alexander Grant said: <span style="font-style: italic;">'Edward's active exercise of feudal superiority proved unacceptable</span>'<sup>1</sup> which explains the move in 1295 by Scottish leaders to sideline King John. <br /><br /><sup>1</sup> Alexander Grant, '<span style="font-style: italic;">Aspects of Scottish National Consciousness in the Later Middle Ages' </span>in C. Bjorn, A. Grant and K. J. Stringer (<span style="font-style: italic;">eds.</span>) Nations, Nationalism and Patriotism in the European Past<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Are there any unwanted italics in the text?
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  Quotations should not be italicised.
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  Quotes should not be italicised.
        ANSWER: Italics are a matter of opinion.
        FEEDBACK: No, sadly not.  Quotations are never italicised.
    QUESTION 1 Is the footnote properly italicised?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  The italics are the wrong way round.  The name of the article should be in ordinary font and the name of the book in italics.  Also, (eds.) should not be italicised.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  The italics are the wrong way round.  The name of the article should be in ordinary font and the name of the book in italics.  Also, (eds.) should not be italicised.
        ANSWER: In this case, it doesn't matter.
        FEEDBACK: It always matters, I'm afraid. Here, the italics are the wrong way round.  The name of the article should be in ordinary font and the name of the book in italics.  Also, (eds.) should not be italicised.
        Task wordclick difficulty 3
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">It was, as often in history, a case of deja vu. A series of mistakes alienated a monarch, who then compounded the mistakes by attempting to exert authority he did not have. Still, it was all <span style="font-style: italic;">grist to the mill</span> of future historians. William Robertson, in his 'History of Scotland' (1759) found plenty of material from the reigns of <span style="font-style: italic;">Mary, Queen of Scots</span>, and <span style="font-style: italic;">James VI</span>. He also wrote a three volume History of the Reign of Charles V. <br /><br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Should deja vu have been italicised?
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  This is a French expression, so should have been italicised.
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  This is a French expression, so should have been italicised.
    QUESTION 1 Should 'grist to the mill' have been italicised?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  This is just an expression, so needed no italics.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  This is just an expression, so needs no italics.
        ANSWER: It is a matter of choice.
        FEEDBACK: Sadly not.  There are rules about italics (click on the blue question mark above the exercises). The rules are not arbitrary: they are designed for clarity and consistency.
    QUESTION 2 Is Robertson's 'History of Scotland' properly styled?
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  Being the name of a book, it should not be in inverted commas, it should be italicised.
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect. The name of a book should not be in inverted commas, it should be italicised.
    QUESTION 3 Should Mary Queen of Scots and James VI be italicised?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  The names of monarchs, unless referring to books with their names as the title, should never be italicised.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  The names of monarchs, unless referring to books with their names as the title, should never be italicised.
        ANSWER: It's a matter of personal choice.
        FEEDBACK: Sadly not.  There are rules for the use of italics, which are intended to help with clarity and consistency.  Press the blue question mark above the exercises for more information.
    QUESTION 4 Should the Reign of Charles V be italicised?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  The names of books should always be italicised.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  The names of books should always be italicised.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO 'If the <span style="font-style: italic;">Select Society</span> and the <span style="font-style: italic;">Poker Club</span> had, together with the Edinburgh Review, been the focal points of Edinburgh's <span style="font-style: italic;">literati</span>, the <span style="font-style: italic;">Mirror Club</span> and its associated journals - the Mirror and the Lounger - were the symbols of a third and different phase which set in soon after the collapse of the <span style="font-style: italic;">Select Society</span> in 1763.'<sup>1</sup> <br /><br /><sup>1</sup> Lynch, <span style="font-style: italic;">Scotland</span>, p.349 <br /><br />(With apologies, because Michael Lynch didn't get his italics wrong: it was just too good a sentence not to use as an exercise.)<br /> 
    QUESTION 0 What is wrong with the italics used for the names in this example?
        ANSWER: Nothing.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  There is a great deal that's wrong.
        ANSWER: The societies are italicised and the journals are not, which is precisely the wrong way round.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  Journals and books should be italicised, societies should not.
        ANSWER: Everything should be italicised.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect. The names of societies don't need italics, only the names of books and journals.
    QUESTION 1 Should literati be italicised?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I would say no, and Michael Lynch agrees.  This word is now in common use in the UK, so has forfeited its claim to be italicised as a foreign word.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I would say correct.  This word is now in common use in the UK, so has forfeited its claim to be italicised as a foreign word.
        ANSWER: It's a matter of fashion.
        FEEDBACK: Ten years ago I'd have agreed, but the word's common usage in the UK means it has forfeited its claim to be italicised as a foreign word.
        Task freetext difficulty 1
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">At this time, France was almost bankrupted by the <span style="font-style: italic;">Seven Year War</span> which ended with the <span style="font-style: italic;">Peace of Paris</span>.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 Are these italics properly used?
        ANSWER: No.  There should be no italics in this sentence.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  Names of wars and peace treaties never need italics.
        ANSWER: Yes.  Unusual names for wars and the names of peace treaties should be italicised.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  Names of wars, however strange they are, don't need italics.  Nor do the names of peace treaties.
        ANSWER: You can italicise if you want to.
        FEEDBACK: This is incorrect. The rules outlining the proper use of italics were not created to trip students up, but for ease of reading and, should it be necessary, printing.  As a historian, you need to follow these guidelines.
    Writing activity 11. Meaning - making your meaning crystal clear
        Task freetext difficulty 2
        Task freetext difficulty 1
        Task freetext difficulty 3
