    Writing activity 19. Argument and evidence - relevance of content to question
        Task wordclick difficulty 3
        Task wordclick difficulty 3
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title: What accounts for the success of nationalism as a modern political force?<br /><br />Serbia and Croatia share a common heritage and spoke language, yet are separated by religious denomination and written language. In Bosnia, there is a closer relationship between the Bosniak and the Serb as all that separates them is confessional identity: Muslim and Orthodox Christian respectively. Why is it that these groups see themselves as separate nationalities when, for example, the Catholic Dutch of the south east Netherlands and the Protestant Dutch of the north west see themselves as being one nationality? The French and Italians are united by religion but divided by language and consequently identify as different nations. The same divide exists between the Flemish and Walloons of Belgium and they share a nation. <br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Is this paragraph relevant to the essay question?
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  The facts are correct and there is interesting stuff here.  But the writer has not used this evidence to help answer the question, so the evidence is wasted.
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: No, it isn't really relevant.  The facts are correct and even interesting, but no attempt has been made to use them to answer the question.  Sadly, this means they are wasted.
