<p class="MsoNormal"><font size="4" style="font-family: trebuchet ms,verdana,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;">Read the following essay title and then the concluding line(s) that are offered. Choose the concluding line(s) you think best. Each selection has an explanation, so even if your choice agrees with ours, it is worth browsing through them all.</font><o:p></o:p></p> <!--EndFragment--> 
        ANSWER: Or if it really was, why would the Scots nowadays again prefer their own devolved parliament?
        FEEDBACK: Ending an essay with a rhetorical question is never a good idea.  It's not entirely wrong, but it can irritate by seeming a little glib.
        ANSWER: The ease with which James was able to control Scotland, compared with his grandfather and great grandfather, was more to do with the distraction of Scottish political elites south to the court at London, the removal of the external threat from England and simply, luck.
        FEEDBACK: This concluding line is too long the some strange word choices (distraction?) are, in themselves, distracting.  This is the last sentence your marker reads. Aim for clarity.
        ANSWER: It could be concluded that the rebellion was not only opposed against the Catholic religion but also against the action of the French arm in the Scottish government.
        FEEDBACK: This is a perplexing sentence, which needs decyphering rather than reading.  'Opposed against'? the 'French arm'? It's never a good thing to leave a marker scratching their head.  Neither does the line echo the essay title.  Not a good choice.
        ANSWER: Thus, through the examining the reigns of James III and James IV, and comparing these reigns with the reign of James VI and I, this essay has shown that the union of the crowns increased the crown's difficulties, and thus paved the way for the disasters that followed.
        FEEDBACK: I liked this concluding line.  It echoed the title of the essay and also showed that the writer, though entirely focused, had a sense of the broader sweep of history.
