<p class="MsoNormal"><font size="4" style="font-family: trebuchet ms,verdana,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;">Read the following essay title and then the concluding line(s) that are offered. Choose the concluding line(s) you think best. Each selection has an explanation, so even if your choice agrees with ours, it is worth browsing through them all.</font><o:p></o:p></p> <!--EndFragment--> 
        ANSWER: Changes in the structure of society together with the crusades increased intolerance in the twelfth century.  Laymen and clerics did not scruple to use evidence of private non-conformity to add weight to any accusation they cared to make.  Thus, non-conformity became a vulnerability, a reason to live in fear.
        FEEDBACK: These concluding lines are fine, but they don't quite nail the question asked in the essay title.  Reading them, it would be hard to tell exactly what the essay title was.  Not bad, but not the best.
        ANSWER: Thus, the extent to which medieval society was tolerant of non-conformity depended on the level of threat perceived by the church to its own authority, and since this was under constant review, toleration could never, even in times apparently peaceful, be guaranteed. 
        FEEDBACK: By making a simple statement, this line, though a little long, finishes the essay off nicely, giving the marker/reader a satisfactory sense of closure.  This is the best option here.
        ANSWER: Medieval society was never tolerant of non-conformity, and society is not much better today.
        FEEDBACK: This is a personal opinion. Although tempting to use as a concluding line because it carries a punch, I'm afraid it has no place in an academic essay
