<p class="MsoNormal"><font size="4" style="font-family: trebuchet ms,verdana,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;">Read the following essay title and then the concluding line(s) that are offered. Choose the concluding line(s) you think best. Each selection has an explanation, so even if your choice agrees with ours, it is worth browsing through them all.</font><o:p></o:p></p> <!--EndFragment--> 
        ANSWER: James VI's rule over multiple monarchies and move to England meant he did not have any power over law and order and increasingly lost touch with public opinion over religion in Scotland causing an uprising against the crown through riots and propaganda.
        FEEDBACK: This sentence is far too long and incoherent for the body of the essay, let alone the concluding lines.  Concluding lines must feel like a gathering up of points made, but in a measured way.  This is a gabble.  If the sentence were divided, it would improve its concluding qualities.  As it stands, this is a very poor concluding line.
        ANSWER: Thus, governing Scotland in the late middle ages was a balancing act:  nobles and king; law and tyranny;  religious dogmatism and religious pragmatism.  The peaceful governance of Scotland depended on this balance, and if no monarch was ultimately successful, this is perhaps less as a result of personal failure, and more because the task was impossible.
        FEEDBACK: This is a neat wrapping up of the topics chosen for discussion in the essay, echoes the wording of the essay title and has a nice sense of closure.  This is the best option.
        ANSWER: I think Scotland was not well governed then, and it is not now, which is why we should back full independence and be allowed another chance.
        FEEDBACK: These lines are too general and too personal.  An academic essay should certainly take a view, but the view has to be kept within the confines of the essay title and not spill over into the polemical.
