    Writing activity 24. Structure - opening lines
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Essay question:<br /><br />In medieval and early modern Scotland, how significant was the English monarch's role in stirring up rebellion and civil war?</font><br /> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Read the following essay title, then, from the selection of opening lines given, choose the one you think is the best. Every title has an explanation, so it is worth browsing through them all.</font> 
        ANSWER: English monarchs have been involved in the shaping of medieval and early modern Scotland, sometimes manipulating internal struggles for their own ends and at other times unintentionally uniting a nation in rebellion against them.
        FEEDBACK: This is a good opening line.  It echoes the terms of the question, and opens up two promising areas for discussion in the body of the essay.
        ANSWER: Throughout medieval and early modern Scotland, English monarchs tended to be involved in Scottish affairs.
        FEEDBACK: This would be fine if followed by specific examples.   With examples, it would carry weight.  Left hanging, it doesn't add anything.
        ANSWER: England and Scotland share much more than a common border, as we can see from the influence they have had on each other over the years, culturally, socially and politically.
        FEEDBACK: This statement, though undoubtedly true, is far too general.  An opening line needs to get straight into the question.  Not a good choice.
        ANSWER: 'Thocht the wysdome off Ingland be extremit greitt, they gane nocht the rycht way to make unuon off thyr twa realmis'.1
        FEEDBACK: This quote is really about the union.  The marker could make it relevant by linking it directly to the question, but as it stands, it would be better to find another quote that was absolutely pertinent to the question set.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title:<br /><br />Did Scots resist closer ties with England for purely patriotic reasons? Discuss in relation to at least two periods from 1290 to 1707 when closer relations were pursued (politically, militarily or ecclesiastically).<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">Read the essay title and then choose which you think is the best opening line. Each line has an explanation, so even if you pick the best option first, it's worth browsing through the rest.</font> 
        ANSWER: Throughout history, Scotland and England have had a trouble relationship to say the least.
        FEEDBACK: This opening line doesn't really grab the attention, or say anything at all.  If, when you reread your essay, you find you can miss out the opening line without any loss to the essay, delete it and turn the first relevant line into the opening line. You will not be alone in adopting this technique.
        ANSWER: Since they came into existence, Scotland and England have been at war with each other many times, approximately up until the 18th century.
        FEEDBACK: This opening line is far too general.  The title asks for 'at least two periods' to be identified.  These two periods should be identified, rather than just a vague reference to the 18th century.
        ANSWER: This essay will try to answer the question 'Did Scots resist closer ties with England purely for patriotic reasons'.
        FEEDBACK: This opening line is a waste of words.  Echoing the terms of the question is one thing;  simply repeating it quite another.  Avoid this style of opening.
        ANSWER: The uprising of William Wallace and the 'middling sorts' of 1297, and events leading up to the 1502 Treaty of Perpetual Peace signed by James IV of Scotland and Henry VII of England are fertile territory in any discussion about the role Scottish patriotism played in Scots resistance to closer ties with England.
        FEEDBACK: This opening line echoes the title and outlines clearly the two periods chosen.  You can tell that the writer read the question and has thought about how to answer it.  This is the best option.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">As the 'middling sorts' emerged in medieval and early modern Scotland, how important was the growth of the burgh-based trade in the creation of this new social group?</font> 
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">Read the following essay title, then choose the best opening line. All the options have explanations, so even if you identify what we feel is the best option first, it's worth browsing through them all.</font> 
        ANSWER: 'The grant of burghal status conferred protection and privilege, ensuring that trade would thrive in areas designated by the king.'1
        FEEDBACK: This quote is well chosen since it echoes, at least in part, the essay question.  The next line would need to link this quote directly to the rise of the middling sorts.  That would make a very good start.
        ANSWER: The social structure of Scotland has changed vastly over the centuries, with the emergence of definitive social classes.
        FEEDBACK: This is too general.  The question asks specifically about medieval and early modern Scotland.  It's sometimes tempting to make a generalisation at the start of an essay, but it never creates a good impression.
        ANSWER: Any examination of 'the middling sorts' in medieval and early modern Scotland has to address their political as well as economic growth.
        FEEDBACK: This opening line launches the reader straight into the essay.  It is punchy, contains an argument and echoes the terms of the question. This is the best option.
        ANSWER: The growth of burgh-based trade within medieval and early modern Scotland played a role in the emergence of the 'middling sorts' during this time.
        FEEDBACK: This opening line is very flat.  It echoes the terms of the question, but adds nothing.  The essay would not suffer at all if the line was deleted.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title: <br /><br />What was the most important factor in the development of knightly ethos in the 11th and 12th centuries?</font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: trebuchet ms,verdana,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;">Choose the opening line or lines most appropriate to the essay title set. Every choice has an explanation, so if you find our preferred option quickly, it is still worth browsing through them all. The same essay title may be used more than once.</span></font><!--EndFragment--> 
        ANSWER: Stories of knights' prowess have been handed down since the days of King Arthur.
        FEEDBACK: This opening line lacks punch and adds nothing to the essay.  A good opening line should get straight to the point.  This is not a particularly good choice.
        ANSWER: In 11th and 12th centuries, knightly ethos developed in many different ways.
        FEEDBACK: This opening line is padding - repeating the terms of the question but adding nothing.  Not a good choice.
        ANSWER: There are three main factors in the development of knightly ethos in 11th and 12th century Europe:  the church, the increasing sophistication of the lay aristocracy; and contemporary attitudes to women.
        FEEDBACK: This gets straight to the heart of the essay and also neatly lays out the essay plan.  Particularly when limited to 1200 words, an opening like this is excellent since it packs a punch and wastes no time.  This is the best choice.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title:<br /><br />To what extent was medieval society tolerant of non-conformity?<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: trebuchet ms,verdana,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;">Choose the opening line or lines most appropriate to the essay title set. Every choice has an explanation, so if you find our preferred option quickly, it is still worth browsing through them all. The same essay title may be used more than once.</span></font><!--EndFragment--> 
        ANSWER: Tolerance can be described as 'allowing a person, religious sect or opinion to exist without interference or molestation'. (footnoted reference)
        FEEDBACK: This is a perfectly acceptabel opening, since defining tolerance is important in the context of this essay.
        ANSWER: In medieval society, where church and state inextricably linked, the tolerance of lay society to non-conformity depended largely on the tolerance or otherwise of the church.
        FEEDBACK: This opening line gets straight to the point which the essay is going to argue.  Of the choices here, this is the best option.
        ANSWER: Whether in medieval or modern times, life has always been difficult for those whose life-styles don't conform to what society defines as 'the norm'.
        FEEDBACK: This statement may be true, but is padding.  Removing it would not detract from the essay.   It is too general an opening line, so not the best choice here.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title: How did the Treaty of Westphalia (1648) change the role of the state in international relations?<br /><br />The Treaty of Westphalia was introduced in 1648 to bring an end to the Thirty Years' War (1618-1648), and many historians believe that by attempting to ensure, as far as possible, the common good of society and harmony in Europe, it changed the role of the state in international relations. <br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Is this a good opening line?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I think so too.  It clearly defines the terms of the question and gets straight to the point.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  I think this opening line clearly defines the terms of the question and gets straight to the point.
    QUESTION 1 Is anything missing from this opening line?
        ANSWER: No.  It's pretty perfect.
        FEEDBACK: I agree that it's very good, but I'd say there was something missing:  an example of an historian.  If you say 'many historians', we need at least one name.
        ANSWER: Yes, there is something missing.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  If you say 'many historians', we need at least one name.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title:<br /><br />Was St. Francis's calling a natural offshoot of the monastic tradition, or was he advocating something radically new and original?</font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: trebuchet ms,verdana,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;">Choose the opening line or lines most appropriate to the essay title set. Every choice has an explanation, so if you find our preferred option quickly, it is still worth browsing through them all. The same essay title may be used more than once.</span></font><!--EndFragment--> 
        ANSWER: St. Francis was born in Assisi in 1182.
        FEEDBACK: This statement may be true, but bears little relation to the essay title.  If you feel this information is important, it is better to incorporate it into more relevant references, rather than give it a line on its own.
        ANSWER: The monastic tradition dated back to St. Benedict of Nursia, who began as a hermit but, when joined by companions, formed the first monastic community in the west.
        FEEDBACK: This is an informative first line, but would pack more of a punch if the essay question itself was addressed.  Not a bad beginning but not the best.  
        ANSWER: It is tempting to draw clear distinctions between the monastic tradition, essentially one of withdrawal from the world, and the type of religious life advocated by St. Francis, which sought to engage with the world - albeit as a conduit to the next.
        FEEDBACK: This line, though a trifle long, hits the ground running.  It outlines the key difference between traditional monasticism and Franciscan monasticism, and opens the essay up in a lively way.  This is the best choice here.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title:<br /><br />Was Henry IV the cause of the rift between the German monarchy and the papacy during the late eleventh and early twelfth centuries?</font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: trebuchet ms,verdana,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;">Choose the opening line or lines most appropriate to the essay title set. Every choice has an explanation, so if you find our preferred option quickly, it is still worth browsing through them all. The same essay title may be used more than once.</span></font><!--EndFragment--> 
        ANSWER: It has been argued by some historians that Henry IV caused the rift between the German monarchy and the papacy during the late eleventh and early twelfth centuries.
        FEEDBACK: This isn't wrong, but it is really just a restatement of the essay question.  Always try and add something, so that the opening line doesn't seem like padding.  This isn't the best choice here.
        ANSWER: Although it is easy to blame Henry IV for the rift between the German monarchy and the papacy during the late eleventh and early twelfth century, at least two other factors were major contributors.
        FEEDBACK: This is a good opening line: it echoes the terms of the question and adds something more.  A reader wants to read on, to discover which two factors the writer has identified. Stirring up a reader's interest is a great virtue in an opening line.
        ANSWER: Henry IV became the emperor of Germany in 1056 and Pope Gregory VII, the pope with whom he came into conflict, was elected to the papacy in 1073.
        FEEDBACK: The information imparted here is correct, but of no direct relevance to the essay question.  A marker would skip over it, which is never a good thing.  This is not the best choice.
