    Writing activity 10. Formatting - essay layout and formatting checklist
    Writing activity 02. Punctuation - brackets
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO  <font size="4">After his return, James's competent rule, his fearsome reputation (possibly modeled on Henry V) and his links with other European dynasties (through the arranged marriages of two daughters), increased the reluctance of the English to meddle.<br /><br />When Mary came to the throne (1588), Scotland was in danger of being absorbed by France. Mary was married to the Dauphin [sic] and had a double claim on the English throne (through Henry VII and Mary Tudor (Henry VIII's sister)) which the French supported.<br /><br />In 1557, a group of Scottish protestants formed the Lords of Congregation [sic]. <br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Are the brackets round the dates used correctly?
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: Correct, although it wouldn't be entirely wrong to enclose 1588 in brackets.  Better to keep it in the main text, though.
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: Well, it's debatable.  It wouldn't be entirely wrong to enclose 1588 in brackets, but it would be better to include the date in the main text.
        ANSWER: It doesn't matter.
        FEEDBACK: It always matters.  Make a choice.  You may have to defend your choice to your marker.
    QUESTION 1 Are both sets of square brackets used properly?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  You don't need square brackets in either of these instances. The word 'Dauphin' and the phrase 'Lords of Congregation' are neither quotations, nor in need of any kind of special attention.
        ANSWER: One is, one isn't.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  Neither are used properly.  Neither the word 'Dauphin' nor the phrase 'Lords of Congregation' are quotations, and even if they were, neither are in need of special attention.
        ANSWER: No, neither are used properly.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  Neither the word 'Dauphin' nor the phrase 'Lords of Congregation' are quotations, and even if they were, neither are in need of special attention.
    QUESTION 2 Are the brackets round the explanation of the double claim to the throne correctly used?
        ANSWER: It's a matter of personal choice.
        FEEDBACK: No, not in this instance.  The brackets are incorrectly used.  If this information is important enough to include in the essay, it shouldn't be confined to brackets.  In this case, too, the double bracket enclosing yet more information clutters the text in an unhelpful way.
