    Writing activity 20. Argument and evidence - narrative versus analysis
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title: War and Peace: How effective has 'people's war' proved in the European context?<br /> <br /> The dismissal of Necker in 1789 as Controller General also displeased the people. This resulted in riots and the storming of the Bastille in 1789. In 1789 the Assembly gathered to restore peace and reforms were passed to satisfy the people. In 1793, the Committee of Public Safety was formed under Maximilian Robespierre. It had twelve members and focused on the protection of France from other European powers. The Committee of Public Safety was formed by the National Convention, which was the first republican government seen in France. The National Convention was formed in 1792.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 Is this paragraph narrative or analytical?
        ANSWER: Analytical.
        FEEDBACK: No, it's not.  The paragraph simply lists events in the French Revolution rather than thinking about the question and then using carefully selected events as illustration.
        ANSWER: Narrative.
        FEEDBACK: Correct. The paragraph simply lists events in the French Revolution rather than thinking about the question and then using carefully selected events as illustration.
    QUESTION 1 Is all this information necessary in the context of the question?
        ANSWER: Yes:  we need all the information, just better presented.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  The question asks how effective 'people's war' was, so the essay needs to show how effective the revolution was.  In this respect, much of the information presented, e.g. how many members formed the Committee for Public Safety and many of the dates, are irrelevant.  We need much more analysis of the effects of the revolution and not so many bald facts about the revolution itself.
        ANSWER: No, all this information isn't necessary.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  The question asks how effective 'people's war' was, so, having chosen the French Revolution as an example, the essay needs to show how effective it was.  In this respect, much of the information presented, e.g. how many members formed the Committee for Public Safety and many of the dates, are irrelevant.  We need much more analysis of the effects of the revolution and not so many bald facts about the revolution itself.
