        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">This is part of an essay entitled: War and peace: how effective has 'people's war' proved in the European context?<br /><br />The only comparison between World War II and the French revolution is that the majority of people affected by the wars were ordinary people. Whilst the revolution was to their advantage, however, World War II was wholly destructive and ineffective in bringing any benefit to anyone. <br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 This is quite a statement.  Can it stand alone, just as it is?
        ANSWER: Yes, it can stand alone because the writer obviously really believes it to be true.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Such a statement requires loads of evidence as backup if it is to be remotely credible. 
        ANSWER: No.  It is so controversial it would need very very strong factual evidence to back it up.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  A reader of such a statement must know on what factual basis it is based.
    QUESTION 1 Are there any places in the essay where this statement might stand alone?
        ANSWER: No.  It would always need evidence.
        FEEDBACK: It's right that such a statement would always need evidence.  However, if the statement was made at the beginning of an essay, the rest of the essay would presumably be spent setting out evidence. If the statement was made at the end of the essay, presumably the essay would have included evidence.  So - the statement might stand either at the beginning or end of the essay, but evidence must be included somewhere. 
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I agree - but with big qualifications.  If the statement was made at the beginning of an essay, the rest of the essay would presumably be spent setting out evidence. If the statement was made at the end of the essay, presumably the essay would have included evidence.  So - the statement might stand either at the beginning or end of the essay, but evidence must be included somewhere.
