INTRO  <font size="4">However, according to Michael Lynch:<br /><br /> <font size="2"> &quot;The document skilfully obscured the fact there were not one but numerous strands to the struggle, as well<br /> as different sets of competing principles: the issue of liberty was for most of the political nation tied up with<br /> feudal right and overlordship or, after 1306, the moral legitimacy of one King of Scots against another.&quot;<sup>1</sup><br /></font> <br />Another reason the Scots were fighting the English was the demand made by the English king, Edward 1, for military service in his army in France, &quot;It was the reluctance of the Scots to become involved in the English war effort which drove them into an alliance with France, which was agreed in October 1295. The contrast could hardly have been starker. England gave Scotland the status of a client state; France offered an alliance of two independent kingdoms guaranteeing each other military assistance and a future marriage between King John's son Edward and the niece of Philip IV.&quot;<sup>2</sup> <br /><sup><br /></sup></font><font size="4"></font><font size="4"> </font> 
    QUESTION 0 Should both quotations be indented, as the first one is?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  If you are going to include quotations of more than forty words, these should be set apart from the main text and indented (though not reduced in font size).  In this text, the writer has indented the first, but not the second, which adds inconsistency into the mix of errors.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  If you are going to include quotations of more than forty words, these should be set apart from the main text and indented (though not reduced in font size).  In this text, the writer has indented the first quotation but not the second, which adds inconsistency into the mix of errors.
        ANSWER: It doesn't matter.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  Referencing style, which has been developed by your department for reasons of clarity and consistency, always matters.  It's part of academic discipline to keep to the style your department prefers.
    QUESTION 1 Should both quotations be in the same font size?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  Both should be in the larger font size.  Quotations should never be in font size smaller than the main text.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  Quotations should always be in the same font size, and that font size should be the same size as the main text.
        ANSWER: It's a matter of personal choice.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  All academic departments have their own referencing style, for the sake of both consistency and clarity.  Students are expected to follow the style of their department.
    QUESTION 2 Is the first quotation in this text properly set out?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.
        ANSWER: It doesn't matter, so long as it's clear that it is a quotation.
        FEEDBACK: I'm afraid it always matters, and there is a reason for this:  clarity.  Referencing style has been refined over the years not to irritate, but to promote consistency.
    QUESTION 3 Should an indented quotation be enclosed in quotation marks?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  Indented quotations do not need quotation marks.  Quotations set in the text need quotation marks, but single quotation marks, not double ones as the writer here has used.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  Indented quotations don't need quotation marks.  Quotations set in the text need quotation marks, but single quotation marks, not double ones as the writer here has used.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <span style="font-style: italic;">Le Droit Public</span> states that &quot;he who is head of state should hold the place of God.&quot;<br /><br /> 
    QUESTION 0 What is wrong with the formatting of this quotation?
        ANSWER: It should be enclosed in single quotation marks.  
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  Quotations are always enclosed in single quotation marks.  Double quotation marks are reserved for quotations within quotations.
        ANSWER: The quotation should be italicised.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  Direct quotations are never italicised, even if from a foreign publication (or in a foreign language).
        ANSWER: It should be introduced with a colon.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  In this instance, the writer has used 'that'.  You do not need 'that' and a colon.
    QUESTION 1 Is the full stop in the right place?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  Since the quotation is embedded into a wider sentence rather than being a complete sentence on its own, the full stop should come after the closing quotation mark.
        ANSWER: No. 
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  Since the quotation is embedded into a wider sentence rather than being a complete sentence on its own, the full stop should come after the closing quotation mark.
        ANSWER: It doesn't matter where the full stop is placed.
        FEEDBACK: I'm afraid it does matter.  Since the quotation is embedded into a wider sentence rather than being a complete sentence on its own, the full stop should come after the closing quotation mark.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">For example, the Venetian Doge Enrico Dandolo is accurately described as a &quot;dedicated, almost fanatical patriot&quot;<sup>4</sup> by J. J. Norwich.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 What is wrong with the quotation marks in this example?
        ANSWER: Nothing.  They are fine.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.
        ANSWER: They are double quotation marks when they should be single quotation marks.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.
    QUESTION 1 When should you use double quotation marks?
        ANSWER: When the quotation is in a foreign language.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  Quotations in a foreign language are still enclosed in single quotation marks.
        ANSWER: When a quotation is longer than 40 words or three lines.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  A quotation of over 40 words, or three lines, does not have quotation marks at all.  Instead, it should be separated from the main text by a line space and indented. 
        ANSWER: When the quotation is a quote within a quote.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  If you are quoting somebody, and they have quoted somebody else within the quotation you are using, that's the place for double quotation marks.  Click on the blue question mark above Quotation Marks, or the blue question mark above these exercises for further information and examples.
    QUESTION 2 Is the footnote number correctly placed?
        ANSWER: No.  It should come after the full stop following 'Norwich'.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.
        ANSWER: Yes.  It should be as near to the closing quotation mark as possible.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  When a quotation comes at the end of a sentence, the full stop should come after the closing punctuation - in this case the full stop after 'Norwich'.
