INTRO <font size="4" style="font-weight: bold;">Analysis of Chopin's Prelude in C major, Op.29 No. 1<br /><br /></font><font size="4">This prelude was composed in 1839 as part of a set of preludes in each of the 24 keys of the piano. Dedicated to Joseph Kessler, although commissioned by piano-maker Camille Pleyel, the preludes are each self-contained and their brevity caused critics to question their worth when they were first published.<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Is the</font> <font size="4">following text indiscriminate description or analysis/critical observation?</font> 
        ANSWER: It's analysis because it tells us important things about the preludes.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  This is description.   However, it's not indiscriminate.  It's a perfectly good start to the essay provided analysis soon follows.  The next paragraph might read:   Prelude No. 1 consists of one repeated pattern that persists through the three formal sections.  Diatonic harmony dominates the eight bar opening section, etc. 
        ANSWER: It's indiscriminate description, not analysis or critical observation.
