        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4"><span style="font-style: italic;">Concerto for Cootie</span> is a prime example of Ellington's striving for the prestige of European classical music without abandoning his roots in African-American musical traditions. The haunting, chromatic line, actually written by the dedicatee, his then trumpeter, Cootie Williams, functions more like a theme than a straightforward 'tune'. The classical reference in the title is also more than bluster in that the piece artfully blends the verse-chorus scheme characteristic of popular music with the concerto form reminiscent of Viennese classicism. Note, too, how the ubiquitous call-and-response patterns, clear reminders of a Black heritage, are transformed into the exchange between soloist and ensemble so typical of the classical concerto. In these ways, the piece doesn't so much contrast or blend African-American, popular and European, classical traditions as find common ground between them.</font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Is this paragraph indiscriminate description or analysis/critical observation?</font> 
        ANSWER: This is description.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  The bits of description are used to analyse. For example the descriptive 'haunting, chromatic line' is closely followed by 'functions more like a theme', which analyses the chromatic line's place in the work.  We also have good examples of critical observation, for example the last sentence about the common ground the piece finds between different types and styles of music.
        ANSWER: This is analysis and critical observation.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  There is description, but it's used to analyse. For example the descriptive 'haunting, chromatic line' is closely followed by 'functions more like a theme', which analyses the chromatic line's place in the work. We also have good examples of critical observation, for example the last sentence about the common ground the piece finds between different types and styles of music.
