    Writing activity 09. Introductory lines
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO  <font size="4">Assignment title:<br /><br /><span style="font-weight: bold;">Aspects of Modernity: Discuss different accounts of the form of Debussy's </span><span style="font-style: italic; font-weight: bold;">Jeux.</span><br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Read the assignment title, then choose the best introductory lines from the options provided. Each option has an explanation as to why it's good or poor, so even if you hit the right one straight away, it might be worth scanning through the others.</font> 
        ANSWER: Jeux, or 'Games', is the 'last work for orchestra written by Debussy' (Wikipedia 2011).  It was written in 1912 for the Ballets Russes and choreographed by Nijinsky.
        FEEDBACK: Although it's often useful to start with a quotation, Wikipedia is an unreliable source and does not demonstrate much effort on the writer's part.  In addition, the facts are baldly presented with no attempt to analyse why they might be relevant to the question.  These lines are not the best option here.
        ANSWER: Debussy's Jeux, or 'Games', has defied one defining account.  This is unsurprising since it was written when the development of musical modernism, for example the move away from tonality, affected all forms of artistic creation.  The two accounts of Jeux chosen for analysis in this essay highlight two different aspects:  the first focuses on the rhythmic organisation; and the second, the idea of unity through the use of cyclical form.
        FEEDBACK: These lines show proper engagement with the piece.  Although the year of composition is not stated, there is far better analysis of the context, and by the end, the reader knows just where the essay is going.  These are the best option on offer here.
        ANSWER: Debussy's Jeux was written for the Ballets Russes, with the scene set in a garden at dusk.  The main protagonists are two girls and a boy, who search for a tennis ball.  Flirting, jealousy, sulking and making up are the themes until a note of alarm is created by the arrival of another tennis ball, thrown in by an unseen hand.  This was the material with which Debussy worked.
        FEEDBACK: These lines simply tell the story without offering any insights or analysis.  Just telling the reader what happens is not acceptable in an academic essay that claims to be discussing form.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Assignment title:</font><br /><br /><font size="4"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Are the facts of composers' lives of relevance to their music?</span></font><br /> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Read the assignment title, then choose the best introductory lines from the options provided. Each option has an explanation as to why it's good or poor, so even if you hit the right one straight away, it might be worth scanning through the others.</font> 
        ANSWER: When looking at a composer's life, there are two main aspects: their music and their ordinary life.  I will discuss whether or not, for most composers, the facts of their lives are of relevance to their music.  I will look at two famous composers, Haydn and Mozart, and examine how their lives affected their music. 
        FEEDBACK: These introductory lines add nothing to the discussion apart from indicating the two composers chosen for analysis.  Just repeating the terms of the question doesn't make a good introduction.  Although it's not wrong to use the active voice - I - take care that the essay doesn't sound childish.  Definitely not the best choice on offer here.
        ANSWER: Information about composers' lives is easy to come by, but how their lives affected their music is still difficult to tell.  It would be hard to tell for anybody's life, but it's particularly hard with creative people since the tendency is to look for links where none may exist.  Nevertheless, it is worth asking whether the facts of a composer's life can be related to their music and this essay will attempt to do just that.
        FEEDBACK: This introduction doesn't start too badly, although the first sentence is very general.  However, the lines then wander along, adding nothing to the discussion.  Not the best option here.
        ANSWER: Although many critics mine composers' lives as a means of understanding their art, for example Kavanaugh on the spiritual lives of the great composers (1996), it is, perhaps, more fruitful to mine composer's works to help understand their lives.  This essay will argue that this is particularly true of Robert Schumann, in whose Kreisleriana it is possible to glimpse future mental breakdown, and also in the much less wellknown work of his wife, Clara, whose 'profound ideas', according to her husband, were often lost because of the strains of running a household (Rattalino 2002).
        FEEDBACK: This is a novel way to start - by inverting the question.  It could go horribly wrong, but the examples and quotation show thought and engagement with the question.  These lines would make a marker want to read on.  These are the best option on offer here.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO  <font size="4" style="font-weight: bold;">Assignment title:<br /><br />What was Claude Debussy's particular contribution to musical development?</font><br /><br /> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Read the assignment title, then choose the best introductory lines from the options provided. Each option has an explanation as to why it's good or poor, so even if you hit the right one straight away, it might be worth scanning through the others.</font> 
        ANSWER: According to Hurd, Claude Debussy 'brought about a revolution', yet neither formulated a 'special theory' nor left behind dedicated disciples 1968:97).  This essay will argue that this is where Debussy's genius lies: that, at a time when other composers, for example Schoenberg, were consciously reacting against traditional forms and tonality, Debussy was instinctively discovering harmonic methods of his own, not as a reaction, but as a progression.  This essay will analyse Debussy's contribution to music through two works:  his Nocturnes, composed in 1895, and Images pour orchestre, composed in 1909.
        FEEDBACK: These lines show engagement with the question and a clear line of argument.  They are the best option here.
        ANSWER: Debussy 'brought about a revolution', and we can see this through all his works.  Living and working in Paris, the cultural capital of the nineteenth century, he was at the centre of artistic activity, and not just in music.  Artists abounded, and new forms took hold: impressionism, post impressionism and symbolism, surrealism.
        FEEDBACK: These lines show some thought, but no analysis, no real examples - lists of 'isms' don't really count.  You need to acknowledge sources and relate any examples to the essay question.  Not the best option here.
        ANSWER: Heavily influenced by Baudelaire, and Verlaine amongst others, Claude Debussy was a true intellectual and also a counter-culturalist.  In 1909, it was reported that 'the Debussy cult is making many people who are really desperately bewildered affect to perceive beauties and wonderful meanings that have probably escaped the attention of the composer' (Langham Smith, p.149).
        FEEDBACK: These sentences are non-sequiturs, i.e. they don't form a logical progression.  We also need evidence of Debussy's influences, and of his being a 'counter-culturalist' - if that really is a good description.  The quotation seems out of place because it is not really backing up the previous assertion.   In addition, there is no date in the reference.  Not the best option here.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4" style="font-weight: bold;">Assignment title:</font><br /><br /><font size="4" style="font-weight: bold;">What do you understand by the term 'folk music', and what is its value?</font><br /> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Read the assignment title, then choose the best introductory lines from the options provided. Each option has an explanation as to why it's good or poor, so even if you hit the right one straight away, it might be worth scanning through the others.</font> 
        ANSWER: 'Folk music' is 'music that originates in traditional popular culture or that is written in such a style.  Folk music is typically of unknown authorship and is transmitted orally from generation to generation' (Oxford online dictionary).  It is important because it is music made by the people for the people.
        FEEDBACK: These introductory lines do not inspire confidence.  It's not really enough simply to copy and paste, even if you do acknowledge your source.  Quotations should add weight to, rather than be a substitute for, a thought of your own.  In addition, the Oxford Online Dictionary is not a specialist source.  Definitions of terms should always come from the Grove: http://www.grovemusic.com. Not the best option on offer here.
        ANSWER: Folk music is the kind of music you hear on the street or in bars.  It is music made by ordinary people without musical training.  It often comes down to us through being played or sung at certain types of work.
        FEEDBACK: All of this may be true, but generalisations like this won't do in an academic essay.  You must provide evidence and examples.  This is not the best option here.
        ANSWER: The term 'folk music' is seldom defined twice in the same way.  For example, composers of the Romantic era thought of it as part of the 'national essence' (Middleton 1990:127); dictionaries add that it is usually transmitted orally (Oxford Online Dictionary 2011); and current exponents argue that it is 'pop music with a social conscience' (Ruehl n.d.).  These three definitions offer three routes into assessing its value: through classical composers heavily influenced by the 'national essence', for example Smetana; through English folk songs, for example 'Summer is a'cummin in'; and through the music of activists such as Bob Dylan.
        FEEDBACK: These introductory lines use quotations to back up a point:  that folk music is seldom defined by two people in the same way.  An essay plan is presented, with examples to be followed up.  The only criticism I'd make is that the Oxford Online Dictionary is not a specialist source.  Definitions of terms should always come from the Grove: http://www.grovemusic.com. Nevertheless, these lines are the best option here.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Assignment title:</span><br style="font-weight: bold;" /><br style="font-weight: bold;" /><span style="font-weight: bold;">Is Adorno's polemic against popular music warranted?</span><br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Read the assignment title, then choose the best introductory lines from the options provided. Each option has an explanation as to why it's good or poor, so even if you hit the right one straight away, it might be worth scanning through the others.</font> 
        ANSWER: Theodor W. Adorno lived from 1903 to 1969, and was a sociologist, philosopher and musicologist.  He wanted to be a composer, but it is has a theorist and critic that he is best known.
        FEEDBACK: This sentence is not wrong, but it does not grab the attention.  Even in your first line, always try to find something more to say than bare facts.
        ANSWER: T. W. Adorno's polemic against popular culture is superficially attractive, particularly in the early 21st century when popular culture is dominated by generic and emotionally manipulative shows, for example The X Factor.
        FEEDBACK: This sentence shows engagement with the question.  Adorno's theory is 'superficially' attractive, which leads the reader to anticipate, with some interest, an argument against it.  An example is put to good use. This is the best option on offer.
        ANSWER: T. W. Adorno's polemic against popular culture has always been controversial.  This essay will discuss why it is controversial and try to discover whether the polemic was warranted or not.
        FEEDBACK: These lines simply repeat the question, adding nothing.  If they were deleted from an essay, they would not be missed.  Not the best option here.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Assignment title:</span><br style="font-weight: bold;" /><br style="font-weight: bold;" /><span style="font-weight: bold;">When popular groups or singers change their style, that's the beginning of the end. Discuss.</span><br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">Read the assignment title, then choose the best introductory lines from the options provided. Each option has an explanation as to why it's good or poor, so even if you hit the right one straight away, it might be worth scanning through the others.</font> 
        ANSWER: Popular groups often churn out the same style of song over their whole span of recording life.  But if they change, is this the beginning of the end?  This essay will try to discover.
        FEEDBACK: These lines provide one generalisation, no evidence and no essay map.  Not the best option here.
        ANSWER: With their seventh studio album, Revolver, the Beatles broke new ground both through the lyrics, for example the mournful 'Eleanor Rigby' and the musical arrangements, for example the use of a string octet.  The album shot to the top of the charts both in Britain and the US.  On 17th May 1966, Bob Dylan exchanged his acoustic guitar for an electric guitar and was famously derided as 'Judas'.
        FEEDBACK: This is an unusual and striking introduction, showing, through examples, two different sides of the discussion.  Such a confident opening makes the reader want to read on.  This is the best option here.
    Writing activity 10. Concluding lines
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Assignment title:<br /><br /></font><font size="4"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Aspects of Modernity: Discuss different accounts of the form of Debussy's </span><span style="font-style: italic; font-weight: bold;">Jeux</span></font>.<br /> 
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">Read the assignment title, then choose the best concluding lines from the options provided. Each option has an explanation as to why it's good or poor, so even if you hit the right one straight away, it might be worth scanning through the others.</font> 
        ANSWER: The two analyses of Debussy's Jeux chosen for discussion inform our understanding of Jeux in different way: Berman's through the prism of another Debussy work; and Pasler through time and form.   Both accounts add to our understanding; both, as has been shown, open up new questions.  All the secrets of Jeux have not yet been uncovered.
        FEEDBACK: These lines draw together the strands of the essay together and also leave room for further discussion.  These are the best option here.
        ANSWER: To conclude, I think Paslar's account of Jeux is the best and the one Debussy would have agreed with.
        FEEDBACK: This conclusion is stark, and the assignment asks for discussion, so there's no need to plump for one account over another.  It's also dangerous to declare what Debussy would have thought unless you have evidence to back up your assertion.  This conclusion is not the best on offer here.
        ANSWER: To conclude, it should be noted that there are many more accounts of Debussy's Jeux than I have had space for here, some equally important.
        FEEDBACK: This conclusion seems to undermine the whole essay.  The conclusion is not the place to mention the limits of the essay.  If this needs to be done, it should be done in the introduction.  The reader needs to feel he or she has come to a satisfactory end, not a dead end.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Assignment title:<br /><br />Are the facts of composers' lives of relevance to their music?</span></font> 
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">Read the assignment title, then choose the best concluding lines from the options provided. Each option has an explanation as to why it's good or poor, so even if you hit the right one straight away, it might be worth scanning through the others.</font> 
        ANSWER: To conclude, when the music does not match the facts, this could be because the facts are not complete.  Most of the time, in my opinion, the facts of a composer's life are relevant to their music.
        FEEDBACK: These concluding lines seem very brisk and offer a superficial analysis, with no mention of any composer by name.  Not the best option here. 
        ANSWER: As has been shown, decades of scrutiny into the lives of Robert and Clara Schumann have thrown up much conjecture as to the relationship between their lives and their music, and it is true that conjecture is not fact.  However, through the Schumanns' own writings we have also seen how their lives and music were inextricably intertwined, so that if the question 'are the facts of your lives relevant to your music?' was put to them, the presumption must be that the answer would be 'yes'.
        FEEDBACK: This conclusion draws the strands of the essay together and faces squarely the inevitable objection that conjecture is not fact.  By using evidence, however, a convincing argument is made.  This conclusion is the best on offer here.
        ANSWER: Thus we can see that in some cases the facts of a composer's life are of relevance to their music and in some cases not.  This is because composers are human beings first and composers second, so it is impossible for the facts of their lives not to influence their music.
        FEEDBACK: This is a rather superficial point, and does not seem to draw on any of the themes that must have made up the essay.  Not a good option.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4" style="font-weight: bold;">Assignment title:</font><br /><br /><font size="4" style="font-weight: bold;">What do you understand by the term 'folk music', and what is its value?</font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Read the assignment title, then choose the best concluding lines from the options provided. Each option has an explanation as to why it's good or poor, so even if you hit the right one straight away, it might be worth scanning through the others.</font> 
        ANSWER: Thus, folk music can be defined as music handed down through the generations and its value lies in this continuity with the past.
        FEEDBACK: This is not bad, it's just a little stark.  Remember that your conclusion is the last thing your marker will read, so last impressions are important.  This isn't the best option here.
        ANSWER: In conclusion, folk music defies definition and its value is that it allows ordinary people to express themselves in whatever way they like.
        FEEDBACK: This conclusion is too general, and seems to give up on the essay question.  Not the best option here.
        ANSWER: As this essay has shown, folk music defies definition only if the definition is too narrow.  It is, in essence, music made in the street and field rather than in the drawing room or concert hall and its value lies in its being 'a faithful reflection of ourselves' (Parry in Middleton 1990:131).
        FEEDBACK: This conclusion grasps the question and tries to answer it, referring back to the essay.  It ends with a good quotation.  This is the best option here.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Assignment title:</span><br style="font-weight: bold;" /><br style="font-weight: bold;" /><span style="font-weight: bold;">When popular groups or singers change their style, that's the beginning of the end. Discuss.</span></font><br /> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Read the assignment title, then choose the best concluding lines from the options provided. Each option has an explanation as to why it's good or poor, so even if you hit the right one straight away, it might be worth scanning through the others.</font> 
        ANSWER: Thus we can see that when popular groups or singers change their style, whether or not that's the beginning of the end depends on them being able to take their fans with them or losing them altogether.
        FEEDBACK: This option is hedges its bets and shies away from answering the question.  Not the best option on offer.
        ANSWER: As this essay has shown, when popular groups or singers change their style, there is always the risk that they will lose their fans and that would mark the beginning of the end.  However, many groups manage the change and go on to forge even more successful careers.
        FEEDBACK: This option is a little plodding.  Your concluding lines are the last lines your marker will read, so it's worth trying to make them more memorable.  Not the best option here.
        ANSWER: As this essay has shown, a change of style is always risky:  the Beatles managed it;  Bob Dylan did not - or at least not at first.  This last point is crucial.  The end of a style is just that: the end of a style.  As Dylan showed, a new style can bring in new fans, so whilst there is certainly an end, it may be an ending that, in time, heralds a new beginning.
        FEEDBACK: These lines reflect back on the essay, and end with a decent flourish.  These lines are the best on offer here.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4" style="font-weight: bold;">Assignment title:<br /><br />What was Claude Debussy's particular contribution to musical development?</font> 
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">Read the assignment title, then choose the best introductory lines from the options provided. Each option has an explanation as to why it's good or poor, so even if you hit the right one straight away, it might be worth scanning through the others.</font> 
        ANSWER: Debussy's contribution to musical development was that he approached music in a new way and wrote many new works that are still highly popular today.
        FEEDBACK: This option is too bland.  It shows little engagement with the question and could have been written with no research at all.  Not the best option here.
        ANSWER: With his interest in the pentatonic and whole-note scales, Debussy opened contemporary listeners' ears to sounds beyond classical harmony based on the diatonic scale and orthodox chord sequences. He was not alone in introducing new harmonies, but his 'delicate washes of sound' (Hurd 1968:98) are unmistakeable and his contribution to musical development was to free others, for example Stravinsky, to push the boundaries of rhythm and tonality even further than he went himself. 
        FEEDBACK: This ending has not forgotten to include examples and to employ musical terms.  It's the best on offer here.
        ANSWER: With his interest in new colours and musical textures, Debussy opened contemporary listeners' ears to sounds with which they were not familiar.  He was not alone in introducing new harmonies but his particular contribution to musical development was to push the boundaries of what was acceptable and so pave the way for others to go further than he wished to go himself.
        FEEDBACK: This conclusion has forgotten that even at the end you must remember to use appropriate technical terms and provide examples.  This is not the best option here.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Assignment title:</span><br style="font-weight: bold;" /><br style="font-weight: bold;" /><span style="font-weight: bold;">Is Adorno's polemic against popular music warranted?</span></font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Read the assignment title, then choose the best concluding lines from the options provided. Each option has an explanation as to why it's good or poor, so even if you hit the right one straight away, it might be worth scanning through the others.</font> 
        ANSWER: Thus we can see that Adorno's polemic against popular music was not warranted because it was informed too heavily by the times in which he lived.
        FEEDBACK: This conclusion is not wrong but it could be better fleshed out.  Not the best option here.
        ANSWER: In conclusion, Adorno's polemic was informed by the times in which he lived, the 1930s, and his method of looking at things 'through the extremes' (Middleton 1990:35).  Both detract from the value of his polemic.  Nevertheless, his dissection of the function of music remains an important reminder of music's role in shaping society, something that without Adorno would be easier to ignore.
        FEEDBACK: This conclusion doesn't forget the necessity of examples and quotations.  It's the best option here.
        ANSWER: In conclusion, Adorno's polemic was informed by his times and his methods.   As has been shown, however, his polemic remains valuable because he was an important contributor to debates about music which still persist today.
        FEEDBACK: This conclusion is very general, which never leaves a good impression.  Not the best option here.
    Writing activity 11. Paragraphing
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <style>&lt;!-- /* Font Definitions */@font-face {font-family:Cambria; panose-1:2 4 5 3 5 4 6 3 2 4; mso-font-charset:0; mso-generic-font-family:auto; mso-font-pitch:variable; mso-font-signature:3 0 0 0 1 0;} /* Style Definitions */p.MsoNormal, li.MsoNormal, div.MsoNormal {mso-style-parent:&quot;&quot;; margin:0cm; margin-bottom:.0001pt; mso-pagination:widow-orphan; font-size:12.0pt; font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; mso-ascii-font-family:Cambria; mso-ascii-theme-font:minor-latin; mso-fareast-font-family:Cambria; mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-latin; mso-hansi-font-family:Cambria; mso-hansi-theme-font:minor-latin; mso-bidi-font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-bidi;}@page Section1 {size:612.0pt 792.0pt; margin:72.0pt 90.0pt 72.0pt 90.0pt; mso-header-margin:36.0pt; mso-footer-margin:36.0pt; mso-paper-source:0;}div.Section1 {page:Section1;}--&gt;</style>
<p>The concert hall was a place of congregation. Concert-goers dressed carefully and there was a general air of anticipation and excitement before a performance, even if the performance did not include a star performer. The introduction of sound recording in the late nineteenth century introduced a new medium for both the listener and the performer. No longer was listening to what might be called %u2018formal%u2019music %u2013 to differentiate it from street music %u2013 an exclusive experience. Over time, as the means of playing recorded music became cheaper, music became ubiquitous. </p> 
    QUESTION 0 Should this text be divided into paragraphs?
        ANSWER: No.  It's all about music, so can remain as one paragraph.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree. Try again.
        ANSWER: Yes, it needs dividing up.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  Go to the next question.
    QUESTION 1 If you think the text should be divided, where should it be divided?
        ANSWER: 'Over time' should start a new paragraph.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again.
        ANSWER: 'The introduction of sound recording' should start a new paragraph.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  The first two sentences are about music in the concert hall.  Sound recording is a new topic, so needs a new paragraph.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">The original sketch for the work contains no indication of tempo or dynamics, and from this he created a piano reduction so that the dancers could practise. The orchestration was completed nine months later. Thus the timescale was brief. In total, it had taken a month. The draft orchestration is filled with particular interest for those looking for the composer's exploration of new ideas. Not all the ideas, for example the solo harp, made it through to the finished score. </font> 
