    QUESTION 1 If you find you have a whole unbroken page of text, should you divide it even if it's on one theme?
        ANSWER: No.  If a block of text is on one theme, it should remain as a blok of text.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Think of the reader.  A whole, unbroken page of text can be off-putting.  Read your text aloud to see where a division might be made. There will almost certainly be somewhere to make a break.
        ANSWER: Yes.  You should find some way of dividing it up.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  Think of the reader.  A whole, unbroken page of text can be off-putting.  Read your text aloud to see where a division might be made. There will almost certainly be somewhere to make a break.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO  The line of great German lieder writers continued after Schubert through Robert Schumann, Johannes Brahms and Hugo Wolf. Wolf's contribution is particularly interesting on account of the use he made of Wagnerian techniques - the main burden of his songs falling to the piano, with the voice adding a realistic, dramatic recitative. French art-song, generally less dramatic than German and more inclined to sensitive lyricism, grew to greatness in the hands of Henri Duparc, Gabriel Faur? and Claude Debussy. Russia produced one outstanding song-writer in Modest Moussorgsky, whose songs are remarkable for their dramatic realism. Like Schubert, he explored unusual aspects of human nature, and found beauty in unlikely places.<br /><br /><font size="4"><font size="1">Adapted for teaching purposes from Michael Hurd's <span style="font-style: italic;">An Outline History of European Music</span>, 1968, Sevenoaks: Novello &amp; Company Ltd.</font></font><br /> 
