        FEEDBACK: You could certainly do this, though the paragraphs would be rather short.  Think of yourself as a reader.  I think a reader would find the theme of song-writer unifies the text nicely. 
        ANSWER: This text should remain as one.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  If you divide it, the paragraphs are rather short.   I think a reader would find the theme of song-writer unifies the text nicely.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO  <font size="4">The Romantic movement, which began in English and German literature about the year 1770, found its musical voice during the early part of the nineteenth century. It remained a dominating force in music for nearly a hundred years. In very broad terms Romanticism is an attitude of mind that rejects the cool logic of the intellect and trusts instead in the instinctive truths of emotion. Thus, the Romantic movement represents a reaction against eighteenth century classicism - an Age of Unreason to counterbalance the Age of Reason.<br /><br /><font size="1">Adapted for teaching purposes from Michael Hurd's <span style="font-style: italic;">An Outline History of European Music</span>, 1968, Sevenoaks: Novello &amp; Company Ltd.</font> <br /></font> 
