        ANSWER: The text should be divided into three:  the second paragraph starting 'Mozart's dramas ...';  the third starting 'So also his arias ...'
        FEEDBACK: I agree that the text needs dividing, but I'd divide it into two, with the second paragraph beginning 'So also his arias'.  I think dividing it into three would make the paragraphs very short, and distract from the meaning of the text, rather than enhancing it.
    Writing activity 07.  Disjointed argument and non-sequitur sentences
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO The introduction of sound recording in the late 19th century added a new dimension. Hanslick claims that music cannot evoke any emotion; everything depends on the artistry of the performer. 
    QUESTION 0 Are these sentences well connected?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  We need to go through certain stages before the first sentence is properly linked to the second: that sound recording meant there was no need for an audience; that this changes the emotional charge of the music and why; that the advent of sound recording saw the emergence of different theories about the emotional power of music.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">Schoenberg composed <span style="font-style: italic;">Pierrot Lunaire</span> in March 1912. Melodrama was fashionable at the end of the 19th century. Schoenberg's music had often been dismissed but he welcomed the idea of <span style="font-style: italic;">Pierrot Lunaire</span>. </font> 
    QUESTION 0 Are these three sentences properly linked?
        ANSWER: Yes.  They are linked because they all refer to the same composer and the same piece of music.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree. Try again.
        ANSWER: No.  The sentences are about the same composer and the same piece of music but the ideas need linking together.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  You must explain that the work is a melodrama before saying anything about melodrama itself. You must also say something specific, using examples, about Schoenberg's music, rather than just stating that it was criticised.  Never assume that your reader will make the links.  Making the links is the writer's job.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">After Beethoven lost his hearing, he was unhappy because he was unable to hear what they sounded like. </font> 
    QUESTION 0 Does the second part of this question necessarily follow on from the first? 
        ANSWER: Yes.  If you can't hear, how can you hear what music sounds like?
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Think about it.  I'll bet you can hear music in your head even though there's nothing actually playing.  If you assert that Beethoven couldn't hear music even in his head, you'll need to provide proof.  In addition, 'they' has no reference.  Who are 'they'?
        ANSWER: No.  He might still have been able to hear music in his head.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  After all, even those of us with no musical genius can hear music in our heads.  If you're going to assert that Beethoven lacked this capacity, you'll need to provide evidence.But the broader problem is that Beethoven's deafness is a complex subject and the text gives a rather simplistic analysis.  In addition, 'they' has no reference.  Who are 'they'?
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">It may come as a surprise that the second subject in Beethoven's 'Waldstein' Sonata, Op. 53, is in E major.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 Does this kind of statement help to illustrate the structure of the sonata in question?
        ANSWER: Yes.  It tell us about the key of the second subject, which is part of the sonata's structure.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  The specification of the key of the second subject is meaningless without the key of the movement as a whole (C major).  In addition, an indication of the 'formal' framework (sonata form) and what would be expected (the dominant G major) would clarify the matter further.   So, here we might have:  Given that its outline is unequivocally in sonata form, it may come as a surprise that the second subject of the first movement of Beethoven's Piano Sonata in C major, Op. 52, 'Waldstein', is in E major instead of the expected dominant, G major. 
        ANSWER: No.  You need to make an argument if you're going to claim something is a 'surprise' in the structure of a piece of music.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  The specification of the key of the second subject is meaningless without the key of the movement as a whole (C major).  In addition, an indication of the 'formal' framework (sonata form) and what would be expected (the dominant G major) would clarify the matter further.  So, here we might have:  Given that its outline is unequivocally in sonata form, it may come as a surprise that the second subject of the first movement of Beethoven's Piano Sonata in C major, Op. 52, 'Waldstein', is in E major instead of the expected dominant, G major.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">In the coda [of the first movement of Schubert%u2019s Trio Op. 100], the tune is first presented in the tonic Eb major, leading naturally to B minor.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 Do the facts in this sentence lead logically on from one another.
        ANSWER: Yes.  We can see the harmonic progression through the listed keys, i.e. the tonic Eb major to B minor.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  The phrase 'leading naturally' hides the fact that B minor is extremely remote from Eb major in conventional terms. We need an explanation.  So, we could have:  The coda of the first movement of Schubert's Trio Op. 100 features a prime example of what Richard Cohn (1999) calls a 'maximally smooth cycle', transforming harmonies by shifting voices by a semitone, one at a time. Moving around the 'western hemisphere' in clockwise direction (Eb major - Eb minor - B major/Cb major - B minor) this explains why the melody appears first in Eb major and then in the seemingly unrelated and enharmonically re-spelt B minor.  Here, the explanation, i.e. the 'maximally smooth cycle' with the intervening harmonies, supplies the context within which the coda's tune makes sense. N.B. listing isolated keys neither reveals anything nor demonstrates any understanding of the underlying harmonic process.
        ANSWER: No, there's something missing.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  The phrase 'leading naturally' hides the fact that B minor is extremely remote from Eb major in conventional terms. We need an explanation.  So, we could have:  The coda of the first movement of Schubert's Trio Op. 100 features a prime example of what Richard Cohn (1999) calls a 'maximally smooth cycle', transforming harmonies by shifting voices by a semitone, one at a time. Moving around the 'western hemisphere' in clockwise direction (Eb major - Eb minor - B major/Cb major - B minor) this explains why the melody appears first in Eb major and then in the seemingly unrelated and enharmonically re-spelt B minor. Here, the explanation, i.e. the 'maximally smooth cycle' with the intervening harmonies, supplies the context within which the coda's tune makes sense. N.B. listing isolated keys neither reveals anything nor demonstrates any understanding of the underlying harmonic process.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">Both Bach's passions manage to display vivid and beautiful imagery that put the pieces into a league of their own. It is clear that the Baroque period and Bach's passions contain many more active areas than static ones, and overall create something unique and beautiful.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">Do these sentences create a clear line of argument, and are the value judgements substantiated or too vague? </font> 
        ANSWER: Yes, these sentences create a clear line of argument, and the use of 'Baroque' and the phrases 'active' and 'static' make the value judgements valid.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  The phrases 'vivid and beautiful', 'into a league of their own and 'unique and beautiful' mean little without further explanation or example, and it's not clear at all how imagery relates to 'active' and 'static' areas.  It's the writer's job to make these links explicitly.
        ANSWER: No, these sentences don't create a clear line of argument, and the value judgements are not substantiated.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  The phrases 'vivid and beautiful', 'into a league of their own and 'unique and beautiful' mean little without further explanation or example, and it's not clear at all how imagery relates to 'active' and 'static' areas.  It's the writer's job to make these links explicitly.
