INTRO  <font size="4">1. Pop music is often inspired by the classics, sometimes quite obviously as in Elvis Presley's 'Can't Help Falling In Love', directly taken from Martini's Plaisir d'Amour; Allan Sherman's 'hello muddah hello faddah' from Ponchielli's Dance of the Hours; Kenn Dodd's <span style="font-style: italic;">So Deep In The Nigh</span>t from Chopin's etude in E; and Kenny Ball and his Jazzmen's Rondo, a jazz version of the rondo of Mozart's Piano Sonata No. 11, popularly dubbed <span style="font-style: italic;">alla Turca</span>.<br /><br />2. </font><font size="4">Pop music is often inspired by the classics, sometimes quite obviously as in Elvis Presley's <span style="font-style: italic;">Can't Help Falling In Love</span>, directly taken from Martini's 'Plaisir d'Amour'; Allan Sherman's <span style="font-style: italic;">Hello Muddah Hello Faddah</span> from Ponchielli's 'Dance Of The Hours'; Kenn Dodd's <span style="font-style: italic;">So Deep In The Nigh</span>t from Chopin's etude in E, </font><font size="4">an Etude also known as <span style="font-style: italic;">Tristesse</span></font><font size="4">; and Kenny Ball and his Jazzmen's rondo, a jazz version of the Rondo of Mozart's <span style="font-style: italic;">Piano Sonata No. 1</span>1, popularly dubbed '<span style="font-style: italic;">Alla Turca'</span>.<br /><br />3. </font><font size="4">Pop music is often inspired by the classics, quite obviously as in Elvis Presley's 'Can't help falling In love with you', directly taken from Martini's <span style="font-style: italic;">Plaisir d'Amour</span>; Allan Sherman's 'Hello muddah, hello faddah' from Ponchielli's <span style="font-style: italic;">Dance of the Hours</span>; Kenn Dodd's 'So deep in the night' from Chopin's Etude in E, an etude also known as 'Tristesse'; and Kenny Ball and his Jazzmen's Rondo, a jazz version of the rondo of Mozart's Piano Sonata No. 11, popularly dubbed 'alla Turca'.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 Which of these is correctly formatted?
        ANSWER: 1.
        FEEDBACK: Not 1.  Try again.
        ANSWER: 2.
        FEEDBACK: Not 2.  Try again.
        ANSWER: 3.
        FEEDBACK: That's correct.  Song titles are set in inverted commas; whole works with particular names are italicised.  Be careful to note when a term like 'etude' is being used as part of a title - i.e. the Etude in E major - and when as a generic term - i.e. A number of etudes use ...  Also, take care of capitals: small words like 'the', 'in' 'of' are seldom capitalised unless coming at the start of a name.  For more information, please click on the blue question mark above the tasks.
