INTRO <font size="4">Which of the following references is correctly formatted?</font> 
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">Read the text then answer the question(s).</font> 
        ANSWER: www.dh.gov.uk, cited 15/01/10, Department of Health, Single Assessment Process for older people: The accreditation process for off the shelf assessment tools.
        FEEDBACK: Not this one.  Try again.
        ANSWER: Department of Health, Single Assessment Process for older people: The accreditation process for off the shelf assessment tools. www.dh.gov.uk, cited 15/01/10
        FEEDBACK: No this one.  Try again.
        ANSWER: Department of Health (2004), Single assessment process for older people: the accreditation process for off the shelf assessment tools, www.dh.gov.uk, [accessed 15/01/10]
        FEEDBACK: Well done.  This one would be fine. Author, date, title, website, date accessed - that order is logical and the reader would easily be able to access this reference.
        Task freetext difficulty 2
        Task freetext difficulty 2
        Task freetext difficulty 2
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">Can you answer the following questions?</font> 
    QUESTION 0 In a references section, should you put a full stop after listing a web page url line?
        ANSWER: Yes.  A full stop separates the url from the next entry in the reference.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.
        ANSWER: No. You should never put a full stop after a url, or add any other punctuation.
        FEEDBACK: Yes, that's right.  Don't add any punctuation to a url line, not even a full stop at the end.
    QUESTION 1 If a published book is not the first edition (i.e. it's the second, or a subsequent edition), do you need to provide this information in the reference?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: That's correct.  The point of referencing is for a reader to be able to access the text that you've used, so the edition might make a difference. 
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  The point of referencing is for a reader to be able to access the text that you've used, so the edition might make a difference.
    QUESTION 2 If you think the edition does matter, where within your reference should this information be placed?
        ANSWER: Directly after the publication date.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  Try again.
        ANSWER: Right at the end of the citation.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  Try again.
        ANSWER: After the city of publication.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.   Try again.
        ANSWER: After the name of the book or journal.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  The edition number needs to go directly after the name of the publication, and in this form: 2nd ed., or 2nd Ed. (or you can use the whole word, i.e. 2nd edition or 2nd Edition).
