    Writing activity 02. Commas and run-on sentences
        Task freetext difficulty 1
        Task freetext difficulty 1
        Task freetext difficulty 2
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Women are more likely to seek help and talk about their health problems than men, this may be because it is more socially acceptable for women to talk about health care, some men feel that discussing their problems is a sign of weakness, furthermore 'an unwillingness to admit weakness may prevent many men from taking health promotion messages seriously' (Doyal, 2001).</font> 
    QUESTION 0 Into how many sentences should this text be divided?
        ANSWER: It's fine as one sentence.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again!
        ANSWER: Two.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  There are several ideas and thoughts in the text.  For clarity and ease of reading, two sentences is not enough.
        ANSWER: Three.
        FEEDBACK: Three might do it, although I'm not sure this is the best solution.
        ANSWER: Four.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  I think four sentences is best for this text.
    QUESTION 1 From the following, which is the best division?
        ANSWER: Women are more likely to seek help and talk about their health problems than men.  This may be because it is more socially acceptable for women to talk about health care.  Some men feel that discussing their problems is a sign of weakness.  Furthermore, 'an unwillingness to admit weakness may prevent many men from taking health promotion messages seriously' (Doyal, 2001).
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  This text is very clear.
        ANSWER: Women are more likely to seek help and talk about their health problems than men, this may be because it is more socially acceptable for women to talk about health care.  Some men feel that discussing their problems is a sign of weakness, furthermore, 'an unwillingness to admit weakness may prevent many men from taking health promotion messages seriously' (Doyal, 2001).
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  I think the first sentence is what we call a 'run-on' sentence, i.e. it feels as though it's two sentences allowed to run together.  If you read the second sentence aloud, it feels clumsy because of the word 'furthermore' and the commas.  Better to make this two sentences too.
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">Both studies actively introduced an intervention, that of a selected educational programme, but one of the key differences between the two studies is that the Baraz et al. (2009) study was aiming to introduce an educational intervention by two methods, oral and video, and then make a comparison as to which intervention, if any, would be more effective at increasing dietary and fluid compliance amongst haemodialysis patients, this is known as a between subjects design (Polit &amp; Beck, 2010).</font> 
    QUESTION 0 If you can only change one of the commas in this text into a full stop, which comma should be changed?
        ANSWER: The comma after 'education'.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  This could only be done by changing the text.  With the current text, 'oral and video education' is a sub-clause, so needs to be enclosed in commas. 
        ANSWER: The commas after 'intervention' in sentence 1.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  This would disrupt the rest of the sentence, making it very difficult indeed to understand.
        ANSWER: The comma after 'patients'.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  The explanation of the intervention is quite long, so we're looking for a full stop.  This is a good place for it, i.e. after the explanation and before a new piece of information.
        ANSWER: After 'programme' in sentence 1, i.e. before 'but'.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  If we can only have one full stop, there's a better place for it.
