        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Can you answer the following questions?</font> 
    QUESTION 0 In a dissertation, can each individual section comprise more than one paragraph?
        ANSWER: No.  A section should be one paragraph.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  Paragraphs are dictated by theme not by section.
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  Paragraphs are dictated by themes, not by sections.
    QUESTION 1 Can a paragraph be any length?
        ANSWER: No.  A paragraph has to be more than five lines long.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  A paragraph can be any length, although a paragraph is normally more than one line or one sentence.  Be careful to make the distinction between a paragraph and a list.  Normally, a paragraph will be several lines long.
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  A paragraph can be any length, although a paragraph is normally more than one line or one sentence.  Be careful to make the distinction between a paragraph and a list.  Normally, a paragraph will be several lines long.
    QUESTION 2 If I have a big theme that takes up more than one page, should I subdivide that into paragraphs?
        ANSWER: No.  You must keep your theme together.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  I think a large block of text is unhelpful to the reader.  Normally, a big theme will break down into smaller ones. Look for these small breaks to make your paragraphs.
        ANSWER: Yes.  It's fine to chop up a theme into paragraphs.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  I think a large block of text is unhelpful to the reader.  Normally, a big theme will break down into smaller ones. Look for these small breaks to make your paragraphs.
