    Writing activity 10. Sentence fragments
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">1. Also, to check for pressure areas as patients may be more susceptible to sores if they are not as mobile as they once were.<br /><br />2. This is a good opportunity for the nurse to ensure that the drain is secure.<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Which of these sentences is the fragment?
        ANSWER: Sentence 1.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  This sentence has no driving verb that tells us when the action has, is, will be or might be performed.
        ANSWER: Sentence 2.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  Sentence 2 has a main verb:  'is'.  This verb sets the action in time.
    QUESTION 1 How can you repair this fragment?
        ANSWER: By inserting 'this is a good opportunity' after 'also' in sentence 1.
        FEEDBACK: You can certainly do it that way.  There's also another way.
        ANSWER: By removing the full stop at the end of sentence 2, adding the word 'and' and joining sentence 1 to the end of sentence 2.
        FEEDBACK: That's also correct.  Well done.  If you do this, remember to remove the comma after 'also' so that the text flows smoothly.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">1. Insulin suppresses glucose production in the liver. <br />2. Stimulating glucose uptake in muscles and fat. </font> 
    QUESTION 0 Which sentence is the fragment (i.e. contains no driving verb)?
        ANSWER: Sentence 1 is the fragment.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not right.  The driving verb in sentence 1 is 'suppresses'.
        ANSWER: Sentence 2 is the fragment.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  'Stimulating' is not a driving verb, i.e. it doesn't set the action in time.  We can put it right by simply running the two sentences together divided only by a comma:  Insulin suppresses glucose production in the liver, stimulating glucose uptake in muscles and fat.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO 1. This worked.<br />2. Suggesting to the patient that since he lived near his work, walking to his office might help combat his weight problem.<br /> 
    QUESTION 0 Which is the sentence fragment (i.e. contains no driving verb), sentence 1 or sentence 2?
        ANSWER: Sentence 1 is the fragment.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  Sentence 1 has a subject - 'This' (a pronoun standing in for a noun or naming word), and a driving verb - 'worked'.  'Worked' sets the action (whatever the action is) in time.
        ANSWER: Sentence 2 is the fragment.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  This has all the feel of a subclause because 'Suggesting' is not a driving verb, i.e. it does not set the action in time.  'Lived' is not the driving verb for this sentence either, since this is part of the subclause enclosed in commas and introduced by the word 'that'.
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task freetext difficulty 2
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">1. Redundancy can cause depression.<br />2. Redundancy causing depression.</font><br /> 
    QUESTION 0 Which is the sentence fragment, sentence 1 or sentence 2?
        ANSWER: Sentence 1 is the fragment.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not right.  We have a driving verb here 'can'.   This sets the sentence in time, since the conditional (might, could, can) is also a verb tense.
        ANSWER: Sentence 2 is the fragment.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  'Causing' is not a driving verb, i.e. it doesn't set the sentence in time.  We could solve the fragment problem by changing the verb into the present tense:   Redundancy causes depression.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">1. Referring to Leventhal et al. (1980).<br />2. Leventhal et al. (1980) was referred to.</font><br /> 
    QUESTION 0 Which of the following is a driving verb?  If you're not sure what a driving verb is, click on the blue question mark above the tasks.
        ANSWER: 'Referring to' is a driving verb.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  This type of verb doesn't set the action in time and a driving verb must set the action in time.
        ANSWER: 'Was referred to' is a driving verb.
        FEEDBACK: That's right:  this sets the action in time.  In this case, 'was' sets the action in the past.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">1. So that she achieves her goal weight.<br />2. This would help to guide Lily.</font><br /> 
    QUESTION 0 Which of these sentence is the fragment?
        ANSWER: Sentence 1 is the fragment.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  This sentence hangs in the air since we don't know what has to happen 'so that she achieves her goal weight'. 
        ANSWER: Sentence 2 is the fragment.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  Sentence 1 is the fragment because the sentence hangs in the air, i.e. there's no driving verb so we don't know what 'she' must to do achieve her goal weight.
    QUESTION 1 How can we cure the fragment without rewriting both sentences?
        ANSWER: We can't.
        FEEDBACK: We can!
        ANSWER: By running the sentences together, with sentence 2 coming first.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  If we do that, we get a complete sentence, reading as follows:   This would help to guide Lily so that she achieves her goal weight.
    Writing activity 09. Article (missing or unnecessary)
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">To achieve a good nursing care, process of nursing is divided into the four main stages: assessment, the planning, an implementation, evaluation (McFarlane &amp; Castledine 1979).</font> 
    QUESTION 0 Is the indefinite article before 'nursing care' necessary?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: That's not correct.  'Good nursing care' is a concept so doesn't need an article.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  'Good nursing care' is a concept so doesn't need an article.
    QUESTION 1 Do we need an article before 'process of nursing'?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  We're talking about a particular process - the process of nursing - so we need the definite article.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  We're talking about a particular process - the process of nursing - so we need the definite article.
    QUESTION 2 Do we need the definite article, as in 'the four main stages'?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  The stages are being referred to as concepts, so we don't need an article here.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: That's correct.  The stages are being referred to as concepts, so we don't need an article here.
    QUESTION 3 Which of these stages are correct in their use of, of leaving out of, the article?
        ANSWER: 'The planning' and 'an implementation' are correct.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  Try again.
        ANSWER: 'An implementation' is right.  The others are wrong.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  Try again.
        ANSWER: 'Assessment' and 'evaluation' are right.
        FEEDBACK: That's right. None of these stages need articles as they are all being referred to as concepts.
        Task freetext difficulty 1
