    Writing activity 16.  Constructing open questions
        Task freetext difficulty 1
        Task freetext difficulty 2
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Question 1. Are things ok at home and at school?<br />Question 2. Are things easier at home or at school?<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Which is the open question, question 1 or question 2?
        ANSWER: Question 1.
        FEEDBACK: Really?  Can you answer it with 'yes' or 'no'?
        ANSWER: Question 2.
        FEEDBACK: That's correct.  Question 2 requires the respondent to engage with the questioner.  The respondent may, of course, resist, but the opportunity is still there for the questioner to press on whereas question 1 closes the conversation down.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Mr. Smith has had a bad night in the hospital and seems upset. You want to find out why. Which of the following might be the best question to ask?</font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Read the text then answer the question(s).<br /></font> 
        ANSWER: Did you sleep well?
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Mr. Smith can say 'yes', 'no' or just grunt.
        ANSWER: How did you sleep?
        FEEDBACK: This is better, since it invites Mr. Jones to say something more informative, but it's not the best option.
        ANSWER: It's often hard to sleep in hospital, and I was wondering how you were managing and whether the nights seem very long?
        FEEDBACK: I like this option.  It invites Mr. Jones to answer at more length than 'How did you sleep?'.  I think this is the best option.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO  <font size="4">An obese patient appears in the clinic. You must find out something about her dietary habits, paying particular attention to whether she has acknowledged that there might be a link between what she eats and how much she weighs. Which of the following questions might it be best to ask as an opener?<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">Read the text and answer the question(s).</font> 
        ANSWER: Does what you eat affect how much you weigh?
        FEEDBACK: This is a poor choice.  It sounds so aggressive that quite apart from eliciting only a 'yes' or a 'no' it's likely to make the patient very defensive. 
        ANSWER: Do you think that your diet has an effect on your weight?
        FEEDBACK: This is less aggressive, but still elicits a 'yes' or 'no'.  Not the best option.
        ANSWER: If we go through your daily routine, how you plan your meals?
        FEEDBACK: This opens up a dialogue, and whatever the patient says will reveal something important.  This is the best choice.
        Task freetext difficulty 2
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">Could aspects of your treatment have been managed better?</font> 
    QUESTION 0 Why is this a poorly phrased question?
        ANSWER: The patient can answer 'yes' or 'no'.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  The patient is being encouraged to make a stark choice, when a stark choice may not be appropriate.  Some parts of the treatment might have been well managed and some not.
        ANSWER: The question is too general.  The patient could go off at a tangent.
        FEEDBACK: This is true, but that might be a good thing because the patient might reveal information that would be useful.  
        ANSWER: The question encourages the patient to complain.
        FEEDBACK: Possibly, but complaining isn't always a bad thing!  It can be very revelatory.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">Are you in pain?</font> 
    QUESTION 0 Is this an open or a closed question?
        ANSWER: Open.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  The patient can answer 'yes' or 'no', so this makes it a closed question.
        ANSWER: Closed.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  The patient can answer 'yes' or 'no' so this makes it a closed question.
    QUESTION 1 Which of the following questions will elicit the most information from the patient?
        ANSWER: On a scale of 1 to 10, how bad is the pain?
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  It's easy for the patient to make a snap decision, particularly as it's not clear how bad 10 is supposed to be.
        ANSWER: Is the pain only in your leg?
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  This question might encourage the patient to expand, but can still be answered 'yes' or 'no'.
        ANSWER: Pain can be very debilitating.  How is it affecting your everyday life?
        FEEDBACK: I like this question.  The small statement offers sympathy and understanding, so the question that follows feels inviting.
    Writing activity 12.  Referencing within your text
        Task freetext difficulty 1
        Task freetext difficulty 1
        Task freetext difficulty 2
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">Can you answer the following questions?</font> 
    QUESTION 0 Should references within the text ever be in italics?
        ANSWER: Yes.  Book titles and journal titles are italicised.
        FEEDBACK: Well - you're right about the book titles and journal titles. However, citations within your text are of authors and publication dates only, so italics are never appropriate.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: That's correct.  Citations within your text are of authors and publication dates only, so italics are never appropriate.
    QUESTION 1 When you cite a reference at the end of a sentence within your text, should the full stop come before or after the final bracket of the reference?
        ANSWER: Before.  The reference is not part of the sentence.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  The reference is part of the sentence, so the full stop should come after the final bracket.
        ANSWER: After.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  The reference is part of the sentence, so the full stop should come after the final bracket.
    QUESTION 2 If you cite a website with no named author, what do you place in brackets in the text?
        ANSWER: The whole url line, including the date you accessed the site.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  Put in the title of the article in brackets, or (website 1) and then list the websites appropriately in your references section.  Only put the date accessed in the references section, not in the text itself.
        ANSWER: The name of the article, and the date you accessed the site.
        FEEDBACK: That's not quite right.   Put in the title of the article, or (website 1) and then list the websites appropriately in your references section.  Only put the date accessed in the references section, not in the text itself.
        ANSWER: The name of the article in brackets, or (website 1).
        FEEDBACK: That's correct.  If you put the name of the article, make sure it tallies correctly with its corresponding entry in your references section.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">When the skin is broken or compromised, as is the case when a pressure ulcer forms, it can be problematic for the individual affected.<br />&quot;A pressure ulcer is localised injury to the skin and/or underlying tissues, usually over a bony prominence, as a result of pressure or pressure in combination with shear&quot; (EPUAP 2009).<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Is this direct quote correctly inserted into the text?
        ANSWER: Yes.  It's in quotation marks, so we know it's a direct quote.
        FEEDBACK: It is in quotation marks, but that's not quite enough.
        ANSWER: No.  It stands out from the text rather than being incorporated into it.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  If you quote directly, the quoted text should, notwithstanding the quotation marks, be incorporated into the flow of your own text.  It should not stand out all on its own.
    QUESTION 1 Should the quotation marks be single or double?
        ANSWER: Quotation marks should be double. 
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  Quotation marks should be single.  Double quotation marks are reserved for quotations within quotations, e.g. Levy argues that Simpson is 'mistaken when he says "women are more prone" '.  If you insert a quotation within a quotation, make sure you close both the double and the single quotation marks, even if it means placing the quotation marks one after the other.
        ANSWER: Quotation marks should be single.
        FEEDBACK: That's correct.  Quotation marks should be single.  Double quotation marks are reserved for quotations within quotations, e.g. Levy argues that Simpson is 'mistaken when he says "women are more prone" '.  If you insert a quotation within a quotation, make sure you close both the double and the single quotation marks, even if it means placing the quotation marks one after the other.
