        ANSWER: Obesity is the term used to describe excess body fat ad the usual measure of obesity in children is the body mass index (BMI) which is calculated by taking the child's weight in kilograms and dividing it by their height in metres squared.
        FEEDBACK: This is not the best choice.  Although it's good to define obesity, there is no mention in the title of children.  You may want to include children in your work, but you must explain why first.
        ANSWER: Type 2 diabetes develops in obese patients because obesity results in the patient's body becoming less sensitive to insulin released from the pancreas, thus leading to a rise in blood glucose levels.
        FEEDBACK: This is a good opening line, directly relevant to the title. The next line should define obesity.  The best option on offer here.
        ANSWER: Type 2 diabetes, when poorly managed, can lead to many other problems including damage to blood vessels.
