        ANSWER: Obesity is currently the most common metabolic disease encountered worldwide and its incidence and prevalence are continuing to rise rapidly (Caterson and Gill, 2002). 
        FEEDBACK: This is not a bad first line.  It defines obesity and is properly referenced. However, it is a little wordy - we don't need incidence and prevalence - and to be perfect, would say something authoritative and informative about the focus of the question, which is the relationship between obesity and type 2 diabetes 
        ANSWER: Quality of life is diminished for those who have diabetes related complications brought on by an existing condition, for example, obesity.
        FEEDBACK: What this opening line says may be true but it does not focus on the question asked.   Not the best option. 
        ANSWER: The relationship between obesity and type 2 diabetes can be clearly illustrated through a study conducted in 2005 by Halpern and Mancini.  They found that not only do obesity and type 2 diabetes frequently occur together, but that 60-90% of all patients diagnosed with type 2 diabetes are, or have been, obese.
        FEEDBACK: These opening lines use the terms of the question as well as providing statistics and properly referenced information.  This is the best option.
