        FEEDBACK: These themes are incorporated, but yet further dissection is needed.
        ANSWER: Five.  This paragraph incorporates sentences from five different parts of a research module.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  I think each of these sentences addresses a different theme in a research module:  an introductory sentence; the focus of need for another study;  how the new study was designed;  the methodology; the results.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">Can you answer the following questions?</font> 
    QUESTION 0 Are research aims the same as research objectives?
        ANSWER: No.  There's a subtle difference between the two.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  Research aims are more general than research objectives, which are quite specific.  A research aim might be to assess what is important to patients attending a palliative daycare centre.  Research objectives might be: to elicit patients' reasons for attending a palliative daycare unit;  to establish what benefits the service provides in the eyes of a) the patient; and b) the staff;  to discover whether there are services patients feel that the daycare service should provide but currently does not.
        ANSWER: Yes. It's just a different way of saying the same thing.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Research aims are more general than research objectives, which are quite specific.  A research aim might be to assess what is important to patients attending a palliative daycare centre.  Research objectives might be: to elicit patients' reasons for attending a palliative daycare unit;  to establish what benefits the service provides in the eyes of a) the patient; and b) the staff;  to discover whether there are services patients feel that the daycare service should provide but currently does not.
        Task freetext difficulty 3
    Writing activity 17. Abstract
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">Can you answer the following question(s)?</font> 
    QUESTION 0 How many paragraphs should an abstract take up?
        ANSWER: As many as it needs.
        FEEDBACK: In a way, but how many should it need?  Try again.
        ANSWER: One.
        FEEDBACK: Yes, that's right.  Ideally, an abstract is one paragraph long.
        ANSWER: At least two.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not right.  Ideally, an abstract should be one paragraph long.
    QUESTION 1 Where, in your project or dissertation, should the abstract be placed?
        ANSWER: After the introduction.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not right.  Try again.
        ANSWER: After the title page.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.
        ANSWER: At the end of the dissertation.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  Try again.
    QUESTION 2 Is the abstract the same as the introduction.
        ANSWER: Yes, they are interchangeable, except that the introduction is a little longer.
        FEEDBACK: That's a common misapprehension! Try again.
        ANSWER: No, they perform different functions.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  The abstract is an overview of your entire text.  The introduction sets the scene in some detail.
    QUESTION 3 What should a reader find in your abstract?
        ANSWER: Your personal reasons for choosing the topic.
        FEEDBACK: No - the personal should not be included in an academic text.
        ANSWER: A brief synopsis of the study, identifying the nature and scope of your work.
        FEEDBACK: Yes - this is very important.  Readers will read your abstract to see if it contains the kind of research they're looking for.
        ANSWER: A history of the topic.
        FEEDBACK: No - the abstract's not the place for a history of the topic. 
        ANSWER: The particular contribution your study makes to knowledge in the field.
        FEEDBACK: Yes - a reader will also expect to find this information in the abstract.
        ANSWER: The major outcomes.
        FEEDBACK: Yes - an abstract is not like a novel, where you want to keep the reader in suspense.  In an abstract for a nursing dissertation, you need to tell the reader what you found right at the start.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO  <font size="4">Which of these opening lines is suitable for an abstract?<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Read the text, then answer the question(s).</font> 
        ANSWER: Delirium is a disturbance of consciousness accompanied by a change in cognition or perception, which occurs suddenly and fluctuates over time.  Research suggests that more than half of all Intensive Care Unit (ICU) patients experience delirium and will continue to do so after discharge to the ward, an half of those experiencing delirium in the ward will die within one year of delirium diagnosis.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  This text sets the scene, which is a function of the introduction, not the abstract.  The abstract should provide a brief synopsis of your study, identifying the nature and scope of your work.  This is not the same as setting the scene.
        ANSWER: This study was undertaken in response to a critical need for better recognition and management of the disturbance of consciousness known as delirium, since research suggests that the condition affects more than half of all Intensive Care Unit (ICU) patients.
        FEEDBACK: This is much better for an abstract, since it identifies the nature of your work right at the start.
