    Writing activity 01. Abstract
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO Report title:<br /><br />An examination of the Curie-Weiss law in capacitors.<br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /> 
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">Read the report title. There are many ways to begin its abstract, but choose which you feel is the best of the options offered. All the options have explanations, so even if your first choice agrees with ours, it might be worth having a look at all the comments.</font>
        ANSWER: This report contains details of an experiment measuring the effect of increasing temperature on capacitors with different dielectrics.
        FEEDBACK: This sentence simply repeats the title of the experiment, adding nothing.  The opening line of an abstract needs to engage the reader.  Not the best option on offer here.
        ANSWER: Capacitors have many applications in the electronics industry, and the dependence of capacitance and impedance of temperature on commercial capacitors needed further exploration.
        FEEDBACK: This is a good opening for an abstract.  It provides the rationale for the experiment, one of the abstract's primary functions.  This is the best option here.
        ANSWER: Capacitors have been around since 1745, when Ewald Georg von Kleist discovered a way to store an electric charge.
        FEEDBACK: An abstract is no place for history.  This type of information belongs, if anywhere, in the introduction.  This is not the best option on offer here.
