        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">What should be included in your summary and conclusions, or just conclusions, section? You can choose as many options as you like.</font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Read the text, then answer the question(s).</font> 
        ANSWER: A list of findings, preferably in bullet points.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  The results section is for findings, not results and conclusions.  In addition, findings should be described, not listed as bullet points.
        ANSWER: Detailed conclusion, linking back to the aims of the experiment.
        FEEDBACK: Yes, absolutely.  We certainly need the conclusion to link back to the aims.
        ANSWER: Outline of ways to improve accuracy in the experimental set-up.
        FEEDBACK: Yes.  This is the place for such an outline.
        ANSWER: A repeat of the rationale for the experiment.
        FEEDBACK: No - we don't need a repeat, just a link between the conclusion and the aims.
        ANSWER: Comparison of results with accepted values.
        FEEDBACK: No - we need a comparison of the actual results with those you expected through the experiment - not quite the same thing.
        ANSWER: Errors with significant effect on results.
        FEEDBACK: Yes.  This is the place to discuss errors.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Hooke's Law and Simple Harmonic Motion</span><br style="font-weight: bold;" /><br style="font-weight: bold;" /><span style="font-weight: bold;">Summary and Conclusion</span></font><br /><br /><font size="3">The aim of this experiment was to study oscillations and how Hooke's law works. This was achieved. <font size="2" style="font-style: italic;">(Details of equations put in here.)</font> Some uncertainties crept in, perhaps because of human error. We all measure in slightly different ways and our reactions also differ. </font><br /> 
    QUESTION 0 Is this a satisfactory conclusion?
        ANSWER: Yes.  It tells us what was achieved, gives details (these are indicated by the italicised text) and outlines reasons for errors.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  To say that the aims of the experiment were achieved tells us nothing, except that the experiment was carried out.  Good to know that equations were included, but human error is not an acceptable source of uncertainty - note that uncertainty and inaccuracy are not the same thing.
        ANSWER: No, this is not a satisfactory conclusion, despite including equations (indicated by the italicised text) and reasons for errors.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  To say that the aims of the experiment were achieved tells us nothing, except that the experiment was carried out.  Good to know that equations were included, but human error is not an acceptable source of uncertainty - note that uncertainty and inaccuracy are not the same thing.
    Writing activity 07. Sentence fragments
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">1. The general aim of the experiment is to study Hooke's law. <br />2. To analyze the data from the experiments. </font>
    QUESTION 0 Which sentence is a complete sentence, and which sentence is a fragment?
        ANSWER: 1. is a complete sentence and 2 is a fragment.
        FEEDBACK: That's correct.  1. has a main verb - 'is'.  'Is' sets the sentence in time, so 1. is a complete sentence. Sentence 2 has no main verb.  It has an infinitive verb - ' to analyze' - but this does not set the sentence in time.  2. is the fragment.
        ANSWER: 1. is a fragment and 2. is a complete sentence.
        FEEDBACK: That's incorrect.   1. has a main verb - 'is'.  'Is' sets the sentence in time, so 1. is a complete sentence. Sentence 2 has no main verb.  It has an infinitive verb - ' to analyze' - but this does not set the sentence in time.  2. is the fragment.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO 1. The green laser pointer replaced the red laser.<br />2. Keeping the distance of the double slit and paper screen the same, with Equation 1 rearranged to find the wavelength of the red laser light.<br /> 
    QUESTION 0 Which of these sentence is a complete sentence and which a fragment?
        ANSWER: 1. is a complete sentence and 2. is a fragment.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  1. has a main verb - 'replaced' - so is a complete sentence.  2. has two sub-clauses.  The first is 'Keeping the distance ... the same'.  The second is 'with ... laser light'.  These sub-clauses qualify something, but whatever it is they are qualifying is missing.   Though containing many words, 2. is still a fragment. 
        ANSWER: 1. is a fragment and 2. is a complete sentence.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not right.  1. has a main verb - 'replaced' - so is a complete sentence.  2. has two sub-clauses.  The first is 'Keeping the distance ... the same'.  The second is 'with ... laser light'.  These sub-clauses qualify something, but whatever it is they are qualifying is missing.   Though containing many words, 2. is still a fragment.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO 1. Producing an uncertain result.<br />2. It was uncertain.<br /> 
    QUESTION 0 Which of these sentences is the complete sentence, and which the sentence fragment?
        ANSWER: 1. is a complete sentence and 2. is a fragment.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  1. has no main verb - 'producing' does not tell us when in time the action is/was/might be set.  2. has a main verb - 'was' - so 2. is a complete sentence.  
        ANSWER: 1. is a fragment and 2. is a complete sentence.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  1. has no main verb - 'producing' does not tell us when in time the action is/was/might be set.  2. has a main verb - 'was' - so 2. is a complete sentence.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">1. A circuit figure was set up.<br />2. In order to verify that the given values for each component were accurate.<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Which of these sentences is the whole sentence, and which the sentence fragment?
        ANSWER: 1. is the whole sentence and 2. is the sentence fragment.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  In sentence 1 we have a main verb:  'was set up'.  This sets the action in time.  Sentence 2 is a sub-clause.  The 'in order to' gives it away since a clause beginning 'in order to' is always a sub-clause.  It tells us more about the main clause, but is not a main clause itself.  Sentence 2 hangs in the air, waiting for something more.
        ANSWER: 2. is the whole sentence and 1. is the sentence fragment.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  In sentence 1 we have a main verb:  'was set up'.  This sets the action in time.  Sentence 2 is a sub-clause.  The 'in order to' gives it away since a clause beginning 'in order to' is always a sub-clause.  It tells us more about the main clause, but is not a main clause itself.  Sentence 2 hangs in the air, waiting for something more.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">1. Nuclear power generates waste.<br />2. Generating waste, which is a problem.<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Which of these sentences is a complete sentence and which is a sentence fragment?
        ANSWER: 1. is a complete sentence and 2. is a sentence fragment.
        FEEDBACK: Yes, that's right.  1. has a subject - 'nuclear power' - and a verb - 'generates'.  That's all you need for a complete sentence.  2. has a type of verb acting as a noun - 'generating' - and leaves us asking 'what is generating waste?'   There's no subject.
        ANSWER: 1. is a fragment and 2. is a complete sentence.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  1. has a subject - 'nuclear power' - and a verb - 'generates'.  That's all you need for a complete sentence.  2. has a type of verb acting as a noun - 'generating' - and leaves us asking 'what is generating waste?'   There's no subject.  2. is a sentence fragment.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO  1. Evaluating the magnitude of potential hazards and coming up with cost-effective solutions.<br />2. The magnitude of potential hazards cannot be evaluated and solutions need to be cost-effective. 
    QUESTION 0 Which of these sentences is a complete sentence and which is a sentence fragment?
        ANSWER: 1. is a sentence fragment and 2. is a complete sentence.
        FEEDBACK: That's right. In sentence 1.,  'evaluating' and 'coming up with' are not main verbs: they don't set the sentence in time.  In sentence 2., the verb phrases 'cannot be evaluated' and 'need to be' set the sentence in time, i.e. the present, so sentence 2. is a complete sentence.
        ANSWER: 1. is the complete sentence and 2. is the fragment.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right. In sentence 1.,  'evaluating' and 'coming up with' are not main verbs: they don't set the sentence in time.  In sentence 2., the verb phrases 'cannot be evaluated' and 'need to be' set the sentence in time, i.e. the present, so sentence 2. is a complete sentence.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">1. The errors were reasonably small. <br />2. Reflecting the degree of accuracy of the experiment and the method used by the experimenters.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 Which sentence is complete and which is a fragment?
        ANSWER: Sentence 1 is a fragment and sentence 2 is complete.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not right.  Sentence 1 has a subject - 'the errors' - and a verb - 'werel'.  That's all a complete sentence needs.  Sentence 2 does not have a subject, and leaves the reader hanging, needing something more to answer the question 'what was reflecting the degree of accuracy' etc.
        ANSWER: Sentence 1 is complete and sentence 2 is a fragment.
        FEEDBACK: Well done.  That's right.   Sentence 1 has a subject - 'the errors' - and a verb - 'were'.  That's all a complete sentence needs.  Sentence 2 does not have a subject, and leaves the reader hanging, needing something more to answer the question 'what was reflecting the degree of accuracy' etc.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">1. Without attaching any leads to the die-cast box.</font><br /><font size="4">2. The LCR meter was set up to show C. <br /><br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Which of these sentence is a fragment and which is a complete sentence? </font> 
        ANSWER: Sentence 1 is complete and sentence 2 is a fragment.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not right.  Sentence 1 has no subject or driving verb.  In other words, nothing sets this sentence in time.  It needs something else to make sense.  Sentence 2 has a subject - 'the LCR meter' - and a verb - 'was set up'.  That's all a complete sentence needs.
        ANSWER: Sentence 1 is a fragment and sentence 2 is complete.
        FEEDBACK: Well done.  That's right.   Sentence 1 has no subject or driving verb.  In other words, nothing sets this sentence in time.  It needs something else to make sense.  Sentence 2 has a subject - 'the LCR meter' - and a verb - 'was set up'.  That's all a complete sentence needs.
