    Writing activity 11. Colons and semi-colons
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">The apparatus employed was as follows; kettle, conductivity bars, beak of hot water, insulation, stopwatch and digital thermometer. The digital thermometer was used to measure air temperature in the room: this temperature was assumed to be the temperature of the cold end of each metal bar. </font> 
    QUESTION 0 Are the semi-colon and colon used properly in this text?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Colons introduce a list, such as this list of apparatus, so we need a colon instead of a semi-colon here.  A semi-colon separates items in a list (although commas will often do just as well) or separates two complete sentences that are closely related.  A semi-colon would be better in the second sentence here. 
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  Colons introduce a list, such as this list of apparatus, so we need a colon instead of a semi-colon here.  A semi-colon separates items in a list (although commas will often do just as well) or separates two complete sentences that are closely related.  A semi-colon would be better in the second sentence here.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">The aim of the experiment was to investigate the thermal conductivity of the metals; copper, iron, brass and steel.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 Is the semi-colon in this text properly used?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  A colon, not a semi-colon, should introduce a list.  A semi-colon separates two complete sentences that are closely linked, or separates items within a list.  We need a colon here.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  A colon, not a semi-colon, should introduce a list.  A semi-colon separates two complete sentences that are closely linked, or separates items within a list.  We need a colon here.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO 1. The EasySense program imports some uncertainties: the acceleration may be out by up to 10%.<br />2. The EasySense program imports some uncertainties; the acceleration may be out by up to 10%.<br />3. The EasySense program imports some uncertainties, the acceleration may be out by up to 10%
    QUESTION 0 Which of these sentences is incorrectly punctuated: 1, 2 or 3.
        ANSWER: 1. is incorrectly punctuated.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  A colon can also stand in for the phrase 'that is' or 'for example', with the second part of the sentence expanding on the first.  A colon seems appropriate here, although other forms of punctuation also work.
        ANSWER: 2. is incorrectly punctuated. 
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  A semi-colon can be used to divide two sentences that are closely connected, so a semi-colon works well here.  It's not the only form of punctuation that works well, though, so you might like to look at the other choices.
        ANSWER: 3. is incorrectly punctuated.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  A comma doesn't work well here.  We need a slightly harder pause.  A colon or a semi-colon works better.
