    Writing activity 12. Commas and run-on sentences
        Task freetext difficulty 1
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">The values for thermal conductivity of metals are high in comparison to other elements, this is because of the ability of the electrons to move around, glass and the insulation used have a low value of k however which is why they are used to stop heat loss in the experiment.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 Into how many sentences should this text be divided?
        ANSWER: It's fine as one sentence.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again.
        ANSWER: It should be two sentences.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again.
        ANSWER: It should be three sentences.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  e.g. The values for thermal conductivity of metals are high in comparison to other elements.  This is because of the ability of the electrons to move around.  Glass and the insulation used have a low value of k, however, which is why they are used to stop heat loss in the experiment.
    QUESTION 1 There is a small sub-clause in this text.  What is it?
        ANSWER: 'in comparison'
        FEEDBACK: Not 'in comparison'.  Try again.
        ANSWER: 'because of'
        FEEDBACK: Not 'because of'.  Try again.
        ANSWER: 'however'
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  The adverb 'however' constitutes a small sub-clause, so needs to be followed by a comma to separate it from the main clause of the sentence.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">In addition, it was alpha particle decay from radioactive polonium that killed the Russian spy Alexander Litvinenko, he unknowingly consumed it and the alpha radiation eroded the inside of his stomach and ultimately killed him from the inside out. </font> 
    QUESTION 0 Into how many sentences should this text be divided?
        ANSWER: It's fine as one sentence.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again.
        ANSWER: It should be two sentences.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.
        ANSWER: It should be three sentences.
        FEEDBACK: It could be divided into three, but I'm not sure that's really necessary.
    QUESTION 1 If you feel the text should be divided into more than one sentence, where should the division(s) go?
        ANSWER: The full stop should come after 'consumed it', with the new sentence beginning 'And the etc.'
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again.
        ANSWER: There should be a full stop after 'Litvinenko', with the new sentence beginning 'He unknowingly ...' 
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  There's a lot of information here, but divided like this, it's all easy to take in.
        ANSWER: There should be a full stop after 'Litvinenko', another after 'stomach'.
        FEEDBACK: I agree with the full stop after Litvinenko, but a full stop after 'stomach' leaves the rest of the text - 'and ultimately killed him from the inside out' - as a sentence fragment, i.e. a sentence with no driving verb.  See 07. Sentence fragments.
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task freetext difficulty 2
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">There are a number of solutions to the problem of nuclear waste, the simplest being landfill and ocean dumping of the waste sealed into drums, for environmental reasons this is unacceptable to many people.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 Into how many sentences should this text be divided?
        ANSWER: It's fine as one sentence.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again.
        ANSWER: It should be two sentences, with the second sentence beginning 'For environmental reasons ...'
        FEEDBACK: I agree.   It should be two sentences, with the second sentence beginning 'For environmental reasons'.  If there's also a full stop after 'waste', we create a sentence fragment, i.e. 'The simplest being landfill and ocean dumping of the waste sealed into drums'.  This is not a complete sentence as it contains no driving verb. (See section 07. of this website.)
        ANSWER: It should be three sentences, the second beginning 'The simplest being ...' and the third beginning 'For environmental reasons ... '
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">1. The natural sciences comprise astronomy, biology, chemistry, earth science and physics, all using objective methods and quantitative methods. <br />2. </font><font size="4">The natural sciences comprise astronomy, biology, chemistry, earth science and physics, all use objective methods and quantitative methods. </font> 
    QUESTION 0 Which sentence should be divided into two sentences?
        ANSWER: 1. should be divided into two sentences, with the full stop coming after 'physics'.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  If you put a full stop after 'physics' you create a sentence fragment, i.e. 'all using objective data and quantitative methods'.  This phrase does not contain a main verb (see section 07. of this website).
        ANSWER: 2. should be divided into two sentences, with the full stop coming after 'physics'.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  In sentence 2 we have two main subjects and verbs: 'The natural sciences' (subject) 'comprise' (main verb);  and 'all' (subject) 'use' (main verb).  This sentence, because it has two main subjects and verbs, should be divided into two complete sentences.   In contrast, if we divide sentence 1 into two, putting the full stop after 'physics', we end up with one complete sentence and one sentence fragment (see section 07. of this website).
    Writing activity 13. Important things to know about graphs and tables
        Task multiplechoice difficulty None
INTRO <font size="4"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Apparatus:</span><br /><br />Diagram 1: pictures of individual parts of apparatus.<br /><font size="2">(The drawings are shown with captions, e.g. temperature sensitive metal bars; beaker; kettle; digital thermometer.)</font><br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Would this be a good example of a diagram?
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  Showing individual pieces of equipment as individual pictures is a waste of a diagram.  You need to show how they interact and work.  You can still label the constituent parts, but set them out as for the experiment.  
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Showing individual pieces of equipment as individual pictures is a waste of a diagram.  You need to show how they interact and work.  You can still label the constituent parts, but set them out as for the experiment.
