    Writing activity 5. Essay layout and formatting
    Writing activity 6. Opening lines
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Essay title:</span><br /><br />What can the literature on fundamentalism and creationism tell us about the problems of modern society?</font><br /> 
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">Read the text then answer the question(s).</font> 
        ANSWER: Fundamentalism and creationism fundamentally reject the modern world, and this rejection in itself describes one major problem of the modern world:  a sense of alienation.  This sense is witnessed by ...
        FEEDBACK: These opening lines fulfil one of the major criteria of a good opening line:  they grab the author's attention.  I like the fact that we're also to get an example early on.  A powerful opening and the best choice here.
        ANSWER: Modern society has many problems and the literature on fundamentalism and creationism tells us a great deal about those problems.
        FEEDBACK: This opening line simply repeats the question.  It tells us nothing.  Nor does it open the essay up.  We wouldn't miss this line if it was removed from the essay.  A poor choice.
        ANSWER: Fundamentalism is 'strict adherence to a specific set of theological doctrines typically in reaction against the theology of Modernism' (Wikipedia 2011).
        FEEDBACK: Although beginning your essay with a defining quotation is a good technique, wikipedia is not a reliable source of information.  For this reason, this is a poor choice.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Essay title:</span><br /><br />Why was the New Economic Policy (NEP) adopted in 1921 but then abandoned only seven years later?<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 This essay will assess the reasons for the rise and fall of the New Economic Policy (NEP) which was adopted in 1921 only to be abandoned seven years later.
        ANSWER: This essay will assess the reasons for the rise and fall of the New Economic Policy (NEP) which was adopted in 1921 only to be abandoned seven years later.
        FEEDBACK: This opening line simply repeats the terms of the question.  Nothing is added and it does not open up the essay in any way.  If you removed this line, the essay would be none the poorer.  A poor choice.
        ANSWER: Marx and Engels both saw communism as a logical step in societal evolution but if communism was the next step forward from industrial capitalism, then Russia would not have been either Marx or Engels' choice for the experiment.  As they ask in the preface to the 1882 edition of the Communist Manifesto ...
        FEEDBACK: These lines are informative but opening lines need to seize the essay question directly.  All this information may be useful within the essay, but as opening lines these are unhelpful.
        ANSWER: The New Economic Policy (NEP) was introduced in 1921 as a direct result of a collapse in production following an international war and a internal revolution.  The reasons for its abandonment are more complex, but an analysis of these reasons shows not just why the NEP lasted only seven years, but also how its own structure meant that failure in the long term was inevitable.
        FEEDBACK: These opening lines address the question directly.  They add information and they open up the question in an interesting way.  These lines are the best choice.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Essay title:</span><br /><br />Critically analyse the effectiveness of public policy in meeting the needs of women.<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Read the essay title and the opening lines. Which opening lines are the best option? All the choices have explanations, so even if your first choice agrees with ours, it's worth clicking on all the options.</font> 
        ANSWER: Throughout the ages, women have been seen as the 'weaker' sex.  In ancient Greece, for example, long hailed as an example of democracy, women were not seen as equal to men.
        FEEDBACK: These opening lines are much too general.  They might do for an article in a tabloid newspaper but simply waste words in an academic essay.  In an academic essay, you need to seize the subject from the very start. Not a good choice.
        ANSWER: That any public policy in 21st century should have to address specifically the needs of women shows that public policy directed at women's equality has been ineffective.  However, this may be more to do with women's expectations than public policy failure.  For example, ...
        FEEDBACK: These lines certainly grab the reader's attention.  Confident and controversial, they would make any reader want to read on.  The best choice on offer here.
        ANSWER: Women have a pretty rough ride as I know from experience.  In 2010, my mother is still not being paid the same as her male counterparts.  Public policy is pretty ineffective if it cannot even guarantee the same wage for the same job.
        FEEDBACK: These lines are too anecdotal and colloquial.   With a few tweaks - for example using the experience of the writer's mother in a more objective way, with hard evidence attached - they could be transformed into lines suitable for an academic essay.  As they stand, however, these lines are not the best choice here.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Essay title:</span><br /><br />What were the main challenges facing public health in the 19th century and how were these challenges overcome?<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Read the essay title and the opening lines. Which opening lines are the best option? All the choices have explanations, so even if your first choice agrees with ours, it's worth clicking on all the options.</font> 
        ANSWER: Urbanisation, attitudes towards health, poor diet, poor housing and environmental degradation were all challenges to public health in the 19th century.
        FEEDBACK: This opening line gets straight to the point.  The best option here.
        ANSWER: During the 19th century, many things changed in Britain and across the whole of Europe.  
        FEEDBACK: This sentence adds nothing to the essay, simply repeating the terms of the question.  We wouldn't miss this opening line if it were deleted.  Not the best choice on offer here.
        ANSWER: Throughout history, nations have faced challenges in public health, but it is only within the last three hundred years that public health has become an issue of real concern.  In 14th century, for example, people were certainly worried about catching the plague and some containment policies were put in place.  However,  you could hardly call this a start to overcoming public health challenges.
        FEEDBACK: These lines tell us something, but they don't get straight into the question.  In an academic essay in Social and Political Science, you should not waste time on a potted history unless it's a necessary part of the answer to the essay question.  This is not the best option on offer here.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4" style="font-weight: bold;">Essay question:<br /><br /></font>How, in some European societies, did World War I create favourable preconditions for the emergence of Fascist parties?<br /> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Read the essay title and the opening lines. Which opening lines are the best option? All the choices have explanations, so even if your first choice agrees with ours, it's worth clicking on all the options.</font> 
        ANSWER: There is a general consensus amongst those who study World War 1 that it left a lasting impact on world politics.  It was, after all, the Great War; the War to End All Wars.  Ten million men lost their lives and it is generally agreed that the world was never the same again.
        FEEDBACK: These lines start well, but the second line begins to drift.  Make sure you stick firmly to the question in your opening lines.  First impressions are very important.
        ANSWER: Three conditions are necessary for the emergence of fascism: nationalist ideology; a charismatic leader and a political environment which provides democratic legitimacy.  By looking closely at the legacy of World War I, it is possible to identify certain preconditions which gave birth to these conditions, and this essay will explore these preconditions with particular reference to Germany and Spain.
        FEEDBACK: This is a clear and confident start.  The reader learns something important from the first sentence, and the second sentence provides an essay map.   These lines are the best choice on offer here.
        ANSWER: World War I (1914-1918) was a conflict caused by a number of factors, but the immediate catalyst was the assassination of the Archduke Franz Ferdinand of Austria and his wife by a Serb.  This assassination set in motion a war of mass carnage, which dragged on until finally ending with Germany's humiliation at the Treaty of Versailles.
        FEEDBACK: Nothing here is wrong - except that by the end of these lines a reader who had not seen the question would have no idea what the essay was supposed to be about.  There is no mention of fascism.  Every fact in your first lines must be relevant to the essay question.  However well written they are, if your first lines are just a wander through history, they'll gain you no marks.
    Writing activity 7. Concluding lines
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title:<br /><br />Is fascism necessarily anti-Christian?<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">Read the essay title and the concluding lines. Which concluding lines are the best option? All the choices have explanations, so even if your first choice agrees with ours, it's worth clicking on all the options.</font> 
        ANSWER: It is clear, then, that one of fascism's most devious strengths is its principle of adapting and gathering   to itself other creeds, even ones seemingly inimical to its beliefs. Fascism is, therefore, not necessarily anti-Christian because it is not, by necessity, anti anything at all.
        FEEDBACK: These are strong closing lines that come to a thought-provoking conclusion.  These are the best on offer here.
        ANSWER: Unfortunately, as this essay has proven, we do not as yet fully understand the relationship between fascism and Christianity.
        FEEDBACK: The statement made by these concluding lines may be true but the lines leave the reader with a sense of anti-climax.  The essay question asked for an answer.  If there is no answer, try not to finish your essay with a sentence beginning 'unfortunately', since this leaves a clear impression of defeat.  These lines are not the best choice on offer here.
        ANSWER: In addition, we might remember that the term 'clerical-fascism' is an oxymoron, which leaves us with the question:  were these Catholic states fascist at all?
        FEEDBACK: Rhetorical questions are not good ways to finish an essay.  Rhetorical question smack of journalism, not academia.  These lines are not the best choice here.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Essay title:</span><br /><br />Why was there famine in Ireland but not in Scotland in the 1840s?<br /><br /><br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">Read the essay title and the concluding lines. Which concluding lines are the best option? All the choices have explanations, so even if your first choice agrees with ours, it's worth clicking on all the options.</font> 
        ANSWER: As has been seen, diversity of crops, a more prosperous economy and famine relief schemes were key to Scotland avoiding famine in the 1840s. In Ireland, failure to address any of these issues in time meant that famine was an inevitable result of potato blight.  When combined with the policies of the British government, mass starvation was unavoidable.
        FEEDBACK: These closing lines briefly recapitulate the themes of the essay in order to give a satisfactory answer to the essay question. These are the best lines on offer here.
        ANSWER: There were also other causes of the famine, for example landlords mismanaging their lands, but these do not truly account for the differences in the effects of famine between Scotland and Ireland.
        FEEDBACK: These lines rather drift to a halt, and it is always a mistake to bring in new ideas right at the end of an essay.  If there are topics you cannot include for space reasons, but you want to make reference to them, the introduction is the right place to mention them, not the conclusion.  Not the best choice here.
        ANSWER: It was a truly terrible time for the Irish and the British government should apologise and hang its head in shame.
        FEEDBACK: You may think this, but an academic essay is not the place to air such views unless specifically asked to do so by the essay question.  Not the best choice here.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Essay title:</span><br /><br />Why should housing policy seek to make a contribution towards improving people's physical health?</font><br /> 
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">Read the essay title and the concluding lines. Which concluding lines are the best option? All the choices have explanations, so even if your first choice agrees with ours, it's worth clicking on all the options.</font> 
        ANSWER: Housing policy plays an important role in people's mental health and so policies should be put in place that reflect this.
        FEEDBACK: Be careful of the question:  this one asks specifically about physical health.  Make sure your conclusion fits with the essay question.   Not the best choice here.
        ANSWER: Where you live is quite important and people in charge of housing policy have a duty to remember this.
        FEEDBACK: Apart from the colloquialism (what does 'quite' really mean?), this concluding line is fine, if a little uninspiring.  It's not the best choice here.
        ANSWER: As has been demonstrated, a three-pronged approach to health through public policy has dramatic effects.  Housing is a key part of this approach and if anybody queries the reason why housing policy should always seek to make a contribution towards improving people's physical health, the answer is simple: the contribution actually works.
        FEEDBACK: These closing lines have a good ring to them.  Confident and focussed, they leave a good impression.  These lines are the best option on offer here.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Essay title:</span><br /><br />Why has it been so difficult for Poland to implement a coherent regional policy?<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">Read the essay title and the concluding lines. Which concluding lines are the best option? All the choices have explanations, so even if your first choice agrees with ours, it's worth clicking on all the options.</font> 
        ANSWER: Poland's not out of the woods yet. 
        FEEDBACK: The expression 'out of the woods' make this concluding line too colloquial for an academic essay.  Not the best choice on offer here.
        ANSWER: Until Poland's organs of regional government achieve independence from central government, further development is not possible.
        FEEDBACK: This is a good, solid concluding line because it leaves the reader with something to think about and a sense of closure.  This line is the best on offer here.
        ANSWER: As has been shown, it is difficult to assess exactly why it has been so difficult for Poland to implement a coherent regional policy.  Perhaps things will be clearer in a few more years.
        FEEDBACK: These are unsatisfactory concluding lines.  Even if a definitive answer is not possible, some conclusions should be drawn.  Not the best option on offer here.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Essay title:</span><br /><br />What are the possible limits of anthropological engagement with different cultures and societies?</font><br /> 
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">Read the essay title and the concluding lines. Which concluding lines are the best option? All the choices have explanations, so even if your first choice agrees with ours, it's worth clicking on all the options.</font> 
        ANSWER: I think that ethnographers' biggest limitation is understanding other cultures.
        FEEDBACK: This line is too personal (avoid 'I think') and although it makes a statement, feels rather flat.  Not the best option here. 
        ANSWER: The possible limits of anthropological engagement with different cultures and societies?  Understanding.
        FEEDBACK: Including a rhetorical question in your concluding lines smacks of journalism rather than academia.  If you have a statement to make, make it.  Avoid the rhetorical question.  These lines are not the best option on offer here.
        ANSWER: From all the examples given, one thing is clear:  ethnographers' biggest limitation is not one of engagement with different cultures and societies but one of understanding, and whether it is possible to break through this barrier is highly doubtful.
        FEEDBACK: This is an example of a good concluding line: it does not provide a definitive answer but still says something definite, i.e. that engagement is limited by understanding.  This answers the question set in the essay title and leaves the reader with something positive to think about.  It is the best option here.
