    Writing activity 14. When is evidence needed?
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO  <font size="4">Which of these three assertions needs evidence (with a reference) to back it up?</font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Read the text then answer the question(s).</font> 
        ANSWER: The concept of globalisation is complex.  It does not simply mean that the world is one marketplace.
        FEEDBACK: If you have taken the phrase 'one marketplace' from a source, you must acknowledge that source.  If, however, this idea is your own thought, you don't need hard evidence here since this is your opinion.  You will, though, want to prove your point and this will usually involve examples.
        ANSWER: Globalisation has brought with it a new kind of crime, in which international financial institutions are charged with not supporting poor nations to uphold, for example, globally accepted safety standards.
        FEEDBACK: This assertion does need evidence. Appropriate evidence might include the 2002 sinking of the Senegalese ferry, as analysed by Rothe, Muzzatti and Mullins (2006).  
        ANSWER: The western media, with its wide reach, contributes to the sense that we are all connected.
        FEEDBACK: Although telling examples are always helpful, this kind of general assertion does not need specific evidence.  However, if you are paraphrasing lines you found in a source, you must acknowledge the source both in the text and in the bibliography.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">Which of the following assertions need to be backed up by hard evidence?</font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Read the text then answer the question(s).</font> 
        ANSWER: Factories in Bosnia and Croatia sent weapons to Baghdad just before the US invasion.
        FEEDBACK: This assertion certainly requires evidence.  Examples of the weapons should be given, and the source should be reputable (i.e. not Wikipedia).
        ANSWER: Illegal arms trafficking compromises public safety.
        FEEDBACK: This general assertion is a topic for a paragraph (which would include examples) rather than something that requires immediate hard evidence.
        ANSWER: In 2001, the Serbian authorities found huge amounts of pure heroin in a bank deposit box.
        FEEDBACK: This type of statement is never acceptable in an academic essay.  How much is 'huge'?  We need to know that 600 kg of 93% pure heroin was discovered, with a street value of about $20 million - and this must be properly referenced.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO  <font size="4">Which of the following assertions needs hard evidence to back it up?</font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4"><br /></font> 
        ANSWER: The Leeds study revealed that walking trips to the main food store increased after retail intervention.
        FEEDBACK: Evidence is certainly needed here, for example '... walking trips to the main food store increased from 12.3% to 30.8% after retail intervention (Wrigley et al. 2004)'.
        ANSWER: A 'food desert' intervention study in Leeds included focus groups as a major part of its design.
        FEEDBACK: This statement does not need specific evidence, although we need a reference for the study, e.g. (Wrigley et al. 2004).  It is highly likely that evidence from the focus groups would be included in the essay.
        ANSWER: Tesco is increasing its market share as Morrison's share is slipping.
        FEEDBACK: Assertions about figures and statistics always need hard evidence to back them up.  This assertion should be followed by:  According to Kantar Worldpanel (in Daily Telegraph 2010a) December 2010 saw Tesco's market share increase to 30.7% from 30.6% whilst Morrison's dipped from 12.1% to 12%.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Which of the following assertions need to be backed up by hard evidence?</font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Read the text then answer the question(s).</font> 
        ANSWER: The Irish famine was precipitated by potato blight.
        FEEDBACK: This is a topic sentence, but does not require hard evidence in the same way as, for example, a statement about how many people died in the famine.
        ANSWER: Before famine struck, adult males in Ireland consumed massive numbers of potatoes each day.
        FEEDBACK: If you mention numbers, you must give numbers, not rely on colloquialisms like 'massive'.  A better sentence would be: Before famine struck adult males in Ireland consumed on average 70 potatoes each day. <br />
        ANSWER: In conclusion, it is clear that these are the reasons Scotland avoided the famine which was so disastrous for their neighbours across the Irish sea.
        FEEDBACK: This would be followed by a reference, formatted in the appropriate style (Harvard or footnote system).
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">Which of the following assertions need hard evidence to back them up?</font> 
    QUESTION 0 
        ANSWER: Thatcher found many ways of increasing her power within cabinet.
        FEEDBACK: The phrase 'found many ways' clearly indicates a need for evidence.  You cannot say 'many ways' and not produce at least two fully referenced examples of those ways.  You might, for example, say:  Thatcher found many ways of increasing her power within cabinet.  For example, she undermined relations between cabinet colleagues and appropriated the powers of her Chancellor of the Exchequer (Smith in Rhodes & Dunleavy 1995).
        ANSWER: Thatcher became the British prime minister following the 1979 general election.
        FEEDBACK: This is a well known and incontrovertible fact so doesn't need proof.
        ANSWER: In 1979, there was a big percentage swing to the Conservatives and they won many more seats than Labour.
        FEEDBACK: If you mention percentages and numbers, you need to provide exact figures, not just concepts like 'big' or 'more'.  Here, we need to know that the percentage swing was 5.2% and that the Conservatives won 339 seats against Labour's 269 (BBC 1997).
Processing course Psychology
    Writing activity 02. Punctuation - commas and run-on sentences
        Task freetext difficulty 2
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">This cognitive restructuring will in turn, lead to a positive change in behaviour and emotional wellbeing (Beck &amp; Fernandez, 1998).</font> 
    QUESTION 0 What is the matter with the comma after 'turn'?
        ANSWER: It's in the wrong place.  It should come after 'restructuring'.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  A comma after 'restructuring' would disrupt the sense.
        ANSWER: Nothing.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  As it stands, the comma after 'turn' disrupts the sense of the sentence.
        ANSWER: Since 'in turn' is being used as a sub-clause, there should be a first comma after 'will', which then encloses the sub-clause.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  A comma after 'will' would indicate the start of the sub-clause, so the sentence would read:  This cognitive restructuring will, in turn, lead to etc.   Read the example sentence aloud, then read it again with the sub-clause properly enclosed.  Listen to how much clearer the sense is with commas correctly placed.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">In fact, Godar, Flament Lecrubier and Jeammet (2000) found that borderline and schizoid personality disorders, along with obsessive compulsive disorder are overly represented in ED groups. </font> 
    QUESTION 0 A comma is missing in this text.  Where should it be placed?
        ANSWER: After (2000).
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  This list of people is the subject of the sentence.  They should not be separated from their verb (found) by a comma.
        ANSWER: After 'represented'.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  A comma here would severely disrupt the sense of the sentence.
        ANSWER: After 'disorder'.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  A comma here would mark the end of the subclause that begins with the comma after 'disorders'.  When you mark the beginning of a subclause with a comma, make sure you close the subclause with another comma.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">If characteristically, a person is angry are they more likely to suffer from bulimia or anorexia?</font> 
    QUESTION 0 This sentence is missing two commas.  Where should they be placed?
        ANSWER: After 'person' and 'bulimia'.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.   A comma after 'person' separates 'person' from 'is' (i.e. separates the subject from its verb) which is nonsensical unless you are inserting a subclause.  A comma after 'bulimia' interrupts the sense of the sentence.
        ANSWER: After 'if' and 'angry'.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  'Characteristically' is a one word subclause, so if the subclause closes with the comma after 'characteristically, it opens after 'if'.  A comma after 'angry', helps the sense of the sentence by suggesting a slight pause before the main question.
        Task freetext difficulty 2
        Task freetext difficulty 2
        Task freetext difficulty 2
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <ol> 
  <li><font size="4">However objects that are further away than the fixation point seem to move in the same direction as your own movement. </font></li> 
  <li><font size="4">An example of this is when a child believes the moon is following them, as in the case with other distance objects, the moon often seems to move in the same direction as your own movement.</font></li> 
</ol> 
    QUESTION 0 There should be a comma in sentence 1. Where should it be?
        ANSWER: After 'point'.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  The verb attached to 'fixation point' is 'seem' and, for the sense of the sentence, it makes no sense to separate the two. 
        ANSWER: After 'move'.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  'Move in the same direction' etc. is all one thought.  No comma required.
        ANSWER: After 'however'.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  After most adverbs (e.g. however, furthermore, finally, similarly, subsequently) or adverb phrases (e.g. in conclusion, in addition, in the meantime, more importantly) particularly when the adverb or adverb phrase begins a sentence, it should be followed by a comma.  Here are two examples. <br />
    QUESTION 1 One of the commas in sentence 2 should be a full stop.  Which one is it?
        ANSWER: The comma after 'them' should be a full stop.
        FEEDBACK: You may be right. The use of commas in this sentence makes the meaning ambiguous.  Does the phrase 'as is the case with other distant objects' belong with the phrase before or the phrase after?  It's impossible to know.  This is why correctly placing commas and full stops is so important.
        ANSWER: The comma after 'objects' should be a full stop.
        FEEDBACK: You may be right. The use of commas in this sentence makes the meaning ambiguous.  Does the phrase 'as is the case with other distant objects' belong with the phrase before or the phrase after?  It's impossible to know.  This is why correctly placing commas and full stops is so important.
        Task freetext difficulty 2
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Examples of true reciprocal altruism in organisms are very rare, vampire bats, for example, fit all the criteria for being reciprocal altruists, except that most in the group are cousins but the clearest case is in humans, as with Mathew Robinson in 2010, he did not save a relative, he saved children from a burning building, so great was the risk that even the fire fighters would not attempt it.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 This is one sentence.  How many could it be?
        ANSWER: It can only be one sentence.
        FEEDBACK: This isn't right.  The sentence doesn't read well as one.  Everything runs on.
        ANSWER: Two.
        FEEDBACK: It's hard to see how it could be two sentences:  there's too much information.
        ANSWER: Three.
        FEEDBACK: With a judicious use of colons and semi-colons, it could be three sentences.
        ANSWER: Four.
        FEEDBACK: With a judicious use of colons, semi-colons and full stops, it could be four sentences.
        ANSWER: Five.
        FEEDBACK: With a judicious use of colons, semi-colons and full stops, it could be five sentences.
        ANSWER: Six.
        FEEDBACK: With a judicious use of full stops, it could be six sentences.
    QUESTION 1 You'll now see the sentence repunctuated.  Which version is correct?
        ANSWER: Examples of true reciprocal altruism in organisms are very rare: vampire bats, for example, fit all the criteria for being reciprocal altruists, except that most in the group are cousins.  But the clearest case is in humans, as with Mathew Robinson in 2010.  He did not save a relative:  he saved children from a burning building;  so great was the risk that even the fire fighters would not attempt it.
        FEEDBACK: I agree. This version is fine.
        ANSWER: Examples of true reciprocal altruism in organisms are very rare.  Vampire bats, for example, fit all the criteria for being reciprocal altruists, except that most in the group are cousins.  But the clearest case is in humans, as with Mathew Robinson in 2010.  He did not save a relative.  He saved children from a burning building.  So great was the risk that even the fire fighters would not attempt it.
        FEEDBACK: This version's fine too.
        ANSWER: Examples of true reciprocal altruism in organisms are very rare, vampire bats, for example, fit all the criteria for being reciprocal altruists, except that most in the group are cousins but the clearest case is in humans, as with Mathew Robinson in 2010, he did not save a relative, he saved children from a burning building, so great was the risk that even the fire fighters would not attempt it.
        FEEDBACK: This version is fine as well.
        ANSWER: Examples of true reciprocal altruism in organisms are very rare:  vampire bats, for example, fit all the criteria for being reciprocal altruists, except that most in the group are cousins.  But the clearest case is in humans, as with Mathew Robinson in 2010.  He did not save a relative: he saved children from a burning building.  So great was the risk that even the fire fighters would not attempt it.
        FEEDBACK: This version is fine as well.
