    Writing activity 04. Punctuation - paragraphs
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">CBT's popularity really began in the 1960s after psychologist Aaron Beck (1963) developed a successful CBT treatment for depression (Beck et al., 1979) and today it is claimed to be successful in the treatment of many psychological disorders including anxiety, eating disorders, obsessive-compulsive disorder and post-traumatic stress disorder. CBT adopts a &quot;hands on&quot;, practical and goal oriented approach using a variety of techniques including general relaxation, problem solving and cognitive restructuring. Specifically, its application is broken down into three phases. </font> 
    QUESTION 0 Where should the new paragraph start?
        ANSWER: This is fine as one paragraph: the new paragraph should start right at the end, after 'three phases'. 
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  The 'three phases' belong to the description of the "hands on" approach and should not be separated from it. 
        ANSWER: After "post traumatic stress disorder".
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  This phrase finishes the history of CBT.  The phrase 'CBT adopts' begins to describe the procedure.
        ANSWER: After "cognitive restructuring".
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  The word "Specifically", which starts the next sentence, shows that the topic is ongoing, with more information being given.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO Sukhodolsky, Kassinove and Gorman (2004) advanced the CBT debate stating that although positive effects for anger and aggression are well documented, little is known about the individual components that make it work or about its exportability from clinical research to practice. This was an area in which further studies were ongoing. In contrast to Cole (2008), the 2004 study of Sukhodolky et al. addressed the &quot;file drawer&quot; problem comprehensively, with 19 of the 40 studies not published and a calculated &quot;fail-safe&quot;<sup>1</sup> to ensure that their results were not influenced. The &quot;file-drawer&quot; problem, however, remains a difficulty with many other studies. 
    QUESTION 0 Where should the new paragraph start?
        ANSWER: After "practice".
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  The next sentence, begins "This was an area", so we are clearly on the same topic.
        ANSWER: There shouldn't be one.  
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  I think there is a new topic in this text.  Try again.
        ANSWER: After "ongoing".
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  We have moved on to the "file-drawer" problem, so I'd say a new paragraph was in order here.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">However, does empirical evidence support the belief that police officers use non-verbal behaviours to detect deceit? Taylor and Hick (2007) carried out empirical research to identify the importance of non-verbal behaviours in detecting deceit. They identified which cues individuals believe are associated with deceit, looking at both serious and trivial consequences.<br /><br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Where should the new paragraph start?
        ANSWER: There's no need for a new paragraph in this text.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  I think we move from the general to the particular, and a new paragraph is needed to mark this.
        ANSWER: After the question mark:  i.e. deceit?
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  This offers a clear break.  The new paragraph starts to answer this question through a particular study.
        ANSWER: After "in detecting deceit."
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  This sentence is part of the ongoing topic.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">A more recent study by Muller (1998, in Kita, 2009) looked at the difference in hand gestures between Germans and Spaniards. Spaniards, it was discovered, made more above the shoulder hand movements. However, no difference was perceived in the number of gestures. Muller (1998) suggests that because the Spaniards' hand gestures were above the shoulder, they created a more abundant impression. One study which empirically investigated cultural differences in hand gestures used US and Taiwanese mothers (Goldin-Meadow &amp; Saltzman, 2000). The results of this interaction were significant.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 Where should the new paragraph start?
        ANSWER: After "Spaniards".
        FEEDBACK: If this sentence came after a long piece of unbroken text, it would be right to start a new paragraph after it.  "Spaniards" can easily be seen as a new topic.  If, however, the text is already broken up into small paragraphs, there is no need for a new paragraph here.  Think of the reader.  What will they find easiest?
        ANSWER: After "abundant impression."
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  The new study mentioned is different from the study previously mentioned.  Read this text aloud.  A new paragraph feels right here.
        ANSWER: After "number of gestures."
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Muller's suggestion flows on from the previous sentence.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">This finding is especially relevant to this Critical Review because the interviewer and the interviewee were from different cultures. This interview was a typical racial situation and the results are important. However the results are four years old. A more recent study investigating cross-cultural differences in eye-contact in a police interview setting has been done by Johnson (2006). </font> 
    QUESTION 0 Where should the new paragraph begin?
        ANSWER: There is no need of a new paragraph in this text.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  This text hangs together well.  The new paragraph would start after "Johnson (2006)" with the description of this study. 
        ANSWER: After "cultures".
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  The sentence beginning "This interview" is clearly linked to the sentence before, which is about the same interview. 
        ANSWER: After "four years old".
        FEEDBACK: I disagree, though you may disagree with me!  I'd say that this sentence is a linking sentence, i.e. it points the way to the next paragraph but does not belong in the next paragraph.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO  <font size="4">A study by Kassin and Fong (1999) investigated the accuracy of lie detection with individuals trained to detect deceit as compared with a group not trained to detect deceit. The training the first group received involved the group learning which non-verbal behaviours are believed to indicate deceit. However, at the end of the study, the group with no training were found to have performed significantly better at lie detection than the trained group. In another, similar, study, Mann, Frij and Bull (2006) also discovered that when lie detecting personnel followed the cues outlined in police manuals, their lie detection accuracy was reduced. </font> 
    QUESTION 0 Where should the new paragraph start?
        ANSWER: After "to detect deceit" (i.e. at the end of sentence 1).
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  We are still on the same topic here:   the accuracy of lie detection.
        ANSWER: We don't need a new paragraph.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  I think this is a whole paragraph about the accuracy of lie detection and, as presented here, doesn't need dividing up.  If, however, there was lots more information about the Mann, Frij and Bull study, we would need a new paragraph after "trained group" because this new study would be a new topic rather than an extension of the existing topic.
        ANSWER: Between "indicate deceit" and "However".
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  "However" does sometimes herald a new paragraph, but as this text is set out, we're still on the topic of accuracy and the text should flow on.
