    Writing activity 11. Article (a, an, the) - missing or unnecessary
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">Study was completed by 51 subjects who were told in advance that they would be required to make the time judgments. Data supports Attentional model.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 There is a 'the' missing in the first sentence.  Where should it be inserted?
        ANSWER: Before 51.
        FEEDBACK: Not unless these subjects have already been specified earlier in the text.  If this is their first mention, then we don't need the article since we are referring to them generally. 
        ANSWER: Before 'Study'.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  This is a very specific study, so we need the article.  'The study was completed ...'
        ANSWER: Before 'advance'.
        FEEDBACK: Not there.  'In advance' is a whole phrase in itself.
    QUESTION 1 Do we need 'the' before 'time judgments'?
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  In this context, the phrase 'time judgments' is being used to describe the concept of time judgments, not particular time judgments. 
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: Not unless some previous texts had described a particular set of time judgments that the subjects would be required to make.  Otherwise, time judgments are being referred to in concept form, and concepts don't need articles.
    QUESTION 2 Do we need a definite article before 'Data'?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: This is one of those occasions when you can choose.  You can refer to specific date, i.e. The data ...,  or you can refer to 'Data' in general. 
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: This is one of those occasions when you can choose.  You can refer to specific date, i.e. The data ...,  or you can refer to 'Data' in general.
    QUESTION 3 Do we need an article before 'Attentional'?
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  This model is being very specifically named, so we do an article:  the Attentional model.
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  This model is being very specifically named, so we do an article:  the Attentional model.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">In this particular case, underestimation of negative slides was significantly greater than that of positive slides.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 Which words need to be preceded by the definite article?
        ANSWER: underestimation, negative, positive
        FEEDBACK: You could put definite articles in all three places although there's actually no need to put articles anywhere.  This is because we can use the word 'underestimation' and the phrases 'negative slides' and 'positive slides' either as specific examples or as concepts.  In this context, both make sense.
        ANSWER: No words need the definite article.
        FEEDBACK: You're right. This is one of those examples where no articles are needed although it's also true that you could put definite articles in all three places.   This is because we can use the word 'underestimation' and the phrases 'negative slides' and 'positive slides' either as specific examples or as concepts.  In this context, both make sense.
        ANSWER: negative, positive
        FEEDBACK: You're right. You could put definite articles before 'negative' and 'positive' and, indeed, before 'underestimation'.  But there's actually no need to put articles anywhere. This is because we can use the word 'underestimation' and the phrases 'negative slides' and 'positive slides' either as specific examples or as concepts.  In this context, both make sense.
