    Writing activity 16.  Opening lines
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Essay title:</span><br /><br />Show how psychology as a science can explore any one problem, e.g. autism, depression, aggression, from various perspectives and levels ranging from social behaviour to basic biology.</font><br /> 
    QUESTION 0 Which of the following are the best opening lines for this essay title?  Each choice has an explanation, so it's worth clicking on them all, even if your first choice agrees with ours.
        ANSWER: Mental disorders are controversial concepts. 'In contrast to physical illness diagnoses, there are no clear physical criteria for mental illnesss' (Passer, 2009, p. 784).  However, psychological evaluation has helped to explore and develop our understanding of mental illnesses such as depression as common 'problems in living' as opposed to purely 'inner disorders' (Szasz, 1963, as in Passer et al., 2009).
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  These lines are not wrong, but could you tell, from reading them, what the essay title is?  There are no echoes of the essay title, so the reader is a little in the dark.  Opening lines need, very specifically, to refer to the terms of the essay title.  Without a specific reference, the essay risks veering wildly off course. 
        ANSWER: As a science, psychology is uniquely equipped to explore, from many perspectives, problems that have psychological as well as physical dimensions.  Employing experimental behavioural techniques as well as basic biological tests, psychology fills in gaps left by purely physical diagnoses.  Using depression as an example, this essay will show how psychology, as a science, goes about its important work.  Firstly, it will look at diagnostic techniques; secondly, at genetic factors; and thirdly, at differing theories, and the effects these theories have had on treatments.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  These lines grasp the essay title, echoing its terms:  psychology as a science; explore; problem; perspectives.  They also provide a coherent essay plan, and all in 84 words.
        ANSWER: Psychology is defined as the 'scientific study of human or other animal mental functions and behaviours' (Wikipedia). It also has a long history, and in this essay I am going to look at the different approaches psychology has taken to examine the problem of depression.  Depression is a condition which makes sufferer feels 'sad, discouraged, apathetic and passive' (Passer et al., 2009).
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  These opening lines are undermined at once by a definition lifted from Wikipedia.  Wikipedia is not a reliable source of referencing and should be avoided.  Then, although we're told what the essay is going to do, the stress is on the history of approaches to depression.  This is veering away from the essay title.  If you keep the essay title in mind, you won't veer off like this.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Essay title:</span><br /><br />Outline the main cues in depth perception.<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Read the title of the essay.  Which are the best opening lines?
        ANSWER: The following essay will outline the main cues for depth perception.  Depth perception can be described as the way in which the individual perceives objects as having three dimensions.  This means individuals see objects as having depth and thickness as well as height and width.  Some parts of an object seem further away than others.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  The first sentence is unnecessary.  It's good to echo the terms of the essay title but not good simply to repeat the title without adding anything.  We then have three sentences telling us the same thing but in different words.  One sentence will do here.
        ANSWER: The main cues for depth perception, i.e. how an individual perceives objects as having three dimensions, can be grouped in two broad categories: stimulus cues and visual system cues.  This essay will look firstly at stimulus cues, then at visual system cues.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  This is a crisp, no-nonsense opening, which gives a clear, concise definition and tells the reader exactly what to expect. 
        ANSWER: The history of our understanding of depth perception is long and complicated, since for centuries it was something we took for granted rather than analysed.  We have only really understood the physical reactions that underpin depth perception since the introduction of sophisticated equipment for tracking the effects of vision on our brains.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  This may be all be true (or it may not be - where are the references?) but the essay question is very precise, and your essay must very precisely answer it.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Essay title:</span><br /><br />Describe and explain kin selection and reciprocal altruism.<br /><br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Which are the best opening lines for this essay question?
        ANSWER: Altruism is a pro-social helping behaviour which seems both difficult to explain and to describe.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  This is a personal opinion.  It adds nothing to the essay except to undermine the reader's confidence in what is to come. Also, why start with altruism when the essay title clearly lists kin selection first?  In your opening lines, try to echo the terms of the question.  That will let your reader know you've actually read it ...
        ANSWER: Kin selection was first outlined by R.A. Fisher, but it was 'W. D. Hamilton who truly formalised the concept, in works published in 1963 and - most importantly - in 1964' (Wikipedia).  Reciprocal altruism  suggests that 'altruism could have evolved since it might be beneficial to incur this cost if there is a chance of being in a reverse situation where the person whom I helped before may perform an altruistic act towards me' (Trivers, 1971, as in Wikipedia). 
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Wikipedia is not a reliable source and should never be used in academic essays.  However, if you find the original text - Wikipedia has references at the bottom of its articles - then quotations are often a good way to start an essay, though they should not be quite this long.
        ANSWER: In my view, there is no such thing as altruistic behaviour, and kin selection cannot work as it is completely at odds with Darwin's theory of classical fitness.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  This is a personal opinion.  What's more, the essay is a discursive essay, i.e. it does not ask you to argue for or against the concepts of kin selection and reciprocal altruism, it asks you to describe and explain.   Not a good choice. 
        ANSWER: Kin selection, the theory that 'organisms are most likely to help others with whom they share the most genes, namely, their offspring and genetic relatives' (Passer, Smith, Holt, Bremner, Sutherland
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  From these two sentences, we know what we are talking about and where we are going.  Note also how other approaches to this essay are acknowledged - 'social learning, cultural differences or other observed behaviours'.  This is an excellent way of showing that you know more than there is space to write about.
