INTRO <font size="4"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Critical Review title:</span><br /><br />The neural components of love.<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Remember:  these are the opening lines of the abstract (i.e. NOT the introduction).
        ANSWER: Love is one of the most desired experiences (Debiec, 2007) within human nature.  None of us can do without it without severe detriment to our wellbeing.  Its definition in the Oxford English Dictionary (OED) is of 'an intense feeling of deep affection or fondness for a person or thing, a sexual passion, or sexual relations'.
        FEEDBACK: The first line here is fine, and the reference adds authority.  But then the text meanders off, wasting words in repetition.   There is no room for meandering in an abstract.  Not the best option.
        ANSWER: Love is one of the most desired experiences (Debiec, 2007) and the focus of much scientific literature.  This Review focused on the role of neurotransmitters in lower mammals such as prairie voles (Zeki, 2007); then assessed Bartels and Zeki's 2004 study of the neural correlates of maternal and romantic love in humans; and finally analysed the neural basis of unconditional love in both humans, as investigated by Beauregard (2009).  
        FEEDBACK: These lines are crisp and informative.  The past tense - focused - shows the writer has understood the function of his/her abstract, which is to allow a reader to see at once whether this particular Critical Review contains what they are looking for.
        ANSWER: Love is one of the most desired experiences (Debiec, 2007).  Firstly, this paper is going to look at the role of neurotransmitters in lower mammals such as prairie voles (Zeki, 2007); secondly, it will assess the neural correlates of maternal and romantic love;  thirdly, it will analyse the neural basis of unconditional love and finally, it will evaluate the value of these studies and suggest where further research is needed.
        FEEDBACK: The writer of these lines has mistaken their function.  Your abstract should be an overview of your whole Critical Review, conclusions included.  These lines read more like the start of an essay.
