    Writing activity 17. Concluding lines
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title:<br /></font><br /><font size="4">Why do we obey?</font><br /> 
    QUESTION 0 Which concluding lines are the best for this essay title? 
        ANSWER: So, why do we obey?  The simple answer is another question: why not?
        FEEDBACK: This may seem clever, but is in fact nonsense!  Concluding lines should certainly echo the terms of the question, but they should leave the reader impressed by your scholarship, not your quirkiness.
        ANSWER: It seems that there are three clear reasons as to why we are likely to obey:  subservience to a perceived legitimate authority;  removal of direct responsibility; and the desire to keep in with the crowd.  Milgram's 1963 experiment demonstrated all these reasons and Burger's rerun in 2009 shows us that the answers to the question 'why do we obey' have not changed.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  This is an excellent conclusion, wrapping up the essay clearly and concisely.
        ANSWER: Miligram, then Burger, illustrated obedience very well in their experiments, and we do not appear to have altered much between 1963 and 2009.  Therefore the answer to the question 'why do we obey' is still the same as the answer to be found in Milgram's conclusion, and there is no reason to believe that things will change.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  This conclusion is not terrible at all, but we need specifics - i.e. to be reminded, specifically but concisely, of what Milgram's conclusions were - if the essay is to remain tight.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Essay title:</span><br /><br />Describe and evaluate the trait theory approach to personality.<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Which are the best concluding lines to this essay?  All the lines have explanations, so even if you are right first time, it is worth skimming through them all.
        ANSWER: As this essay has shown, there are many different approaches to personality, from Galen to Freud, from Allport to Cattell's list of personality factors.  All feed into our notion of what a person is and all, therefore, have value.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  These lines may be coherent, but they do not relate to the essay question.  You can write the best essay in the world, but if it doesn't grasp and answer the question set, it has failed in its purpose.
        ANSWER: I think that the trait theory approach to personality works when when attempting to measure individual personalities.  It is much better than other theories and, as I've shown, seems to manage a fair degree of accuracy.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  These closing lines are too personal and informal in style:  'I think', 'I've shown'.  And what is a 'fair degree' of accuracy?  Academic essays must be objective and precise.  
        ANSWER: As has been shown, the trait theory approach to personality, through embracing variety, has proven itself a valuable tool in the dissection of individuals' personalities.  However, as has also been shown, the multitude of varieties is very hard to manage, particularly amid the multitude of combinations.  Trait theory, however, by not fixing individuals into types, can claim an accuracy that broader theories cannot claim, and for this reason is of greater value.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  These lines reveal clearly what the essay has been discussing, and are relevant to the essay title.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Essay title:</span><br /><br />To what extent are biological explanations of ADHD sufficient to account for the condition?<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Which are the best concluding lines for this essay?
        ANSWER: I believe that compromise reaches out further towards the cause of the disorder as it takes into account both the biological hard-wiring that one is born with, the effect of narcotics and toxins in the pre-natal stage and the circumstances in which one grows up in.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  What does 'compromise reaches out further' actually mean?  The phrase 'it takes into account BOTH' is then followed by three items, the last of which is a jumble of words - 'in which one grows up in'. Some of the content may be good, but the style is off-putting.  Not a good choice. 
        ANSWER: It is clear, then, that biological explanations are insufficient to account for ADHD, and that although research into genetics and brain anomalies presents good evidence, psychological and environmental factors cannot be disregarded. 
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  This concluding line answers the essay question with clarity and precision.
        ANSWER: The causes of ADHD are difficult to pin down.  What we do know is that the condition causes a great deal of suffering that that the sooner we get to the bottom of the causes, the better.
        FEEDBACK: This is journalese, i.e. it might do for an article in a newspaper or magazine but it's too general and vague for an academic essay.
