INTRO <div style="text-align: center;"><font size="4" style="font-weight: bold;">Abstract</font><br /></div><font size="4"><br />Ostracism can have a huge effect on an individual both physiologically and psychologically. A considerable amount of research has been done looking at ostracism and the reaction it elicits. However, less has been completed looking at why these reactions are induced. Experimental evidence has shown that social exclusion can elicit both pro and anti social responses. However as of yet no consensus has been made on what factors lead to these reactions. We suggest that response to ostracism is controlled by a variety of items including situational factors and individual differences. We argue that although these are not the only factors important in influencing reaction to ostracism each of these is valuable. This Critical Review will then conclude with suggestions for further research and a summary of the main points being made within this Review.<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 An abstract is an overview of a whole Critical Review, including the conclusions and suggestions for further work.   Would you say this was a good example?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  This example tells us what the Critical Review is going to do, which would be fine for the first paragraph of an essay, but is not fine in the abstract of a Critical Review.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  This example tells us what the Critical Review is going to do, which would be fine for the first paragraph of an essay, but is not fine in the abstract of a Critical Review.
    QUESTION 1 Does every word in this abstract add something to valuable?
        ANSWER: Yes.  It's been well thought through.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  I find this abstract wordy and general.  What is meant by a 'huge effect'?  What is 'a considerable amount'?  An abstract needs to be tight and informative.  I don't think this qualifies.
        ANSWER: No.  It's not clear what the function of every phrase or sentence is.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  I find this abstract wordy and general.  What is meant by a 'huge effect'?  What is 'a considerable amount'?  An abstract needs to be tight and informative.  I don't think this qualifies.
    QUESTION 2 Is every word properly used?
        ANSWER: No.  
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  I think the very first word - ostracism - should actually be 'Being ostracised'.  This shows that ostracism is something that happens to you, which is important to remember.  I'm also unhappy with 'induced'.  It's not absolutely wrong, but it certainly jolts the reader.  I think 'reactions to it' would be simpler and more comprehensible.
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.   I think the very first word - ostracism - should actually be 'Being ostracised'.  This shows that ostracism is something that happens to you, which is important to remember.  I'm also unhappy with 'induced'.  It's not absolutely wrong, but it certainly jolts the reader.  I think 'reactions to it' would be simpler and more comprehensible.
