INTRO <font size="4"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Critical Review title:</span><br /><br />'You have the right to remain silent, but anything you <span style="text-decoration: underline;">do</span> may be used against you.' Issues with using non verbal behaviours to detect deceit in a multicultural environment.<br /><br /></font>
<div style="text-align: center;"><font size="4"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Abstract</span></font><br /></div><font size="4"><br />Evidence exists which suggests that non-verbal behaviours are commonly used in a variety of applied settings. Specifically, this evidence suggests they are important in police interviews, where they are used to detect deceit. However, a body of empirical evidence also exists which demonstrates that non verbal behaviours vary across cultures. This Critical Review will analyze whether cross cultural differences in specific non-verbal behaviours will result in ethnic individuals being misperceived as deceptive in police interviews. In order for this misperception to take place a culture's natural display of non verbal behaviours must match the profile of non-verbal behaviours which police officers believe indicate deceit. This Critical Review will impose a new structure on already existing evidence to investigate whether this problem exists. The structure of the Review is three fold. Section One .... Section Two ... Section Three. It will then conclude that cross cultural difference in the amount of eye contact displayed by Black, Hispanic and Japanese individuals could lead to them being perceived as deceptive when they are innocent.<br /><br /><br /></font> 
