        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">In an introduction, would you expect to find the following?</font> 
    QUESTION 0 A detailed history of the problem or topic from its first appearance in psychological literature to the present day?
        ANSWER: Yes.  
        FEEDBACK: I disagree in one respect:  we need to have the problem or topic set in context, and this may involve a short history.  But don't get too carried away with historical facts and dates.  Your Critical Review is a Critical Review, not a historical perspective.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I agree up to a point.  The introduction is certainly the place to set the problem or topic in context, and this may involve a short history.  But you would be right not to get too carried away with historical facts and dates.  Your Critical Review is a Critical Review, not a historical perspective.
    QUESTION 1 An description of the studies on which you are going to focus?
        ANSWER: No.  They should have sections of their own.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  By the end of the introduction, the reader should know what literature is under scrutiny.  This doesn't mean that you can't also have sections on each piece of literature, if that seems appropriate for your particular Review.
        ANSWER: Yes.  The reader will expect this.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  By the end of the introduction, the reader should know what literature is under scrutiny.  This doesn't mean that you can't also have sections on each piece of literature, if that seems appropriate for your particular Review.
    QUESTION 2 An idea of the practical and theoretical implications of your Review?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  Thinking about the practical and theoretical implications of your Review does not mean you have to prejudge your conclusions; only that you should be able to justify the focus of your Review.
        ANSWER: No. That should be reserved for the Results/Discussion section.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Thinking about the practical and theoretical implications of your Review does not mean you have to prejudge your conclusions; only that you should be able to justify the focus of your Review.
