    Writing activity 19. Analytical and critical skills
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Carl Jung asserted that individuals are either &quot;extraverted' or &quot;introverted&quot;. He defined eight personality types. Katharine Briggs expanded on Jung's observations and Katharine's daughter, Isabel Briggs Myers, visualised personality types through a combination of Jung's theories and her mother's. </font> 
    QUESTION 0 Are these sentences analytical or factual?
        ANSWER: Analytical.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  These sentences tell us facts.  There is no analysis attached to them.
        ANSWER: Factual.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  These sentences tell us facts.  There is no analysis attached to them.
    QUESTION 1 Could they still be included in an essay?
        ANSWER: No - they have no place in an essay.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  All essays need facts. It's what you do with the facts that matters.   If you just leave them hanging, without scrutiny or expansion, they don't have much value.  But referenced facts are good starting point for some analytical digging. 
        ANSWER: Yes - you could include them.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  All essays need facts. It's what you do with the facts that matters.   If you just leave them hanging, without scrutiny or expansion, they don't have much value.  But referenced facts are a good starting point for some analytical digging.
    QUESTION 2 How might these facts be used in an analytical or critical way?
        ANSWER: By looking at them in more detail and assessing their importance.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  That is a good way of turning facts into analysis.
        ANSWER: By comparing these facts to other facts in more modern literature.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  Assessing how Jung etc. has contributed to modern character mapping would be a very useful expansion of these facts.
        ANSWER: By showing what part character mapping played in the lives of Jung, Briggs and Briggs Myers.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  You are not writing a history essay.  All the facts that you use must answer the essay question set, be evidence for a hypothesis you are trying to prove or disprove, or be otherwise useful for the purposes of your essay or Critical Review.
