    Writing activity 14. Referencing within your text
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">These are based on the research of Carl Jung and Katharine C. Briggs. Carl Jung first developed his theory that individuals each have a psychological type. Katharine Briggs expanded on Jung's initial observations and developed the theories further.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 Do we need references in the text here?
        ANSWER: No.  So long as there are references in the referencing section, there's no need for references here.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  I think there's every need for author/date references here.  It's important that your reader knows where you've been looking.
        ANSWER: Yes, we need author/date references here.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  There's every need for author/date references here.  It's important that your reader knows where you've been looking.
        ANSWER: It doesn't matter if there's a reference or not.
        FEEDBACK: I'm afraid it always matters, and there's every need for author/date references here.  It's important that your reader knows where you've been looking.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">It also manifests itself in a predisposition to cause accidents. (Kring 2007) There are two main opposing sides in the debate, one representing biological factors and the other psychological factors. (Davey, 2008) </font> 
    QUESTION 0 There is a referencing error in this text.  What is it?
        ANSWER: We need page numbers for these references. 
        FEEDBACK: No, we don't need page numbers.  Page numbers are only needed for direct quotations enclosed in double quotation marks within the text.
        ANSWER: We need the initials of the author.
        FEEDBACK: No, we don't need the initials.  In the author/date system, the surname and date are enough.
        ANSWER: The year should be in brackets.
        FEEDBACK: No, the year is fine as it is.
        ANSWER: The references should be just as they are, but should be placed before the full stop.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  The reference is considered part of the sentence, so don't leave it hanging after the full stop; place it before the full stop.
        Task freetext difficulty 2
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">Several studies (Sonuga-Barke, E.J.S. &amp; Rubia, K. 2008a, 2008b and Grant, 2004a) illustrated the importance of this link.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">In this example in-text reference, what do the letters a, b and c mean?</font> 
        ANSWER: That there is more than one work by one of these authors cited in the References section.
        FEEDBACK: Not quite that.  Try again.
        ANSWER: That there is more than one work by these authors (or two authors in the same order) in the References section.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  The suffix letters (a, b, c. etc.) differentiate between the cited works.
        ANSWER: That the authors wrote more works, even though these other works are not cited in this essay.
        FEEDBACK: No, not that.  Try again.
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">1. The first extensive use was in the 1960s after psychologist Aaron Beck (1963) developed successful CBT treatment for depression, as reported by Beck, Rush, Shaw &amp; Emery. (1979)<br />2. The first extensive use was in the 1960s after psychologist Aaron Beck (1963) developed successful CBT treatment for depression (Beck, Rush, Shaw &amp; Emery, 1979).</font> 
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">Which of the following references is correctly formatted?</font> 
        ANSWER: Sentence 1.
        FEEDBACK: That's not correct.
        ANSWER: Sentence 2.
        FEEDBACK: That's correct.  Note the way Beck, Rush et al. are referenced in brackets, rather than through the phrase 'as reported by'.  The ampersand should be used only when the referees are listed in brackets.  When names are listed in the main body of the text, use the full 'and'.  References come before the full stop.  They are part of the sentence and should never be left hanging.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">1. Butler, Chapman, Forman &amp; Beck (2006) cite evidence from Hollon, Thase &amp; Markowitz (2002).<br /><br />2. </font><font size="4">Butler, Chapman, Forman and Beck (2006) cite evidence from Hollon, Thase and Markowitz (2002).</font> 
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">Which of the following sentences has the references correctly formatted?</font> 
        ANSWER: Sentence 1.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right. If you list authors in the main body of the text rather than in brackets, use the full 'and' and not the ampersand.
        ANSWER: Sentence 2.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  If you list authors in the main body of the text rather than in brackets, use the full 'and' and not the ampersand.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">Butler et al cite evidence from Hollen et al which suggests that the effects of psychological interventions like CBT weaken if treatment is discontinued. </font> 
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">What is wrong with this in-text reference?</font> 
        ANSWER: The 'et al' should be in brackets.
        FEEDBACK: No, this isn't it.  Try again.
        ANSWER: All the names of the authors should be listed.
        FEEDBACK: Only in the first reference.  After that it's fine to use only the first name so long as you show that there are others.
        ANSWER: There should be a full stop after 'al.'
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  'Et al' stands for the Latin 'et alii', which means 'and others'.  You must put a full stop after 'al.' to show that it is a short form.
    Writing activity 15. References section
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO  <font size="4">1. Eysenck, H.J. (1994). Creativity and personality: Word association, origence and Psychoticism. <span style="font-style: italic;">Creativity Research Journal</span>, 7, 209-216.<br /><br />2. Hans Eysenck, (1994). Creativity and personality: word association, origence and psychoticism. Creativity Research Journal, 7, 209-216.<br /><br /></font><font size="4">3. Eysenck, H.J. (1994). Creativity and personality: Word association, origence and psychoticism. <span style="font-style: italic;">Creativity Research Journal</span>,<span style="font-style: italic;"> 7</span>, 209-216.<br /><br /></font><font size="4">4. Eysenck, H.J. (1994). Creativity and personality: Word Association, Origence and Psychoticism. Creativity Research Journal, 7, 209-216.<br /><br /><font size="1">(In Psychology, we follow the guidelines drawn up by the <span style="font-style: italic;">Publication Manual of the American Psychological Association</span> (APA) - Glasgow University Library call no. Psychology B235 AME.) </font><br /> </font><br /><br /> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Which of the following references is correctly formatted for a reference section? </font>
        ANSWER: 1. is correct.
        FEEDBACK: I'm afraid not!  Try again.
        ANSWER: 2. is correct.
        FEEDBACK: I'm afraid not!  Try again.
        ANSWER: 3. is correct.
        FEEDBACK: Well done.  The author is listed surname first, with the date of the publication in brackets.  The capital letters are properly formatted in accordance with APA guidelines - N.B. the APA rule is that important words in titles are capitalised only within the text, not in the References section.  Only capitalise proper names and the first word after the colon or dash in a title in the References section.  The title of the journal and the issue number are italicised.
        ANSWER: 4. is correct.
        FEEDBACK: I'm afraid not.  Try again.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO Inoue, Y., Sakihara, K. and Gunji, A. et al. (2009, May). Reduced prefrontal activation during response inhibition in children with attention-deficit/hyperactivity disorder: A near infrared spectroscopy (NIRS) study. From 2nd International Congress on ADHD. From Childhood to Adult Disease, Vienna, Austria. In ADHD Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder, 1, 100. 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">There is one mistake in this entry into a References section. What is it?</font> 
        ANSWER: The date should come after the information about the Congress.
        FEEDBACK: No, the date's in the right place.Try again.
        ANSWER: There's no need to put in the Congress details.
        FEEDBACK: I think these details are helpful, so I'd leave them in.
        ANSWER: The important words in the titles should be capitalised.
        FEEDBACK: The APA, whose guidelines Psychology follow, like titles capitalised within the text, but not in the References section.  Try again.
        ANSWER: The title of the journal in which the study appears should be italicised.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  Italicising titles makes them immediately obvious, thus helping with quick identification.
        Task freetext difficulty 2
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4"><span style="font-weight: bold;">References</span><br /><br />SAMHSA, (2008). Results from the 2005 National Survey on Drug Use and Health: National findings. Retrieved March 10, 2010, from www.drugabusestatistics </font> 
    QUESTION 0 Should SAMHSA be written out in full in the References section, even if it has been written out in full when first mentioned in the text?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: Quite right.  In the References section it should read Substance Abuse and Mental Health Services Administration (SAMHSA).
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  In the References section it should read Substance Abuse and Mental Health Services Administration (SAMHSA).
        ANSWER: It doesn't matter.
        FEEDBACK: I'm afraid it does matter.  The point of the References section is that readers should be able, without effort, to see your source.  Writing out the name in full helps.
    QUESTION 1 There is another mistake in this reference.  What is it?
        ANSWER: 'Results from 2005 survey' etc. should be italicised.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not right.  Only the titles of books or journals should be italicised, not the titles of articles, reports or results.
        ANSWER: There should not be a capital letter after the colon.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not right.  APA style recommends a capital after a colon.
        ANSWER: The website URL should be given in full.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  Always put the URL in full.  This makes it very easy for the reader to look up the source.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">Huizink A.; Mulder E.; (2006) <span style="font-style: italic;">Maternal Smoking, Drinking or Cannabis Use during Pregnancy and Neurobehavioural and Cognitive Functioning in Human Offspring.</span> Neuroscience and Biobehavioural Reviews, 30, 24-41.<br /><br /></font><font size="4">Huizink, A., Mulder E., (2006). Maternal smoking, drinking or cannabis use during pregnancy and neurobehavioural and cognitive functioning in human offspring. <span style="font-style: italic;">Neuroscience and Biobehavioural Reviews</span>, <span style="font-style: italic;">30,</span> 24-41.</font><br /><font size="4"><br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Which of these references is correctly formatted?
        ANSWER: Example 1.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not right.  There are formatting mistakes in the authors' names;  the name of the article should be neither italicised nor capitalised; the name of the journal should be italicised;  the journal issue number should be italicised.
        ANSWER: Example 2.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  The problems with Example 1 are numerous:  formatting mistakes in the authors' names;  the name of the article should be neither italicised nor capitalised; the name of the journal should be italicised;  the journal issue number should be italicised.
        Task freetext difficulty 2
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">Piaget, J. The Grasp of Consciousness, Action and Concept in the Young Child, Routledge &amp; Keagan Paul Ltd., London.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 There is something missing from this entry.  What is it?
        ANSWER: The issue number.
        FEEDBACK: No, not that.  This is clearly a book entry.
        ANSWER: The date of publication.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  It's really important to put that in, directly after the author's name.
        ANSWER: The country of publication.
        FEEDBACK: No, the city is enough.
    QUESTION 1 Is the title properly formatted?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: No - the title of the book should be italicised.  This makes the title immediately apparent to the reader.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: That's correct.  The title of the book should be italicised.  This makes the title immediately apparent to the reader.
    QUESTION 2 There is something wrong with the formatting of the publisher and place of publication.  What is it?
        ANSWER: There should be no ampersand between 'Routledge' and 'Keagan'.  The 'and' should be written in full.
        FEEDBACK: No - if there is an ampersand in the publisher's printed name, that is how it should appear in your reference.
        ANSWER: The city of publication should come before the publisher, and be separated from the publisher's name with a colon.
        FEEDBACK: That's correct.
        ANSWER: We need 'UK', not London.
        FEEDBACK: No - the city of publication is correct.  You might put in the name of the country if there might be a misunderstanding, i.e. Manchester, New Hampshire (to differentiate from Manchester in England).
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO  <font size="4"><span style="font-weight: bold;">References</span><br /><br /></font><font size="4">Gottesman and Shields, </font><font size="4">Schizophrenia and Genetics: A Twin Vantage Point, (1972) New York and London.<br />The Encyclopaedia of Psychology, http://www.psychology.org/<br /><br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Are these references in the correct order?
        ANSWER: Yes.  They are in alphabetical order.
        FEEDBACK: That's incorrect.  If there is no named author, the name of the book, publication or website comes first, but we ignore the 'The' and take the first letter of the first important word, in this case E. 
        ANSWER: No.  They are not in alphabetical order.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.   If there is no named author, the name of the book, publication or website comes first, but we ignore the 'The' and take the first letter of the first important word, in this case E.
    QUESTION 1 In the book reference, is the title of the book properly formatted?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not right.  The title of the book should be italicised.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: That's right. The title of the book should be italicised.
    QUESTION 2 In the book reference, is the date in the right place?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: No, it's not.  The date should come after the authors.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  The date should come after the authors.
    QUESTION 3 There's something missing from the book reference.  What is it?
        ANSWER: The span of pages.
        FEEDBACK: No.  Page spans are needed for journal references but not for books.  If you directly quote from a book, you need the page number in your in-text reference.  In the References section, for a chapter in an edited book (i.e. where there is one editor, with different authors contributing different chapters) you should put down the chapter number.  The same goes for a particularly entry in a reference book.
        ANSWER: The publisher's name.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  Although we have the date, we need the publisher's name.  That will help the reader, since often books are published more than once, and by different publishing firms.
    QUESTION 4 In the web example, should the title of the web-book be italicised?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: That's correct.  Titles of books put onto the web should be italicised.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: That's incorrect.  Titles of books put onto the web should be italicised.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4"><span style="font-weight: bold;">References</span><br /><br />Grant, A. A. and Smith, G., Have we gone soft? In G. Forbes, A. Alan (Eds.) <span style="font-style: italic;">Mollycoddling: A Phenomenon</span>. London: A Publishing Company. <br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Is this entry for an edited collection correctly formatted?
        ANSWER: No.  There are several formatting errors.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not right.  This is perfect APA style!
        ANSWER: Yes.  Everything is correct.
        FEEDBACK: Correct!  This is perfect APA style.
    Writing activity 12. Avoiding wrong/poorly chosen words and phrases
        Task selectcat difficulty 2
        Task wordclick difficulty 1
        Task wordclick difficulty 2
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">One major theory is the trait theory, in regards to personality. Trait theory is an effective approach since personality is so complex that creating a method to be 100% accurate is all but impossible.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 Which words/phrases are wrong or wrongly put together here?
        ANSWER: effective
        FEEDBACK: No, this is fine.  Effective means 'to have an effect'.   (If you thought this should be 'affective', that would be incorrect.  Affective is a word meaning 'arousing the emotions'.
        ANSWER: creating a method to be 100% accurate
        FEEDBACK: Well done.  You don't 'create a method to be', you 'create a method that is'.  When you read, take note of these phrases and try to express them correctly.
        ANSWER: in regards to
        FEEDBACK: Well done.  This is a common mistake that irritates markers no end.  The expression is not 'in regard to'.  It could be 'WITH regard to'.  The example sentence would read much better as 'Regarding personality, one major theory is trait theory'.
