    Writing activity 18. Formatting (font, line spacing etc.)
    Writing activity 24. Introduction: mini-project
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO  <font size="4">Which of the following sub-sections should be found in an introduction? You can pick more than one.</font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4"><br /></font> 
        ANSWER: Background to the question.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  This should be the start of your introduction.
        ANSWER: The reason you are asking the question.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  You must provide a justification for your experiment.
        ANSWER: All the work done on this question so far.
        FEEDBACK: Not ALL the work, just the most relevant work.  If there is large quantity of literature, you must choose which you feel is the most important/relevant to your experiment.
        ANSWER: A brief description of the method you have chosen to use.
        FEEDBACK: No:  this is not the place to describe your method, even briefly.  Wait for the Method section.  This follows the introduction.
        ANSWER: The hypothesis.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  We need to know exactly what you hope your experiment will support or not support.
    QUESTION 1 Should the introduction be divided into sections, with headings and/or bullet points?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: That's not correct.  The introduction should be written in plain prose.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: That's correct.  The introduction should be written in plain prose.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">Mini-project title: <span style="font-weight: bold;">A comparison of mnemonic strategies for aiding memory</span><br /><br />Here is a list of hypotheses for this title. Which one is the best and why?</font><br /><br /><font size="4">1. It is predicted that use of mnemonics will increase memory.<br />2. It is predicted that there will be a difference in the number of words recalled by participants using different mnemonics, due to the way the memory encodes verbal information. </font><br /><font size="4">3. It is predicted that there will be a difference in the number of words recalled by participants using two different mnemonics and also that both mnemonics conditions will produce better recall in participants than the recall of participants using no strategy.</font><br /><br /><font size="2">Acknowledgment: Paul Bishop, 2008, Report Writing Guide, http://portal.psy.gla.ac.uk/</font><br />
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">Read the text then answer the question(s).</font> 
        ANSWER: Hypothesis 1 is the best.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  This hypothesis is too vague.  It needs more detail.
        ANSWER: Hypothesis 2 is the best.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  This hypothesis contains information about the interpretation of the results - i.e. 'due to the way the memory encodes verbal reasoning'.  A hypothesis should predict the results and nothing else.  Not the best choice.
        ANSWER: Hypothesis 3 is the best.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  There are two hypotheses here.  They provide direct predictions about the data that can be tested by statistical analysis.  This is the best choice.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">What is the main purpose of an introduction?<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">Read the text then answer the question(s).</font> 
        ANSWER: To provide background history to the experiment.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again!
        ANSWER: To outline how the experiment is going to be carried out.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again!
        ANSWER: To show why your experiment is important and how it fits in with previous research.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  This is the main purpose of the introduction.  Remember:  you are conducting an experiment, not writing a history book.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4"><font size="4" style="font-weight: bold;">Mini project title:</font><br /><br /><span style="font-weight: bold;">An investigation into the relationship between paranormal beliefs and anthropomorphism in pets.</span><br /><br />1. Schizotypical personality disorder is relatively uncommon: the prevalence is estimated to be less than one percent (Davison, Neale &amp; Kring, 2004) and it is often comorbid with a number of personality disorders.<br /><br />2. The relationship between paranormal beliefs, magical ideation and schizopty has been extensively investigated, especially after the creation of the Magical Ideation (MI) Scale by Eckblad and Chapman in 1983. <br /><br /></font><font size="4">3. Superstitious, magical and paranormal beliefs are theoretically linked as a form of cognitive confusion between the key features of mental, physical and biological entities and processes (Lindeman &amp; Aarnio, 2007). Therefore anthropomorphic tendencies may be considered a form of superstitious or paranormal belief and </font><font size="4">a practical study to test the theory was a logical next step.</font><br />
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">Here are three sentences from an introduction. Two are out of place, one is spot-on. Which sentence is spot-on, and why?</font> 
        ANSWER: 1 is spot-on because it cites a source and provides information.
        FEEDBACK: It does indeed do both those things, but read the title of the mini-project.  The passage and the title may be related, but this relationship is not pointed out, so the information, whilst correct, is irrelevant. 
        ANSWER: 2 is spot-on because it links anthropomorphism and the paranormal. 
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Passage 2 does link anthropomorphism and the paranormal but in a vague way.  Vague is never good in a project report.
        ANSWER: 3 is spot-on because it links the paranormal and anthropomorphism and cites a relevant study.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  Passage 3 links all the elements of the project together and provides a rationale for the experiment.  This is exactly what the introduction should do.
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Mini-project title:</span><br /><br />Anxiety as a factor in task time-prediction distortions.<br /><br />Hypothesis.<br /><br />1. The higher the anxiety level, the longer the amount of time predicted to complete a given task.<br />2. There is no relationship between anxiety levels and the amount of time predicted to complete a given task.<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Which of these hypotheses is correctly structured?
        ANSWER: Both.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.   Try again.
        ANSWER: Hypothesis 2.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  Hypothesis 2 is a 'null hypothesis', i.e. it proposes a default position - in this case that there is no relationship between the phenomena being observed.  You should not include details of a null hypothesis in your report.
        ANSWER: Hypothesis 1.
        FEEDBACK: Hyothesis 1 is correct.  The second hypothesis is a null hypothesis, i.e. it proposes a default position, in this case that there is no relationship between the phenomena being observed.  You should not include details of a null hypothesis in your report.
        Task freetext difficulty 2
    Writing activity 25. Method: mini-project
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">Can you answer the following questions?</font> 
    QUESTION 0 Should the Method section be written in bullet points?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  The Methods section needs to be written in continuous prose.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: That's correct.  The Methods section needs to be written in continuous prose.
        ANSWER: It's up to you.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right, I'm afraid!  The Methods section needs to be written in continuous prose.
    QUESTION 1 Should the Method section be divided into sections and if so, how many?
        ANSWER: No.  The Method section should just run straight through.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  The Method section should be divided into four sections:  design; participants; materials/stimuli; and procedure.
        ANSWER: Yes.  The Method section should be divided into four sections.
        FEEDBACK: That's correct.  The Method section should be divided into four sections:  design; participants; materials/stimuli; and procedure.
        ANSWER: It's up to the writer.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right, I'm afraid.  The Method section should be divided into four sections:  design; participants; materials/stimuli; and procedure.  That way, you know you've covered everything.
    QUESTION 2 What tense should you use when writing the procedure sub-section of a Method section?
        ANSWER: Present.
        FEEDBACK: That's incorrect.  Try again.
        ANSWER: Future.
        FEEDBACK: That's incorrect.  Try again.
        ANSWER: Past.
        FEEDBACK: That's correct.  The procedure sub-section gives details of what happened in the experiment, and since the experiment is over, the procedure section should be written in the past tense.
        Task freetext difficulty 1
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Method<br /><br />Design:<br /><br />Participants were split into two conditions and give a verbal memory task. In condition 1, 12 participants were told to use the counting mnemonic to remember the words. It was not known whether English was all the participants' first language, and this may have had some bearing on how quickly they performed the task. In condition 2, 12 participants used the loci mnemonic. One participant spoke aloud, although he had been instructed to memorize the given words in silence. The dependent measure was the number of correctly recalled words. <br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 There are two different mistakes in this design sub-section of a Method section.   What are they?
        ANSWER: We don't need the dependent measure.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  How the results were to be measured is part of the design.  Try again.
        ANSWER: We don't need the name of the mnemonics; in the design sub-section, it's enough to know that mnemonics were used.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Details are the meat of the design sub-section.  We do need the names of the mnemonics.
        ANSWER: We don't need any speculation, e.g. about first languages.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  Speculation - i.e. whether participants' first language affected the results - should be found in the Discussion section.  The Discussion section comes after the Results section of a mini-project.
        ANSWER: We don't need to know about the participant who spoke.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  That piece of information should come in the procedure sub-section, not the design section.  The procedure section tells the reader exactly what happened, so that the experiment could be repeated exactly.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Method<br /><br />Participants<br /><br />The participants were randomly chosen, and the ratio between men and women was 60/40. All were paid a flat fee of ?10 no matter how long they took to complete walking the circuit whilst talking on the mobile phone. They could speak to whoever they chose about any subject. The only information given was that they were taking part in an undergraduate experiment focusing on concepts of privacy in mobile phone use.<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 From this information, could you replicate this experiment exactly?
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  We'd need more information.
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  We need more information.
    QUESTION 1 Choose what is missing from the list below.  You can choose more than one item.
        ANSWER: The number of participants.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  This is crucial.  Without knowing the number of participants, we can neither replicate the experiment nor assess its value properly.
        ANSWER: What people chose to speak about.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  That might come into the discussion section, if that had a bearing on the results.
        ANSWER: How long the walking route was and how long it took most participants to complete the circuit.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  How long the route was (a measurement) would be part of the Design sub-section.  How long participants took to complete the walk should be listed in the Results section.
        ANSWER: How the participants were chosen.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  'Random' is fine, but how were they recruited?  Poster? Facebook?  In the street?
        ANSWER: The median age.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  We need to know the median age as well as the gender ratio.  This would help us if we needed to carry out the exact experiment again.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">Method<br /><br />Materials and Stimuli<br /><br />Three participants were given a questionnaire about their fruit eating habits; three were given a questionnaire about their vegetable eating habits.<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Does this materials and stimuli sub-section of a Methods Section adequate information?
        ANSWER: Yes.  It may be short, but it contains all the information needed.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Short is fine, but only if all the information needed is included.
        ANSWER: No.  It doesn't contain all the information needed.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  We don't have enough information here to replicate the experiment.
    QUESTION 1 If you don't think this Materials/Stimuli sub-section contains enough information, from the following choices, pick the ones that best represent what you feel should be included.  You can choose as many as you like.
        ANSWER: How many questions in each questionnaire?
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  How could we replicate this experiment without this information?
        ANSWER: What kind of questions were asked?
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  An example would be helpful.
        ANSWER: How long did it take each participant to complete the questionnaire?
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  This really describes what happened in the experiment, so should be in the Procedure sub-section.
        ANSWER: A summary of the written instructions.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  This is important.
        ANSWER: The colour ink in which the questions were printed.
        FEEDBACK: Only if this was pertinent to the experiment.
        ANSWER: How participants were expected to respond, i.e. multiple choice, rating out of 5, free text.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  This gives us a clear picture of the questionnaire.
        ANSWER: How participants responded - i.e. did they obey the instructions.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  How the participants responded would be part of the Procedure sub-section, not the Materials/Stimuli  sub-section.
        ANSWER: A description of the participants, i.e. how many males/females, ages and any other relevant information.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  This information would be placed in the Participants sub-section.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">To which parts of the Method section of a mini-project do these sentences belong?</font> 
    QUESTION 0 It is predicted that pet owners will show significantly more anthropomorphic tendencies than non pet owners.
        ANSWER: Participants.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  Try again.
        ANSWER: Design.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again.
        ANSWER: Materials/Stimuli
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.   Try again.
        ANSWER: Hypothesis.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  The phrase 'It is predicted' gives the game away.
    QUESTION 1 The average time taken by participants to complete the study was five minutes, just as it was designed to do.
        ANSWER: Design.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Don't be fooled by the word 'designed'.  Read the sentence again.  What is it telling you?  Try again!
        ANSWER: Participants.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  There is no description of the participants, only a description of their performance.
        ANSWER: Materials/Stimuli.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  We know nothing about the study, or the response it was soliciting, so this sentence could not come from a Materials/Stimuli sub-section.
        ANSWER: Procedure.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  The Procedure sub-section should tell us what actually happened during the experiment, which is what this sentence is doing.
