        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">Which of the following options is the best example of a Design sub-section of a Method section?<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Read the text then answer the question(s).<br /></font> 
        ANSWER: Participants were asked to score out all the instances of the letter 'e' in a Harry Potter text.  There are five dependent variables in this experiment and these were to be analysed using regression.
        FEEDBACK: Crucial information is missing here:  how long is the text?  What are the variables?  This is not a good choice.
        ANSWER: In a correlation designed experiment, participants were asked to score out all the instance of the letter 'e' in a short Harry Potter text.  The independent variable was the anxiety level of each participant.   There were three who scored highly on an anxiety ratio and two whose scores were much lower.  There were five dependent variables: the prediction of time taken to complete the task; the actual time taken to compete the task; the difference between the actual and predicted time; the prediction of instances of the letter 'e'; and the difference between the prediction and the actual number of e's.  
        FEEDBACK: This choice includes some information that is misplaced:  the anxiety scores should be in the Results section.  Not the best choice for the Design sub-section of the Method section.
        ANSWER: In a correlation designed experiment, participants were asked to score out all the instance of the letter 'e' in a short Harry Potter text.  The independent variable was the anxiety level of each participant.   There were five dependent variables: the prediction of time taken to complete the task; the actual time taken to compete the task; the difference between the actual and predicted time; the prediction of instances of the letter 'e'; and the difference between the prediction and the actual number of e's.
        FEEDBACK: This paragraph is full of information, but apropos the Harry Potter text, how short is short?  This kind of information would be crucial if the test were to be replicated.  Not the best choice.
        ANSWER: In a correlation designed experiment, participants were asked to score out all the instance of the letter 'e' in a 552 word text taken from the first page of Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone.   The independent variable was the anxiety level of each participant.  There were five dependent variables: the prediction of time taken to complete the task; the actual time taken to compete the task; the difference between the actual and predicted time; the prediction of instances of the letter 'e'; and the difference between the prediction and the actual number of e's.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  This is the best choice.  We have lots of information here, all of it relevant to the design of the experiment.  Incidentally, the Harry Potter book title should be italicised (see section of this site on italics), but this computer programme won't allow it!
    Writing activity 26. Results: mini-project
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Can you answer the following questions?</font> 
    QUESTION 0 What should the first sentence of your Results section contain?
        ANSWER: An outline of the raw statistics.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again.
        ANSWER: The inferential statistics.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again.
        ANSWER: A restatement of the hypothesis/es.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  This is extremely helpful to the reader.
        ANSWER: A summary of the results, which will then be expanded.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again.
    QUESTION 1 What is the second step to take in your Results section?
        ANSWER: A summary of the results, for future expansion.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again.
        ANSWER: An account of how you have treated the raw data.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  You need to give an overview not, I repeat NOT, of the raw data itself, but of how it was prepared for analysis, e.g. if a total score was used, if a partial score was used, if some data was discarded altogether.
        ANSWER: A description of the raw data.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Raw data goes should be placed in an Appendix.  There's a difference between presenting raw data (e.g. the individual scores for each participant) and describing how the raw data has been treated (e.g. if the total number of questions answered by participants have been included, or only some; whether all scores below 5 were discarded).
    QUESTION 2 Should the Results section be written in bullet points or continuous prose?
        ANSWER: Continuous prose.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  You may want to use bullet points within your prose, but the Results section should be a passage of text, plus clearly labelled graphs and tables if appropriate.
        ANSWER: Bullet points.
        FEEDBACK: That's incorrect.  You may want to use bullet points within your prose, but the Results section should be a passage of text, plus clearly labelled graphs and tables if appropriate.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO  <font size="4">An independent t-test compared aspirational social comparison scores for males and females and revealed that males scored higher than females on ASC, and this difference was significant.<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Is this t-test report complete?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  There's quite a lot missing.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  There's quite a lot missing.
    QUESTION 1 If you think things are missing, from the list below, choose what those things are.  You can choose more than one from the list.
        ANSWER: The acronym for 'aspirational social comparison'.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  When we see ASC later in the text, it's not clear what this is.
        ANSWER: The total number of participants in the experiment.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  That number should come in the Participants sub-section of the Method section.
        ANSWER: The data, e.g. (M=47, SD=3.2) before 'males scored higher than females'.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  This is the Results section.  We need hard data.
        ANSWER: The data for the females.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  It would look very odd to give only the male data.
        ANSWER: A quick overview of what ASC is.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  This should have been included in, as appropriate, either your introduction or your Method section.  The Results section should only contain results.
        ANSWER: The result of the t-test in the correct format, e.g. t(38)=6.8, p<.05'.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  We need to see the report of the t-test in the correct format.
    QUESTION 2 Is there anything else missing?
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Read the text carefully again.
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  This independent t-test is two-tailed, i.e. it relates to distributions other than the normal.
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO  1. Data set out in appropriately headed horizontal rows and vertical columns, with the whole thing clearly labelled. <br />2. Data provided through graphs, maps, pie-charts, diagrams, photographs.<br /> 
    QUESTION 0 Does sentence 1 describe a table or a figure?
        ANSWER: Table.
        FEEDBACK: Correct. 
        ANSWER: Figure.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  A figure refers to graphs, maps, diagrams, photographs or pie-charts.  A table is set out in appropriately headed rows and columns, with the whole thing clearly labelled.
    QUESTION 1 Should figures and tables be numbered as well as labelled?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  Figures and tables are numbered sequentially.  Since they are different ways of presenting data, their numerical sequence should be kept separate:  i.e. Table 1, Table 2, Figure 1, Figure 2.  
        ANSWER: No.  You can choose either a label or a figure.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not right.  Figures and tables are numbered and labelled.  The number sequences for each should be kept separate:  i.e. Table 1, Table 2, Figure 1, Figure 2.
    QUESTION 2 Do tables supplement or duplicate the text?
        ANSWER: Supplement.
        FEEDBACK: That's correct.  If you find yourself simply repeating, in the text, all the information to be found in the table, ask yourself if the table is really necessary.  A table should provide detailed information not provided in the text.  The text refers to the table:  it does not repeat the information.
        ANSWER: Duplicate:  i.e. they provide the same information but in a different form.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  If you find yourself simply repeating, in the text, all the information to be found in the table, ask yourself if the table is really necessary.  A table should provide detailed information not provided in the text.  The text refers to the table: it does not repeat the information.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO  Here are some Table labels. Can you pick the best one? 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4"><br /> </font> 
        ANSWER: Relation between boys and exam performance.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  I think this is too general.  It doesn't tell us what the data represents, e.g. exam scores or anxiety levels, etc.  A label needs to be more specific.
        ANSWER: Average performance of boys in 6th Year studying History, Maths and Psychology in preliminary examinations (prelims) conducted three months prior to the exam date.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  This is too detailed.  The headings within the Table will provide much of this information.  A label needs to provide a clear, concise overview.
        ANSWER: Average performance scores of 6th year boys in prelims.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  This is clear.  The headings within the Table will supply the rest of the information.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO  <font size="4">The following are descriptions of different types of figure. Can you fit the descriptions to the type of figure? <br /><br /><font size="2">Acknowledgment: <span style="font-style: italic;">Publication Manual of the American Psychological Association</span> (2002), p.151</font><br /></font><br />
    QUESTION 0 This type of figure displays the relationship between two quantitative indices or between a continuous quantitative variable (usually displayed as the y axis) and groups of subjects displayed along the x axis.  Is the figure a graph or a chart?
        ANSWER: Graph.
        FEEDBACK: That's correct.
        ANSWER: Chart.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not right.  A chart generally displays nonquantitative information, such as the flow of subjects through a process, e.g. flow charts.
    QUESTION 1 What do we call a figure that displays spatial information?
        ANSWER: A drawing.
        FEEDBACK: No, not a drawing.  A drawing shows information pictorially.
        ANSWER: A map.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  A map shows spatial information.
