    Writing activity 27. Discussion: mini-project
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">To conclude, the results of this study indicate a number of relationships. First, a significant positive correlation between anthropomorphism and paranormal belief scales was found, although only partial support for pet ownership having a significant effect. A significant difference does exist between the anthropomorphic tendency scores of non pet-owners and pet-owners, with pet-owners scoring significantly higher. However, the difference between non pet-owners and pet-owners in paranormal belief scores is non-significant.<br /><br />A number of design faults were noted during the running of this experiment:<br /></font>
<ul>
  <li><font size="4">participants missed out questions</font></li>
  <li><font size="4">no research was done into the order of the questions (e.g. some questions may have been 'leading')</font></li>
  <li><font size="4">participants were not screened for pre-existing beliefs</font></li>
</ul><font size="4"><br /><br />Future research should concentrate on rectifying design problems. In addition, the anthropomorphic scale used in this study was far from ideal, since it measure how valuable a pet was as a family member rather than the attribution of human characteristics.<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 On a scale of 1 to 5, with 1 the lowest and 5 the highest mark, how would you mark this introduction?
        ANSWER: 5
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again!
        ANSWER: 4
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again!
        ANSWER: 3.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again!
        ANSWER: 2.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again.
        ANSWER: 1.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  The discussion should be a really interesting part of your mini-project.  Not quite the case here.
    QUESTION 1 What is wrong with the first paragraph?  You can choose more than one item.
        ANSWER: Nothing.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again.
        ANSWER: It's just a repeat of the results.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  It repeats the results without either discussing them or relating them to the hypothesis/es.  
        ANSWER: It should begin by stating the hypothesis.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not right.  A RESTATEMENT of the hypothesis should be made at the beginning of the Results section.  What we should be told is whether the results SUPPORT` or DON'T SUPPORT the hypothesis/es.
        ANSWER: There's no mention of other research.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  Part of the discussion is to relate your experiment to other research findings and theoretical models.  Questions to be asked include:  do my findings agree or disagree with published research? If there are major differences, how can this be explained?
    QUESTION 2 Should the second item - design faults - be displayed in bullet points?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  The discussion should be written in continuous prose.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  The discussion should be presented in continuous prose.
    QUESTION 3 How would you describe the third paragraph, which concentrates on future research? 
        ANSWER: Comprehensive.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  I think there's lots more to say.
        ANSWER: Precise.
        FEEDBACK: It is precise, but is it interesting?
        ANSWER: Unimaginative.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  It's too easy just to say 'tighten up the method'.  Whilst some methodological errors only come to light once the experiment has begun, others - in this case, the unsatisfactory nature of on of the marking scales - could have been forseen.   This type of discussion might well bring your mark down.
        ANSWER: Adequate.
        FEEDBACK: I don't agree.  The passage doesn't really discuss, it just makes some statements.
