INTRO  <font size="4">Mini-project title:<br /><br />Time estimation and anxiety.<br /><br />Which of the following would be the best first lines for the Discussion section? All the examples have explanations, so it's worth scrolling through them all even if your first selection agrees with ours.<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Read the text, then answer the question(s).</font> 
        ANSWER: Time estimation, and the effects of anxiety on it, is an interesting area of study.
        FEEDBACK: This is a superfluous sentence.  It adds nothing to the Discussion section.  There's no need for the kind of introduction this is clearly intended to be.  Not the best option.
        ANSWER: Over-estimation of time was linked to exam-related anxiety in 90% of our study participants, a finding that supported our hypothesis that time estimation and exam-related anxiety are related. 
        FEEDBACK: This is a clear statement of results, and linked straight to the hypothesis.  A good opening to the Discussion section.
        ANSWER: There are many theories and observations on the possible determinants of exam-related anxiety, Moneta and Spada cited motivational factors in their 2009 study.
        FEEDBACK: It's good to have a reference, but this opening of the Discussion section reads more like a general introduction, so is not the best choice.  The reference should be directly linked to your hypothesis and results, e.g. This study's results suggest that exam-related anxiety is associated with motivation, which supports the findings of Moneta and Spada's 2009 study.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Mini-project title<br /><br />Does posture affect the Body Gestalt effect in imitation?</font><br /> 
    QUESTION 0 Which of the following options are the best concluding lines for the Discussion section?  All the options have explanations, so even if you agree with us first time, it's worth scrolling through them all.
        ANSWER: Suggestions for further research should include further analysis of Block B, to test whether information from the face is used in the Body Gestalt, or only information from the hands.
        FEEDBACK: This is a good concluding line, which suggests ways of furthering research rather than just correcting faults in the mini-project methodology.  The best option on offer here.
        ANSWER: This study was limited to 11 participants and this might have had significant effects on the results.  More participants would give more accurate results.
        FEEDBACK: This is an old stand-by!  In nearly all samples, larger studies would be better.  We're looking for something a little more imaginative.  
        ANSWER: The Body Gestalt is a vital area of study, since understanding and predicting the actions of others greatly impacts on societal cohesion.  Further work can only be welcome.
        FEEDBACK: These lines read more like the end of an essay than the end of the Discussion section of a mini-project.  The same style does not work for everything.   The end of the Discussion section of a mini-project needs to be factual and precise.  This is not the best choice.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO  <font size="4">Mini-project title<br /><br />Rain as a catalyst for depression</font><br /><br /><font size="2">(The example has been adapted. Don't quote it.)</font><br /> 
    QUESTION 0 Which of the following options best links the mini-project to previous research and theories?  
        ANSWER: Our findings support the findings of Grant (2010), who found that rain and depression are causally linked.  Our findings do not support Smith (2010) that rain and depression appear to be causally linked but this is only perception, not fact. 
        FEEDBACK: It is not enough just to say that the mini-project supports or does not support other studies.  You must say why or why not, e.g. Our hypothesis supports Grant (2010), by showing that during long periods of rain, levels of depression increase in men who work outside as well as in women who work in offices. 
        ANSWER: Our results show that depression amongst women working in offices is linked to rain, thus expanding on Grant (2010), who found that rain increased levels of depression in men working outside.  However, Grant's study was limited to men over 45, and age is also a factor in depression (Prince et al., 1997).
        FEEDBACK: Here, the mini-project's findings and other research are well linked, with reasons given.  This is the best option.
        ANSWER: Our study supported Grant (2010) but was not truly comparable because we did not ask the gender or age of participants.
        FEEDBACK: This more or less says that your study is worthless.  Not a good thing to say!  If you are aware of design flaws, making the flaws the focus of your discussion will not help.  Find some way round the flaws.  For example, research different studies.  Always make sure that your Discussion section is valuable, even if it doesn't have quite the value you hoped.
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO Discussion<br /><br />This study supports the hypothesis that perceptions of adulthood are directly linked to perceptions of responsibility (68% of teenagers; 69% of people in their 20s; 90% of people in mid-life). The study was divided equally by gender, with 30 male participants and 30 female, and the participants came from a wide variety of different backgrounds and cultures, so the findings seem robust.<br /> 
    QUESTION 0 There is a clear error in this Discussion section.  What is it?
        ANSWER: 'Robust' is an inappropriate word.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  If your findings are clear and you feel your method is rock solid, then 'robust' seems a very appropriate word.
        ANSWER: Statements should be made about the results, but figures should not be included. 
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  It's enough to say that your findings support your hypothesis.  You should discuss the meaning of your results, but not repeat your results. 
        ANSWER: A Discussion section should start with a more general sentence, leading in to the hypothesis.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree. By the time we've reached the Discussion section, the reader will be familiar with the focus of the project.  No introduction is needed.
    QUESTION 1 What should come next?
        ANSWER: More about the method.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again.
        ANSWER: More about the participants.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Try again.
        ANSWER: More about other studies in the same field.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  Your report should be set the context of, and compared with, other studies in this field.
    QUESTION 2 How should your Discussion end?
        ANSWER: With a grand flourish.
        FEEDBACK: Grand flourishes are really for essays.
        ANSWER: With a restatement of your main findings and important points raised.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  The reader of your report should, at the close of the Discussion section, be able to say exactly what your findings were, and already curious as to what further studies might reveal.
        ANSWER: With a discussion of the study's potential problems.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  That would leave a very negative impression.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO  <font size="4">1. Gender played a significant role (t(79)=7.07, p&lt;0.05) with women scoring higher than men.<br />2. The greater percentage of women participants may have affected the results, since women are statistically more likely to go with a child to an Accident and Emergency unit.<br />3. The proximity of Accident and Emergency units to residential areas always stirs up passionate debate.<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Which of these sentences is appropriate for the Discussion section?
        ANSWER: Sentence 1.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree. The raw results should be in the Results section. 
        ANSWER: Sentence 2.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  Sentence 2 is discussing the shortcomings of the method, which is appropriate.  
        ANSWER: Sentence 3.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  This sentence would be a good start to the introduction but is unnecessary in the Discussion section.
