    Writing activity 10.  Sentence fragments
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">1. The marginalisation of the traditional middle classes displays the negative aspects of modernity.<br />2. Leading to intense disillusionment as modernity delivers nothing that progress promised.<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">In the following text, which is the fragment and which is the complete sentence?</font> 
        ANSWER: Sentence 1 is a complete sentence.  Sentence 2 is the fragment.
        FEEDBACK: That's correct.  Sentence 1 has a main verb: 'displays'.  Sentence 2 is a sub-clause.  We're left asking 'what is leading to etc.'  This sub-clause does contain a verb - 'delivers' - but this verb is attached  something within the sub-clause.  Sentence 2 has no main clause, i.e. something that tell us what it is that leads to intense disillusionment. 
        ANSWER: Sentence 1 is the fragment. Sentence 2 is a complete sentence.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  Sentence 1 has a main verb: 'displays'.  Sentence 2 is a sub-clause.  We're left asking 'what is leading to etc.'  This sub-clause does contain a verb - 'delivers' - but this verb is attached  something within the sub-clause.  Sentence 2 has no main clause, i.e. something that tell us what it is that leads to intense disillusionment.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">1. Country towns miss state funding.<br />2. Whereas cities have tended to thrive in a market economy, attracting foreign investment as well as domestic funds (Ferry 2004: 3). <br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">In the following text, which is the fragment and which is the complete sentence?</font> 
        ANSWER: Sentence 1 is the fragment and sentence 2 is a complete sentence.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  Sentence 1 has a subject - country towns - and a verb - miss.  Sentence 2 is a sub-clause.  The word 'whereas' tells us that this clause is adding information to a main clause which will come later, only in this example the main clause never comes.  We are left asking where the comparison flagged up by 'whereas' might be.
        ANSWER: Sentence 1 is a complete sentence and sentence 2 is the fragment.
        FEEDBACK: That's correct.  Sentence 1 has a subject - country towns - and a verb - miss.  Sentence 2 is a sub-clause.  The word 'whereas' tells us that this clause is adding information to a main clause which will come later, only in this example the main clause never comes.  We are left asking where the comparison flagged up by 'whereas' might be.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">1. The main way Labour managed to reduce child poverty with its tax and benefit system.<br />2. Labour reduced child poverty.<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">In the following text, which is the fragment and which is the complete sentence?</font> 
        ANSWER: Sentence 1 is a complete sentence. Sentence 2 is the fragment.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  The subject of sentence 1 is 'the main way' not 'Labour', so 'the main way' needs a verb of its own, e.g. 'The main way Labour managed to reduce child poverty WAS with its tax and benefit system.'  Sentence 2 has a subject - Labour - and a verb - reduced.  That's all you need for a complete sentence.
        ANSWER: Sentence 1 is the fragment and sentence 2 is a complete sentence.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  The subject of sentence 1 is 'the main way' not 'Labour', so 'the main way' needs a verb of its own, e.g. 'The main way Labour managed to reduce child poverty WAS with its tax and benefit system.'  Sentence 2 has a subject - Labour - and a verb - reduced.  That's all you need for a complete sentence.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">1. Most historians are agreed that women faced barriers to employment.<br />2. Notably the marriage barrier, which mean that married women were not encouraged to work.</font><br /> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">In the following text, which is the fragment and which is the complete sentence?</font> 
        ANSWER: Sentence 1 is the fragment.  Sentence 2 is a complete sentence.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  Sentence 1 has a subject - historians - and a verb attached to the subject - are agreed.  Sentence 2 is a sub-clause, i.e. it adds information to a main subject, only in this example there is no main subject.  The verb - were not encouraged -  is attached to 'married women', but 'married women' are part of the sub-clause.  They are not the main subject of the sentence. 
        ANSWER: Sentence 1 is the complete sentence and sentence 2 is the fragment.
        FEEDBACK: That's right. Sentence 1 has a subject - historians - and a verb attached to the subject - are agreed.  Sentence 2 is a sub-clause, i.e. it adds information to a main subject, only in this example there is no main subject.  The verb - were not encouraged -  is attached to 'married women', but 'married women' are part of the sub-clause.  They are not the main subject of the sentence.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">1. However, the left was deeply divided and </font><font size="4">in some European societies </font><font size="4">could not form a significant bloc against the emerging fascist parties.<br />2. Leaving the way open for the rise of charismatic leaders who could unite people behind them.<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">In the following text, which is the fragment and which is the complete sentence?</font> 
        ANSWER: Sentence 1 is a fragment and sentence 2 is a complete sentence.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  Sentence 1 has a subject - the left - and a verb attached to that subject - was deeply divided.  Sentence 2 is a sub-clause.  It leaves us asking 'what was leaving the way' etc. 
        ANSWER: Sentence 1 is a complete sentence and sentence 2 is a fragment.
        FEEDBACK: That's correct.  Sentence 1 has a subject - the left - and a verb attached to that subject - was deeply divided.  Sentence 2 is a sub-clause.  It leaves us asking 'what was leaving the way' etc.
