    Writing activity 06. Punctuation - quotation marks
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task freetext difficulty 1
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO  <font size="4">Bivalves are &quot;among the commonest shelly components of beach sands throughout the world.&quot; (Benton and Harper, 2009, p. 332). Shallow infaunal bivalves burrow using their muscular &quot;foot&quot;. They burrow close to the surface so that their &quot;siphon&quot; may poke through the sediment. </font> 
    QUESTION 0 Are the quotation marks round the direct quote correctly formatted, including the placing of the full stop?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: That's not correct.  If a quotation is enclosed in a bigger sentence, the full stop should come after the closing quotation marks.  In this case, the full stop should come after the reference.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: That's correct.  If a quotation is enclosed in a bigger sentence, the full stop should come after the closing quotation marks.  In this case, the full stop should come after the reference.
    QUESTION 1 Should the words "foot" and "siphon" be enclosed in quotation marks?
        ANSWER: Yes.  This indicates that they are not real feet or siphons, but that these are simply terms we use.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  These words should not be enclosed in quotation marks.  Terms in Earth Science are used as real terms, otherwise everything would have to be in quotation marks.  Quotation marks should be used very very sparingly unless enclosing actual quotations.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: That's correct. These words should not be enclosed in quotation marks.  Terms in Earth Science are used as real terms, otherwise everything would have to be in quotation marks.  Quotation marks should be used very very sparingly unless enclosing actual quotations.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Bivalve molluscs are characterised by a &quot;calcareous shell that completely encloses the animal (Lapitus et al, 2006)&quot;.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 What is the matter with the formatting of this quotation?
        ANSWER: Nothing.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not right.  Try again.
        ANSWER: It should be enclosed in single quotation marks.
        FEEDBACK: No, in Earth Science we use double quotation marks.  Try again.
        ANSWER: The closing quotation mark should come after the full stop.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  When a direct quotation is incorporated into a sentence (rather than being a whole sentence in itself), the full stop comes after the closing quotation marks.
        ANSWER: The closing quotation marks should come before the opening bracket of the reference.
        FEEDBACK: That's correct.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO Bivalve molluscs could also be swimming, since &quot;swimming shells are usually equilateral but not equivalved. The lower (usually the left) valve is usually slightly larger (website 1)&quot;. 
    QUESTION 0 Are the quotation marks in this text correctly placed?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  Try again.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  The closing quotation marks should come before the reference.
