    Writing activity 15. Relevance of content to question
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title: </font><font size="4">Provide a general discussion on palaeoecology, including that of three of the fossil groups you have studied.<br /><br /><span style="font-weight: bold;">Introduction</span><br /><br />Palaeontology was a discipline which became a subject of much enthusiasm and research after the discovery of dinosaur bones in 19th century (Brenchley et al, 1998). In 1859, Darwin published his theory of evolution based on the many fossil examples that had been recently found (Press et al. 2004). Fossils are accepted as providing definitive proof of the process of evolution (Benton et al, 2009) and can also help in the assessment of the relative ages of sedimentary rocks. This was a technique realised in 1793 by William Smith (Press et al. 2004). Palaeoecology developed from this science of palaeontology. <br /><br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 If you had to mark this introduction out of 5 for relevance, how many marks would you give it? 
        ANSWER: 5
        FEEDBACK: I wouldn't give it 5.  The essay title specifically asks for a general discussion on palaeoecology and this example starts with palaeontology, causing the reader to wonder if the writer has misread the question.   So, although background information on palaeontology is interesting, and is not entirely irrelevant, it is misplaced.  Your introduction needs to get straight to the point - a brief description of palaeoecology, followed by a list of the fossil groups you are going to include.  The broader discussion of palaeoecology (as requested in the essay title) would come in the paragraph following the introduction, and in that paragraph, the information provided (which is very well referenced) would be relevant.  So - placing of information is just as important as the information itself. 
        ANSWER: 4.
        FEEDBACK: I wouldn't give it 4.  The essay title specifically asks for a general discussion on palaeoecology and this example starts with palaeontology, causing the reader to wonder if the writer has misread the question.   So, although background information on palaeontology is interesting, and is not entirely irrelevant, it is misplaced.  Your introduction needs to get straight to the point - a brief description of palaeoecology, followed by a list of the fossil groups you are going to include.  The broader discussion of palaeoecology (as requested in the essay title) would come in the paragraph following the introduction, and in that paragraph, the information provided (which is very well referenced) would be relevant.  So - placing of information is just as important as the information itself. 
        ANSWER: 3.
        FEEDBACK: I wouldn't give it 3.  The essay title specifically asks for a general discussion on palaeoecology and this example starts with palaeontology, causing the reader to wonder if the writer has misread the question.   So, although background information on palaeontology is interesting, and is not entirely irrelevant, it is misplaced.  Your introduction needs to get straight to the point - a brief description of palaeoecology, followed by a list of the fossil groups you are going to include.  The broader discussion of palaeoecology (as requested in the essay title) would come in the paragraph following the introduction, and in that paragraph, the information provided (which is very well referenced) would be relevant.  So - placing of information is just as important as the information itself. 
        ANSWER: 2.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  This low mark is because the essay title specifically asks for a general discussion on palaeoecology and this example starts with palaeontology, causing the reader to wonder if the writer has misread the question.   So, although background information on palaeontology is interesting, and is not entirely irrelevant, it is misplaced.  Your introduction needs to get straight to the point - a brief description of palaeoecology, followed by a list of the fossil groups you are going to include.  The broader discussion of palaeoecology (as requested in the essay title) would come in the paragraph following the introduction, and in that paragraph, the information provided (which is very well referenced) would be relevant.  So - placing of information is just as important as the information itself. .
        ANSWER: 1.
        FEEDBACK: I think it deserves slightly more than 1.  The low mark reflects the fact that the essay title specifically asks for a general discussion on palaeoecology and this example starts with palaeontology, causing the reader to wonder if the writer has misread the question.   So, although background information on palaeontology is interesting, and is not entirely irrelevant, it is misplaced.  Your introduction needs to get straight to the point - a brief description of palaeoecology, followed by a list of the fossil groups you are going to include.  The broader discussion of palaeoecology (as requested in the essay title) would come in the paragraph following the introduction, and in that paragraph, the information provided (which is very well referenced) would be relevant.  So - placing of information is just as important as the information itself.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title: What differences can we observe between oceanic plate separation and continental plate separation, and how do these movements fit into the theory of plate tectonics?<br /><br /><span style="font-weight: bold;">Introduction</span><br /><br />The theory of plate tectonics suggests that the lithosphere, which is the outer shell of Earth that encases the asthenosphere and whose crust is rigid, is not one continuous shell, but is broken into plates (Grotzinger et al, 2007). These plates can be divided into continental plates: for example, the North American plate (although it should be noted that continental plates are not the same size and shape as the continent after which they are named); and oceanic plates, the largest of which is the Pacific plate. These plates move and separate, causing observable features. This essay will look first at the features caused by oceanic plate separation and then the features caused by continental plate separation, and relate both to the theory of plate tectonics. <br /><br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Out of 5, with 1 being the lowest score, how many marks for relevance would you give this introduction?
        ANSWER: 1.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree. I think this introduction is clear, concise and relevant.  It relates directly to the essay title, provides relevant information and offers a precise essay structure. 
        ANSWER: 2.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree. I think this introduction is clear, concise and relevant.  It relates directly to the essay title, provides relevant information and offers a precise essay structure. 
