        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title: Discuss the value of fossils in biostratigraphy.<br /><br /><span style="font-weight: bold;">Introduction</span><br /><br />Fossils, the remnants of plants or animals that lived in a different era, form the core of biostratigraphy, the discipline which dates rocks from these fossil fragments. The first person to really work on fossils was William Smith, who lived from 1769-1839. He was a canal engineer, and through his work he began to see that different fossils were embedded in different rocks. His fascination with the fossils led him to be labelled the &quot;Father of English Geology&quot; (Wikipedia). It was he who published the first geological map of Britain, which illustrated his realisation that you could use fossils &quot;to match rocks across regions&quot; (Wikipedia). This did not gain him recognition at first, and he ended up in the debtors' jail as people copied his map and sold it cheaply. In the end, however, he was recognised and now merits a place in all the textbooks.<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 If you had to mark this introduction out of 5 for relevance, with 1 being the lowest and 5 being the highest, what mark would you give it?
        ANSWER: 5.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  The first sentence is excellent, but then the essay starts to drift.  It's good to mention William Smith, but you must relate his work to the essay title rather than go off on a tangent about his life.  Also, Wikipedia is not a good source of information for an academic essay.  Instead of a potted life of Smith, we need examples of groups of fossils to be discussed and a sentence telling us how the question of the value of the study of fossils will be addressed.
        ANSWER: 4.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  The first sentence is excellent, but then the essay starts to drift.  It's good to mention William Smith, but you must relate his work to the essay title rather than go off on a tangent about his life.  Also, Wikipedia is not a good source of information for an academic essay.  Instead of a potted life of Smith, we need examples of groups of fossils to be discussed and a sentence telling us how the question of the value of the study of fossils will be addressed.  That would all be much more relevant.
