        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title: Provide a general discussion on palaeoecology, including that of three of the fossil groups you have studied.</font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Read the following essay title, then choose the best introduction from the selection offered.</font> 
        ANSWER: Life on Earth underwent radical change in the middle of the Palaeozoic period. Lots of new species appeared in the sea, including trilobites, eurypterid and other invertebrates.  These replace species that had disappeared at the end of the Ordovician.  This essay will look at three groups of invertebrates, starting with bivalve molluscs.
        FEEDBACK: The essay title specifically asks firstly for a general discussion on palaeoecology.  This has been ignored, which is not a good sign.  We also need a list of the invertebrates to be discussed.  It's not clear whether all those mentioned are going to be included.  Altogether, this is a muddling introduction for the reader and would not gain good marks.
        ANSWER: Palaeoecology, or the study of ancient organisms and their relationship with the environments in which they lived, creates a clear picture of the world's earliest ecosystems through fossil records.   This essay will describe and discuss the variety of ways ancient sea organisms lived, interacted and adapted to their environments, using as illustrations trilobites, brachiopods, bivalve molluscs and corals.   Finally, the essay will assess the broader value of palaeoecology in helping us to understand how creatures from the past survived catastrophic events that might have been expected to wipe them out. 
        FEEDBACK: This introduction is clear and directly relates to the essay title.  The definition of palaeoecology is neatly inserted into the first sentence, and a broader discussion signposted for the end.  This is the best option.
        ANSWER: Shipman, P. (1981) describes palaeoecology as "the study of ancient ecosystems and the habits, lifestyles and interdependencies of the species in that ecosystem".  This defines palaeoecology as the study of ancient fossils in relation to their environments and how they lived thousands of years ago.  I shall discuss the palaeoecology of brachiopods, bivalve molluscs and corals.
        FEEDBACK: This introduction lists the creatures to be discussed, but the quotation at the start is wrongly inserted (see the section on 'excessive use of quotations' on this site) and there's not much point using a quote if you are then just going to repeat it in different words.   Despite the list, this is a poor option.
