INTRO <font size="4">Trilobites are an example of an extinct arthropod. Arthropods are essentially invertebrate creatures that have jointed limbs as well as segmented bodies. Trilobites first appeared in the early Cambrian period, 520 million years ago, and eventually disappeared about 250 milllion years ago during the Permian era.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 Is it necessary to put references into this type of text?
        ANSWER: No.  This type of text is clearly taken from a text book, so no reference is needed.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  You MUST reference your information so that a marker could, if necessary, look it up.  If the textbook has made a mistake, for example, you might lose marks if we cannot see that the mistake was not yours.
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  You MUST reference your information so that a marker could, if necessary, look it up.  Quite apart from referencing being essential to combat charges of plagiarism, if the textbook has made a mistake, for example, you might lose marks if we cannot see that the mistake was not yours.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO  <font size="4">Much of Earth's heat is released at these ridges (according to platetectonics.com). Heat rises and the convection cells in the form of magma flow create mid-oceanic ridges (ref. Grotzinginer and others in Understanding Earth). These structures are symmetrical about the vertical axis (as can be seen in figure 1 below). Formation of these structures is encouraged by ridge-pull and slab-pull (as discussed later).</font> 
    QUESTION 0 Is the second reference, (Grotzinger and others in Understanding Earth) correctly inserted and formatted? 
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  In Earth Science, we use the author/date system, so the reference should read (Grotzinger et al., 2007) with a corresponding, fuller entry on the references cited page.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  In Earth Science, we use the author/date system, so the reference should read (Grotzinger et al., 2007) with a corresponding, fuller entry on the references cited page.
        ANSWER: It doesn't matter.
        FEEDBACK: I'm afraid it does.  All scientists conform to an agreed referencing style for ease of checking out references.  In Earth Science, we use the author/date system, so the reference should read (Grotzinger et al., 2007) with a corresponding, fuller entry on the references cited page.
    QUESTION 1 Is the first reference (according to platetectonics.com) properly formatted and inserted?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  This reference should read (website 1), with a corresponding entry on the references cited page that gives the whole url line and date accessed.  As it stands, this reference is not only wrongly inserted, it is also much too vague to be any use.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  This reference should read (website 1), with a corresponding entry on the references cited page that gives the whole url line and date accessed.  As it stands, this reference is not only wrongly inserted, it is also much too vague to be any use.
        ANSWER: It doesn't matter.
        FEEDBACK: I'm afraid it does.  All scientists adhere to an agreed referencing system, for ease of checking out the references.  In the case of websites, we need (website 1) in the text, then a corresponding entry, giving the whole url line and date of access, on the references cited page.
    QUESTION 2 Is the third reference (as can be seen in Figure 1) properly inserted and formatted?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  We just need (Figure 1) or (Fig.1) here.  Do not litter your text with unnecessary words.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  We just need (Figure 1) or (Fig.1) here.  Do not litter your text with unnecessary words.
        ANSWER: It doesn't matter.
        FEEDBACK: I'm afraid it does, as littering your text with unnecessary words looks very unprofessional.  We need only (Figure 1) or (Fig.1) here.
    QUESTION 3 Is the fourth reference (as discussed later) properly inserted and formatted?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  This is almost always an unnecessary interjection.   How your discussion is structured should be clear from your introduction.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  This is almost always an unnecessary interjection.   How your discussion is structured should be clear from your introduction.
        ANSWER: It's fine in this context.
        FEEDBACK: I'd say that this is not correct. How your discussion is structured should be clear from your introduction, rendering this interjection unnecessary.
