    Writing activity 18. Observation, interpretation and evidence - understanding the difference
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">1) Nearly all species produce far more young than can survive to adulthood.<br /><br />2) Not every cod egg develops into a cod. <br /><br />3. Natural selection is daily and hourly scrutinising, throughout the world, every variation, even the slightest.<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Is sentence 1 observation, interpretation or evidence?
        ANSWER: 1 is interpretation.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  I'd say it was interpretation, since it is a supposition made after observation.
        ANSWER: 1 is observation.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.   I'd say it was interpretation, since it is a supposition made after observation.
        ANSWER: 1 is evidence.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree. I'd say it was interpretation, since it is a supposition made after observation.
    QUESTION 1 Is sentence 2 observation, interpretation or evidence?
        ANSWER: 2 is observation.
        FEEDBACK: I don't agree.  I'd say this was concrete evidence in support of sentence 1.
        ANSWER: 2 is interpretation.
        FEEDBACK: I don't agree.  I'd say this was concrete evidence in support of sentence 1.
        ANSWER: 2 is evidence.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  I'd say this was concrete evidence in support of sentence 1.
    QUESTION 2 Is sentence 3 observation, interpretation or evidence?
        ANSWER: 3 is observation.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  I'd say that 3 is interpretation, based on sentences 1 and 2 (observation and evidence).
        ANSWER: 3 is interpretation.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  I'd say that 3 is interpretation, based on sentences 1 and 2 (observation and evidence).
        ANSWER: 3 is evidence.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  I'd say that 3 is interpretation, based on sentences 1 and 2 (observation and evidence).
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO 1) The Archaeopteryx was a winged creature the size of a magpie, with clawed hands and feet.<br /><br />2) The Archaeopteryx has been hailed as proof of evolution in action.<br /><br />3) The claws suggest that the Archaeopteryx could climb trees. <br /> 
    QUESTION 0 Is sentence 1 observation, interpretation or evidence?
        ANSWER: Sentence 1 is observation.
        FEEDBACK: I'd say 1) was evidence, since it is a physical example being used to show the theory of evolution in action.
        ANSWER: Sentence 1 is interpretation.
        FEEDBACK: I'd say 1) was evidence, since it is s physical example being used to show the theory of evolution in action.
        ANSWER: Sentence 1 is evidence.
        FEEDBACK: I'd say that's right, since the physical example is being used to show the theory of evolution in action.
    QUESTION 1 Is sentence 2 observation, interpretation or evidence?
        ANSWER: Sentence 2 is observation.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  I'd say 2) was interpretation.  Evidence and observation are being interpreted to confirm a theory.
        ANSWER: Sentence 2 is interpretation.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  Evidence and observation are being interpreted to confirm a theory.
        ANSWER: Sentence 2 is evidence.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree. I'd say 2) was interpretation.  Evidence and observation are being interpreted to confirm a theory.
    QUESTION 2 Is sentence 3 observation, interpretation or evidence?
        ANSWER: Sentence 3 is observation.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  This is an interpretation of the morphology of this creature.  In geology, it can only be an observation if it is physically seen, so saying the Archaeopteryx has claws is observation, but suggesting they used them to climb trees is interpretation.
        ANSWER: Sentence 3 is interpretation.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  This is an interpretation of the morphology of this creature.  In geology, it can only be an observation if it is physically seen, so saying the Archaeopteryx has claws is observation, but suggesting they used them to climb trees is interpretation.
        ANSWER: Sentence 3 is evidence.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  This is an interpretation of the morphology of this creature.  In geology, it can only be an observation if it is physically seen, so saying the Archaeopteryx has claws is observation, but suggesting they used them to climb trees is interpretation.
