    QUESTION 0 There are two pairs of dashes in this text.  Which pair is used correctly?
        ANSWER: The first.
        FEEDBACK: That's incorrect.  The first pair of dashes clutters rather than clarifies the text.  This pair should be deleted.
        ANSWER: The second.
        FEEDBACK: This set is also not necessary but is not as intrusive as the first.  This pair of dashes could be left in without detriment to the text.<br />
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO 
<ol>
  <li>While Descartes and Darwin - perhaps the two most influential philosophers to discuss the subject - seem to favour the view that scientific/mechanical explanations cannot be applied directly to the workings of the mind, the arguments put forward - particularly those of Descartes - seem to be somewhat unsubstantiated.</li>
  <li>Descartes' dismissal of the mind - as something separate from the body - can now be viewed as rather backward - the study of biology being much more advanced these days.</li>
</ol> 
    QUESTION 0 In one of these examples, the dashes are used correctly.  Which example is it?
        ANSWER: 1.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  Here, the dashes help with the sense, telling us important things without interrupting the flow of the sentence, just as you might hear in speech.  If you remove the words inside the dashes, the sentence still makes sense.
        ANSWER: 2.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  Here, the dashes interrupt the sentence, since what the information enclosed between them is actually part of the sentence, not an aside.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">We use one word - 'gold', for example - to refer to a cluster of feature - shape, size, colour and movement.<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 There are three dashes in this text.  Which are used correctly?
        ANSWER: The first dash but not the second or third.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  The first dash is used correctly, but ONLY if paired with the second dash.  These dashes are used to enclose a comment that is important, but essentially an aside, as you might use in speech.
        ANSWER: The second dash only.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  The second dash is correct but ONLY if paired with the second dash.  These dashes are used to enclose a comment that is important, but essentially an aside, as you might use in speech.
        ANSWER: The third dash only.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  The third dash is wrongly used.   It should be replaced by a colon, which would be the right way to introduce a list.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">There can be no doubt that a large percentage of the planet's population base their morality on religion - the word of God. People put their faith in an all-power, omniscient God - and through the church ad clergy discover and obey His will.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 Which of the two dashes in this text are properly used?
        ANSWER: The first.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  A dash is fine here, as the phrase 'the word of God' adds a flourish to the sentence.   The dash could be replaced by a colon, which would stand in place of the words 'that is to say'.  But a dash does a good job here.
        ANSWER: The second.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  This dash has no purpose at all.  If you take it out, it is not missed.  Indeed, the sentence flows better without it.  Try not to include punctuation just for the sake of it: punctuation should always have a purpose.
    Writing activity 06. Punctuation - quotation marks
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO As Lowe tells us, &quot;Even solidity, understood as propensity in objects to resist penetration ... is something we apparently only understand by reference to its effect ... what 'real quality' in objects, if any, is the ground of this propensity ... is not something ... regarded as being part of our 'core' of natural knowledge&quot; 3 It may be, therefore, etc. 
    QUESTION 0 Have the correct quotation marks been used in this passage?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not right.  Single quotation marks should be used for quotations, with double quotation marks reserved for quotations within quotations.  This text has them the wrong way round.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  Single quotation marks should be used for quotations, with double quotation marks reserved for quotations within quotations.  This text has them the wrong way round.
    QUESTION 1 What does ... mean?
        ANSWER: That the thought is unfinished.
        FEEDBACK: No, they don't mean that.
        ANSWER: That some of the words from the quotation have been purposefully left out.
        FEEDBACK: That's right.  You must always indicate if you've left some of the quotation out, however many times ... appears in your text as a result.
    QUESTION 2 There is no full stop at the end of the quotation.  Where should it go?
        ANSWER: After the footnote number.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not correct.
        ANSWER: After the quotation mark but before the footnote number.
        FEEDBACK: That's correct.  When a quotation is part of a sentence, as here, rather than a whole sentence on its own, the full stop comes after the closing quotation marks.
        ANSWER: Before the closing quotation marks.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not right.  When a quotation is part of a sentence, rather than a sentence on its own, the full stop comes after the closing quotation mark.
    QUESTION 3 Is the footnote number correctly formatted?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: No, it's not.  Footnote numbers should be in superscript.  Endnote numbers can be in the same font as the text, but should be placed in brackets.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  Footnote numbers should be in superscript.  Endnote numbers can be in the same font as the text, but should be placed in brackets.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Whilst 'elitist' is now used as a term of abuse, like 'racist', it does not need to be used in a derogatory sense. The 'Collins English Dictionary' defines elite as 'the choice or select body; the pick or best part of society'.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 Which of these sets of quotation marks are wrongly used?
        ANSWER: 'Elite' and 'racist'
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  When you are referring to words as words (as in the example), rather than just using the word for its sense, quotation marks (also known as inverted commas) are fine.
        ANSWER: The 'Collins English Dictionary'.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  There is no need to put the dictionary in quotation marks.  They add nothing to the sense or meaning.<br />
    QUESTION 1 Should the quotation marks around the actual quotation from the dictionary be double quotation marks?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  Quotation marks should be single.  The only time to use double quotation marks is for a quotation within a quotation.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  Quotation marks should be single.  The only time to use double quotation marks is for a quotation within a quotation.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">In order to discern the strength of the accusation, it is necessary to determine the meaning of 'elitist'. Another aspect of his doctrine that might be considered 'elitist' is his notion of 'competent judges'.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 One of these sets of quotation marks should be deleted.  Which set is it?
        ANSWER: The quotation marks round the first use of 'elitist'.
        FEEDBACK: No, these quotation marks are not strictly necessary, but they are fine, since the word is being specially highlighted.
        ANSWER: The quotation marks round the second use of 'elitist'.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  Here, the word 'elitist' is being used in an ordinary way, i.e. for its meaning.  It should not be enclosed in quotation marks.
        ANSWER: The term 'competent judges'.
        FEEDBACK: I'd say that this was a quotation from Mill, so needs quotation marks and a reference (see referencing section of this website).
