        Task multiplechoice difficulty 1
INTRO <font size="4">With numerous theories as to how to reach summo bonum (the highest good for man), Mill derived his greatest happiness principle: '<span style="font-style: italic;">Actions are right in proportion as they tend to promote happiness, wrong as they tend to produce the reverse of happiness</span>.'</font> 
    QUESTION 0 Are the italics in this text the right way round, i.e. ordinary font for the Latin and italics for the quotation?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: That's incorrect.  Latin text, for example summa bonum should be italicised, but quotations should be typed in ordinary font.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: That's correct.   Latin text, for example summa bonum should be italicised, but quotations should be typed in ordinary font.
        Task wordclick difficulty 2
        Task freetext difficulty 1
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">However disparate people's ideas of the uses of <span style="font-style: italic;">gold</span>, they have a common link, which is the substance of gold itself. </font><font size="4">By contrast, there is no such substance as 'chair'.</font><br />
    QUESTION 0 Are italics used properly here?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  It's fine to put 'gold' in italics. 
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  I think it's fine to put 'gold' in italics.
    QUESTION 1 There is a problem, though.  What is it?
        ANSWER: If one reference to 'gold' is italicised, all the references should be italicised.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Italicisation depends on the context.  Click on the blue question mark for further details.
        ANSWER: If you are going to italicise 'gold', you need to italicise 'chair'.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  In this example, these two words are being used in the same context, so the writer should be consistent.  Either put both 'gold' and 'chair' in quotation marks, or italicise them both.  Do not mix up the two formats.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">To be consistent, we need to say that part of this idea is the <span style="font-style: italic;">conjecture</span> of the real essence as conjecture is all there can be in relation to an unobservable <span style="font-style: italic;">quality</span>. </font> 
    QUESTION 0 Which word is correctly italicised in this sentence?
        ANSWER: Conjecture.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  I don't think the writer needs to emphasis 'conjecture' here.  Also, the writer has not been consistent.  If you use a word in exactly the same way twice, you should format it the same way twice.  Here, I would choose not to italicise.
        ANSWER: Quality.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  I've no idea why 'quality' has been italicised.  Random italicisation is a bad habit.  Italics certainly have a place in philosophy essays, but not in this particular context.
        ANSWER: Neither.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  It's not clear why either 'conjecture' or 'quality' need italics, and nothing is lost by getting rid of them.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">Terms like <span style="font-style: italic;">chair</span> or <span style="font-style: italic;">pencil</span> do not refer to a real essence, only to the observable nominal essence whereas terms such as 'water' or 'gold' refer to phenomenal properties <span style="font-style: italic;">and</span> another kind of property. </font> 
    QUESTION 0 Which of these three words is wrongly italicised?
        ANSWER: chair
        FEEDBACK: This could be correct.  The main trouble here is inconsistency.  If, for emphasis, you're going to italicise the terms you are using, you must do this consistently.  If you italicise 'chair', you must also italicise 'pencil', 'water' and 'gold'. 
        ANSWER: pencil
        FEEDBACK: This could be correct.  The main trouble here is inconsistency.  If, for emphasis, you're going to italicise the terms you are using, you must do this consistently.  If you italicise 'chair', you must also italicise 'pencil', 'water' and 'gold'. 
        ANSWER: and
        FEEDBACK: In this context, I think it's ok to italicise 'and', for emphasis.  Just make sure you don't italicise too often, or the emphasis will be lost.
