    Writing activity 21. Referencing - how to insert direct quotations
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">&quot;The CREED which accepts as the foundation of morals, Utility, or the greatest happiness principle, holds that actions are right in proportion as they tend to promote happiness, wrong as they tend to produce the reverse of happiness.&quot; Wrote Mill, in the beginning of the part that addresses his view concerned about higher and lower pleasures.</font> 
    QUESTION 0 Are the double quotation marks used correctly here?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: No, they are not.  Our departmental style (which conforms with the style currently preferred in many publications) is for single quotation marks enclosing a quote, with double quotation marks reserved for a quote within a quote.  Click the blue question mark above the exercises for more detailed information and examples.  
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  Our departmental style (which conforms with the style currently preferred in many publications) is for single quotation marks enclosing a quote, with double quotation marks reserved for a quote within a quote.  Click the blue question mark above the exercises for more detailed information and examples.  
        ANSWER: It doesn't matter.
        FEEDBACK: I'm afraid it does matter. Conforming to the preferred style of your target readership (in this case, your marker at Glasgow University), is part of your academic training.  Our departmental style (which, incidentally, itself conforms with the style currently preferred in many publications) is for single quotation marks enclosing a quote, with double quotation marks reserved for a quote within a quote.  Click the blue question mark above the exercises for more detailed information and examples.
    QUESTION 1 Is the full stop in this quotation correctly placed?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  If a quotation is a whole sentence in itself, then the full stop comes before the closing quotation marks.  If the quotation is part of a bigger sentence, then the full stop comes after.  Click on the blue question mark above the exercises for examples.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  The full stop is correctly placed here.  If a quotation is a whole sentence in itself, then the full stop comes before the closing quotation marks.  If the quotation is part of a bigger sentence, then the full stop comes after.  Click on the blue question mark above the exercises for examples.
        ANSWER: It doesn't matter.
        FEEDBACK: I'm afraid it does matter because it lets the reader know whether the quotation is a whole sentence in itself or part of a bigger sentence.  If a quotation is a whole sentence in itself, then the full stop comes before the closing quotation marks.  If the quotation is part of a bigger sentence, then the full stop comes after.  Click on the blue question mark above the exercises for examples.
    QUESTION 2 What might usefully have been inserted after 'happiness' and before the full stop, to show that the capitals were the author's (i.e. John Stuart Mill's) and not the essay writer's?
        ANSWER: (sic)
        FEEDBACK: Right word, wrong brackets.  Sic should be enclosed in square brackets.
        ANSWER: (author's italics)
        FEEDBACK: No, there's a quicker and better way of saying 'author's italics'.
        ANSWER: [sic]
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  [sic] indicates that the quotation is reprinted exactly as it appears in the original.
    QUESTION 3 Is this quotation correctly inserted into the essay?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: No, it's not.  'Wrote Mill, etc.' is not a complete sentence in itself.  So, this quote needs either embedding in the sentence (e.g. with no full stop after 'happiness') so that 'wrote' (which would not be capitalised) is not a new sentence, but a continuation;  or, if a new sentence is preferred, it should begin 'Thus wrote Mill etc.'.  
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: Quite right.  'Wrote Mill, etc.' is not a complete sentence in itself.  So, this quote needs either embedding in the sentence (e.g. with no full stop after 'happiness') so that 'wrote' (which would not be capitalised) is not a new sentence, but a continuation;  or, if a new sentence is preferred, it should begin 'Thus wrote Mill etc.'.
    QUESTION 4 What is missing at the end of the quote?
        ANSWER: A footnote number.
        FEEDBACK: That could be right, except that in philosophy, the Harvard system of referencing is used, so we would need not a footnote, but an 'author, date' reference.  See section on referencing for more details.
        ANSWER: An author-date reference.
        FEEDBACK: That's correct.  In philosophy, the Harvard system of referencing is used, so we would need an 'author, date' reference.  See section on referencing for more details.
        ANSWER: Nothing is missing.
        FEEDBACK: That's not right.  A reference is missing (see referencing section for details).  Just saying that Mill wrote the quote 'at the beginning of the part that, etc.' is of no help at all if the reader wants to verify the source or just look up the quote for himself.   You MUST reference every quote.
