    Writing activity 26. Structure - focusing and signposting a discussion
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title: Why does Crisp prefer an ideal-based account of welfare to a experience or desire-based accounts? Is he right so to prefer? Why or why not?<br /><br />(<span style="font-style: italic;">paragraph 2 of the essay)<br /><br /><span style="font-style: italic;"></span></span>In chapter two of <span style="font-style: italic;">Utilitarianism</span>, Mill begins to define the differences between his theory and that of his mentor, Jeremy Bentham. Bentham thought that, in principle, it was possible not only to measure happiness, but also to compare the happiness of different people as the source of each individual's happiness was, in itself, irrelevant. As far as Bentham saw it, the blissful state was important, the absence of pain and the presence of happiness, not how this was achieved. However, Mill thought this approach 'crude' (Tyreman Williams, 1995) and suggested that there was a distinction between so-called higher pleasures, happiness or pleasure in the abstract, and lower pleasures, those that give reality and content to the former. Thus Mill refined utilitarian theory and remains today one of its greatest pioneers. However, for many contemporary thinkers</font><font size="4">, even with these refinements Mill's utilitarianism is difficult to swallow and Crisp is no exception.</font><font size="4"><span style="font-style: italic;"><span style="font-style: italic;"></span><br /></span></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Given the essay title, how focused is this paragraph?
        ANSWER: Very.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Read the essay title again. This paragraph appears to be answering a different question, with Mill as its focus.  The focus of this essay should always be Crisp, with Mill, Bentham and other utilitarian theorists pulled in to demonstrate why Crisp preferred an ideal-based account of welfare.  Whenever you write a sentence in an essay, ask yourself:  <br />
        ANSWER: Quite.
        FEEDBACK: is this sentence focused on the essay question? <br />
        ANSWER: Not at all.
        FEEDBACK: how does this sentence add weight to my answer?
    QUESTION 1 Does this paragraph signpost the next stage in the writer's argument?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  The paragraph gives us a description of Mill's refining of Bentham's utilitarianism.  Right at the end, it points out that Crisp was unconvinced by Mill's account but there's no pointer to tell us on what grounds.  This means that we have no idea where the essay is going next.  Argumentative essays in philosophy require signposts to map out the progression of the argument.  At the end of this example paragraph, we need to be told, succinctly, perhaps in list form, why Crisp was unconvinced.  The next paragraph would then expand on each of the listed reasons.   
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  The paragraph gives us a description of Mill's refining of Bentham's utilitarianism.  Right at the end, it points out that Crisp was unconvinced by Mill's account but there's no pointer to tell us on what grounds.  This means that we have no idea where the essay is going next.  Argumentative essays in philosophy require signposts to map out the progression of the argument.  At the end of this example paragraph, we need to be told, succinctly, perhaps in list form, why Crisp was unconvinced.  The next paragraph would then expand on each of the listed reasons.
    QUESTION 2 Out of 3, with 3 being the best mark and 1 the worst, what mark would you give this paragraph in terms of focusing and signposting?
        ANSWER: 1.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  The paragraph spends too long on Mill and Bentham, as if they were the focus of the essay.  To get a higher mark, all the information needed not just to be stated, but to be directly related to Crisp.
        ANSWER: 2.
        FEEDBACK: I'd say that was too generous.  The paragraph spends too long on Mill and Bentham, as if they were the focus of the essay.  To get a higher mark, all the information needed not just to be stated, but to be directly related to Crisp.
        ANSWER: 3.
        FEEDBACK: I'd say that was not the right judgement.  The paragraph spends too long on Mill and Bentham, as if they were the focus of the essay.  To get a higher mark, all the information needed not just to be stated, but to be directly related to Crisp.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
