    Writing activity 24. Structure - concluding lines
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title: What is the problem of other minds as Ayer sees it in <span style="font-style: italic;">Language, Truth and Logic</span>, and is his solution satisfactory?</font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Read the essay title, then the choice of opening lines offered. Click on the one you think the best. Each choice has an explanation, so you might find it helpful to click on them all.</font> 
        ANSWER: In conclusion, the problem of other minds persists even after Ayer's attempted answer.  The verification in principle of other minds is certainly his most acceptable argument since our every day observations lead us to believe in other people's mental states.  However, I do not think that Ayer convinces with his argument from verification in practice.  This is too shallow an explanation and thus, taking both arguments together, I would say that Ayer's solution remains unsatisfactory. 
        FEEDBACK: This is the best option.  These concluding lines use the terms of the essay question to remain focused; restate concisely the points addressed in the essay; and finish with a direct answer to the very direct question that was asked.
        ANSWER: In conclusion, Ayer's solution is weak and there is a general consensus amongst philosophers that his answer has too many flaws to be a plausible explanation.  However, that he offered an explanation at all is admirable, and after all, who is really to say that he is wrong?
        FEEDBACK: This conclusion is more journalistic than academic.  The essay may have been tightly argued, but the conclusion lets go of the reins.  Keep your argument tight right to the last word and don't let yourself down by finishing with irrelevant generalities.  This is not the best option.
        ANSWER: In conclusion, Ayer's solution to the problem of other minds, as he see describes it in Language, Truth and Logic, would appear to be largely unsatisfactory.
        FEEDBACK: This conclusion, though it admirably employs the terms of the essay question, is too abrupt.  We need a nod back to the arguments made in the essay before drawing the essay to a close.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title: Explain and evaluate the Lockean account of solidity. What problems does this cause for his distinction between primary and secondary qualities?<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Read the essay title and the concluding lines. Click on the concluding line you think is best for the essay title, and see if you agree with us. All the concluding lines have explanations, so even if you click on the best one first, it's still worth clicking on the others.</font> 
        ANSWER: In conclusion, as has been shown, the circularity created by the elevation of solidity to a matter-defining property destroys the concepts of primary and secondary qualities.  Thus, though it is well argued, Locke's indirect realist position ultimately fails.
        FEEDBACK: You may take issue with the writer's argument, but these concluding lines are clear and directly relate to the essay question.  This is the best option.
        ANSWER: In conclusion, Locke's account of solidity is unclear and causes great problems for his primary/secondary distinctions.
        FEEDBACK: This concluding line packs too little punch.  The essay question asks what problems Locke's account of solidity poses for his distinction between primary and secondary qualities, and the answer 'great problems' is a little limp.  Not the best choice.
        ANSWER: I'm very prone to thinking that by all traditional accounts Locke is doomed by his errors of judgment regarding solidity, but with a slight reinterpretation and a fairly large presumption on the subject of dated science, I think the problem can be overcome.
        FEEDBACK: This conclusion is not entirely clear.  Firstly, the phrase 'I'm very prone', has been misused.  To be 'prone' means 'to be accustomed to thinking'.  I think the writer meant 'inclined'.  In addition, 'fairly', 'presumption' and 'I think' all crammed together smack of woolly rather than clear thinking.  Not the best option.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title: Is it possible to articulate a clear and plausible account of positive liberty?</font> 
    QUESTION 0 <font size="4">Read the essay title and choose which of the concluding lines is most appropriate.</font> 
        ANSWER: From Berlin's account of liberty, there seems to be no plausible account of positive liberty, and therefore the answer to the question is probably 'no'. 
        FEEDBACK: This is an unconvincing conclusion.  An admission that only Berlin's account has been scrutinised reinforces the impression of a thin essay, an impression reinforced further by the 'probably' with which the essay ends.
        ANSWER: Fulfilling one's own aspirations requires a society with a minimal level of interference, but which simultaneously insures a citizen's basic needs in order to facilitate this.
        FEEDBACK: This sentence, which contains none of the terms of the essay question, is hard to read (not entirely sure what 'insure' means in this context).  It packs no punch, and leaves the reader feeling dissatisfied.  This is a poor option.
        ANSWER: In conclusion, I have shown that it is not possible to articulate a clear and plausible account of positive liberty for many reasons, but particularly because the clear and plausible account of higher nature and self-realisation on which positive liberty depends is always threatened by state coercion over the autonomous agent.
        FEEDBACK: This concluding line is a clear answer to the essay question.  This is the best option.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 2
INTRO <font size="4">Essay question: 'Oxygen = the element with the atomic number 8.' This is both true and informative but poses a puzzle for naive semantics. What is the puzzle? Give a critical account of Frege's solution to the puzzle.</font> 
    QUESTION 0  <font size="4">Read the essay title, then, from the options offered, choose the best concluding lines.</font> 
        ANSWER: ... the puzzle of identity.  Frege provides a workable solution to this puzzle, allowing us to justify the cognitive value of the identity 'Oxygen = the element with atomic number 8'.  Sense makes sense.
        FEEDBACK: This is clear, refers back to the essay question and finished with a good punch.  I'd say this was the best option.
        ANSWER: My conclusion, therefore, is that while Frege's theory is a vast improvement on naive semantics, solving several large problems of language, in particular how the meanings of two names can differ whie the object they refer to is the same, it is not sufficiently convincing to throw in with, as it still doesn't explain how 'oxygen' manages to refer to 'oxygen'.
        FEEDBACK: The sense of this concluding line is fine, but the language is a muddle.  What does 'to throw in with' mean?  Take care that your choice of words does justice to your thought.  A badly expressed concluding line can undermine what might be otherwise a pretty good essay.  This is not the best choice.
        ANSWER: Frege's philosophy marks an important step in the development of semantics theory. Thus, his philosophical legacy is an important mark in mankind's ultimate quest to understand ourselves.
        FEEDBACK: This is all perfectly true, but provides a wandery ending to a very specific essay question.  In philosophy, it's very important to stick directly to the point right to the very end. This is not the best choice.
    Writing activity 25. Structure - building your argument
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title: 'Society tells us that it is good to perform certain actions. When we think about it, some of these recommended actions turn out to be pointless. But how can it be good to do what is pointless? Surely that's just irrational.' How would you respond to this argument from the free rider?<br /><br />(<span style="font-style: italic;">The following paragraph is paragraph 2 of the essay</span>)<br /><br />The free rider problem questions a person's motive for action and considers the personal and wider ramifications. Take a person riding the bus without paying. The free rider would argue that the action causes no perceptible harm. He has the benefit; nobody suffers. With regard to voting, the free rider could argue that his one vote makes no difference to the election's outcome, so he chooses not to vote. The question we must ask in both instances is what would happen if everybody behaved in this way.<br /><br />(<span style="font-style: italic;">The essay goes on to ask this question</span>.)<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 This paragraph is clearly written.  In many disciplines it would pass muster.  But this is a philosophy essay, so what is missing?
        ANSWER: More examples.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  These two examples are well chosen.  Another would not add more weight to the argument.
        ANSWER: Quotes or references to primary or secondary texts.
        FEEDBACK: I disagree.  Well-chosen quotes and references could be used, but their absence is not the problem here.
        ANSWER: An explanation as to WHY we need to ask this question.
        FEEDBACK: That's correct.  In a philosophy essay, you must build your argument block by block.  Just stating that you need to ask a question without stating why this particular question needs asking leaves a gap in your building blocks.  Philosophers have to be as painstaking as builders - the good sort of builder, that is, the sort who lays every plank carefully and drives home every nail.
        Task freetext difficulty 3
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO <font size="4">Essay title: Is it possible to articulate a clear and plausible account of positive liberty?<br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 What is the best way to start this essay?
        ANSWER: The definition of 'freedom' found in the Oxford dictionary.
        FEEDBACK: Since 'freedom' is not part of the essay title, I'd say this was a poor option.
        ANSWER: An assessment of the theory of positive liberty as defined by Isaiah Berlin in his essay 'Two Concepts of Liberty'. 
        FEEDBACK: The crucial words here are 'an assessment'.  If you just set out in Berlin's theory in a long quote, this would not be effective, but if used properly, Berlin's theory would be an excellent way into this essay.
        ANSWER: 'To coerce a man is to deprive him of freedom - freedom from what? Almost every moralist in human history has praised freedom. Like happiness and goodness, like nature and reality, it is a term whose meaning is so porous that there is little interpretation that it seems able to resist. I do not propose to discuss either the history of this protean word or the more than two hundred senses of it recorded by historians of ideas. I propose to examine no more than two of these senses - but they are central ones, with a great deal of human history behind them, and, I dare say, still to come. The first of these political senses of freedom or liberty (I shall use both words to mean the same), which (following much precedent) I shall call the 'negative' sense, is involved in the answer to the question 'What is the area within which the subject - a person or group of persons - is or should be left to do or be what he is able to do or be, without interference by other persons?' The second, which I shall call the 'positive' sense, is involved in the answer to the question 'What, or who, is the source of control or interference that can determine someone to do, or be, this rather than that?' The two questions are clearly different, even though the answers to them may overlap.' (Berlin, 1969: 2)
        FEEDBACK: This quote, simply parked at the beginning of this essay, is not a good choice.  The quote is too long; it is unexplained; and because of its length, it sits outside the essay instead of being incorporated into it.
    QUESTION 1 After the opening paragraph, what might the next building block of the argument?  
        ANSWER: A discussion about positive and negative liberty.
        FEEDBACK: This would be a good building block.  The end of the paragraph would need to relate the discussion back to the essay question.
        ANSWER: A paragraph stating why the distinction between positive and negative liberty was important to Berlin.
        FEEDBACK: I'd say this was not a good choice.  The essay question asks if it is possible to articulate a clear and plausible account of positive liberty, not why any account might have been important to Berlin.
        ANSWER: Another quotation defining liberty from a different source.
        FEEDBACK: I would not say that this was a good choice.  Too much quoting often looks like prevarication.  You need to get into the argument yourself.
    QUESTION 2 What must the writer of this essay take care NOT to do?
        ANSWER: The writer must take care not simply to list different accounts of positive liberty.
        FEEDBACK: That's correct.  Different accounts must be used to make an argument either FOR the possibility of articulating a clear and plausible account of positive liberty, or AGAINST.
        ANSWER: The writer must take care not to only make arguments and include quotations that uphold the position the writer has taken.  
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  Counter arguments are very important not only for a balanced essay, but also because by tackling counter arguments head on, you strengthen your own argument.
        ANSWER: The writer must take care not to end up sitting on the fence.
        FEEDBACK: I agree.  The essay question demands an answer, and an answer should be given.
    Writing activity 22.  Bibliography and referencing
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO  Bibliography:<br /><br />Mackie, J. L., <span style="font-weight: bold;">Ethics, Inventing Right and Wrong</span> (Penguin Books: London, 1990)<br /><br />POIDEVIN, R. LE, Arguing for Atheism: An introduction to the Philosophy of Religion, London, Routledge<br /><br />Rachels, J. (1999) <span style="font-style: italic;">The Elements of Moral Philosophy</span>, 3rd. ed., Singapore: McGraw-Hill Book Co.<br /><br />M. Thompson, <span style="font-style: italic;">Ethical Theory; access to philosophy </span>(1999) (Hodder &amp; Stoughton, London)<br /> 
    QUESTION 0 Out of these 4 bibliographical entries, which one is correctly formatted in the Harvard system?
        ANSWER: The first - Mackie.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  The author's surname should be followed by the date of the publication.  The book title should be italicised and not in bold.  The city of publication should come before the publisher's name.  Please click on the blue question mark above the tasks for more detailed information and helpful examples.
        ANSWER: The second - POIDEVIN.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  The author's surname should not be capitalised, and Le is part of the  surname.   The surname should be followed by the date of the publication.  The book title should be italicised.  The city of publication should come before the publisher's name.  Please click on the blue question mark above the tasks for more detailed information and helpful examples.
        ANSWER: The third - Rachels.
        FEEDBACK: Correct. Please click on the blue question mark above the exercises for more helpful examples.
        ANSWER: The fourth - M. Thompson.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  The surname should come before the initial.  The author's initials should be followed by the date of the publication.  The city of publication should come before the publisher's name.  Please click on the blue question mark above the tasks for more detailed information and helpful examples.
        Task multiplechoice difficulty 3
INTRO  <font size="4">Bibliography<br /><br />Crisp, Roger, Mill on Utilitarianism, 1997, Chapters 2-3<br />Mill, J.S., On Liberty, Chapter 3, 1991<br />Downie, R. S., Mill on Pleasure and Self-Development, 1966<br />The Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy<br /><br /></font> 
    QUESTION 0 Are any of these references properly formatted?
        ANSWER: Yes, they all are except for the internet reference.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  None of the references are properly formatted.
        ANSWER: None of them are.
        FEEDBACK: Correct.
        ANSWER: The internet reference is correct but not the others.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  Not one of the references is correctly formatted.
    QUESTION 1 What is the name of the system preferred by the Philosophy department at Glasgow University?
        ANSWER: The MHRA system.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not right.
        ANSWER: The Chicago system.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's not right.
        ANSWER: The Harvard system.
        FEEDBACK: That's correct.  This department prefers the Harvard system, which is an author/date system.  Click on the blue question mark above the exercises for detailed information.
    QUESTION 2 Are these references listed in the correct order?  e.g. Crisp, Mill, Downie, the internet?
        ANSWER: Yes, if that is the order in which the works were consulted.
        FEEDBACK: No, that's incorrect.   In a bibliography, sources should be listed alphabetically by author surname.  If, as sometimes happens with an internet reference, there is no author name, we find the website's place in the bibliography from the first word.  So - this particular list should read: Crisp, Downie, Mill, The Internet Encyclopedia.  (C, D, M, T)
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: That's correct.   In a bibliography, sources should be listed alphabetically by author surname.  If, as sometimes happens with an internet reference, there is no author name, we find the website's place in the bibliography from the first word.  So - this particular list should read: Crisp, Downie, Mill, The Internet Encyclopedia.  (C, D, M, T)
        ANSWER: The order doesn't matter so long as you list all the works.
        FEEDBACK: I'm afraid it does matter.   In a bibliography, sources should be listed alphabetically by author surname.  If, as sometimes happens with an internet reference, there is no author name, we find the website's place in the bibliography from the first word.  So - this particular list should read: Crisp, Downie, Mill, The Internet Encyclopedia.  (C, D, M, T)
    QUESTION 3 Is the style used for the book titles correct?
        ANSWER: Yes.
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  Book titles and journal titles should be italicised.
        ANSWER: No.
        FEEDBACK: That's correct.  Book titles and journal titles should be italicised.
    QUESTION 4 Which is the correct format for the reference to Crisp?
        ANSWER: Crisp, Roger, Mill on Utlitarianism (in italics) 1997
        FEEDBACK: This is incorrect.  Try again.
        ANSWER: Crisp, Roger, 1997, Mill on Utlitarianism (in italics) Routledge, London, Chapters 2-3
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  Try again.
        ANSWER: Crisp, Roger (1997) Mill on Utilitarianism (in italics), London: Routledge
        FEEDBACK: Correct.  Please click on the blue question mark above the exercises to see explanations and examples, and N.B. that in the bibliography you do not put in the chapter or page reference.  With the author/date system, if this information is necessary, it should be embedded into the text.  You'll find more information about this also behind the blue question mark.
    QUESTION 5 Which is the correct format for the internet reference?
        ANSWER: The Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy, accessed 12.04.10
        FEEDBACK: Incorrect.  Try again.
        ANSWER: The Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy, http://www.iep.utm.edu/, accessed 12.04.10
        FEEDBACK: No, not this one.  Try again.
        ANSWER: Heydt, C. (2006) John Stuart Mill, The Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy (in italics), http://www.iep.utm.edu/milljs/ [accessed 12.04.10]
        FEEDBACK: This is correct.  For more information, click on the blue question mark above the exercises.
